e = 5 June\n|       T20Idebutyear = 2009\n|         lastT20Ifor = England\n|     lastT20Iagainst = South Africa\n|        lastT20Idate = 16 February\n|        lastT20Iyear = 2020\n\n|               club1 = [[Middlesex County Cricket Club|Middlesex]]\n|               year1 = 2006\u2013present\n|               club2 = [[England Lions cricket team|England Lions]]\n|               year2 = 2007\n|               club3 = [[Royal Challengers Bangalore]]\n|               year3 = 2010\n|               club4 = [[Kolkata Knight Riders]]\n|               year4 = 2011\u20132013\n|               club5 = [[Sydney Thunder]]\n|               year5 = 2013/14\n|              club6 = [[Sunrisers Hyderabad]]\n|               year6 = 2015\u20132016\n|               club7 = Sydney Thunder\n|               year7 = 2016/17\n|               club8 = [[Peshawar Zalmi]]\n|               year8 = 2017\n|               club9 = [[Kings XI Punjab]]\n|               year9 = 2017\n|               club10 = [[Barbados Tridents]]\n|               year10 = 2017\n|              club11 = [[Karachi Kings]] \n|              year11 = 2018\n|             columns = 4\n|             column1 = [[Test cricket|Test]]\n|            matches1 = 16\n|               runs1 = 700\n|            bat avg1 = 30.43\n|           100s/50s1 = 2/3\n|          top score1 = 130\n|         deliveries1 = \u2013\n|            wickets1 = \u2013\n|           bowl avg1 = \u2013\n|            fivefor1 = \u2013\n|             tenfor1 = \u2013\n|       best bowling1 = \u2013\n|  catches/stumpings1 = 11/0\n|             column2 = [[One Day International|ODI]]\n|            matches2 = 233{{refn|23 for Ireland, the rest for England|group=nb}}\n|               runs2 = 7,348\n|            bat avg2 = 39.71\n|           100s/50s2 = 13/46\n|          top score2 = 148\n|         deliveries2 = \u2013\n|            wickets2 = \u2013\n|           bowl avg2 = \u2013\n|            fivefor2 = \u2013\n|             tenfor2 = \u2013\n|       best bowling2 = \u2013\n|  catches/stumpings2 = 83/0\n|             column3 = [[First-class cricket|FC]]\n|            matches3 = 102\n|               runs3 = 5,042\n|            bat avg3 = 33.39\n|           100s/50s3 = 11/24\n|          top score3 = 209[[not out|*]]\n|         deliveries3 = 120\n|            wickets3 = 2\n|           bowl avg3 = 47.00\n|            fivefor3 = 0\n|             tenfor3 = 0\n|       best bowling3 = 2/24\n|  catches/stumpings3 = 76/1\n|             column4 = [[List A cricket|LA]]\n|            matches4 = 364\n|               runs4 = 11,301\n|            bat avg4 = 39.10\n|           100s/50s4 = 21/67\n|          top score4 = 161\n|         deliveries4 = 42\n|            wickets4 = 0\n|           bowl avg4 = \u2013\n|            fivefor4 = \u2013\n|             tenfor4 = \u2013\n|       best bowling4 = \u2013\n|  catches/stumpings4 = 123/0\n|                date = 16 February 2020\n|              source = http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/content/player/24598.html ESPNcricinfo\n}}\n'''Eoin Joseph Gerard Morgan''' {{post-nominals|country=GBR|size=100%|CBE}} (born 10 September 1986) is an  Irish-born cricketer who captains the [[England cricket team]] in [[limited overs cricket]]. A left-handed batsman, he plays [[county cricket]] for [[Middlesex County Cricket Club|Middlesex]] and has played for England's [[Test cricket|Test]], [[One Day International]] (ODI), and [[Twenty20 International]] (T20I) teams. He previously played for the [[Ireland cricket team]] in ODIs, and was the first player to score an ODI hundred for two nations. His ability to hit boundaries at the end of innings sees him labelled as a \"finisher\"; he is also among the most skilful exponents of the [[reverse sweep]] shot.\n\nAfter [[Alastair Cook]] was removed from the ODI captaincy on 19 December 2014, Morgan was named as the England captain for the [[2015 Cricket World Cup]], having already captained England in ODIs and T20Is as a stand-in. He is the only England captain to have scored more than 4 ODI centuries. Under his captaincy, England won the [[2019 ICC Cricket World Cup]], the first time they had won the tournament.\n\n{{As of|December 2019}}, Morgan is the all-time leading run scorer and most capped player for England in ODI matches.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cricketcountry.com/news/england-vs-pakistan-3rd-odi-eoin-morgan-to-surpass-paul-collingwood-as-englands-most-capped-player-843592 |title=England vs Pakistan, 3rd ODI: Eoin Morgan to surpass Paul Collingwood as England's most-capped player |work=Cricket Country |accessdate=14 May 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190514113331/https://www.cricketcountry.com/news/england-vs-pakistan-3rd-odi-eoin-morgan-to-surpass-paul-collingwood-as-englands-most-capped-player-843592 |archive-date=14 May 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> He also holds the England record for the fastest fifty in ODIs and during the 2019 ICC World Cup he scored the highest number of sixes in an ODI innings, with 17 sixes against Afghanistan.\n\n==Youth and early career==\nMorgan was born in [[Dublin]] and brought up in [[Rush, Dublin|Rush]], where his father was from.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.independent.ie/regionals/fingalindependent/news/jodys-pride-over-professional-and-gracious-eoin-29566334.html|title=Jody's pride over 'professional and gracious' Eoin|website=Independent.ie|language=en|access-date=2019-07-02|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190702082637/https://www.independent.ie/regionals/fingalindependent/news/jodys-pride-over-professional-and-gracious-eoin-29566334.html|archive-date=2 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> His mother is English.<ref name=pp /> He learnt to play cricket at [[Rush Cricket Club]], where his father, Jody, was Third XI captain.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/cricket/2019/05/02/special-report-making-eoin-morgan/|title=Special report: The making of Eoin Morgan|last=Wigmore|first=Tim|date=2019-05-02|work=The Telegraph|access-date=2019-07-02|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190509052417/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/cricket/2019/05/02/special-report-making-eoin-morgan/|archive-date=9 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> He was educated at the [[Catholic University School]] on Leeson Street,<ref name=\"future\">{{cite news |work=Sunday Times |date= 21 March 2004|url=http://link.galegroup.com/apps/doc/A114723005/GPS?sid=wikipedia |title=One for the future; Eoin Morgan, Middlesex and Ireland |accessdate=26 September 2017 |page=28}}{{subscription required|via=Academic OneFile}}</ref> where he played in three Leinster Senior Schools Cup champion teams. In his early teens Morgan played [[hurling]] twice a week and this helped develop his skills as a batsman, particularly as the grip for hurling is the same as for the reverse sweep.<ref name=\"Switching\">{{cite web |date=21 May 2009 |title=Switching colours, switching hits |url=http://www.cricinfo.com/engvwi2009/content/story/405314.html |publisher=Cricinfo |accessdate=20 September 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100611154425/http://www.cricinfo.com/engvwi2009/content/story/405314.html |archive-date=11 June 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref> Morgan clarified later that the hurling influence on his cricket career was very minimal.<ref>{{cite web\n|url=https://www.balls.ie/gaa/dublin-cricketer-eoin-morgan-hurlings-influence-cricket-career-158509\n|title=Dublin Cricketer Eoin Morgan On Hurling's Influence On His Cricket Career\n|quote=Everybody asked does it contribute to anything I do in cricket. Maybe a little bit of my reverse sweep but that is it. It gets blown out of proportion all the time. It's a fantastic sport and I love watching it but I didn't play a great deal\n|access-date=5 November 2019\n|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191105160549/https://www.balls.ie/gaa/dublin-cricketer-eoin-morgan-hurlings-influence-cricket-career-158509\n|archive-date=5 November 2019\n|url-status=live\n}}</ref>\n\nDuring this time he also briefly attended [[Dulwich College]] in south London to further his cricketing education and it was here that his ambition to play for England began.<ref name=\"Switching\" /> He represented Ireland's youth teams and was capped at Under-13, Under-15 and Under-17 level, eventually he became Ireland's youngest senior international.<ref name=\"future\"/> He spent a number of summer spells with [[Middlesex County Cricket Club|Middlesex]]'s under-age setup.<ref name=\"future\"/> He was selected in the [[Ireland under-19 cricket team|Irish under-19 squad]] for the [[2004 Under-19 Cricket World Cup]], and was Ireland's top run-scorer in the competition.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cricinfo.com/db/ARCHIVE/2003-04/OTHERS/U19-WC2004/STATS/U19-WC2004_FEB-MAR2004_AVS_IRELAND-U19.html |title=ICC U/19 Cricket World Cup, 2003/04 Averages: Ireland Under-19s |publisher=Cricinfo |accessdate=1 March 2007 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090530024255/http://www.cricinfo.com/db/ARCHIVE/2003-04/OTHERS/U19-WC2004/STATS/U19-WC2004_FEB-MAR2004_AVS_IRELAND-U19.html |archive-date=30 May 2009 |url-status=live }}</ref> Two years later, he captained Ireland in the [[2006 ICC Under-19 Cricket World Cup|2006 Under-19 World Cup]] where he finished as the second-highest overall run-scorer.<ref>{{cite web |title=ICC Under-19s Cricket World Cup, 2005/06 Batting \u2013 Most Runs |publisher=Cricinfo |accessdate=1 March 2007 |url=http://www.cricinfo.com/db/ARCHIVE/2005-06/OTHERS/U19-WC2006/STATS/U19-WC2006_FEB2006_AVS_BAT_MOST_RUNS.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080302012938/http://www.cricinfo.com/db/ARCHIVE/2005-06/OTHERS/U19-WC2006/STATS/U19-WC2006_FEB2006_AVS_BAT_MOST_RUNS.html |archive-date=2 March 2008 |url-status=live }}</ref> He has also played for [[Finchley]] CC.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://cricketarchive.com/Players/60/60781/Middlesex_Premier_League_Matches.html |website=Cricket Archive |accessdate=2 June 2017 |title=MIDDLESEX PREMIER LEAGUE MATCHES PLAYED BY EOIN MORGAN |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170926143902/http://cricketarchive.com/Players/60/60781/Middlesex_Premier_League_Matches.html |archive-date=26 September 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> He is the leading runscorer in [[U19 Cricket World Cup]] history with an aggregate of 606 runs.<ref>{{cite web |title=ICC Under-19s Cricket World Cup \u2013 Most Runs |publisher=Cricinfo |url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/batting/most_runs_career.html?id=109;type=trophy |accessdate=1 March 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170322205638/http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/batting/most_runs_career.html?id=109;type=trophy |archive-date=22 March 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Domestic career==\n\nMorgan scored his maiden first-class century for Middlesex on 5 July 2008 at Uxbridge. This was compiled from 250 balls. He achieved this against the touring [[South Africa cricket team|South Africans]] before their Test series against England; the innings included three sixes off spinner [[Paul Harris (cricketer, born 1978)|Paul Harris]].<ref>{{citation |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/7491639.stm |title=Morgan frustrates SA with century |publisher=BBC Sport |date=5 July 2008 |accessdate=5 July 2008}}</ref> Morgan was part of Middlesex's victorious [[Twenty20 Cup]] winning side in 2008. He underlined his growing maturity after leading Middlesex to victory in the [[County Championship]] against Kent.\n\nAfter regular captain [[Shaun Udal]] was injured on the morning of the match, Morgan was named captain, at an age of just 22, having been chosen over senior players [[Owais Shah]], [[Chris Silverwood]], [[Murali Kartik]] and [[Tyron Henderson]]. It was Middlesex's first four-day victory of the season. Udal returned to captain the side for the next match against Essex. He hit a six off the final ball of the innings to win a [[KFC Twenty20 Big Bash]] for the [[Sydney Thunder]] against the [[Melbourne Stars]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.theage.com.au/sport/cricket/big-bash/a-six-and-thunder-roar-back-and-sink-stars-20170104-gtm2mj.html|title=A six and Thunder roar back and sink Stars|last=Nicholson|first=Larissa|date=2017-01-04|website=The Age|access-date=2017-01-04}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2020, Eoin Morgan was named as the captain for Middlesex\u2019s T20 team for the 2020 Vitality Blast campaign. \u201cI\u2019m delighted to be awarded the T20 Captaincy. The role is one that I have really enjoyed. We\u2019ve got an exciting group of players here at [[Middlesex]], with plenty of talent and a good blend of youth and experience, and I\u2019m really looking forward to helping the club build on the improvements we made in this format last year,\u201d Morgan's statement read upon assuming the captain's role.<ref>{{cite_web|url=https://www.middlesexccc.com/news/2020/01/eoin-morgan-named-as-middlesexs-vitality-blast-captain|title=EOIN MORGAN NAMED AS MIDDLESEX'S VITALITY BLAST CAPTAIN|accessdate=8 January 2020|website=Middlesex Cricket}}</ref> \n\n===T20 franchise cricket===\nMorgan took part in the [[2010 Indian Premier League]] (IPL). In the preceding player auction, he was bought by Royal Challengers Bangalore for a sum of $220,000.<ref>{{citation|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2010/jan/19/eoin-morgan-ipl-auction|title=Eoin Morgan bought by Royal Challengers Bangalore at IPL auction|newspaper=Guardian.co.uk|date=19 January 2010|first=Dileep|last=Premachandran|accessdate=2 May 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140808045159/http://www.theguardian.com/sport/2010/jan/19/eoin-morgan-ipl-auction|archive-date=8 August 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> However, he was frequently in and out of the side and was not given much opportunity.<ref name = \"espn profile\"/>\nMorgan was purchased by the Kolkata Knight Riders for $350,000 at the 2011 IPL auctions for the next 3 years.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.ipl-schedule.com/485-kolkata-knight-riders-buys-eoin-morgan-at-350000.html|title=Kolkata Knight Riders buys Eoin Morgan at $350,000|publisher=IPL-schedule.com|date=10 January 2011|access-date=4 November 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120403144753/http://www.ipl-schedule.com/485-kolkata-knight-riders-buys-eoin-morgan-at-350000.html|archive-date=3 April 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, Morgan decided not to enter [[IPL 2014]] due to England playing an ODI series against Sri Lanka at home when IPL took place.\n\nIn 2015, Eoin Morgan decided to play the [[Indian Premier League]] and was bought by [[Sunrisers Hyderabad]] for $150,000. During the tournament he missed the England ODI game against Ireland. He also played 7 games for the Sunrisers in [[IPL 2016]].\n\nIn 2017 IPL Auctions, he was bought by [[Kings XI Punjab]] for Rs. 2 Crore. He played until 30 April before returning to England for a training camp.\n\nMorgan played in the [[Pakistan Super League]] (PSL) for the [[Peshawar Zalmi]] in the [[2017 Pakistan Super League|2017 season]]. He was bought in for US$140,000 in Platinum Category.\n\nIn October 2018, he was named in [[Tshwane Spartans]]' squad for the [[2018 Mzansi Super League|first edition]] of the [[Mzansi Super League]] T20 tournament.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.sport24.co.za/Cricket/live-mzansi-super-league-player-draft-20181017 |title=Mzansi Super League - full squad lists |work=Sport24 |accessdate=17 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190423174005/https://www.sport24.co.za/Cricket/live-mzansi-super-league-player-draft-20181017 |archive-date=23 April 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.iol.co.za/sport/cricket/domestic/mzansi-super-league-player-draft-the-story-so-far-17521199 |title=Mzansi Super League Player Draft: The story so far |work=Independent Online |accessdate=17 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190423174005/https://www.iol.co.za/sport/cricket/domestic/mzansi-super-league-player-draft-the-story-so-far-17521199 |archive-date=23 April 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> In July 2019, he was selected to play for the Dublin Chiefs in the [[2019 Euro T20 Slam|inaugural edition]] of the [[Euro T20 Slam]] cricket tournament.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.espncricinfo.com/story/_/id/27222261/eoin-morgan-represent-dublin-franchise-inaugural-euro-t20-slam |title=Eoin Morgan to represent Dublin franchise in inaugural Euro T20 Slam |work=ESPN Cricinfo |accessdate=19 July 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190719161334/https://www.espncricinfo.com/story/_/id/27222261/eoin-morgan-represent-dublin-franchise-inaugural-euro-t20-slam |archive-date=19 July 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cricketeurope.com/DATABASE/ARTICLES2019/articles/000010/001060.shtml |title=Euro T20 Slam Player Draft completed |work=Cricket Europe |accessdate=19 July 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190719163945/https://www.cricketeurope.com/DATABASE/ARTICLES2019/articles/000010/001060.shtml |archive-date=19 July 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> However, the following month the tournament was cancelled.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.espncricinfo.com/story/_/id/27387389/inaugural-euro-t20-slam-cancelled-two-weeks-notice |title=Inaugural Euro T20 Slam cancelled at two weeks' notice |work=ESPN Cricinfo |accessdate=14 August 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190814215557/https://www.espncricinfo.com/story/_/id/27387389/inaugural-euro-t20-slam-cancelled-two-weeks-notice |archive-date=14 August 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> In the [[List of 2020 Indian Premier League personnel changes|2020 IPL auction]], he was bought by the [[Kolkata Knight Riders]] ahead of the [[2020 Indian Premier League]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.espncricinfo.com/story/_/id/28338426/ipl-auction-analysis-do-eight-teams-their-best-xis-place? |title=IPL auction analysis: Do the eight teams have their best XIs in place? |work=ESPN Cricinfo |accessdate=20 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Ireland==\nMorgan made his [[One Day International]] debut for [[Ireland cricket team|Ireland]] on 5 August 2006 at the [[European Cricket Championship|European Championships]] against [[Scottish cricket team|Scotland]]. He fell one run short of a century, scoring 99 before he was [[run out]]. It was the first time in ODI history that a player had been dismissed for 99 on debut. Only two other batsmen passed 20 as Ireland beat Scotland by 85 runs.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cricinfo.com/ireland/engine/match/253010.html |title=Scotland v Ireland at Ayr, 5 August 2006 |publisher=Cricinfo |access-date=1 March 2007 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090901145545/http://www.cricinfo.com/ireland/engine/match/253010.html |archive-date=1 September 2009 |url-status=live }} Retrieved on 1 March 2007.</ref> His maiden ODI hundred came not long after, on 4 February 2007 against [[Canadian cricket team|Canada]] in Nairobi. At the time he was the youngest ever non-[[Indian subcontinent|subcontinental]] player to make a century in ODI cricket, a record subsequently beaten by two other players.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.cricinfo.com/db/STATS/ODIS/BATTING/ODI_YOUNGEST_CENTURIONS.html | title=ODIs \u2013 Youngest to Score Century | publisher=Cricinfo | access-date=1 March 2007 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070217225153/http://www.cricinfo.com/db/STATS/ODIS/BATTING/ODI_YOUNGEST_CENTURIONS.html | archive-date=17 February 2007 | url-status=live }} Retrieved on 1 March 2007.</ref>\n\nMorgan was the first cricketer to score a [[first-class cricket|first-class]] double century for Ireland, with an unbeaten 209 against the [[United Arab Emirates cricket team|United Arab Emirates]] in February 2007 at Abu Dhabi.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://newsimg.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/6351361.stm |title=Dominant Morgan sets Irish record |publisher=BBC Sport |date=11 February 2007 |access-date=17 February 2007 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160116092024/http://newsimg.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/6351361.stm |archive-date=16 January 2016 |url-status=live }} Retrieved on 1 March 2007.</ref> In February 2007, Morgan was named in Ireland's 15-man squad for the [[2007 Cricket World Cup]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.cricinfo.com/ireland/content/story/280255.html |title=Ireland stick with tried and tested |publisher=Cricinfo |date=13 February 2007}} Retrieved on 1 March 2007.</ref> Although Ireland performed well in the tournament, Morgan struggled personally, scoring just 91 runs from nine innings.<ref name = \"espn profile\">{{cricinfo|ref=england/content/player/24598.html}}</ref> In all, Morgan played in 23 ODIs for Ireland, scoring 744 runs at an average of 35.42.\n\n==England==\n\n===On the fringes===\nIn 2010 Morgan told the ''[[Sunday Times]]'' that \"From the age of 13, I wanted to play cricket for England. I\u2019ve never felt any shame in saying this is what I wanted to do. And the people at home involved in cricket, they were like, 'Fair play, it\u2019s going to be unbelievable if you make it'. So I\u2019ve never had any shame about this and my father\u2019s never had any shame about it.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.spiked-online.com/index.php/site/article/9887/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-11-12 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101203031507/http://www.spiked-online.com/index.php/site/article/9887/ |archivedate=3 December 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> He has subsequently stated that his mother is English, and that he has held a British passport since birth.<ref name=pp>{{Cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/story/_/id/23746348/eoin-morgan-dampens-talk-jofra-archer-being-england-world-cup-squad|title=Eoin Morgan dampens talk of Jofra Archer being in England's World Cup squad|date=2018-06-09|website=ESPNcricinfo|language=en|access-date=2019-02-18|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190218202251/http://www.espncricinfo.com/story/_/id/23746348/eoin-morgan-dampens-talk-jofra-archer-being-england-world-cup-squad|archive-date=18 February 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> At the time, England was one of the ten full members of the [[International Cricket Council]], while Ireland was an associate member; only full member nations can play a full schedule of international cricket, including Test matches. Ireland were subsequently admitted as full members in 2017.\n\nIn May 2007, Morgan was named as one of England's twelfth men for the Lord's Test versus West Indies,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/engvwi/engine/current/match/258459.html |title=Cricinfo \u2013 1st Test: England v West Indies at Lord's, May 17\u201321, 2007 |publisher=Cricinfo |date=21 May 2007 |access-date=17 May 2007 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071010102124/http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/engvwi/engine/current/match/258459.html |archive-date=10 October 2007 |url-status=live }} Retrieved 10 September 2008.</ref> and came on for [[Matthew Hoggard]] on the third day.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/england/6672179.stm |title=First Test, day three as it happened |publisher=BBC Online |date=21 May 2007 |access-date=19 May 2007 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070522101116/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/england/6672179.stm |archive-date=22 May 2007 |url-status=live }} Retrieved 10 September 2008.</ref> On 16 August 2008, Morgan represented the England Lions in a list A match against the touring South Africans. He scored 47* in an unbeaten partnership of 113 with [[Samit Patel]] in the course of England Lions securing a six wicket victory.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/countycricket2008/content/current/story/365203.html |title=Patel gives Lions some bite |author=Cricinfo staff |publisher=Cricinfo |date=16 August 2008 |access-date=18 August 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080819053951/http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/countycricket2008/content/current/story/365203.html |archive-date=19 August 2008 |url-status=live }} Retrieved 18 August 2008.</ref> Morgan was part of the England Performance Programme squad in India in the winter of 2008,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/india/content/squad?object=371668 |title=England Performance Programme Squad |publisher=Cricinfo.com |access-date=29 December 2008 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120716073533/http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/india/content/squad?object=371668 |archive-date=16 July 2012 |url-status=live }} Retrieved 29 December 2008.</ref> although no matches were played as the tour was cancelled after the [[November 2008 Mumbai attacks]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/england/7751756.stm |title=England to return home from India |publisher=BBC Online |date=27 November 2008 |access-date=29 December 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081205074211/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/england/7751756.stm |archive-date=5 December 2008 |url-status=live }} Retrieved 30 November 2008.</ref> Morgan was also part of the [[England Lions cricket team|England Lions]] for the winter tour of New Zealand.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/wiveng2009/content/current/story/384526.html |title=Vaughan misses out on West Indies |author=Cricinfo staff |publisher=Cricinfo.com |date=29 December 2008 |access-date=29 December 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090207035813/http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/wiveng2009/content/current/story/384526.html |archive-date=7 February 2009 |url-status=live }} Retrieved 29 December 2008.</ref>\n\nAfter touring with the England Lions over the winter, it was announced in April 2009 that Morgan was in England's 30-man provisional squad for the [[2009 ICC World Twenty20]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://content.cricinfo.com/wt202009/content/current/story/398560.html |title=No place for Strauss in England's Twenty20 squad |author=Cricinfo staff |publisher=Cricinfo.com |date=6 April 2009 |access-date=9 April 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090409075535/http://content.cricinfo.com/wt202009/content/current/story/398560.html |archive-date=9 April 2009 |url-status=live }} Retrieved on 9 April 2009.</ref> This meant that he could not play for Ireland, who were also participating in the tournament. While disappointed to be denied Morgan's batting, Irish cricket team manager [[Roy Torrens]] said \"[Morgan's] made no secret of that fact [wanting to play Test cricket]. So you know, it's not totally unexpected to us. We realise this is always going to be a problem with our better players playing in England\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://content.cricinfo.com/wt202009/content/current/story/398710.html |title=Ireland frustration at Morgan call |author=Will Luke |publisher=Cricinfo.com |date=7 April 2009 |access-date=9 April 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090410065920/http://content.cricinfo.com/wt202009/content/current/story/398710.html |archive-date=10 April 2009 |url-status=live }} Retrieved on 9 April 2009.</ref>\n\n===2009 West Indies, Australia and South Africa===\n\nMorgan's progression towards representing the senior England side continued when in May 2009 he was named in England's 14-man squad to face [[West Indies cricket team|West Indies]] in a three-match ODI series and the 15-man squad for the World Twenty20.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://content.cricinfo.com/engvwi2009/content/current/story/402459.html |title=Morgan named in one-day squad |author=Cricinfo staff |publisher=Cricinfo.com |date=1 May 2009 |access-date=1 May 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090504081627/http://content.cricinfo.com/engvwi2009/content/current/story/402459.html |archive-date=4 May 2009 |url-status=live }} Retrieved on 1 May 2009.</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://content.cricinfo.com/wt202009/content/current/story/402433.html |title=Collingwood named Twenty20 captain |author=Cricinfo staff |publisher=Cricinfo.com |date=1 May 2009 |access-date=1 May 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090505173247/http://content.cricinfo.com/wt202009/content/current/story/402433.html |archive-date=5 May 2009 |url-status=live }} Retrieved on 1 May 2009.</ref> Morgan made his England debut in the second One Day International (after the first was abandoned due to rain), and also played in the third of the series. Morgan was not given much of a chance to impress with the bat, due to not coming in to bat until late in the innings, making scores of 2 and 6 not out, but was praised for his athletic fielding.\n\nMorgan played in the opening match of the World Twenty20 against the Netherlands, but after England's defeat played no further part in the tournament.<ref>{{cite web\n|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/match/355991.html\n|title=ICC World Twenty20, 2009 / Scorecard\n|publisher=Cricinfo\n|accessdate=18 February 2012\n|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120402052303/http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/match/355991.html\n|archive-date=2 April 2012\n|url-status=live\n}}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/wt202009/engine/match/355996.html\n|title=ICC World Twenty20 \u2013 6th match, Group B, England v Pakistan\n|publisher=Cricinfo\n|accessdate=18 February 2012\n|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170718150841/http://www.espncricinfo.com/wt202009/engine/match/355996.html\n|archive-date=18 July 2017\n|url-status=live\n}}</ref>\n\nAt the end of the English Summer, Morgan was involved in the ODI against [[Australian cricket team in England in 2009|Australia]]. Although they had just lost the [[2009 Ashes series|Ashes]] to England in the Test series, Australia won the first five games with Morgan one of few batsmen to emerge with any credit, including a first one-day half century for England in the fifth match, winning praise with his innovative style.\n\nIn the first game of the [[2009 ICC Champions Trophy]], Morgan led England to an unexpected victory over much fancied [[Sri Lankan cricket team|Sri Lanka]]. He hit an unbeaten 62, and was well supported by Middlesex colleague Owais Shah. Morgan kept wicket for the first time in his professional career in the next match against South Africa, after regular wicket-keeper [[Matt Prior]] was struck down by illness.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/sport/cricket/article6835916.ece | work=The Times | location=London | title=Eoin Morgan leads England to strong total | first=Robert | last=Dineen | date=15 September 2009 | accessdate=2 May 2010}}</ref> Morgan scored 67 runs from just 34 balls in England's innings.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/england/8276962.stm | work=BBC News | title=South Africa v England as it happened | date=27 September 2009 | accessdate=2 May 2010}}</ref>\n[[File:Eoin Morgan batting vs Bangladesh 2010-06-04.jpg|thumb|right|Morgan batting against Bangladesh in 2010]]\n\nIn the ODI series against South Africa, Morgan was selected in the team for the second match of the series. He made 27 to help England secure a seven wicket victory. In the following match he was dismissed for a duck as South Africa secured a convincing victory, winning by 112 runs. He kept his place for the next match, where he scored 28 to help England win the match by seven wickets.\n\n===2010 Bangladesh, World T20, Australia and Pakistan===\n\nAfter making 33 in the first match of the ODI series in Bangladesh, he hit an unbeaten 110 to help England win the second ODI by two wickets, with innings earning him the man of the match award. He made 36 in the final match of the series, meaning he had scored 169 runs in the three matches he had played. Morgan was one of England's stand out batsmen in the series and his performances earned him praise from the media.\n\nHe was an important part of England's Twenty20 team that won the [[2010 ICC World Twenty20]] tournament in the West Indies. He top-scored in England's group games against the West Indies and his native Ireland,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cricinfo.com/world-twenty20-2010/engine/match/412685.html|title=England fall victim to rain rules|publisher=CricInfo|date=3 May 2010|access-date=23 June 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100506200724/http://www.cricinfo.com/world-twenty20-2010/engine/match/412685.html|archive-date=6 May 2010|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cricinfo.com/world-twenty20-2010/engine/match/412681.html|title=Rain saves England in tense washout|publisher=CricInfo|date=4 May 2010|access-date=23 June 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100508164720/http://www.cricinfo.com/world-twenty20-2010/engine/match/412681.html|archive-date=8 May 2010|url-status=live}}</ref> as well as the Super Eights game against [[New Zealand cricket team|New Zealand]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cricinfo.com/world-twenty20-2010/engine/match/412698.html|title=New Zealand eliminated by impressive England|publisher=CricInfo|date=10 May 2010|access-date=23 June 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100514124635/http://www.cricinfo.com/world-twenty20-2010/engine/match/412698.html|archive-date=14 May 2010|url-status=live}}</ref> Due to effective team bowling and half-centuries from [[Kevin Pietersen]] and [[Craig Kieswetter]], he was hardly needed in the semi-final against Sri Lanka and final against [[Australian cricket team|Australia]], finishing not-out in both matches.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cricinfo.com/world-twenty20-2010/engine/match/412701.html|title=England stroll to resounding win|publisher=CricInfo|date=13 May 2010|access-date=23 June 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100516053450/http://www.cricinfo.com/world-twenty20-2010/engine/match/412701.html|archive-date=16 May 2010|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cricinfo.com/world-twenty20-2010/engine/match/412703.html|title=Kieswetter and Pietersen seal title for England|publisher=CricInfo|date=16 May 2010|access-date=23 June 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100519104211/http://www.cricinfo.com/world-twenty20-2010/engine/match/412703.html|archive-date=19 May 2010|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nEngland then hosted Australia in a [[Australian cricket team in England in 2010|five-match ODI series]]. In the first game, Morgan scored an unbeaten 103 off 85 balls at the [[The Rose Bowl (cricket ground)|Rose Bowl]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cricinfo.com/england-v-australia-2010/content/current/story/464269.html|title=England cruise home on Morgan ton|publisher=CricInfo|date=22 June 2010|access-date=23 June 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100626000542/http://www.cricinfo.com/england-v-australia-2010/content/current/story/464269.html|archive-date=26 June 2010|url-status=live}}</ref> and followed it up with a half-century in the second, with England winning both matches. England won the series with two games to spare, although they lost both dead rubbers, and Morgan was named Player of the Series.\n\nOn the back of his one-day success, he was then included in England's Test squad for the [[Bangladesh cricket team in England in 2010|home series against Bangladesh]]. With [[Paul Collingwood]] rested, he made his debut in the first Test at [[Lord's]] on 27 May 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cricinfo.com/england-v-bangladesh-2010/content/story/461080.html|title=Morgan Debuts in International Test Cricket against Bangladesh at Lords|date=31 May 2010|access-date=27 May 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100530064058/http://www.cricinfo.com/england-v-bangladesh-2010/content/story/461080.html|archive-date=30 May 2010|url-status=live}}</ref> He scored 44 runs in the first innings but was not required in the second innings as England won by eight wickets after making Bangladesh [[follow-on]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/england/8714520.stm|title=England beat Bangladesh by eight wickets in first Test |publisher=BBC Sport|date=31 May 2010}}</ref> In the second Test, he scored 37 runs as England won by an innings and 80 runs.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/england/8724493.stm|title=Ruthless England seal innings win against Bangladesh |publisher=BBC Sport|date=6 June 2010}}</ref>\n\nAn injury to [[Ian Bell]] saw Morgan retained for the Test series against [[Pakistan cricket team in England in 2010|Pakistan]]. In the first Test at [[Trent Bridge]], he scored a century as England won by 354 runs. He was only needed to bat once in the next match, where he made 6 runs as England took a 2\u20130 lead in the series. In the third match he made scores of 17 and 5, as England won to go 3\u20130 up in the series. Morgan was out for a duck in his only innings in the final match of the series, but England still won 4\u20130. In the first ODI he made 13 runs. In the third ODI he made an impressive 61, although England lost the match by 23 runs. In the final match of the series he scored 107 not out to help England win by 121 runs.\n\n===2011 Australia and World Cup===\n\nMorgan did not perform well during the ODI series with Australia. His top score of the series came in the third match between the two sides, where he made 30. He made 24 in the next match to help England win by 21 runs. In the fifth ODI he made just two as Australia won the match by 51 runs. The sixth match of the series saw Morgan make 21 from just 13 balls, but it was not enough to prevent another an England defeat, this time by two wickets.\n\nMorgan was not initially named in England's squad for the [[2011 Cricket World Cup|2011 World Cup]] as he was suffering from a fractured finger,<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/icc_cricket_worldcup2011/content/story/499951.html |title=Morgan to miss World Cup with fractured finger |publisher=ESPN Cricinfo |date=8 February 2011 |accessdate=11 July 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111027053642/http://www.espncricinfo.com/icc_cricket_worldcup2011/content/story/499951.html |archive-date=27 October 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref> but was later called up following an injury to Kevin Pietersen.<ref>{{citation |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/9416748.stm |title=Kevin Pietersen v Eoin Morgan |publisher=BBC Sport |date=7 March 2011 |accessdate=11 July 2011}}</ref> On 11 March 2011 he made his World Cup debut for England, scoring 63 runs in the defeat to [[Bangladesh national cricket team|Bangladesh]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/england/9421100.stm|title=BBC Sport - Cricket - Cricket World Cup: Bangladesh rally to shock England|publisher=}}</ref> making him only the fourth player to have represented two different nations at the Cricket World Cup.<ref>[http://www.espncricinfo.com/icc_cricket_worldcup2011/content/story/505040.html Morgan ready to step into the breach] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110313081202/http://www.espncricinfo.com/icc_cricket_worldcup2011/content/story/505040.html |date=13 March 2011 }} \u2013 ESPN Cricinfo, 9 March 2011</ref> He made 7 in the next match against the West Indies as England qualified for the Quarter Finals. However, they lost to Sri Lanka by ten wickets, although Morgan made 50 off 66 balls.\n\n===2011 India and Sri Lanka===\n\n[[File:Eoin Morgan batting, July 2011.ogv|thumb|left|300px|Eoin Morgan batting in July 2011 in the 5th ODI against Sri Lanka. He scored 57&nbsp;runs from 60&nbsp;balls.]]\nThe retirement of Paul Collingwood from Test cricket opened up a place in England's batting order. Morgan and [[Ravi Bopara]] were the leading contenders for the position; while Bopara stayed in England to play county cricket, Morgan chose to play in the IPL for six weeks.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/england-v-sri-lanka-2011/content/story/514647.html |title=Morgan and Bopara face Test shootout |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=11 May 2011 |accessdate=19 June 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110514151925/http://www.espncricinfo.com/england-v-sri-lanka-2011/content/story/514647.html |archive-date=14 May 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref> In nine innings for Kolkata Knight Riders Morgan scored 137&nbsp;runs with a highest score of 66.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/england/content/story/515930.html |title=Morgan set to return to IPL |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=20 May 2011 |accessdate=19 June 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110523125746/http://www.espncricinfo.com/england/content/story/515930.html |archive-date=23 May 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref> His first first-class innings of the English season was in a match for the England Lions against the touring Sri Lankans alongside batsmen competing to the vacant place in England's batting line up.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/england-v-sri-lanka-2011/content/story/515841.html |title=Calm Morgan returns in style |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |author=Andrew McGlashan |date=19 May 2011 |accessdate=19 June 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110522173050/http://www.espncricinfo.com/england-v-sri-lanka-2011/content/story/515841.html |archive-date=22 May 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref> He scored 193 and according to the national selector it was enough to secure his selection for the squad to face Sri Lanka in first Test [[Sri Lankan cricket team in England in 2011|against Sri Lanka in May]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/england-v-sri-lanka-2011/content/story/516171.html |title=Morgan wins selection race |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |author=Andrew McGlashan |date=22 May 2011 |accessdate=19 June 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110525100952/http://www.espncricinfo.com/england-v-sri-lanka-2011/content/story/516171.html |archive-date=25 May 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nEngland won the three-match series 1\u20130, with Morgan scoring 168&nbsp;runs from four innings including two half-centuries.<ref>{{citation |url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/batting/most_runs_career.html?id=6109;type=series |title=Records / Sri Lanka in England Test Series, 2011 / Most runs |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=16 July 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110728124005/http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/batting/most_runs_career.html?id=6109;type=series |archive-date=28 July 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref> [[Stuart Broad]] replaced Collingwood as T20I captain in June, and Morgan was named as vice-captain in the format.<ref>{{citation |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/13882279.stm |title=Eoin Morgan named England Twenty20 vice-captain |publisher=BBC Sport |date=22 June 2011 |accessdate=11 July 2011}}</ref> England also won the five-match ODI series 3\u20132,<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/england-v-sri-lanka-2011/content/story/522477.html |title=Six points to ponder for England |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |first=Andrew |last=McGlashan |date=9 July 2011 |accessdate=16 July 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110713153207/http://www.espncricinfo.com/england-v-sri-lanka-2011/content/story/522477.html |archive-date=13 July 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref> with Morgan scoring 158&nbsp;runs including another two half-centuries.<ref>{{citation |url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/batting/most_runs_career.html?id=6111;type=series |title=Records / NatWest Series [Sri Lanka in England], 2011 / Most runs |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=16 July 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110712220301/http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/batting/most_runs_career.html?id=6111;type=series |archive-date=12 July 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref> His performance in the series saw Morgan move up one place in the ICC's ODI rankings to 23rd.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/england-v-sri-lanka-2011/content/story/522543.html |title=Swann crowned world No. 1 ODI bowler |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=10 July 2011 |accessdate=16 July 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110714081230/http://www.espncricinfo.com/england-v-sri-lanka-2011/content/story/522543.html |archive-date=14 July 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nMorgan retained his place when [[India cricket team|India]] toured England later that summer for four Tests. In the first three innings Morgan managed just 19&nbsp;runs, including two ducks<ref>{{citation |url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/302/302314.html |title=f53294 t2000 England v India: India in England 2011 (1st Test) |publisher=CricketArchive |accessdate=23 August 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121109002727/http://www.cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/302/302314.html |archive-date=9 November 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"India 2011, 2nd Test\">{{citation |url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/302/302315.html |title=f53303 t2001 England v India: India in England 2011 (2nd Test) |publisher=CricketArchive |accessdate=23 August 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120409213245/http://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/302/302315.html |archive-date=9 April 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> however in the second innings of the second Test Morgan partnered Matt Prior as the two scored rapid half-centuries against a struggling Indian bowling attack.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/england-v-india-2011/content/story/525427.html |title=England's batsmen flatten India on 417-run day |first=George |last=Binoy |publisher=Cricinfo |date=31 July 2011 |accessdate=23 August 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110925233224/http://www.espncricinfo.com/england-v-india-2011/content/story/525427.html |archive-date=25 September 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref> England won the match by 319&nbsp;runs.<ref name=\"India 2011, 2nd Test\"/> An injury to [[Jonathan Trott]] meant that Ravi Bopara, with whom Morgan had been competing for a place earlier that summer, was called into the side.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/england-v-india-2011/content/story/527409.html |title=Tremlett available but Trott still injured |publisher=Cricinfo |date=14 August 2011 |accessdate=23 August 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121113144738/http://www.espncricinfo.com/england-v-india-2011/content/story/527409.html |archive-date=13 November 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> Whereas Bopara scored just seven runs in the third Test, Morgan scored his second Test century as England amassed 710/7 declared.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/england-v-india-2011/content/story/527409.html |title=Cook's epic sets up victory push |publisher=Cricinfo |first=Andrew |last=McGlashan |date=14 August 2011 |accessdate=23 August 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121113144738/http://www.espncricinfo.com/england-v-india-2011/content/story/527409.html |archive-date=13 November 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> England won the Test series 4\u20130 and in the process replaced India as the number&nbsp;1 ranked Test team in the world.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/england-v-india-2011/content/story/527348.html |title=England dethrone India to become No.1 |work=Cricinfo |date=13 August 2011 |accessdate=23 August 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111230075028/http://www.espncricinfo.com/england-v-india-2011/content/story/527348.html |archive-date=30 December 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/england-v-india-2011/content/story/529033.html |title=Swann's six completes India's humiliation |first=Andrew |last=McGlashan |date=22 August 2011 |accessdate=22 August 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111002081922/http://www.espncricinfo.com/england-v-india-2011/content/story/529033.html |archive-date=2 October 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref> Morgan's 194&nbsp;runs in the series came at an average of 32.33.<ref>{{citation |url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/batting/most_runs_career.html?id=6112;type=series |title=Records / Pataudi Trophy, 2011 / Most runs |publisher=Cricinfo |accessdate=23 August 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110924043610/http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/batting/most_runs_career.html?id=6112%3Btype%3Dseries |archivedate=24 September 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nAfter the series win against India, Cook was rested for England's one-off ODI against Ireland and Morgan handed the captaincy for the fixture,<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/ireland/content/story/529394.html |title=Morgan takes reins against old allies |first=Andrew |last=McGlashan |publisher=Cricinfo |date=24 August 2011 |accessdate=13 September 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110927235153/http://www.espncricinfo.com/ireland/content/story/529394.html |archive-date=27 September 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref> becoming only the third Irish man to lead England.{{refn|The other two were [[Sir Tim O'Brien, 3rd Baronet|Timothy O'Brien]] and [[Frederick Fane]].<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/sport/2011/0822/1224302805126.html |title=Morgan to lead England in Clontarf |newspaper=[[Irish Times]] |first=Emmet |last=Riordan |date=22 August 2011 |accessdate=2011-08-23 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110822055937/http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/sport/2011/0822/1224302805126.html |archive-date=22 August 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref>|group=nb}} An innings of 59 from Morgan shepherded his inexperienced team, which featured three debutantes, to victory and secured him the Man-of-the-Match award.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/ireland/content/story/529537.html |title=England have the better of brief Irish sojourn |first=Andrew |last=McGlashan |publisher=Cricinfo |date=25 August 2011 |accessdate=13 September 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111103210349/http://www.espncricinfo.com/ireland/content/story/529537.html |archive-date=3 November 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref> During a T20I against India in late August, Morgan's shoulder became acutely painful. He underwent surgery and missed the home and away ODI series against India.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/india-v-england-2011/content/story/531784.html |title=Morgan to miss India tour for surgery |publisher=Cricinfo |date=9 September 2011 |accessdate=13 September 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110925144753/http://www.espncricinfo.com/india-v-england-2011/content/story/531784.html |archive-date=25 September 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref> Mitigating this disappointment, in September Morgan was awarded a central contract for the first time by the [[England and Wales Cricket Board]] (ECB).<ref>{{citation |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/14899602.stm |title=Tim Bresnan, Eoin Morgan and Chris Tremlett given ECB contracts |publisher=BBC Sport |date=13 September 2011 |accessdate=13 September 2011}}</ref>\n\n===2012 Pakistan and West Indies===\n\nMorgan recovered from his shoulder injury to participate in England's [[Pakistani cricket team vs England in the UAE in 2011\u201312|series against Pakistan in the UAE]] from January to February 2012. England lost the Test series 3\u20130 with their batsmen struggling to cope against Pakistan's spin bowlers. Morgan made scores of 24 and 14 in the first Test. It was in the second Test where he came under increased pressure, scoring just 3 runs in the entire match after being dismissed for a duck in the second innings. His top score of the series came in his final innings of the tour, where he made 31.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/pakistan-v-england-2012/content/story/552359.html |title=England spun to record low |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |first=Madhusudhan |last=Ramakrishnan |date=6 February 2012 |accessdate=28 February 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120209092920/http://www.espncricinfo.com/pakistan-v-england-2012/content/story/552359.html |archive-date=9 February 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> Morgan, Pietersen, and Bell played in all three matches and each scored fewer than 90&nbsp;runs in the series.<ref>{{citation |url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/batting/most_runs_career.html?id=6859;type=series |title=Records / Pakistan v England Test Series, 2011/12 / Most runs |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=28 February 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120213064140/http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/batting/most_runs_career.html?id=6859%3Btype%3Dseries |archivedate=13 February 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Coach [[Andy Flower]] commented that Morgan had struggled during the tour of the UAE, and the batsman was dropped from England's Test squad to [[English cricket team in Sri Lanka in 2011\u201312|tour Sri Lanka]] in March.<ref>{{citation |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/cricket/17186695 |title=Eoin Morgan dropped by England for Test series in Sri Lanka |publisher=BBC Sport |date=28 February 2012 |accessdate=28 February 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120228071948/http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/cricket/17186695 |archive-date=28 February 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nAlthough he was omitted from the Test side, Morgan remained a key figure in the limited overs formats. He made 21 in the first ODI against the West Indies, although he did not bat in the second match. He also only played a small part in the T20 match between the two sides, as he made 2 at the back end of England's innings.\n\n===2012 Australia and South Africa===\n{{BLP unsourced section|date=March 2017}}\n\nHe made 89 not out in the first ODI against Australia to help England win the match by 15 runs. He followed this up by making an unbeaten 43 in the second ODI, and did not have to bat in the fourth match of the series as England won by eight wickets. He made nine not out in the final match of the series to help England over the line and secure a seven wicket victory.\n\nHe was seen as one of contender to replace Kevin Pietersen, who was not selected for the Test team following reports of him texting South Africans players,  but selectors chose [[James Taylor (cricketer, born 1990)|James Taylor]]. He still played a big part in the limited overs series. He scored 27 as England made 207 in the first ODI, losing by 80 runs. In the second match he made an impressive 73 as England levelled the series. He made 36 not out in the next match as England took a lead in the series. However, Morgan was out for a duck in the final match as England lost by 7 wickets. He was not effective with the bat in the T20 series, scoring just 15 runs in the series, although this was partly due to him having limited time at the crease.\n\nIn the World T20, Morgan was seen as a vital player who would have to perform if England were to do well. He made 27 in their opening win against Afghanistan but was out for 2 as England were thrashed by India, but still qualified in second place. He hit 71 runs of just 36 against the West Indies in the first match of the Super Eight stage. Despite his efforts, England still lost by 15 runs. He hit 30 against New Zealand as England won to keep their hopes of qualification alive. However, England lost to Sri Lanka by seven wickets meaning that their hopes of progressing were over as they were knocked out of the competition.\n\n===2013 India and New Zealand===\n{{BLP unsourced section|date=June 2017}}\nIn 2013, Morgan captained the T20I team against India in the absences of Stuart Broad, who was out injured. He only made 5 in the first game but made an unbeaten 49 in the second as England won by 5 wickets to level the series. Morgan was praised for captaincy and many pundits suggested he would lead England on a permanent basis in the future.\n\nMorgan was selected for the One Day series against India at the beginning of 2013. He made 41 from 38 balls in the first match, as England won by 9 runs. He suffered poor form as England lost the next three games, his scores including 10 and a duck. However, he returned to form for the final match of the series where he hit an unbeaten 40 as he guided England to an impressive 7 wicket win. Although England lost the series 3\u20132, it was seen as an improvement given their recent poor performances in ODIs in India.\n\nIn the first T20I match against New Zealand, he helped England set 214 after he smashed 46 off just 26 balls as England won the match by 40 runs. In contrast, he only made 13 from 22 deliveries in the next match as England lost by 55 runs. The series decider was rained off. He started the ODI Series in poor fashion, making just 1 in their opening defeat. He did not bat in the next game as England levelled the series at 1\u20131. He helped England win the decider, hitting 39 off 24 balls to help set up a 5 wicket win. He made just 6 in the first match of the return series, before making 21 in the second. England lost this game by 86 runs after New Zealand scored 359. He made 28 in the final game as England won by 34 runs. He made seven in the only T20 International, as England lost the one off game by 5 runs.\n\n===2013 Champions Trophy and Australia===\nMorgan had an unproductive start to the [[2013 ICC Champions Trophy]], making a score of 8 against Australia,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/match/578616.html |title=2013 ICC Champions Trophy Australia v England |accessdate=13 March 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170717234609/http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/match/578616.html |archive-date=17 July 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> then 13 against Sri Lanka.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/match/578621.html |title=2013 ICC Champions Trophy England v Sri Lanka |accessdate=13 March 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160423103010/http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/match/578621.html |archive-date=23 April 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref> With England needing to beat New Zealand to qualify from their group, Morgan made 15 to help England secure a victory.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/match/578624.html |title=2013 ICC Champions Trophy New Zealand v England |accessdate=13 March 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170705085618/http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/match/578624.html |archive-date=5 July 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> In the semi final against South Africa, he made an unbeaten 15 to help guide England to victory and reach the final against India.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/match/566946.html |title=2013 ICC Champions Trophy South Africa v England semifinal |accessdate=13 March 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170715043947/http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/match/566946.html |archive-date=15 July 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> He made 33 in the final, which turned out to be a low scoring affair, but could not get England over the line as they finished the tournament as runners up.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/match/566948.html |title=2013 ICC Champions Trophy India v England final |accessdate=13 March 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170715003901/http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/match/566948.html |archive-date=15 July 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nHe was named as the captain for ODI series against Ireland and Australia. He won the one-off match against Ireland where he scored his career best, an unbeaten 124, along with Ravi Bopara who also scored a maiden century after Ireland scored 269 and English team of was reduced to 48 for 4. He was consistent against the series against Australia where he led by example as captain even though his team lost 2\u20131 in series. He scored 54, 5 not out, 53 and 30 in ODIs and in T20Is he scored a duck and 20.\n\nHe joined up with the England squad in Australia after they had lost the Ashes 5\u20130, meaning morale was low. In the first ODI, he made 50 off 47 balls, but England went on to lose by 5 wickets. He made a century in the next match, but England were unable to close the game and lost by a single wicket. Morgan made yet another 50 in the third match, but they lost the game to go 3\u20130 down in the series. He hit 33 in the next match as England won their first game of the tour, but lost again in the final game where Morgan made 39. He did not take his impressive ODI form into the T20I series, where he scored just 10 runs in the first two matches. However, he top scored with 34 in the final match, as England were bowled out for 111 to end a miserable tour.\n\n===2014 West Indies and T20 World Cup===\n\nIn the warm up to the T20 World Cup, England embarked on a limited-overs tour of the West Indies. Morgan failed to make a big impact on the T20 series between the two team, making just 19 in the first match as England lost by 27 runs. He made just three as England lost the next match by five wickets. In the final match of the series he made 18 to help England win the match, although they lost the series 2\u20131.\n\nIn the T20 World Cup, England lost their first game to New Zealand, with Morgan making just 12. However, they secured an unlikely victory in the next game against Sri Lanka with Morgan hitting 57 and batting well alongside [[Alex Hales]] to help England chase down a large Sri Lankan score and keep their hopes of winning the tournament alive. The pair set a new record for the highest 3rd wicket partnership in T20 World Cup history (152).<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/fow/highest_partnerships_by_wicket.html?id=89;type=trophy|title=Cricket Records {{!}} Records {{!}} World T20 {{!}} Highest partnerships by wicket {{!}} ESPN Cricinfo|work=Cricinfo|access-date=2017-04-19|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170411221922/http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/fow/highest_partnerships_by_wicket.html?id=89%3Btype%3Dtrophy|archivedate=11 April 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/match/682939.html|title=22nd Match, Group 1: England v Sri Lanka at Chittagong, Mar 27, 2014 {{!}} Cricket Scorecard {{!}} ESPN Cricinfo|work=Cricinfo|access-date=2017-04-19|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160710115932/http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/match/682939.html|archive-date=10 July 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> However, they lost their next game to South Africa, with Morgan scoring just six to end their hopes of qualifying. In the final game of the tournament they suffered a humiliating defeat to the Netherlands, with Morgan scoring just six.\n\n===2014 Sri Lanka and India===\n\nIn the ODI series against Sri Lanka, Morgan made 3 in the first match. He top scored with 40 in the next game as England were bowled out for 99 to allow Sri Lanka to level the series. He was not needed to bat in the third match as England secured a big win to retake the lead in the series. Morgan only made 12 in the next match as Sri Lanka won by seven runs to level the series once more. In the final match of the series he made 17 as England lost the game and the series 3\u20132.\n\nAfter the first game against India was rained off, Morgan made 28 in the second match as England lost to go 1\u20130 down in the series. He made 10 in the next match as India secured another win, this time by six wickets. He made 32 in the next match as England suffered a humiliating nine wicket defeat. The manner of the lead to questions over the personnel in the team, and the pressure increased on captain Alastair Cook. Despite this, England won the final match of the series, although Morgan again failed to make a big score, being dismissed for 14. In the only T20 match between the two sides, Morgan hit 71 from just 31 balls in an innings that included seven sixes. England won the match by three runs and Morgan was named man of the match.\n\nIn the return series in Sri Lanka, Morgan endured a poor time. He scored just 19 runs in the first three games as England went 2-1 down in the series. In the fourth game, Alastair Cook was suspended due to a slow over rate in the previous game, and so Morgan took over as captain. He made 62, his only fifty of the tour, although England still went on to lose the game. In the next game Morgan could only make and he was dismissed for a duck in the penultimate game of the series as Sri Lanka secured a series victory. In the final match Morgan again failed to make an impression, this time making just four runs as England suffered another defeat.\n\nOn 19 December 2014, 2 months before the [[2015 ICC Cricket World Cup]], it was announced that Cook had been removed as one-day captain due to poor form, and replaced by Eoin Morgan.<ref>{{cite news |title=Irishman to add bite to England campaign |work=[[Sydney Morning Herald]] |date=3 January 2015 |page=52 |accessdate=26 September 2017 |last=Lane |first=Daniel |url=http://link.galegroup.com/apps/doc/A395695497/GPS?sid=wikipedia}}{{subscription required|via=[[Academic OneFile]]}}</ref><ref name=\"BBC Sport\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/cricket/30555167|title=Alastair Cook removed as England one-day captain|publisher=BBC Sport|date=19 December 2014|accessdate=19 December 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141219214739/http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/cricket/30555167|archive-date=19 December 2014|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nHe was named in the T20I XI of the year 2014 by Cricbuzz.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cricbuzz.com/cricket-news/67711/t20i-team-of-the-year|title=2014 review: T20I team of the year|work=Cricbuzz|accessdate=25 July 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190725173545/https://www.cricbuzz.com/cricket-news/67711/t20i-team-of-the-year|archive-date=25 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===2015 Tri-Series and 2015 ICC Cricket World Cup===\nFollowing his appointment as captain, Morgan's first series as skipper was a tournament contested by India, Australia and England. Morgan promised a more aggressive approach as captain and said England would be a more dynamic team. However, they suffered a loss in his first match leading the side against Australia. Morgan himself made an impressive 121 but it was not enough as the rest of England's batsmen struggled. Morgan was not needed to bat in the next match as England secured a comfortable win over India, Morgan's first as permanent captain. He again suffered defeat against Australia in the next game, being dismissed for a duck. England beat India again in the next game to qualify for the final, but Morgan was again unimpressive, making just two. England lost the final to Australia, with Morgan being dismissed for a duck again.\n\nMorgan's poor form continued into the World Cup, where he only scored 90 runs in five innings.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/icc-cricket-world-cup-2015/engine/records/averages/batting_bowling_by_team.html?id=6537;team=1;type=tournament|title=Cricket Records - ICC Cricket World Cup, 2014/15 - England - Records - Batting and bowling averages - ESPN Cricinfo|work=Cricinfo|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150307205343/http://stats.espncricinfo.com/icc-cricket-world-cup-2015/engine/records/averages/batting_bowling_by_team.html?id=6537%3Bteam%3D1%3Btype%3Dtournament|archivedate=7 March 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref> His tournament started badly as he was dismissed for a duck in England's opening game against Australia. He made 17 in the next match against New Zealand as England slumped to a humiliating eight wicket defeat. He made 46 against Scotland as England won their first match of the tournament, and made 27 in England's nine wicket defeat against Sri Lanka. He was out for yet another duck in England's must win game against Bangladesh, meaning they exited the tournament. They won their final match against Afghanistan, with Morgan not be required to bat. This meant that England managed to win only 2 out of 6 games in the tournament under Morgan's captaincy, both victories came against much lower ranked teams Afghanistan and Scotland.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/icc-cricket-world-cup-2015/engine/series/509587.html?view=pointstable|title=Points Table - ICC Cricket World Cup 2015 - ESPN Cricinfo|work=Cricinfo|access-date=13 March 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150313214119/http://www.espncricinfo.com/icc-cricket-world-cup-2015/engine/series/509587.html?view=pointstable|archive-date=13 March 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===2015 New Zealand===\nMorgan continued in his role as ODI captain in the five-game series at home against New Zealand. The series began with a dominant performance by England, winning by 210 runs, Morgan contributing 50. The following match was a much more close-run affair, with New Zealand clinching the match by 13 runs (D/L method). Morgan performed strongly with the bat and scoring 88 off only 47 balls. New Zealand were victorious again in the third match, winning by 3 wickets with an over remaining. Morgan scored 71 in England's innings. In the fourth ODI, Morgan scored 113 from 82 balls, which helped England win the match by 7 wickets, a performance which earned him the Man of the Match award. In the final match of the series he was out for a duck, but England went on to win the game and the series 3\u20132. In the one off T20 match between the two sides, Morgan made 4 as England went on to win the game.\n\n===2015 Australia===\nIn the T20 against Australia, Morgan put in a strong performance, scoring 74 to send England on their way to a narrow victory. In the first ODI between the two sides, Morgan scored 38 but England went on to lose the match. England were also defeated in the second match, although Morgan impressed, scoring 85. Morgan scored another half century in the next match, making 62, as England won their first game of the series. England levelled the series in the next match, with Morgan hitting 92 to send England on their way to victory. The final match of the series between the two sides ended with Australia claiming an eight wicket victory, with Morgan being forced to retire hurt.\n\n===2015-16 Pakistan and South Africa===\nMorgan made 76 in a losing cause in the first game of the ODI series against Pakistan. However, England went on to win the next three games to win the series 3-1. Morgan did not make a significant contribution with the bat in any of the victories, making scores of 29, 35 and 14. Despite this, he was praised for his captaincy and the amount of improvement that had been seen in the England side since the disappointing World Cup campaign. Morgan made a score of 45 in the first T20I against Pakistan. After making 15 in the next match, Morgan rested himself for the final match of the series, with Jos Buttler replacing him as captain. England won the series 3-0.\n\nMorgan had a poor series against South Africa. He made scores of 23 and 29 in the first two games of the tournament, as England won both to take a 2-0 series lead. However, after these matches his own performances and that of the teams declined and Morgan failed to make double figures in the final three games of the series, being dismissed for scores of 8, 2 and 2 as South Africa won the final three games to take the series 3-2. Morgan played in both T20Is against South Africa, making scores of 10 and 38, although England lost both games to make it five defeats in a row.\n\n===2016 World T20===\nMorgan made 27 in the opening match of the T20 World Cup against West Indies, as England lost their opening group game. In the next match against South Africa, England completed a historic chase of 230, although Morgan himself only made 12. He followed this up with a duck against Afghanistan, although England recovered to win the game. After making 22 against Sri Lanka as England won to qualify for the semi-finals, Morgan was out for a first ball duck against New Zealand, although England won the match comfortably, winning by seven wickets. England lost the final against the West Indies, with Morgan making just five.\n\n===2016 Sri Lanka and Pakistan===\nMorgan made 43 in the first ODI to help England tie the match after matching Sri Lanka's total of 286. He did not bat in the second match as England won the match by ten wickets. In the third match, he again did not bat as the match was abandoned due to rain early in England's reply to Sri Lanka's 248/9. He made 22 in the fourth match to help England win by six wickets, and he made 20 in the final match of the series as England scored 324 to win by 122 runs. In the only T20I between the sides, he made an unbeaten 47 and hit the winning runs as England won by eight wickets.\n\nMorgan made an unbeaten 33 in the first ODI against Pakistan, as England won by 44 runs on the D/L Method. He scored 68 in the second match as England chased down Pakistan's total of 251 to win by four wickets. He scored an unbeaten 57 in the third ODI as England set a world record total of 444/3 and won the match by 169 runs. He scored 11 in the fourth match as England won again to go 4-0 up. However, in the final match Morgan only made ten as England lost by four wickets, although they won the series 4-1. In the only T20I between the two sides, Morgan made 14 as England scored 135/7 and went on to lose the match by nine wickets.\n\n===2017 India===\nMorgan made 28 in the first ODI against India, which England lost by three wickets. He made 102 in the second match as England fell short of India's target to lose by 15 runs. He made 43 in the next match as England won by five runs, although they lost the series 2-1. He made 51 in the first T20I as England won the match by seven wickets. He made 17 in the next match although England lost the match by five runs as India levelled the series. In the third T20I he made 40, but England collapsed and lost the match by 75 runs.\n\n===2017 West Indies===\nMorgan made 107 in the first ODI against the West Indies to help England to 296-6 and they won the game by 45 runs. With this century, which is the fifth as a captain, Morgan became the highest century maker for England as a captain, bettered previous record of 4 ODI centuries each by [[Alastair Cook]] and [[Andrew Strauss]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/west-indies-v-england-2016-17/content/story/1085073.html |title=Morgan ton, seamers seal England win |accessdate=3 March 2017 |work=ESPN Cricinfo |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170304050517/http://www.espncricinfo.com/west-indies-v-england-2016-17/content/story/1085073.html |archive-date=4 March 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> In the second match he made seven as England secured a four wicket victory. In the final match of the series he made 11 as England made 328 and won by 186 runs to win the series 3-0.\n\n===2018===\n[[File:2018.01.21.17.03.33-Eoin Morgan out (39081508940).jpg|thumb|right|Morgan in January 2018]]\nIn March 2018, the ICC named Morgan as the captain of a [[World XI (cricket)|World XI team]] to play a [[West Indies v ICC World XI in England in 2018|one-off T20I fixture]] against the West Indies at [[Lord's]] in May 2018.<ref name=\"WorldXI\">{{cite web |url=https://www.icc-cricket.com/media-releases/649555 |title=Eoin Morgan to captain ICC World XI against Windies |accessdate=22 March 2018 |work=International Cricket Council |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180322204719/https://www.icc-cricket.com/media-releases/649555 |archive-date=22 March 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> He had to withdraw from the team because of a broken finger.<ref>{{cite web |title=Shahid Afridi set to lead World XI after Eoin Morgan pulls out |url=https://www.icc-cricket.com/news/694523 |website=International Cricket Council |publisher=ICC |accessdate=11 June 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180530035641/https://www.icc-cricket.com/news/694523 |archive-date=30 May 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> On 10 June, he captained England when they lost to Scotland by six runs, at [[The Grange Club]] in Edinburgh.<ref>{{cite web |title=Eoin Morgan: 'England not finished article after Scotland defeat' |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/cricket/44432883 |website=BBC Sport |publisher=BBC |accessdate=11 June 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180617091939/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/cricket/44432883 |archive-date=17 June 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn 19 June 2018, during the third match of [[Australian cricket team in England in 2018|the home ODI series against Australia]], Morgan surpassed the record of [[Ian Bell]] as the all-time leading run scorer for England in One Day International matches. In the same match England posted the highest ever ODI total of 481/6,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.express.co.uk/sport/cricket/976551/England-cricket-Australia-Alex-Hales-Eoin-Morgan-Jonny-Bairstow|title=England cricketers run RIOT: Alex Hales, Eoin Morgan send records tumbling at Trent Bridge|last=Wilson|first=Jack|date=2018-06-19|work=Express.co.uk|access-date=19 June 2018|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180620001011/https://www.express.co.uk/sport/cricket/976551/England-cricket-Australia-Alex-Hales-Eoin-Morgan-Jonny-Bairstow|archive-date=20 June 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> with Morgan breaking another record: that held by [[Jos Buttler]] for the fastest ever fifty by an Englishman in ODIs. (21 balls)<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/cricket/44539728|title=England v Australia: Hosts make record 481-6 in third ODI|last=|first=|date=2018-06-19|work=BBC Sport|access-date=19 June 2018|language=en-GB|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180619172803/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/cricket/44539728|archive-date=19 June 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===2019 Cricket World Cup===\nIn April 2019, he was named as the captain of [[2019 Cricket World Cup squads#England|England's squad]] for the [[2019 Cricket World Cup]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/content/story/1181187.html |title=Jofra Archer misses World Cup cut but included to play Ireland, Pakistan |work=ESPN Cricinfo |accessdate=17 April 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190417102319/http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/content/story/1181187.html |archive-date=17 April 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.icc-cricket.com/news/1183273 |title=England leave out Jofra Archer from World Cup squad |work=International Cricket Council |accessdate=17 April 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190417102319/https://www.icc-cricket.com/news/1183273 |archive-date=17 April 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> In the opening match of the World Cup, against [[South Africa national cricket team|South Africa]], Morgan played in his 200th ODI match for England,<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2019/may/29/eoin-morgan-low-key-england-world-cup-south-africa |title=Eoin Morgan warns England against \u2018blind belief\u2019 as World Cup bid begins |work=The Guardian |accessdate=30 May 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190529224140/https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2019/may/29/eoin-morgan-low-key-england-world-cup-south-africa |archive-date=29 May 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> and scored his 7,000th run in ODIs.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.latestly.com/sports/cricket/eoin-morgan-completes-7000-odi-runs-in-eng-vs-sa-icc-cricket-world-cup-2019-match-at-the-oval-887582.html |title=Eoin Morgan Completes 7000 ODI Runs in ENG vs SA ICC Cricket World Cup 2019 Match at The Oval |work=LatestLY |accessdate=30 May 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190530113722/https://www.latestly.com/sports/cricket/eoin-morgan-completes-7000-odi-runs-in-eng-vs-sa-icc-cricket-world-cup-2019-match-at-the-oval-887582.html |archive-date=30 May 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> On 14 June 2019, in the match against the [[West Indies cricket team|West Indies]], Morgan played in his 300th international match for England.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://cricketaddictor.com/cricket/icc-cricket-world-cup-2019-match-19-england-vs-windies-stats-preview/ |title=ICC Cricket World Cup 2019 (Match 19): England vs Windies \u2013 Stats Preview |work=Cricket Addictor |accessdate=14 June 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190616082623/https://cricketaddictor.com/cricket/icc-cricket-world-cup-2019-match-19-england-vs-windies-stats-preview/ |archive-date=16 June 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn 18 June 2019, in the match against Afghanistan at Old Trafford, Morgan scored 148 from 71 balls. His innings included 17 sixes, the [[List of One Day International cricket records#Most sixes in an innings 2|most sixes by an individual in an ODI innings]]; his team scored 25 sixes in total, the [[List of One Day International cricket records#Most sixes in an innings|most sixes by a team in an ODI innings]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.sportinglife.com/cricket/news/morgan-makes-history-with-17-sixes/167907 |title=Eoin Morgan makes 148 off 71 balls including 17 sixes - a new ODI record |work=Sporting Life |accessdate=18 June 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190618130521/https://www.sportinglife.com/cricket/news/morgan-makes-history-with-17-sixes/167907 |archive-date=18 June 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Morgan's century came from 57 balls, the fastest by an England batsman in a Cricket World Cup match.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://metro.co.uk/2019/06/18/eoin-morgan-england-set-world-records-afghanistan-cricket-world-cup-clash-10002339/ |title=Eoin Morgan and England set world records in Afghanistan World Cup demolition |work=Metro |accessdate=18 June 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190619163221/https://metro.co.uk/2019/06/18/eoin-morgan-england-set-world-records-afghanistan-cricket-world-cup-clash-10002339/ |archive-date=19 June 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> On 21 June 2019, in the match against [[Sri Lanka cricket team|Sri Lanka]], Morgan scored his 9,000th international run for England.<ref name=\"AMEM\">{{cite web |url=https://www.crictracker.com/icc-world-cup-2019-match-27-england-vs-sri-lanka-malingas-magic-roots-form-and-more-stats/ |title=ICC World Cup 2019: Match 27, England vs Sri Lanka \u2013 Malinga\u2019s magic, Root's form and more stats |work=CricTracker |accessdate=22 June 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190622082135/https://www.crictracker.com/icc-world-cup-2019-match-27-england-vs-sri-lanka-malingas-magic-roots-form-and-more-stats/ |archive-date=22 June 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn 14 July 2019, led by Morgan, England won the World Cup for the first time, beating [[New Zealand Cricket Team|New Zealand]] in the [[2019 Cricket World Cup Final|final]] on boundaries after the match and [[Super Over|super over]] were tied.\n\n==International statistics==\n{{As of|July 2019}}, Morgan has appeared in 16 Tests (all for England), 233 One Day Internationals (23 for Ireland, 210 for England) and 81 Twenty20 Internationals (all for England). He has scored 700 runs in Tests, 7348 in ODIs and 1810 in T20Is.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/player/24598.html?class=11;template=results;type=batting|title=Batting records {{!}} Combined Test, ODI and T20I records {{!}} Cricinfo Statsguru {{!}} ESPNcricinfo.com|website=Cricinfo|access-date=2019-02-18|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190219020414/http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/player/24598.html?class=11;template=results;type=batting|archive-date=19 February 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n{|class=wikitable style=\"font-size:100%\"\n|-\n!colspan=\"6\"|Batting\n|-\n!Format\n!Country!!Matches!!Runs!!100s!!Average\n|-\n!Test\n|England || 16 || 700 || 2 || 30.43\n|-\n!rowspan=3|ODI\n|Ireland || 23 || 744 || 1 || 35.42\n|-\n|England || 210 || 6,604 || 13 || 40.26\n|-\n!Total \n| 233 || 7,348|| 14 || 39.71\n|-\n! T20I\n| England || 77 || 1810 || 0 || 28.73\n|}\n\n==Honours==\n* [[File:Order of the British Empire (Civil) Ribbon.png|60px]] Morgan was appointed [[Commander of the Order of the British Empire]] (CBE) in the [[2020 New Year Honours]] for services to cricket.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=62866|supp=y|page=N9|date=28 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of cricketers who have played for more than one international team]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=nb}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* {{cricinfo|id=24598}}\n* [http://www.middlesexccc.com/ Middlesex County Cricket Club]\n* [http://www.eoinmorgan.net/ Personal website]\n* {{Twitter}}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{S-sports}}\n{{Succession box\n| before=[[Alastair Cook]]\n| title=[[List of England cricket captains|Acting England ODI cricket captain]]\n| years=2011\u20132014<br /><small>deputising for [[Alastair Cook]]</small>\n| after=[[Alastair Cook]]\n}}\n{{Succession box\n| before=[[Alastair Cook]]\n| title=[[List of England cricket captains|England ODI cricket captain]]\n| years=2015\u2013present\n| after=Incumbent\n}}\n{{Succession box\n| before=[[Graeme Swann]]\n| title=[[List of England cricket captains|Acting England Twenty20 captain]]\n| years=2012\u20132014<br /><small>deputising for [[Stuart Broad]]</small>\n| after=[[Stuart Broad]]\n}}\n{{Succession box\n| before=[[Stuart Broad]]\n| title=[[List of England cricket captains|England Twenty20 captain]]\n| years=2015\u2013present\n| after=Incumbent\n}}\n{{Succession box\n|  before=[[Neil Dexter]]\n|  title=[[:Category:Middlesex cricket captains|Middlesex<br>List A captain]]\n|  years=2014\u20132015 \n|  after=[[James Franklin (cricketer)|James Franklin]] \n}}\n{{Succession box|\n| before=[[Neil Dexter]] \n| title=[[:Category:Middlesex cricket captains|Middlesex Twenty20 captain]] \n| years=2014\u20132015 \n| after=[[Dawid Malan]] \n}} \n{{Succession box|\n| before=[[Dawid Malan]] \n| title=[