{"title_page": "Netherlands national cricket team", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox cricket team\n| name                  = Netherlands\n| image                 = Netherlandscricketlogo.jpg\n| alt                   = Refer to caption\n| caption               = Netherlands cricket crest\n| association           = [[Koninklijke Nederlandse Cricket Bond|Royal Dutch Cricket Board]]\n| captain               = [[Pieter Seelaar]]\n| coach                 = [[Ryan Campbell]]\n\n| icc_status            = Associate Member with ODI status\n| icc_member_year       = 1966\n| icc_region            = [[European Cricket Council|Europe]]\n\n| odi_rank              = 13th\n| t20i_rank             = 16th\n| odi_rank_best         = 12th\n| t20i_rank_best        = 11th\n\n| first_odi             = v. {{cr|NZ}} at [[IPCL Sports Complex Ground|Reliance Stadium]], [[Vadodara]]; 17 February 1996\n| most_recent_odi       = v. {{cr|ZIM}} at [[Sportpark Het Schootsveld]], [[Deventer]]; 21 June 2019\n| num_odis              = 80\n| num_odis_this_year    = 0\n| odi_record            = 31/45<br>(1 tie, 3 no result)\n| odi_record_this_year  = 0/0<br>(0 ties, 0 no result)\n\n| wc_apps               = 4\n| wc_first              = [[1996 Cricket World Cup|1996]]\n| wc_best               = Group stage<br>([[1996 Cricket World Cup|1996]], [[2003 Cricket World Cup|2003]], [[2007 Cricket World Cup|2007]], [[2011 Cricket World Cup|2011]])\n| wcq_apps              = 11\n| wcq_first             = [[1979 ICC Trophy|1979]]\n| wcq_best              = Champions ([[2001 ICC Trophy|2001]])\n\n| first_t20i            = v. {{cr|KEN}} at [[Stormont (cricket ground)|Stormont]], [[Belfast]]; 2 August 2008\n| most_recent_t20i      = v. {{cr|PNG}} at [[Dubai International Cricket Stadium]], [[Dubai]]; 2 November 2019\n| num_t20is             = 75\n| num_t20is_this_year   = 0\n| t20i_record           = 39/32<br>(1 tie, 3 no result)\n| t20i_record_this_year = 0/0<br>(1 tie, 0 no result)\n\n| wt20_apps             = 3\n| wt20_first            = [[2009 ICC World Twenty20|2009]]\n| wt20_best             = Super 10 ([[2014 ICC World Twenty20|2014]])\n| wt20q_apps            = 6\n| wt20q_first           = [[2008 ICC World Twenty20 Qualifier|2008]]\n| wt20q_best            = Champions (2008, [[2015 ICC World Twenty20 Qualifier|2015]], [[2019 ICC T20 World Cup Qualifier|2019]])\n\n| a_pattern_la          = _navyborder\n| a_pattern_b           = _navyrightsideshoulder\n| a_pattern_ra          = _orange_border\n| a_pattern_pants       = \n| a_leftarm             = FF5F00\n| a_body                = FF5F00\n| a_rightarm            = 000080\n| a_pants               = 000080\n| a_title               = ODI and T20I kit\n\n| asofdate              = 22 February 2020\n}}\nThe '''Netherlands national cricket team''' is the team that represents the [[Kingdom of the Netherlands]] and is administered by the [[Koninklijke Nederlandse Cricket Bond]] (''Royal Dutch Cricket Association'').\n\nCricket has been played in the Netherlands since at least the 19th century, and in the 1860s was considered a major sport in the country. Other sports \u2013 notably [[association football|football]] \u2013 have long since surpassed cricket in popularity amongst the Dutch, but today there are around 6,000 cricketers in the Netherlands. The first national association, the forerunner of today's Royal Dutch Cricket Association, was formed in 1883 and the Netherlands achieved Associate Membership of the [[International Cricket Council]] (ICC) in 1966.\n\nThe Netherlands have taken part in all eleven [[ICC World Cup Qualifier|ICC Trophy/World Cup Qualifier]] tournaments, winning the competition in Canada in 2001 and finishing as runners-up twice (in 1986 and 1990). The Netherlands also participated in the 1996, 2003, 2007 and 2011 [[Cricket World Cup]]s, and from 1996 onwards the national team entered the English domestic [[NatWest Trophy]] competition (and its successor, the [[C&G Trophy]]). In 2004 they played [[first-class cricket]] in the [[ICC Intercontinental Cup]], drawing with [[Scottish cricket team|Scotland]] in Aberdeen and then going down to an [[The result in cricket|innings defeat]] against [[Irish cricket team|Ireland]] in [[Deventer]].\n\nThe Netherlands enjoyed full [[One Day International]] status from 1 January 2006 until 1 February 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/content/story/714845.html |title=Netherlands, Kenya and Canada lose ODI status |publisher=[[ESPNcricinfo]] |date=1 February 2014 |accessdate=3 February 2016}}</ref> They regained [[Twenty20 International]] status in June 2014, having played their first match in this format in 2008.<ref name=\"espncricinfoci\">{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci-icc/content/story/756175.html?CMP=chrome |title=Nepal, Netherlands get T20 international status |publisher=[[ESPNcricinfo]] |date=28 June 2014 |accessdate=28 June 2014}}</ref> The Netherlands regained their ODI status after the conclusion of the [[2018 Cricket World Cup Qualifier]] in March 2018. They had guaranteed this status before the tournament as a result of winning the [[2015\u201317 ICC World Cricket League Championship]] and thus qualifying for the [[2020\u201322 ICC ODI League]], and will retain the status until the [[2022 Cricket World Cup Qualifier]].\n\nIn April 2018, the ICC decided to grant full [[Twenty20 International]] (T20I) status to all its members. Therefore, all [[Twenty20]] matches played between the Netherlands and other [[List of International Cricket Council members|ICC members]] after 1 January 2019 will be a full T20I.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.icc-cricket.com/media-releases/672322|title=All T20 matches between ICC members to get international status|work=[[International Cricket Council]]|date=26 April 2018|accessdate=1 September 2018}}</ref> [[Pieter Seelaar]] is the current team captain.<ref name=\"Apr18\">{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/story/_/id/23233670/peter-borren-calls-netherlands-career |title=Borren calls time on Netherlands career |work=ESPN Cricinfo |accessdate=18 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n===19th century===\n\nCricket was introduced to the Netherlands by British soldiers during the [[Napoleonic Wars]] in the 19th century.<ref name=\"ref1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.justlanded.com/english/netherlands/tools/articles/living_in_the_netherlands/a_little_known_fact_about_the_netherlands|title=Cricket below sea level|publisher=}}</ref> Further clubs came into existence in the 1870s. The Netherlands national team played their first game in 1881. They fielded 22 players against an [[Uxbridge]] Cricket Club XI, but still lost by an innings. The Dutch Cricket Union was formed in 1883, with 18 member clubs, four of which are still in existence today.<ref name=\"TL\">[http://www.cricketeurope4.net/NETHERLANDS/GENERAL/timeline.shtml Netherlands timeline] at CricketEurope</ref>\n\nThe first national tournament was held the following year, and was won by [[Haagsche CC]]. English touring teams then began visiting in 1886 including one in 1891 that featured the author of [[Sherlock Holmes]], Sir [[Arthur Conan Doyle]].<ref name=\"TL\" />\n\nIn 1894, the Gentlemen of Holland were the first Dutch team to visit England. The tour included a game against the [[Marylebone Cricket Club|MCC]] at [[Lord's]], which the MCC won by an innings and 169 runs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://uk.cricinfo.com/db/ARCHIVE/1890S/1894/OTHERS%20ICC/GENTLEMEN-NL_IN_ENG/GENTLEMEN-NL_MCC_10-11AUG1894.html|title=Oops\u2026 Looks like something went wrong! This page does not exist or has been moved.|publisher=}}</ref> Tours by English sides continued for the rest of the 1890s, which also saw the emergence of [[Carst Posthuma]], who was later the first Dutch player to play first class cricket.<ref name=\"TL\" /> He took 2339 wickets at an average of 8.66 in his career in the Netherlands.<ref>[http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/ci/content/player/24933.html Carst Posthuma] at Cricinfo</ref>\n\n===1900s to 1910s===\n\n1901 saw another visit to England by the Gentlemen of Holland. They played five games on the tour, drawing two and losing the remainder.<ref>[http://uk.cricinfo.com/db/ARCHIVE/1900S/1901/OTHERS+ICC/GENTLEMEN-NL_IN_ENG/ Netherlands in England], 1901 at Cricinfo</ref> 1905 saw the first international game against [[Belgian cricket team|Belgium]], which finished in a draw.<ref name=\"TL\" /> Cricket began a decline in popularity in the first decade of the 20th century, particularly amongst young athletes, due, in part, to the Dutch sympathizing with the Boers in the Boer War and therefore not being attracted to a game with links to England.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/netherlands/content/current/story/261623.html |title=A brief history... Netherlands cricket |publisher=[[ESPNcricinfo]] |accessdate=18 February 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 1910, the Dutch team visited [[Belgium]] to take part in an exhibition tournament, which also featured the MCC, Belgium and [[French cricket team|France]]. They lost to the MCC by 2 wickets,<ref>[http://uk.cricinfo.com/db/ARCHIVE/1910S/1910/OTHERS+ICC/BEXT/NL_MCC_BEXT_23-24JUN1910.html Scorecard] of MCC v Netherlands, 23 June 1910 at Cricinfo</ref> and to France by 63 runs,<ref>[http://uk.cricinfo.com/db/ARCHIVE/1910S/1910/OTHERS+ICC/BEXT/NL_FRANCE_BEXT_26JUN1910.html Scorecard] of France v Netherlands, 26 June 1910 at Cricinfo</ref> but beat Belgium by 116 runs.<ref>[http://uk.cricinfo.com/db/ARCHIVE/1910S/1910/OTHERS+ICC/BEXT/BELGIUM_NL_BEXT_25JUN1910.html Scorecard] of Belgium v Netherlands, 25 June 1910 at Cricinfo</ref>\n\nDuring [[World War I]], in which the Netherlands remained neutral, large numbers of British officers were [[Internment|interned]] in the country, and many of these joined local cricket clubs. A team made up of these players even won the Dutch championship in 1918.<ref name=\"TL\" />\n\n===1920s to 1940s===\n\nThe Flamingos, a Dutch touring side, was formed in 1921, and later made several tours of England. Tours by English teams also continued in this period. The 1930s are said to be the heyday of Dutch cricket. In 1934, the first Dutch women's league was formed, and the women's national team played two games against Australia in 1937, losing heavily in both. Cricket was of course curtailed after the German invasion in 1940.<ref name=\"TL\" />\n\n===1950s to 1980s===\n\nThe 1950s saw visits to the Netherlands by [[Australia national cricket team|Australia]] and the [[West Indies cricket team|West Indies]], in addition to their first match against [[Denmark national cricket team|Denmark]]. In 1958, the Cricket Board received a Royal Charter, and became the \"Koninklijke Nederlandse Cricket Bond\", a name which it retains to this day.<ref name=\"TL\" />\n\nIn August 1964, the Netherlands achieved their first victory against a Test-playing nation when they beat Australia by three wickets at The Hague.<ref name=\"TL\" /> They were rewarded with [[List of International Cricket Council members#Associate Members|associate membership of the ICC]] two years later.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cricketarchive.co.uk/Archive/Countries/20.html |title=Netherlands |publisher=CricketArchive}}</ref>\n{{Limited overs international\n  | date = 29 August 1964\n  | team1 = {{cr-rt|AUS}}\n  | score1 = 197 (50.1 overs)\n  | score2 = 201/7 (57.4 overs)\n  | team2 = {{cr|NED}}\n  | runs1 = [[Norm O'Neill]] 87 \n  | wickets1 = Ben Trijzelaar 3/41 (11 overs)\n  | runs2 = Pieter Marseille 77\n  | wickets2 = [[Bob Cowper]] 4/69 (12.4 overs)\n  | result = Netherlands won by 3 wickets\n  | report = [https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/161/161412.html Scorecard]\n  | venue = De Diepput, [[The Hague]]\n  | umpires = W Amons and G Stallman\n  | motm = \n  | toss = Australia won the toss and elected to bat\n  | notes = One-day single-innings match\n}}\n\nThe first two [[ICC Trophy]] tournaments, in 1979 and 1982, brought little success to the Dutch, who were eliminated in the first round in both tournaments. But in the [[1986 ICC Trophy|1986 tournament]], they finished as runners-up to [[Zimbabwe national cricket team|Zimbabwe]]. The same year, [[Paul-Jan Bakker]] became the first Dutch player to play county cricket.<ref name=\"TL\" /> In 1989, the Dutch beat a strong [[England cricket team|England XI]] that included two future England captains, [[Alec Stewart]] and [[Nasser Hussain]], by 3 runs.<ref>[http://www.cricketarchive.co.uk/Archive/Scorecards/51/51747.html Scorecard] of Netherlands v England, 16 August 1989 at Cricket Archive</ref>\n\n===1990s===\n\nIn 1990 the Netherlands hosted the [[1990 ICC Trophy|ICC Trophy]], the first such tournament outside England, and again finished runners-up to Zimbabwe.<ref name=\"TL\" /> In 1991 they achieved a five-wicket win over a West Indies XI,<ref>[http://uk.cricinfo.com/db/ARCHIVE/1991/WI_IN_ENG/WI_NL_OD1_15AUG1991.html Scorecard] of Netherlands v West Indies, 15 August 1991 at Cricinfo</ref> followed in 1993 by a seven-wicket win over an England XI<ref>[http://uk.cricinfo.com/db/ARCHIVE/1993/OTHERS+ICC/ENG-XI_NL_10JUL1993.html Scorecard] of Netherlands v England, 10 July 1993 at Cricinfo</ref> and in 1994 a nine-wicket win over a [[South Africa national cricket team|South Africa XI]].<ref>[http://uk.cricinfo.com/db/ARCHIVE/1994/RSA_IN_ENG/RSA_NL_04SEP1994.html Scorecard] of Netherlands v South Africa, 4 September 1994 at Cricinfo</ref> In 1994 the Dutch finally qualified for the [[Cricket World Cup|World Cup]], after finishing third in [[1994 ICC Trophy|that year's ICC Trophy]]. In the [[1996 Cricket World Cup|World Cup]] itself in 1996, they were eliminated in the first round, but performed with some credit in their game against England.<ref name=\"TL\" />\n\n{{Limited overs matches\n | date = 22 February\n | team1 = {{cr-rt|ENG}}\n | score1 = 279/4 (50 overs)\n | score2 = 230/6 (50 overs)\n | team2 = {{cr|Netherlands}}\n | runs1 = [[Graeme Hick]] 104[[not out|*]] (133)\n | wickets1 = [[Roland Lefebvre]] 1/40 (10 overs)\n | runs2 = [[Klaas van Noortwijk]] 64 (82)\n | wickets2 = [[Phil DeFreitas]] 3/31 (10 overs)\n | result = England won by 49 runs\n | report = [http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/match/65166.html Scorecard]\n | venue = [[Arbab Niaz Stadium]], [[Peshawar]]\n | umpires = [[Steve Bucknor]] and [[K.T. Francis]]\n | motm = [[Graeme Hick]] (Eng)\n | rain = \n}}\n1995 saw the Netherlands enter the [[Friends Provident Trophy|NatWest Trophy]] for the first time. They took part in this tournament for ten years, and their best performance came in [[1999 NatWest Trophy|1999]] when they reached the fourth round, beating [[Durham County Cricket Club|Durham]] along the way.\n\nThe Netherlands failed to qualify for the [[1999 Cricket World Cup|1999 World Cup]], as they could only manage sixth in the [[1997 ICC Trophy]]. However, the country hosted one World Cup match, between [[Kenya national cricket team|Kenya]] and South Africa at [[VRA Cricket Ground|Amstelveen]].<ref name=\"TL\" />\n\nThe Netherlands competed in the first [[European Cricket Championship|European Championship]] in 1996, coming second. They have competed in every tournament since, winning in 1998 and 2000.<ref name=\"TL\" />\n\n===21st century===\n====2000\u20132009====\n\n2001 finally saw the Netherlands win the ICC Trophy, beating [[Namibian cricket team|Namibia]] in the final in [[Toronto]]. They thus qualified for the [[2003 Cricket World Cup|2003 World Cup]]. They again failed to progress beyond the first round in the tournament, but recorded their first one-day international win over Namibia during the tournament. [[Feiko Kloppenburg]] (with 121) and [[Klaas-Jan van Noortwijk]] (134 not out) scored the first two One Day International centuries in the side's history.<ref name=\"TL\" />\n\nIn the [[2005 ICC Trophy]], the Netherlands finished 5th, qualifying for the [[2007 Cricket World Cup]], and gaining one-day International status until the [[2009 ICC World Cup Qualifier]]. Their first one-day international with this new status was scheduled to be against [[Kenyan cricket team|Kenya]] in March 2006; however this match was cancelled due to a Kenyan tour of [[Bangladesh]]. Instead their first ODI with this status (and their twelfth overall) came against [[Sri Lankan cricket team|Sri Lanka]]; this was their first ODI at home. However Sri Lanka won the two match series 2\u20130, with a then-record ODI score of 443\u20139.<ref name=\"TL\" />\n\nThe Dutch played their first Intercontinental Cup match of 2006 against [[Kenyan cricket team|Kenya]] in Nairobi in March. The game was drawn, but the Netherlands gained six points for a first innings lead.<ref>[http://www.cricketarchive.co.uk/Archive/Scorecards/86/86450.html Scorecard] of Kenya v Netherlands, 29 March 2006 at Cricket Archive</ref> In August, the Netherlands competed in Division One of the [[European Cricket Championship|European Championship]]. They beat [[Danish cricket team|Denmark]] and [[Italian cricket team|Italy]], but lost to [[Scottish cricket team|Scotland]] and their game against [[Irish cricket team|Ireland]] was rained off. They finished third in the tournament.<ref name=\"TL\" />\n\nIn November, the Dutch travelled to South Africa. They first played an Intercontinental Cup match against [[Bermuda national cricket team|Bermuda]]:   [[David Hemp]] achieved what was then a competition record score of 247 [[not out]] in the drawn match.<ref>[http://www.cricketarchive.co.uk/Archive/Scorecards/86/86457.html Scorecard] of Bermuda v Netherlands, 21 November 2006 at Cricket Archive</ref> This was followed by a triangular series against Bermuda and [[Canada national cricket team|Canada]], which they won.<ref>[http://www.cricketarchive.co.uk/Archive/Events/Tables/ICC_Associates_South_Africa_Tri-Series_2006-07.html ICC Associates South Africa Tri-Series points table] at Cricket Archive</ref> Their final game of 2006, also in South Africa, was an Intercontinental Cup game against Canada. They won the match by 7 wickets, with [[Ryan ten Doeschate]] setting a new competition record individual score of 259 not out.<ref>[http://www.cricketarchive.co.uk/Archive/Scorecards/86/86458.html Scorecard] of Canada v Netherlands, 5 December 2006 at Cricket Archive</ref>\n\nIn early 2007, they travelled to [[Nairobi]], Kenya to take part in [[2007 ICC World Cricket League Division One|Division One]] of the [[World Cricket League]], finishing third out of six.<ref name=\"2007WCL1\">[http://www.cricketarchive.co.uk/Archive/Events/Tables/ICC_World_Cricket_League_2007.html 2007 ICC World Cricket League Division One points table] at Cricket Archive</ref> This was followed by the [[2007 Cricket World Cup|2007 World Cup]] in the West Indies, where they were eliminated in the first round, though they did beat [[Scotland national cricket team|Scotland]] along the way.<ref name=\"2007WC\">[http://uk.cricinfo.com/db/ARCHIVE/WORLD_CUPS/WC2007/ 2007 World Cup] at Cricinfo</ref>\n\nFollowing the World Cup, they underwent a period of transformation. Captain [[Luuk van Troost]] retired, as did [[Tim de Leede]] and their coach Peter Cantrell. [[Daan van Bunge]] also opted to take a break from international cricket, and the new coach opted not to retain the services of bowling coach [[Ian Pont]].\n\nIn June 2007, they visited Canada, first winning an Intercontinental Cup match against Canada in [[King City, Ontario]].<ref>[http://www.cricketarchive.co.uk/Archive/Scorecards/123/123036.html Scorecard] of Canada v Netherlands, 28 June 2007 at Cricket Archive</ref> They then won the first ODI by 117 runs,<ref>[http://www.cricketarchive.co.uk/Archive/Scorecards/123/123079.html Scorecard] of Canada v Netherlands, 3 July 2007 at Cricket Archive</ref> with the second one being abandoned.<ref>[http://www.cricketarchive.co.uk/Archive/Scorecards/123/123080.html Scorecard] of Canada v Netherlands, 4 July 2007 at Cricket Archive</ref> They then played a quadrangular series in Ireland, losing by ten wickets to the [[West Indies cricket team|West Indies]],<ref>[http://www.cricketarchive.co.uk/Archive/Scorecards/123/123073.html Scorecard] of Netherlands v West Indies, 10 July 2007 at Cricket Archive</ref> and by one run to [[Ireland cricket team|Ireland]],<ref>[http://www.cricketarchive.co.uk/Archive/Scorecards/123/123073.html Scorecard] of Ireland v Netherlands, 11 July 2007 at Cricket Archive</ref> with the game against Scotland being abandoned due to rain.<ref>[http://www.cricketarchive.co.uk/Archive/Scorecards/123/123076.html Scorecard] of Netherlands v Scotland, 13 July 2007 at Cricket Archive</ref>\n\nIn August 2008, The Netherlands participated in the [[2009 ICC World Twenty20 Qualifier]]. This was their debut playing [[Twenty20 International]] matches.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/ci-icc/content/story/354462.html|title=Ireland to host inaugural World Twenty20 qualifiers|publisher=}}</ref> They finished in first place in Group B, based on their run-rate.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/iccworldtwenty20/engine/series/353665.html?view=pointstable|title=Points Table \u2013 ICC World Twenty20 Qualifier 2008 \u2013 ESPN Cricinfo|publisher=}}</ref> After beating Scotland in the Semi-Finals,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/iccworldtwenty20/engine/current/match/361531.html|title=2nd Semi-Final: Netherlands v Scotland at Belfast, Aug 4, 2008 \u2013 Cricket Scorecard \u2013 ESPN Cricinfo|publisher=}}</ref> the final was abandoned due to rain and the trophy was shared between The Netherlands and Ireland.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/iccworldtwenty20/content/story/363767.html|title=Ireland and Netherlands share the trophy|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nThe Netherlands caused a sensation in the cricketing world by beating England<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/wt202009/engine/match/355991.html|title=1st Match, Group B: England v Netherlands at Lord's, Jun 5, 2009 \u2013 Cricket Scorecard \u2013 ESPN Cricinfo|publisher=}}</ref> in the opening match of the [[ICC World Twenty20 2009]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cricinfo.com/wt202009/engine/current/match/355991.html|title=1st Match, Group B: England v Netherlands at Lord's, Jun 5, 2009 \u2013 Cricket Scorecard \u2013 ESPN Cricinfo|publisher=}}</ref> whilst being 500/1 outsiders.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://uk.reuters.com/article/idUKL522562120090605 | work=Reuters | title=Update 2-Cricket-Dutch upset England in spectacular start | date=5 June 2009}}</ref>\n{{Limited overs matches\n| date = 5 June 2009\n| time = 17:30\n| daynight = yes\n| team1 = {{cr-rt|ENG}}\n| score1 = 162/5 (20 overs)\n| score2 = 163/6 (20 overs)\n| team2 = {{cr|NED}}\n| runs1 = [[Luke Wright]] 71 (49)\n| wickets1 = [[Ryan ten Doeschate]] 2/35 (4 overs)\n| runs2 = [[Tom de Grooth]] 49 (30)\n| wickets2 = [[James Anderson (cricketer)|James Anderson]] 3/23 (4 overs)\n| result = Netherlands won by 4 wickets\n| report = [http://www.espncricinfo.com/wt202009/engine/match/355991.html Scorecard]\n| venue = [[Lord's]], [[London]]\n| umpires = [[Asoka de Silva (cricketer)|Asoka de Silva]] (SL) and [[Steve Davis (umpire)|Steve Davis]] (Aus)\n| motm = [[Tom de Grooth]] (Ned)\n| toss = Netherlands won the toss and elected to field.\n}}\nThey lost their second match to the eventual winners Pakistan<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cricinfo.com/wt202009/engine/match/355999.html|title=9th Match, Group B: Netherlands v Pakistan at Lord's, Jun 9, 2009 \u2013 Cricket Scorecard \u2013 ESPN Cricinfo|publisher=}}</ref> and did not qualify for the super 8 stage based on run rate.\n\n[[File:Netherlands cricket team.jpg|thumb|Netherlands national cricket team at [[Rotterdam]], [[2010 ICC World Cricket League Division One|ICC WCL Division One in 2010]]]]\n\n====2010\u2013present====\n\nOn 20 July 2010, The Netherlands beat a full-member nation for the first time in an ODI. In a one-off match shortened by rain to 30 overs a side, they beat Bangladesh by 6 wickets.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cricinfo.com/england-v-bangladesh-2010/engine/current/match/450105.html|title=Only ODI: Bangladesh v Netherlands at Glasgow, Jul 20, 2010 \u2013 Cricket Scorecard \u2013 ESPN Cricinfo|publisher=}}</ref> The win in combination with their winning percentage against other associate and affiliate nations resulted in The Netherlands being included in ICC's official ODI-rankings.<ref>http://www.cricketeurope4.net/DATABASE/ARTICLES3/articles/000041/004143.shtml</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/bangladesh/content/story/468126.html|title=Barresi carries Netherlands to major victory|date=20 July 2010|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n{{Limited overs matches\n| date = 20 July 2010\n| time = \n| team1 = {{cr|BAN}}\n| team2 = {{cr|NED}}\n| score1 = 199/7 (30 overs)\n| score2 = 200/4 (28.5 overs)\n| runs1 = [[Imrul Kayes]] 52 (50)\n| wickets1 = [[Peter Borren]] 3/30 (6 overs)\n| runs2 = [[Eric Szwarczynski]] 67 (54)\n| wickets2 = [[Nazmul Hossain]] 2/28 (6 overs)\n| result = Netherlands won by 6 wickets (with 7 balls remaining)\n| report = [http://www.espncricinfo.com/england-v-bangladesh-2010/engine/current/match/450105.html Scorecard]\n| venue = [[Titwood]], [[Glasgow]] {{cr|SCO}}\n| umpires = [[Kumar Dharmasena]] (SRL) and [[Ian Ramage]] (SCO)\n| motm = \n| toss = Netherlands won the toss and elected to field.\n| rain = \n| notes = Match reduced to 30 overs a side.<br>First ever ODI win for Netherlands over a full ICC Member team.\n}}\n\nOn 22 February 2011, The Netherlands posted their highest ever total against a full-member nation, scoring 292 against England, batting first at the [[2011 Cricket World Cup]]. [[Ryan Ten Doeschate]] top scored 119 from 110 balls. However, the Netherlands were unable to defend their strong total and failed to pull off a huge shock, England winning by 6 wickets with 2 overs to spare. They eventually failed to win any of their group matches and were last in their Group.\n\nIn September 2011, Netherlands whitewashed [[Kenya cricket team|Kenya]] in a short two-match ODI series held at home.<ref>{{cite web| title=India vs Netherlands, ICC World Cup 2011  | url=http://iccworld-cup2011.blogspot.com/2011/03/india-vs-netherlands-delhi-9th-march.html | publisher =Cricket Archives }}</ref>\n\nIn the [[2014 ICC World Twenty20]], Netherlands had one win and one loss before their final game. In order to go through on net run rate against [[Zimbabwe cricket team|Zimbabwe]] and [[Ireland national cricket team|Ireland]], they needed to chase down Ireland's score in 14.2 overs or less. As Ireland scored 189, this seemed unlikely. However, strong and aggressive batting enabled them to score 193/4 in 13.5 overs, securing passage to the [[2014 ICC World Twenty20 Super 10s]]. Although they lost their first three games in the group, including a 39/10 against [[Sri Lanka national cricket team|Sri Lanka]], they pulled off an upset against [[England national cricket team|England]] in their last game.\n{{Cricket match summary\n| date = 31 March\n| daynight = \n| team1 = {{cr-rt|Netherlands}}\n| score1 = 133/5 (20 overs)\n| team2 = {{cr|England}}\n| score2 = 88 (17.4 overs)\n| result = Netherlands won by 45 runs\n| venue = [[Zohur Ahmed Chowdhury Stadium]], [[Chittagong]]\n| scorecard = [http://www.espncricinfo.com/icc-world-twenty20-2014/engine/match/682953.html Scorecard]\n}}\nIn June 2014, Nepal along with [[Netherlands cricket team|Netherlands]] granted [[Twenty20 International|T20]] status by the [[International Cricket Council|ICC]] board at the annual conference in [[Melbourne]].<ref name=\"espncricinfoci\"/>\n\n==International grounds==\n{{main|List of cricket grounds in the Netherlands}}\n\n{{location map+|Netherlands|float=center|width=350|caption=Locations of all stadiums which have hosted an international cricket match within the Netherlands|places=\n{{location map~|Netherlands|label=<small>[[Hazelaarweg Stadion|Hazelaarweg]]</small>|position=right|lat=51.967909|long=4.484975}}\n{{location map~|Netherlands|label=<small>[[Sportpark Thurlede|Thurlede]]</small>|position=bottom|lat=51.92985|long=4.394658}}\n{{location map~|Netherlands|label=<small>[[Sportpark Westvliet|Westvliet]]</small>|position=left|lat=52.068597|long=4.374369}}\n{{location map~|Netherlands|label=<small>[[VRA Cricket Ground|VRA Ground]]</small>|position=bottom|lat=52.319444|long=4.849058}}\n{{location map~|Netherlands|label=<small>[[Sportpark Het Schootsveld|Schootsveld]]</small>|position=left|lat=52.150910|long=6.133370}}\n{{location map~|Netherlands|label=<small>[[Sportpark Maarschalkerweerd|Maarschalkerweerd]]</small>|position=right|lat=52.0438|long=5.091435}}\n}}\n{{-}}\n\n==Tournament history==\n''A red box around the year indicates tournaments played within the Netherlands''\n\n===ICC Cricket World Cup===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|-\n!colspan=8|[[Cricket World Cup|World Cup record]]\n|-\n! width=200 |Year\n! width=150 |Round\n! width=50 |Position\n! width=50 |GP\n! width=50 |W\n! width=50 |L\n! width=50 |T\n! width=50 |NR\n|-\n|{{flagicon|ENG}} [[1975 Cricket World Cup|1975]] || colspan=\"7\" | Did not participate\n|-\n|{{flagicon|ENG}} [[1979 Cricket World Cup|1979]] || colspan=\"7\" | Did not qualify\n|-\n|{{flagicon|ENG}} [[1983 Cricket World Cup|1983]] || colspan=\"7\" | Did not qualify\n|-\n|{{flagicon|IND}} {{flagicon|PAK}} [[1987 Cricket World Cup|1987]] || colspan=\"7\" | Did not qualify\n|-\n|{{flagicon|AUS}} {{flagicon|NZL}} [[1992 Cricket World Cup|1992]] || colspan=\"7\" | Did not qualify\n|-\n|{{flagicon|IND}} {{flagicon|PAK}} {{flagicon|SRI}} [[1996 Cricket World Cup|1996]] || Group stage || 12/12 || 5 || 0 || 5 || 0 || 0\n|-\n|style=\"border: 3px solid red\"|{{flagicon|ENG}} [[1999 Cricket World Cup|1999]] || colspan=\"7\" | Did not qualify\n|-\n|{{flagicon|RSA}} [[2003 Cricket World Cup|2003]] || Group stage || 11/14 || 6 || 1 || 5 || 0 || 0\n|-\n|{{flagico