9 World Cup Qualifier]]<br>[[2010 ICC World Cricket League Division One|2010 WCL (Div. 1)]]<br>[[2011 Cricket World Cup|2011 World Cup]]<br>[[2011\u201313 ICC World Cricket League Championship|2011\u201313 WCL Championship]]\n|-\n| {{flagicon|RSA}} [[Anton Roux]] ''(initially acting)'' || October 2013<ref name=\"drin1\"/> || 2016 || [[2014 Cricket World Cup Qualifier|2014 World Cup Qualifier]]\n|-\n| {{flagicon|AUS}} [[Ryan Campbell]] || April 2017<ref name=\"campbell-coach\"/> ||  || [[2018 Cricket World Cup Qualifier|2018 World Cup Qualifier]]\n|}\n\n==See also==\n\n*[[Dutch national cricket captains]]\n*[[List of Netherlands ODI cricketers]]\n*[[List of Netherlands Twenty20 International cricketers]]\n*[[Netherlands national women's cricket team]]\n*[[Cricket in the Netherlands]]\n{{portal|Cricket}}\n{{clear}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.kncb.nl/ Koninklijke Nederlandse Cricket Bond (in Dutch)]\n*[https://theeurot20slam.com/euro-t20-slam-venues/ VRA, Amsterdam]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Cricket in the Netherlands}}\n{{National sports teams of the Netherlands}}\n{{National cricket teams}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Netherlands National Cricket Team}}\n[[Category:Cricket in the Netherlands]]\n[[Category:National cricket teams]]\n[[Category:National sports teams of the Netherlands|C]]\n[[Category:Netherlands in international cricket]]\n", "name_user": "103.60.175.78", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Netherlands_national_cricket_team"}
{"title_page": "James Anderson (cricketer)", "text_new": "{{short description|English cricketer}}\n{{About|the England Test player|the Oxford University player|James Anderson (cricketer, born 1931)}}\n{{EngvarB|date=November 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox cricketer\n| name = James Anderson\n| honorific-suffix = [[Officer of the Order of the British Empire|OBE]]\n| image = JIMMY ANDERSON.jpg\n| caption = Anderson in 2014\n| country = England\n| fullname = James Michael Anderson\n| nickname = The King of Swing,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/cricket/international/theashes/8244183/The-Ashes-James-Anderson-the-king-of-swing-earns-his-place-among-Englands-fast-bowling-greats.html |title= The Ashes: James Anderson, the king of swing, earns his place among England's fast-bowling greats |author=Scyld Berry |work=The Daily Telegraph |date=6 January 2011 | location=London}} Retrieved on 27 June 2008.</ref> The Burnley Express, The Burnley [[Brian Lara|Lara]],<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/cricket/article-2725289/James-Anderson-England-captain-s-dream-gets-job-hand.html |title= James Anderson is an England captain's dream... he gets on with the job in hand |author=David Lloyd |newspaper=Daily Mail |date=14 August 2014 | location=London}} Retrieved on 27 June 2008.</ref> Daisy (early career)<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/cricket/international/england/2302708/James-Andersons-search-for-perfection.html |title= James Anderson's search for perfection |author=Simon Hughes |work=The Daily Telegraph |date=9 June 2008 | location=London}} Retrieved on 27 June 2008.</ref>\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|df=y|1982|7|30}}\n| birth_place = [[Burnley]], Lancashire, England\n| height = 6 ft 2 in\n| role = [[Bowling (cricket)|Bowler]]\n| batting = Left-handed\n| bowling = Right-arm [[Fast bowling|fast-medium]]\n| international = true\n| internationalspan = 2002\u2013present\n| testdebutdate = 22 May\n| testdebutyear = 2003\n| testdebutagainst = Zimbabwe\n| testcap = 613\n| lasttestdate = 3 January\n| lasttestyear = 2020\n| lasttestagainst = South Africa\n| odidebutdate = 15 December\n| odidebutyear = 2002\n| odidebutagainst = Australia\n| odicap = 172\n| odishirt = 9\n| lastodidate = 13 March\n| lastodiyear = 2015\n| lastodiagainst = Afghanistan\n| T20Icap = 21\n| T20Idebutdate = 9 January\n| T20Idebutyear = 2007\n| T20Idebutagainst = Australia\n| lastT20Idate = 15 November\n| lastT20Iyear = 2009\n| lastT20Iagainst = South Africa\n| club1 = [[Lancashire Cricket Board]]\n| year1 = 2000\n| club2 = [[Lancashire County Cricket Club|Lancashire]]\n| year2 = 2002\u2013present\n| clubnumber2 = 9\n| club3 = [[Auckland cricket team|Auckland]]\n| year3 = 2007/08\n| columns = 4\n| column1 = [[Test cricket|Test]]\n| matches1 = 151\n| runs1 = 1,185\n| bat avg1 = 9.63\n| 100s/50s1 = 0/1\n| top score1 = 81\n| deliveries1 = 32,779\n| wickets1 = 584\n| bowl avg1 = 26.83\n| fivefor1 = 28\n| tenfor1 = 3\n| best bowling1 = 7/42\n| catches/stumpings1 = 93/\u2013\n| column2 = [[One Day International|ODI]]\n| matches2 = 194\n| runs2 = 273\n| bat avg2 = 7.58\n| 100s/50s2 = 0/0\n| top score2 = 28\n| deliveries2 = 9,584\n| wickets2 = 269\n| bowl avg2 = 29.22\n| fivefor2 = 2\n| tenfor2 = 0\n| best bowling2 = 5/23\n| catches/stumpings2 = 54/\u2013\n| column3 = [[First-class cricket|FC]]\n| matches3 = 248\n| runs3 = 1,826\n| bat avg3 = 9.61\n| 100s/50s3 = 0/1\n| top score3 = 81\n| deliveries3 = 49,905\n| wickets3 = 959\n| bowl avg3 = 24.92\n| fivefor3 = 48\n| tenfor3 = 6\n| best bowling3 = 7/42\n| catches/stumpings3 = 146/\u2013\n| column4 = [[List A cricket|LA]]\n| matches4 = 261\n| runs4 = 376\n| bat avg4 = 8.95\n| 100s/50s4 = 0/0\n| top score4 = 28\n| deliveries4 = 12,730\n| wickets4 = 358\n| bowl avg4 = 28.57\n| fivefor4 = 2\n| tenfor4 = 0\n| best bowling4 = 5/23\n| catches/stumpings4 = 68/\u2013\n| date = 7 January 2020\n| source = http://www.espncricinfo.com/england/content/player/8608.html ESPNcricinfo\n}}\n\n'''James Michael Anderson''', {{post-nominals|country=GBR|size=100|OBE}} (born 30 July 1982), usually known as '''Jimmy Anderson''', is an English international [[cricket]]er who plays for [[Lancashire County Cricket Club]] and the [[England cricket team]]. Anderson is the [[Fast bowling#Top five fast bowlers|all-time leading wicket-taker among fast bowlers]] surpassing Glenn McGrath (563 wickets) and holds the record of most wickets for England in both Test and One-Day International (ODI) cricket. He is the only English bowler, and the 6th overall, to pass 500 Test wickets.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/wi/content/records/93276.html|title=Test matches {{!}} Most wickets in career |publisher=ESPNcricinfo|access-date=12 September 2018}}</ref>Anderson is also a co-presenter alongside [[Greg James]] and [[Felix White]] on the Tailenders podcast. \n\nAnderson plays [[first-class cricket]] for [[Lancashire County Cricket Club|Lancashire county cricket club]] and since arriving on the international scene in 2002/03 (before his first full season of County cricket) has represented England in 150 [[Test cricket|Test matches]] and nearly 200 [[One Day International]]s.<ref name=\"cricinfo player profile\"/> He is England's all-time highest international wicket-taker when combined across all three formats. He and [[Joe Root]] posted the highest ever 10th-wicket Test batting partnership in the 1st Test of India's 2014 tour of England.\n\nA right-arm [[Fast bowling|pace bowler]], Anderson made his international debut at the age of just 20, on England's 2002/03 tour of [[Australia national cricket team|Australia]]. When he played his first ODI he had only played five [[List A]] matches. Anderson went on to feature in the [[2003 Cricket World Cup|2003 ICC World Cup]] and made his Test match debut against [[Zimbabwe national cricket team|Zimbabwe]] at [[Lord's]] the next summer. Later in 2003, he experienced a dip in form and confidence against [[South Africa national cricket team|South Africa]]. After this, he was in and out of the team and experienced numerous injuries, including a [[stress fracture]] of the back which kept him out of action for most of the 2006 season. He returned to action and is now the opening bowler in England's Test team. He was a regular strike bowler in England's one-day team but has not played in that format since the 2015 World Cup. He is the first English bowler to reach 400 and 500 wickets in Test matches, and on 11 September 2018, he became 4th highest Test wicket-taker of all time. He reached this position when he took his 564th Test wicket, passing [[Glenn McGrath]] as the leading wicket-taker among fast bowlers. {{As of|2019|January}} he is ranked No.2 in the [[ICC Player Rankings#Top 10 Test Bowlers|ICC Test Bowling Rankings]], having previously reached the top position at various times between 2016 and 2018.\n\nOn 25 July 2016, during the second Test of that year's England-Pakistan series at [[Old Trafford Cricket Ground|Old Trafford]], he became the first fast bowler to take 50 wickets against all other 7 major Test-playing nations, Australia, India, [[New Zealand national cricket team|New Zealand]], [[Pakistan national cricket team|Pakistan]], South Africa, [[Sri Lanka national cricket team|Sri Lanka]] and [[West Indies national cricket team|West Indies]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/england/2282874.stm |author=Scott Heinrich |title=Anderson on fast track |publisher=BBC |date=31 December 2002}} Retrieved on 26 June 2008.</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sportstar.thehindu.com/cricket-videos/ashes-2019-james-anderson-world-class-stuart-broad-cricket/article29391846.ece|title=James Anderson delighted for 'world class' Stuart Broad|last=Sportstar|first=Team|website=Sportstar|access-date=10 October 2019}}</ref> In December 2019, in the first Test [[English cricket team in South Africa in 2019\u201320|against South Africa]], Anderson became the ninth cricketer to [[List of Test cricket records#Individual records (other)|play in 150 Test matches]].<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.espncricinfo.com/series/19430/preview/1185304/south-africa-vs-england-1st-test-icc-world-test-championship-2019-2021 |title=Bruised England look to improve touring record against battered South Africa |work=ESPN Cricinfo |accessdate=26 December 2019}}</ref> In January 2020, in the second Test of the series against South Africa, Anderson took his [[List of international cricket five-wicket hauls by James Anderson|28th five-wicket haul]] in Test cricket.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.skysports.com/cricket/news/12123/11901500/james-anderson-completes-five-for-before-england-grow-lead-in-cape-town |title=James Anderson completes five-for before England grow lead in Cape Town |work=Sky Sports |accessdate=5 January 2020}}</ref> He surpassed Sir [[Ian Botham]]'s record of 27, to become the bowler with the [[List of cricketers by number of international five-wicket hauls|most five-wicket hauls]] for England in Test cricket.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eveningexpress.co.uk/sport/dom-sibley-builds-on-more-good-work-from-james-anderson-as-england-flourish/ |title=Dom Sibley builds on more good work from James Anderson as England flourish |work=Evening Express |accessdate=5 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Early and personal life==\nJames Anderson was a pupil at St Mary's and [[St Theodore's RC High School]], [[Burnley]]. He played cricket at [[Burnley Cricket Club]] from a young age. His childhood dream was to be a cricketer, and at the age of 17, after a growth spurt, Anderson was one of the fastest bowlers in the [[Lancashire League (cricket)|Lancashire League]].<ref name=\"lessons in life\">{{cite web |url=http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/england/content/story/133792.html |author=Emma John |title=Lessons in life |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=19 September 2003}} Retrieved on 29 May 2008.</ref> He stated that \"I've always bowled [[seam bowling|seam]], but when I was about 17 I don't know what it was but I just started bowling fast all of a sudden\".<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.cricbuzz.com/cricket-news/81851/england-cricket-team-bowler-james-anderson-becomes-first-seamer-to-take-50-plus-wickets-against-seven-teams |author=Deepu Narayanan |title=Anderson becomes first seamer to take 50-plus wickets against seven teams |publisher=Cricbuzz |date=5 August 2016}} Retrieved on 8 August 2016.</ref>\n\nJust months after his debut he had become one of the biggest stars in English cricket. Continuous alteration of hair styles, attractive looks, and up-to-the-minute outfits earned him comparisons with some of the most recognisable sports personalities around, including [[David Beckham]].<ref name=\"lessons in life\"/> In 2006, at Holy Angels' RC Church, [[Hale, Greater Manchester|Hale]], he married Daniella Lloyd, a model he met in 2004 while on England duty in London; he stated that marriage has made him \"a much happier person\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/wisdencricketer/content/story/313823.html |author=Emma John |title=How the pin-up grew up |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=October 2007}} Retrieved on 10 December 2007.</ref> On 8 January 2009, Daniella Anderson gave birth to a baby girl, Lola Rose. The couple's second daughter, Ruby Luxe, was born on 9 December 2010.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.lccc.co.uk/index.php?p=news&id=2553 |author=Lancashire County Cricket Club |title=Jimmy's Finest Delivery |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=12 January 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110616100852/http://www.lccc.co.uk/index.php?p=news&id=2553 |archivedate=16 June 2011  }} Retrieved on 12 January 2009.</ref>\n\n===Fashion design===\nAnderson has ventured into fashion design since 2012, designing for Elvis Jesus with proceeds of the sale going to his sponsored charity, [[Nordoff-Robbins]]. In April 2014, he launched his first collection with London-based menswear brand, Chess London. He has stated that he would like to be \"the first cricketer to become a designer\".<ref>{{cite news  |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/lifestyle/esmagazine/rising-from-the-ashes-englands-cricket-stars-on-finding-their-mojo-9582207.html?origin=internalSearch |title= Rising from the Ashes: England's cricket stars on finding their mojo |author=Joshi Herrmann |work=London Evening Standard |date=4 July 2014 | location=London}} Retrieved on 13 August 2014</ref> He launched his own menswear brand in late October 2014,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.613collection.com/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=14 October 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141017191000/http://www.613collection.com/ |archivedate=17 October 2014 }}</ref> and has been working in conjunction with British watchmaker [[Christopher Pinchbeck|Harold Pinchbeck]] to release a watch in 2015.<ref>http://www.activatemanagement.co.uk/who-we-manage/james-anderson/</ref>\n\n===Media===\nAnderson became the first cricketer to model naked for ''[[Attitude (magazine)|Attitude]]'', \"Britain's biggest-selling gay magazine\", in September 2010. He stated \"if there are any gay cricketers they should feel confident enough to come out because I don't think there is any homophobia in cricket.\"<ref>{{cite news | url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-lancashire-11377673| title= Naked Lancashire cricketer James Anderson in Attitude| accessdate =20 September 2010| date=20 September 2010|publisher=BBC News }}</ref>\n\nAlongside former cricketer [[Graeme Swann]] and [[BBC Radio 1]] radio presenter [[Greg James]], Anderson hosts a cricket-themed radio show on [[BBC Radio 5 Live]], \"Not Just Cricket\". The radio show was nominated for Best Sports Programme at the 2013 [[Radio Academy Awards]].\n\nOn 15 November 2017, Anderson along with Felix White and Greg James, began hosting a cricketing podcast 'Tailenders'. This was initially a weekly podcast covering the 2017\u201318 Ashes series, since 23 May 2018 it was renewed to continue on a weekly basis.[9] Features include 'General Cricketing Sadness', 'Mattchin's Quiz' and 'Black Wednesday/Xmas Show/App Launch'.\n\n==Domestic career==\nAnderson made his [[first-class cricket|first-class]] debut for Lancashire in 2002; he played 13 matches and took 50 wickets at an average of 22.28, including three five-wicket hauls.<ref name=\"fc bowling by season\">{{cite web |url=http://www.cricketarchive.co.uk/Lancashire/Players/10/10687/f_Bowling_by_Season.html |title=First-class bowling in each season by James Anderson |publisher=Cricket Archive}} Retrieved on 29 May 2008.</ref> He was awarded the [[NBC Denis Compton Award]] for Lancashire's most promising young County player in the 2002 season.<ref name=\"cricinfo player profile\">{{cite web |url=http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/england/content/player/8608.html |title=James Anderson |publisher=ESPNcricinfo}} Retrieved on 29 May 2008.</ref> In 2003, Anderson became the youngest player to take a [[Hat-trick (cricket)|hat-trick]] for Lancashire, just a week before his Test match debut against Zimbabwe; it was the first hat-trick at [[Old Trafford Cricket Ground|Old Trafford]] in eight years.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/england/content/story/131313.html |title=Hat-trick for Anderson as Essex stumble at Old Trafford |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=14 May 2003}} Retrieved on 26 May 2008.</ref> In a match against [[Worcestershire County Cricket Club|Worcestershire]] in May 2004, Anderson recorded his maiden first-class ten-wicket haul.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/england/content/story/140927.html |title=Anderson and Keedy take Lancashire top |author=Andrew Miller |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=14 May 2004}} Retrieved on 29 May 2008.</ref>\n\n2005 was Anderson's first full season for Lancashire. He was propelled into the England side soon after his Lancashire debut and had returned to rediscover his form after winter tours with England where he had spent the majority of his time on the sidelines, and when given a chance for England he often bowled poorly due to a lack of match practice.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/england/content/story/220383.html |title=Cooley backs Anderson for Pakistan |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=28 September 2005}} Retrieved on 30 May 2008.</ref> He finished the season with 60 first-class wickets at an average of 30.21 and 27 one day wickets at an average of 22.00.<ref name=\"fc bowling by season\"/><ref name=\"od bowling by season\">{{cite web |url=http://www.cricketarchive.co.uk/Lancashire/Players/10/10687/a_Bowling_by_Season.html |title=ListA bowling in each season by James Anderson |publisher=Cricket Archive}} Retrieved on 30 May 2008.</ref>\n\nAnderson was prevented from playing much for Lancashire in the 2006 season by a [[stress fracture]] of the back sustained in early May.<ref name=\"stress frac\">{{cite web |url=http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/england/content/story/245931.html |title=Anderson out for two months |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=2 February 2006}} Retrieved on 29 May 2008.</ref>\nHe played in only two matches for Lancashire, and at one point it was considered sending Anderson to play for [[Glamorgan County Cricket Club|Glamorgan]] to prove his fitness; however, Lancashire decided they would rather have Anderson play for them if only in a limited capacity.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/england/content/story/259822.html |title=Anderson included in Lancashire squad |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=17 September 2006}} Retrieved on 29 May 2008.</ref> In the only first-class match he played for Lancashire that season, he was limited to three four-over spells by the [[England and Wales Cricket Board|ECB]] who were wary of injuring him again.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/england/content/story/260182.html |title=Cork haul overshadows Anderson |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=21 September 2006}} Retrieved on 29 May 2008.</ref>\n\nIn 2008, after the Test and One-Day series against South Africa ended at the beginning of September, Anderson was made unavailable to play for Lancashire for the rest of the season.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/england/content/current/story/367275.html |title=Harmison available for season finale |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=1 September 2008}} Retrieved on 1 September 2008.</ref> He finished the season with 20 first-class wickets at 7.75 for Lancashire.<ref name=\"fc bowling by season\"/><ref>\n{{cite web |url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Players/10/10687/t_Bowling_by_Season.html |title=Test bowling in each season by James Anderson |publisher=Cricket Archive}} Retrieved on 26 April 2009.</ref>\n\nAt the start of the 2009 English cricket season, Anderson took career-best match figures in a first-class match with 11/109 against [[Sussex County Cricket Club|Sussex]] as Lancashire won by 8&nbsp;wickets. It was the only first-class match he played for Lancashire before being called into the England squad for a series against the West Indies.<ref>{{Cite book |url=http://content.cricinfo.com/england/content/story/401296.html |title=Big wins for Nottinghamshire and Lancashire |publisher=Cricinfo |author=Cricinfo staff |date=24 April 2009}} Retrieved on 26 April 2009.</ref> As of 26 April 2009, Anderson had taken 188&nbsp;wickets at 24.37 from 48&nbsp;first-class matches with Lancashire,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Players/10/10687/f_Bowling_by_Team.html |title=First-class bowling for each team by James Anderson |publisher=CricketArchive.com}} Retrieved on 26 April 2009.</ref> and 66&nbsp;wickets at 21.78 in 44 list A matches.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Players/10/10687/a_Bowling_by_Team.html |title=List A bowling for each team by James Anderson |publisher=CricketArchive.com}} Retrieved on 26 April 2009.</ref>\n\n==International career==\n===2002\u201303: World Cup, Zimbabwe and South Africa===\n\nWhen Anderson was selected for the England one-day squad, he had played only five List A matches, taking 9 wickets at an average of 26.75.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cricketarchive.co.uk/Lancashire/Players/10/10687/a_Bowling_by_Season.html |title=ListA bowling in each season by James Anderson |publisher=Cricket Archive}} Retrieved on 29 May 2008.</ref> At the age of 20, he made his [[One Day International|ODI]] debut on 15 December 2002 against [[Australia national cricket team|Australia]] at [[Melbourne]]. He opened the bowling and recorded figures of 1/46 from six overs.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cricketarchive.co.uk/Archive/Scorecards/76/76049.html |title=Australia v England VB Series 2002/03; Melbourne Cricket Ground 15 December 2002 (50-over match) (day/night) |publisher=Cricket Archive}} Retrieved on 29 May 2008.</ref> His debut came before he was even awarded his County cap, which occurred in 2003.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cricketarchive.co.uk/Lancashire/Players/10/10687/10687.html |title=James Anderson |publisher=Cricket Archive}} Retrieved on 29 May 2008.</ref> He showed good promise in this series \u2013 a three-team tournament also including [[Sri Lanka national cricket team|Sri Lanka]] \u2013 which earned him a place in the [[2003 Cricket World Cup|2003 World Cup]] squad. It was here that he really broke into international cricket with a match-winning spell against [[Pakistan national cricket team|Pakistan]], where he took four wickets in day/night game to collect the Man of the Match award. In what proved to be England's last match of the tournament he conceded 12 runs off the penultimate [[over (cricket)|over]] against eventual world champions Australia, and England lost a closely fought contest.\n\nIn the summer of 2003, he made his first [[Test cricket]] appearance against [[Zimbabwe national cricket team|Zimbabwe]] at [[Lord's]], and took [[List of England cricketers who have taken five-wicket hauls on Test debut|five wickets in an innings on debut]],<ref name=\"5wktsDebut\">{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/match/64032.html |title=1st Test: England v Zimbabwe at Lord's, May 22\u201324, 2003 |accessdate=13 December 2011|publisher=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> becoming the 42nd Englishman to do so. His success continued in the subsequent One-Day tournaments against [[Pakistan national cricket team|Pakistan]] (against whom he took a hat-trick at [[The Oval]]), [[South Africa national cricket team|South Africa]] and Zimbabwe. His hat-trick against Pakistan, the first by an English bowler in an ODI, claimed the wickets of [[Abdul Razzaq (cricketer)|Abdul Razzaq]], [[Shoaib Akhtar]] and [[Mohammad Sami]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/statsguru/content/story/129793.html |title=Anderson and Trescothick batter Pakistan to defeat |author=Andrew Miller |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=20 June 2003}} Retrieved on 4 September 2008.</ref>\n\nThe Test series against South Africa dented Anderson's reputation as England's golden boy;<ref>{{cite web |url=http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/england/content/story/124771.html |title=Don't panic! |author=Freddie Auld |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=6 August 2003}} Retrieved on 28 May 2008.</ref> in a series England drew 2\u20132 after coming from behind, Anderson finished the five-match series with 15 wickets at an average of 39.86.<ref name=\"Anderson series by series Test bowling\">{{cite web |url=http://stats.cricinfo.com/statsguru/engine/player/8608.html?class=1;template=results;type=bowling;view=series |title=Statsguru \u2013 JM Anderson \u2013 ODI Batting \u2013 Career summary |publisher=ESPNcricinfo}} Retrieved on 28 May 2008.</ref> His best figures of 5/102 came at [[Trent Bridge]] in the third Test where he used movement of the seam to claim his second five-wicket haul in his fifth Test.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/england/content/story/124964.html |title=Into the hands of fate |author=Andrew Miller |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=6 August 2003}} Retrieved on 16 May 2008.</ref> Although Anderson was England's lead wicket taker,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://stats.cricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/averages/batting_bowling_by_team.html?id=488;team=1;type=series |title=South Africa in England Test Series, 2003 \u2013 England averages |publisher=ESPNcricinfo}} Retrieved on 28 May 2008.</ref> [[Graeme Smith]] \u2013 the South African captain \u2013 particularly punished Anderson's bowling, taking 157 runs at a strike rate of 90.23 off his bowling in the series and only being dismissed once.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/ci/content/story/133550.html |title=As the dust settles ... |author=Rob Smyth |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=9 September 2003}} Retrieved on 28 May 2008.</ref> In August, despite a mixed series against South Africa, Anderson was named [[Cricket Writers' Club Young Cricketer of the Year|Young Cricketer of the Year]]; he became the first player to be unanimously voted the award.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/england/content/story/124942.html |title=Anderson voted Young Cricket of the Year |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=15 August 2003}} Retrieved on 28 May 2008.</ref> In September, Anderson was awarded a central contract with the ECB.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/england/content/story/133589.html |title=Anderson, Flintoff and Collingwood awarded central contracts |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=11 September 2003}} Retrieved on 28 May 2008.</ref> He suffered from a niggling knee injury and fatigue as the season wore on;<ref name=\"automatic choice\"/> the knee injury \u2013 to a tendon on the outside of his left knee \u2013 meant he was rested for the winter tour of [[Bangladesh national cricket team|Bangladesh]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/england/content/story/133938.html |title=Anderson to miss Bangladesh Tests |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=25 September 2003}} Retrieved on 28 May 2008.</ref> After the South Africa series and some good performances by other bowlers during the Bangladesh tour, Anderson admitted that he was no longer an automatic choice for England.<ref name=\"automatic choice\">{{cite web |url=http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/england/content/story/131870.html |title=Anderson \u2013 \"I'm not an automatic choice\" |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=14 November 2003}} Retrieved on 28 May 2008.</ref> England and Wales Cricket Board declared James Anderson as the England Cricketer of the year 2011\u201312.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/cricket/18066639|title=James Anderson\n|accessdate=17 May 2012}}</ref>\n\nAnderson has an unusual bowling action. At the moment of delivery he has his head down, eyes closed and does not look where he is bowling; he attempted to bowl with his head up but found that he lost pace in doing so, so reverted to his original action.<ref name=\"lessons in life\"/> In 2003, ex-England pace bowler [[Bob Willis]] claimed that Anderson would only be able to play for five years with his action.<ref name=\"lessons in life\"/> Between 2004 and 2005, the England coaching staff attempted to alter Anderson's bowling action.<ref name=\"consistency\">{{cite web |url=http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/england/content/story/346937.html |author=Andrew Miller |title=Anderson seeks consistency in England comeback |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=18 April 2008}} Retrieved on 3 June 2008.</ref> Anderson was selected in the One-Day and Test squads for the winter tour [[Sri Lanka national cricket team|Sri Lanka]], but injuries left him able to play in only one of the three Tests on that tour. He bowled well below his potential to collect figures of 0\u201385 in his sole appearance.\n\n===2004\u201305: West Indies, Zimbabwe and Pakistan===\n[[File:James Anderson bowl.jpg|120px|right|thumb|Anderson bowls in the [[Adelaide Oval]] nets.]]\nAlthough fit and included in both the Test and one-day squads for the tour of the West Indies,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/england/content/story/137409.html |title=England name unchanged squad for Windies tour |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=7 January 2004}} Retrieved on 29 May 2008.</ref> Anderson did not play in the Test series, having been superseded by players such as [[James Kirtley]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/england/content/story/134625.html |title=Anderson waits for his opening |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=22 April 2004}} Retrieved on 29 May 2008.</ref> He did feature in the ODI series which England drew 2\u20132, playing in 4&nbsp;matches and taking 4&nbsp;wickets at an average of 37.00;<ref>{{cite web |url=http://uk.cricinfo.com/db/ARCHIVE/2003-04/ENG_IN_WI/STATS/ENG_IN_WI_MAR-MAY2004_ODI_AVS.html |title=England in West Indies, 2003\u201304 One-Day Series Averages |publisher=ESPNcricinfo}} Retrieved on 21 December 2008.</ref> in the final match of the series, Anderson took his 50th ODI wicket, that of [[Chris Gayle]] for 41.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/79/79510.html |title=a15876, o2127: West Indies v England, England in West Indies 2003/04 (7th ODI) |publisher=CricketArchive.com}} Retrieved on 21 December 2008.</ref> After the ODI series against the West Indies, Anderson had 50&nbsp;wickets from 31&nbsp;ODIs at an average of 23.78.<ref name=\"ODI landmarks\">{{cite web |url=http://stats.cricinfo.com/statsguru/engine/player/8608.html?class=2;template=results;type=bowling;view=cumulative |title=JM Anderson: One-Day Internationals \u2013 Bowling analysis, cummulative |publisher=ESPNcricinfo}} Retrieved on 21 December 2008.</ref>\n\nAnderson retained his place in the Test squad, and his next big break came when an injury to [[Simon Jones (cricketer)|Simon Jones]] forced the Welshman out of the last three Tests of the 2004 summer series against the [[West Indian cricket team in England in 2004|West Indies]]. Despite being in the team, Anderson's bowling was used infrequently. It was clear now that Anderson had now not only lost all his form and rhythm, but consequentially all his confidence as well. A performance by a resurgent Anderson in the final Test of the summer prompted speculation that he had regained his confidence and would return to the top of his game.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/england/content/story/135342.html |title=Anderson shines on a golden day |author=Andrew Miller |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=21 August 2004}} Retrieved on 21 December 2008.</ref> He was selected for the winter tour to Zimbabwe and South Africa. Much of the post-season talk, however, was dominated by the debate over whether to go on tour to Zimbabwe. England eventually did end up in [[Harare]], after a brief stop over in [[Namibian cricket team|Namibia]]. Anderson once again struggled in his three One-Day appearances. The England management, however, continued to show faith in his ability.\n\nTravelling as a barely-used reserve on [[English cricket team in South Africa in 2004-05|the winter South Africa tour]] while seemingly struggling for form, Anderson was given another shot at redemption, after Simon Jones was dropped for the third Test after a poor performance in the second. Anderson, though, did even worse than Jones, collecting figures of 2/117 and 0/32 in his two innings. Anderson spent the following summer with Lancashire; bowling regularly a quota of overs one would associate with a new ball bowler, something he had not done enough in his England stint. He was recalled to the England squad for the last match of [[the 2005 Ashes]] series after taking 60&nbsp;wickets for Lancashire in 2005, once again as a replacement for the injured Jones, but all-rounder [[Paul Collingwood]] was selected for the team.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/england/content/story/269504.html |title=Anderson learning a tough lesson |author=Andrew McGlashan |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=9 December 2005}} Retrieved on 26 June 2008.</ref>\n\nAnderson was selected in the Test squad for the tour of Pakistan, but spinner [[Shaun Udal]] was chosen to fill the bowler's spot left empty by the still injured Simon Jones. When [[Ashley Giles]] had to miss the third Test due to injury, young [[Durham County Cricket Club|Durham]] debutant seamer [[Liam Plunkett]] was chosen ahead of Anderson and Anderson did not play a single Test on the tour.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/england/content/story/227560.html |title=Vaughan could prove the difference |author=Andrew Miller |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=28 November 2005}} Retrieved on 21 December 2008.</ref> Despite this disappointment he played in all five of England's One-Day games in Pakistan, showing improvements in form to be England's joint-leading wicket-taker in the series with Andrew Flintoff, taking 7&nbsp;wickets at 25.57.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://uk.cricinfo.com/db/ARCHIVE/2005-06/ENG_IN_PAK/STATS/ENG_IN_PAK_OCT-DEC2005_ODI_AVS.html |title=England in Pakistan, 2005\u201306 One-Day Series Averages |publisher=ESPNcricinfo}} Retrieved on 21 December 2008.</ref>\n\n===2006: India and Australia===\nAnderson was not selected for the senior side's tour to India in January 2006 as Simon Jones returned from injury and was chosen ahead of him.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/england/content/story/232847.html |title=Anderson loses Test place as Jones returns |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=13 January 2006}} Retrieved on 21 December 2008.</ref> Instead, Anderson was selected for England A's tour of the West Indies.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/england/content/story/234702.html |title=Anderson called up for England A tour |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=27 January 2006}} Retrieved on 21 December 2008.</ref> In February, days before the start of the first A-match between England and the West Indies, James Anderson (along with batsmen [[Alastair Cook]] and [[Owais Shah]]) was called up as an injury reinforcement to the England senior squad in India, after captain [[Michael Vaughan]] and fast bowler Simon Jones flew home with knee injuries and vice-captain Marcus Trescothick departed for undisclosed \"personal\" reasons.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/england/content/story/238623.html |title=Cook and Anderson fly to India |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=25 February 2006}} Retrieved on 21 December 2008.</ref> After an unconvincing display by Liam Plunkett in the second Test in [[Mohali]] Anderson was recalled for the final match of the series. He impressed in England's victory, taking figures of 4/40 in the first innings.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/magazine/content/story/241447.html |title=Anderson's resurgence |author=John Stern |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=20 March 2006}} Retrieved on 21 September 2008.</ref>\n\nAfter his impressive display in the final match in India, Anderson looked likely to feature as one of England's main bowlers in both the ODI series and Test matches against Pakistan and Sri Lanka; however an early season stress fracture of the back ruled Anderson out for all of the summer internationals and all but two matches of his county season.<ref name=\"stress frac\"/> Lancashire teammate [[Sajid Mahmood]] was called up to the England squad the replacement for Anderson.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/england/content/story/246404.html |title=Mahmood and Lewis earn call-up |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=8 May 2006}} Retrieved on 29 May 2008.</ref>\n\nAnderson was named in England's [[ICC Champions Trophy|Champions Trophy]] and Ashes squads in September 2006 although at that point he had not played any first-class cricket in six months.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/england/content/story/259631.html |title=Anderson set for Glamorgan loan |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=15 September 2006}} Retrieved on 29 May 2008.</ref> He was straight back into England colours for the 0\u20135 Ashes whitewash against [[Australia national cricket team|Australia]]. His performance, like much of the England team, was well below standard. Anderson was sent home midway through the One-Day tournament with Australia and [[New Zealand national cricket team|New Zealand]] as a precaution when he felt a twinge in his back;<ref>{{cite web |url=http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/england/content/story/280451.html |title=Anderson builds up to bowling |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=15 February 2007}} Retrieved on 31 May 2008.</ref> during the tournament he had begun to regain some of his form and in the four matches he played he took 8 wickets at an average of 20.62.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/england/content/story/277652.html |title=Anderson cool over back stiffness |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=25 January 2007}} Retrieved on 31 May 2008.</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://uk.cricinfo.com/db/ARCHIVE/2006-07/OD_TOURNEYS/CBS/STATS/CBS_JAN-FEB2007_ODI_AVS_ENG.html |title=Commonwealth Bank Series, 2006\u201307 Averages |publisher=ESPNcricinfo}} Retrieved on 31 May 2008.</ref>\n\n===2007: World Cup===\nAlthough Anderson was returned home early from the England's victorious ODI series in Australia, Anderson was selected in England's squad for the [[2007 Cricket World Cup]]. He recovered from his back injury and was expected to play ahead of the likes of [[Liam Plunkett]], [[Sajid Mahmood]] and [[Jon Lewis (cricketer, born 1975)|Jon Lewis]]. However, on 14 March 2007, only days before England's first game, it was reported by the BBC that Anderson had broken his finger during fielding practice and his involvement in the tournament was in question, although he was able to play despite the pain.<ref name=\"broken finger\">{{cite web |url=http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/england/content/story/285240.html |title=England delay Anderson decision |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=15 March 2007}} Retrieved on 26 June 2008.</ref>\n\n===2007: West Indies, India and Sri Lanka===\nWhen [[Peter Moores (cricketer)|Peter Moores]] replaced [[Duncan Fletcher]] as England coach after the World Cup, it was felt that Anderson would benefit under new management; along with the rest of the England team he was allowed to play more for his county. It was felt that it was not beneficial for players who were not representing England to just sit on the sideline and match practice would allow him to rediscover his form.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/magazine/content/story/295114.html |title=Moore's fresh outlook |author=Andrew McGlashan |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=22 May 2007}} Retrieved on 31 May 2008.</ref> Anderson did not feature in the Test series against the West Indies, but he did play in the ODI series. During the second ODI, he clashed with [[Runako Morton]] when he appeared to get in the way of Morton when the batsman was running between the wickets. Anderson was fined half of his match fee for the incident and match referee [[Mike Procter]] stated \"James Anderson is not a player with a reputation for bad behaviour...and I am sure he will do everything he can to ensure there is no repeat of this unfortunate incident\".<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/england/6274274.stm |title=Anderson fined after Morton clash |publisher=BBC |date=5 July 2007}} Retrieved on 22 August 2008.</ref> Anderson finished the series with five wickets at 30.40 as England lost the series 2\u20131.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://stats.cricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/bowling/most_wickets_career.html?id=2870;type=series |title=NatWest Series [West Indies in England], 2007 |publisher=ESPNcricinfo}} Retrieved on 22 August 2008.</ref>\n\n[[File:Anderson bowling, 2007.jpg|thumb|400px|Anderson bowling during the second Test of India's tour of England in 2007. He opened the bowling with [[Ryan Sidebottom]].]]\n\nAnderson played in all three Tests of the series with [[India national cricket team|India]], coming into the side for the injured [[Matthew Hoggard]] and leading a pace attack comprising himself, [[Ryan Sidebottom]] and [[Chris Tremlett]] with only 20 caps between them.<ref name=\"drinks are on Jimmy\">{{cite web |url=http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/magazine/content/story/303500.html |title=The drinks are on Jimmy |author=Andrew McGlashan |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=24 July 2007}} Retrieved on 31 May 2008.</ref> In the first Test of the series, Anderson claimed his 50th Test wicket when he dismissed [[Mahendra Singh Dhoni]] for 0;<ref>{{cite web |url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/103/103089.html |title=t1840, f49898: England v India, India in British Isles 2007 (1st Test) |publisher=CricketArchive.com}} Retrieved on 21 December 2008.</ref> the feat was achieved in Anderson's 17th Test match and after the match he had 53&nbsp;wickets at an average of 35.67.<ref name=\"landmark wickets\">{{cite web |url=http://stats.cricinfo.com/statsguru/engine/player/8608.html?class=1;template=results;type=bowling;view=cumulative |title=JM Anderson: Test matches \u2013 Bowling analysis, cumulative}} Retrieved on 21 December 2008.</ref> He became the first England bowler to dismiss [[Rahul Dravid]], [[Sachin Tendulkar]], and [[Sourav Ganguly]] in the same innings.<ref name=\"drinks are on Jimmy\"/> Although England lost the series, Anderson demonstrated greater consistency than before and managed 14 wickets, at 35.57 and getting the Man of the Series award.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/england/content/story/306970.html |title=The road to redemption |author=Andrew Miller |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=14 August 2007}} Retrieved on 31 May 2008.</ref> He also managed to get his name on the honours board at Lord's for the second time with his best Test figures of 5/42.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/england/content/story/303038.html |title=Zaheer gives India hope after Anderson's haul |author=Andrew McGlashan |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=21 July 2007}} Retrieved on 31 May 2008.</ref> The ODI series which followed was England's first ODI series win at home in three years. Anderson was the leading wicket-taker of either side with 14 wickets at an average of 22.57.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/england/content/story/310141.html |title=The Bell factor and India's bowling worries |author=Mathew Varghese |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=10 September 2007}} Retrieved on 31 May 2008.</ref> In the first ODI of the series, Anderson claimed his 100th ODI wicket when he dismissed [[Gautam Gambhir]] for 3;<ref>{{cite web |url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/103/103097.html |title=o2611, a18335: England v India, India in British Isles 2007 (1st ODI) |publisher=CricketArchive.com}} Retrieved on 21 December 2008.</ref> after the match, he had taken 103&nbsp;wickets from 70&nbsp;matches at an average of 27.02.<ref name=\"ODI landmarks\"/> Anderson was also included for the England squad for the [[2007 ICC World Twenty20|World Twenty20]], held in September 2007, replacing an injured [[Ravi Bopara]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/engvind/content/story/309928.html |title=Anderson replaces Bopara for Twenty20 |author=Andrew McGlashan |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=7 September 2007}} Retrieved on 31 May 2008.</ref> He played in all four of England's matches, taking three wickets at 34.00, as England failed to progress beyond the second stage of the competition.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://stats.cricinfo.com/twenty20wc/engine/records/bowling/most_wickets_career.html?id=3115;type=tournament |title=Most wickets: ICC World Twenty20, 2007/08 |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071012193551/http://stats.cricinfo.com/twenty20wc/engine/records/bowling/most_wickets_career.html?id=3115%3Btype%3Dtournament |archivedate=12 October 2007 }} Retrieved on 27 December 2008.</ref> Following a successful summer, he was one of twelve players awarded a central contract for 2007/08 by the ECB.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/england/content/story/310246.html |title=Prior misses out on central contract |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=10 September 2007}} Retrieved on 31 May 2008.</ref>\n\nAnderson was part of the squad which toured Sri Lanka in the winter. The One-Day side completed their first ever series victory in Sri Lanka; Anderson's contribution was four wickets in five matches at an average of 48.25 and tying down Sri Lanka's top order along with Sidebottom and [[Stuart Broad]], although they finished with more wickets at a lower average.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/england/content/story/314907.html |title=Collingwood's men confound expectations |author=Andrew Miller |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=10 October 2007}} Retrieved on 2 June 2008.</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://stats.cricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/bowling/most_wickets_career.html?id=3151;type=series |title=England in Sri Lanka ODI Series, 2007/08 |publisher=ESPNcricinfo}} Retrieved on 2 June 2008.</ref> Despite suffering a bruised left ankle,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/england/content/story/322999.html |title=Vaughan keeps his cards close |author=Andrew Miller |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=30 November 2007}} Retrieved on 2 June 2008.</ref> Anderson was selected for the first Test. Although he bowled economically in the first innings,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/slveng/content/current/story/323065.html |title=England's bowlers take the honours |author=Andrew McGlashan |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=1 December 2007}} Retrieved on 2 June 2008.</ref> he was expensive in the second; during the course of the second innings he became only the second bowler in Test cricket to have six boundaries taken off a single over.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/slveng/content/current/story/323473.html |title=Sri Lanka build lead on Murali's record day |author=Andrew McGlashan |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=3 December 2007}} Retrieved on 2 June 2008.</ref> He finished the match with figures of two wickets for 167 runs<ref>{{cite web |url=http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/slveng/engine/current/match/291222.html |title=England in Sri Lanka Test Series \u2013 1st Test Sri Lanka v England |publisher=ESPNcricinfo}} Retrieved on 2 June 2008.</ref> and was dropped for the final two Tests; his replacement was debutant Stuart Broad.\n\n===2008: New Zealand, South Africa and India===\nIn the spring of 2008, Anderson toured [[New Zealand national cricket team|New Zealand]] with England. He played in the Twenty20 series, which England won 2\u20130, and he was then involved in the one-day series which New Zealand won 3\u20132. Although he played in all five matches of the One-Day series, he struggled and only managed four wickets at an average of 67.50.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://stats.cricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/bowling/most_wickets_career.html?id=3309;type=series |title=England in New Zealand ODI Series, 2007/08 |publisher=Cricinfo.com Retrieved on 3 June 2008.}}</ref> In an effort to regain some form, Anderson was allowed to join [[Auckland Aces|Auckland Cricket Club]], who were lacking their strike bowlers due to international call ups, as an overseas player.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/england/content/story/341134.html |title=Anderson links up with Auckland |author=Andrew Miller |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=5 March 2008}} Retrieved on 3 June 2008.</ref> The move was controversial with critics including [[Gavin Larsen]], [[Wellington Firebirds|Wellington Cricket Club]]'s chief executive, who feared that Anderson would be able to bowl himself into form.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/england/content/story/341178.html |title=Larsen slams Anderson deal |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=6 March 2008}} Retrieved on 3 June 2008.</ref> Although he was left out for the first Test, Anderson was recalled for the second when he and Stuart Broad replaced the out of form [[Steve Harmison]] and Matthew Hoggard after England were defeated by 189 runs; the decision to axe both bowlers was heralded as the end of an era in English cricket.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/england/content/story/342058.html |title=Harmison and Hoggard axed by England |author=Andrew Miler |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=12 March 2008}} Retrieved on 3 June 2008.</ref> Anderson's selection was a surprise as it was expected that Broad would replace Harmison, but not that Hoggard would be dropped.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/england/content/story/342386.html |title=Many thanks to Auckland |author=Andrew Miler |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=14 March 2008}} Retrieved on 3 June 2008.</ref> In the first innings of the second Test, Anderson took 5/73 and finished with match figures of 7/130 and helped England to a 126-run victory.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/england/content/story/342353.html |title=Anderson five puts England in control |author=Will Luke |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=14 March 2008}} Retrieved on 3 June 2008.</ref> He sustained an ankle injury while playing football before the third Test but recovered in time to be selected. Anderson's performance in the final Test was less effective,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/england/content/story/343980.html |title=Sidebottom's transformation |author=Andrew Miller |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=26 March 2008}} Retrieved on 3 June 2008.</ref> recording match figures of 1/153 as England won the match by 121 runs and the series 2\u20131.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/england/engine/match/300444.html |title=England in New Zealand Test Series \u2013 3rd Test New Zealand v England |publisher=ESPNcricinfo}} Retrieved on 3 June 2008.</ref> Searching for consistency, Anderson's action reverted to the action he used in 2003, one with which he felt comfortable.<ref name=\"consistency\"/>\n\n[[File:Anderson bowls against New Zealand, cropped.jpg|thumb|left|Anderson bowling against New Zealand in England]]\nHe was retained for the home series, when New Zealand toured England later in 2008. He continued to enjoy success against the touring side, taking 19 wickets at 19.31 and finishing as the leading wicket-taker of the series. This was his highest return of wickets in a series.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://stats.cricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/bowling/most_wickets_career.html?id=3241;type=series |title=New Zealand in England Test Series, 2008 |publisher=ESPNcricinfo}} Retrieved on 8 June 2008.</ref> Anderson bowled well in the first Test, recording match figures of 130/5 as the match was drawn.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/engvnz/content/current/story/351200.html |title=England make spirited response to New Zealand's 277 |author=Will Luke |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=16 May 2008}} Retrieved on 8 June 2008.</ref> In the second Test, Anderson finished with match figures of 5/139 as England won by six wickets; on the first day he struck New Zealand batsman [[Daniel Flynn (cricketer)|Daniel Flynn]] in the face, knocking out a tooth, in a spell of short, aggressive bowling when he also hit [[Jacob Oram]] on the helmet.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/engvnz/content/current/story/352057.html |title=Taylor responds in kind to England's aggression |author=Will Luke |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=23 May 2008}} Retrieved on 8 June 2008.</ref> Anderson was disconcerted by injuring Flynn said that striking him \"wasn't pleasant\".<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/7417778.stm |title= Flynn injury disconcerts Anderson |publisher=BBC |date=23 May 2008}} Retrieved on 8 June 2008.</ref> In the final match of the series Anderson scored a career Test best of 28 in a partnership of 76 with Stuart Broad.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/england/7440617.stm |title=Kiwis reeling after Anderson haul |author=Jamie Lillywhite |publisher=BBC |date=6 June 2008}} Retrieved on 8 June 2008.</ref> This was followed up by career best bowling of 7/43 in the first innings and Test best match figures of 9/98 overall as he won the Man of the Match award and England secured an innings and nine run victory and a 2\u20130 series win.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/england/7442595.stm |title=England v New Zealand 3rd Test report |publisher=BBC |date=8 June 2008}} Retrieved on 8 June 2008.</ref> Anderson's performance in the series prompted England bowling coach [[Ottis Gibson]] to say that Anderson has the potential to become a world-class bowler if he can improve his self-belief.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/england/7442595.stm |title=England v New Zealand 3rd Test reaction |publisher=BBC |date=8 June 2008}} Retrieved on 8 June 2008.</ref> In the One-Day series that followed Anderson managed five wickets from five matches at an average of 41.40 as England lost the series 3\u20131.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://stats.cricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/bowling/most_wickets_career.html?id=3245;type=series |title=NatWest Series [New Zealand in England], 2008 |publisher=ESPNcricinfo}} Retrieved on 22 August 2008.</ref>\n\nAfter the Test series against New Zealand, Anderson's figures revealed that he struggled to bowl to left-handed batsmen and his contrasting fortunes between the start of his career and his resurgence. By the end of June 2008, Anderson had played 25 Test matches; in the 16 Tests before July 2007 he took 46 wickets at an average of 38.39, but since then in 9 Tests he took 43 wickets at 30.58 at a much lower strike rate.<ref name=\"achilles\">{{cite web |url=http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/magazine/content/story/354352.html |title=Splendid Anderson and his Achilles heel |author=S Rajesh |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=13 June 2008}} Retrieved on 22 August 2008.</ref> In the five Tests Anderson played against New Zealand in a four-month period, 22 of the 27 wickets he managed were against right-handed batsmen. Against the right-handers he averaged 20.77 compared to 38.60 against left-handers.<ref name=\"achilles\"/> This was an improvement however on his career statistics, since he averaged 70 wickets at 29.11 against right-handers and 19 at 54.94 against left-handers. This first became clear in the 2003 Test series against South Africa when Graeme Smith and [[Gary Kirsten]] milked him for 276 runs while only being dismissed once between them.<ref name=\"achilles\"/>\n\nAnderson's batting showed a marked improvement in the summer's home Test series against South Africa. In the second innings of the second Test, at [[Headingley Carnegie Cricket Ground|Headingley]], Anderson scored a Test-career best 34 runs, having come to the crease as a nightwatchman late on Day 3. In the course of his innings he was struck on the wrist and then on the grille of his helmet by [[Dale Steyn]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/england/content/story/361991.html |author=Andrew McGlashan |title=Ballsy batting, and a different sort of rearguard |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=21 July 2008}} Retrieved on 3 September 2008.</ref>\n\nIn the final match of the series, Anderson took his 100th Test wicket. The landmark wicket was that of [[Jacques Kallis]] [[Leg Before Wicket]] for 2;<ref>{{cite web |url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/123/123962.html |title=f50678, t1885: England v South Africa, South Africa in England 2008 (4th Test) |publisher=CricketArchive.com}} Retrieved on 21 December 2008.</ref> this feat was achieved in Anderson's 29th Test and after the match he had 104&nbsp;wickets at an average of 34.51.<ref name=\"landmark wickets\"/>\n\nEngland's One-Day series in India was cut short due to terror attacks in Mumbai. Seven matches were due to be played, but due to the terrorism England flew home after five games. They were 5\u20130 down in the series and Anderson had not taken one wicket, despite bowling in every one of the five games.\n\n===2009: West Indies===\nFollowing the sacking of [[Peter Moores (cricketer)|Peter Moores]] in January 2009,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/england/7822596.stm |title=Pietersen insists he is blameless |publisher=BBC News |date=11 January 2009 |accessdate=14 July 2013}}</ref> and the replacement of [[Kevin Pietersen]] by [[Andrew Strauss]] as England captain,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/england/7816389.stm |title=Strauss to lead West Indies tour |publisher=BBC News |date=7 January 2009 |accessdate=14 July 2013}}</ref> England left for a tour to the West Indies.\n\nFollowing two low-key performances in the warm-up matches against a St. Kitts XI<ref>{{cite news|title= Tour match: St Kitts Invitational XI v England |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/shared/fds/hi/statistics/cricket/scorecards/2009/1/15127/html/scorecard.stm |publisher=BBC Sport |accessdate=14 May 2013}}</ref> and West Indies A,<ref>{{cite news|title= Tour match: West Indies A v England |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/shared/fds/hi/statistics/cricket/scorecards/2009/1/15128/html/scorecard.stm |publisher=BBC Sport |accessdate=14 May 2013}}</ref> Anderson was dropped for the first Test in [[Jamaica]]. Surprisingly, the West Indies inflicted a large defeat on England, following a third innings batting collapse. With the form of [[Ryan Sidebottom]] a cause for concern, and some doubts over his fitness, Anderson was recalled for the second Test at the [[Sir Vivian Richards Stadium]] in [[Antigua]]. However, this match was abandoned with fewer than two overs bowled due to an unfit outfield.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/england/7886840.stm |title=Test abaondoned over poor outfield |publisher=BBC News |date=13 February 2009 |accessdate=14 July 2013}}</ref> The Test match was rearranged to take place two days later at the [[Antigua Recreation Ground]]. After making 4 as a night-watchman during England's first innings, Anderson bowled 19 wicketless overs as the West Indies were bowled out for 285, although he did take the catch of [[Chris Gayle]] off [[Steve Harmison]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cricinfo.com/ci/engine/match/390680.html |title=3rd Test: West Indies v England at St John's, Feb 15\u201319, 2009 &#124; ESPN Cricinfo |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=18 July 2011}}</ref> After making 20, again as night-watchman, in the second batting innings, England fell one wicket short of bowling the West Indies out and securing a Test victory as the tail-enders of [[Daren Powell]] and [[Fidel Edwards]] survived 10 overs to bat out the draw.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cricinfo.com/wiveng2009/content/story/391505.html |title=West Indies show hitherto hidden steel |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=14 July 2013}}</ref>\n\nAfter sitting out the tour match against the BCA President's XI in [[Barbados]], England and the West Indies played the fourth Test at the [[Kensington Oval]]. Both sides found bowling difficult on a very flat track, and the first two innings produced 1,349 runs for the loss of just 15 wickets. England batted first and made 600/6 declared, and Anderson again opened the bowling in the West Indies reply. After striking early to dismiss Chris Gayle LBW on a [[Umpire Decision Review System|referral]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cricinfo.com/ci/engine/match/352663.html |title=4th Test: West Indies v England at Bridgetown, Feb 26 \u2013 Mar&nbsp;2, 2009 |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=18 July 2011}}</ref> he also dismissed [[Shivnarine Chanderpaul]] and [[Sulieman Benn]], finishing with 3 for 125 from 37 overs. With England batting out the match, Anderson did not feature again as the Test match was drawn.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cricinfo.com/wiveng2009/content/story/393131.html |title=Cook century ensures the stalemate |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=14 July 2013}}</ref> With England still 1\u20130 down in a series they were expected by many to win comfortably, victory was needed in the fifth and final Test at [[Queen's Park Oval]] in [[Trinidad]]. After England made 546/6 declared, Anderson again struggled as the West Indies were bowled out for 544, a deficit of 2 runs, with Anderson picking up the wicket of [[wicket-keeper]] [[Dinesh Ramdin]] for 70 runs, with an economy of just 2.18, one of his best in Test cricket.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cricinfo.com/ci/engine/match/352664.html |title=5th Test: West Indies v England at Port of Spain, Mar 6\u201310, 2009 &#124; ESPN Cricinfo |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=18 July 2011}}</ref> With England setting the West Indies a target of 240 runs to win, Anderson had arguably his best innings of the tour. After dismissing opener [[Lendl Simmons]], Anderson bowled 16 overs of reverse swing, picking up two more wickets as again England fell just short of victory, this time by two wickets.\n\nWith the Test series lost, England were keen to regain some honour in the [[Twenty20|T20]] and [[One Day International|ODIs]] which remained. After taking 3 for 48 in 8 overs in a warm-up match against the WIPA President's Select XI,<ref>{{cite news|title= Tour match: WIPA President's Select v England |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/shared/fds/hi/statistics/cricket/scorecards/2009/3/15134/html/scorecard.stm |publisher=BBC Sport |accessdate=14 May 2013}}</ref> Anderson led the England attack in the T20 international. Despite finishing with decent figures of 1\u201319 in 3 overs,<ref>{{cite news |title=NatWest International Twenty20 Match: West Indies v England |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/shared/fds/hi/statistics/cricket/scorecards/2009/3/15135/html/scorecard.stm |publisher=BBC Sport |accessdate=14 May 2013}}</ref> England were beaten soundly.<ref>{{cite news|last=Brett |first=Oliver |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/england/7939028.stm |title=Sarwan condemns England to defeat |publisher=BBC News |date=15 March 2009 |accessdate=14 July 2013}}</ref> The first One-Day International, however, saw England inflict their first defeat on the West Indies of the tour. After posting 270 for 7 in their 50 overs,<ref>{{cite news|title=One Day International Series: West Indies v England |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/shared/fds/hi/statistics/cricket/scorecards/2009/3/15136/html/scorecard.stm |publisher=BBC Sport |accessdate=14 May 2013}}</ref> Rain interrupted the West Indies' reply, leading to the result being decided on the [[Duckworth\u2013Lewis method]]. With the light fading, Anderson succeeded in having [[Kieron Pollard]] caught on the boundary by Steve Harmison. Due to the intricacies of the D/L system, this wicket ensured England won the match by a single run.<ref>{{cite news|last=Brett |first=Oliver |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/england/7949237.stm |title=England win after farcical finish |publisher=BBC News |date=1 January 1970 |accessdate=14 July 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn the next two ODIs, England suffered two more defeats, with Anderson taking 3 for 37 from 9 overs in the second ODI, as well as making 8 with the bat,<ref>{{cite news |title=One Day International Series: West Indies v England |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/shared/fds/hi/statistics/cricket/scorecards/2009/3/15137/html/scorecard.stm |publisher=BBC Sport |accessdate=14 May 2013}}</ref> and went on to take 1 for 39 from 5 overs and 0 not out<ref>{{cite news |title=One Day International Series: West Indies v England |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/shared/fds/hi/statistics/cricket/scorecards/2009/3/15138/html/scorecard.stm |publisher=BBC Sport |accessdate=14 May 2013}}</ref> as England fell 2\u20131 behind in the five-match series. England therefore needed to win the fourth ODI in Barbados to keep the series alive. Bowling first, England restricted the West Indies to 239/9 in their 50 overs, with Anderson himself taking the wicket of Fidel Edwards to finish with figures of 1 for 41 with 1 maiden in the 10 he bowled. Duckworth-Lewis again helped England as they chased down 136 in 18 overs to win by nine wickets.<ref>{{cite news|title=One Day International Series: West Indies v England |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/shared/fds/hi/statistics/cricket/scorecards/2009/3/15139/html/scorecard.stm |publisher=BBC Sport |accessdate=14 May 2013}}</ref> Thus, the series was tied at 2\u20132 going into the final match in [[St. Lucia]]. The West Indies won the toss and elected to bowl first, with England able to post 172/5 in 29 overs (the innings shortened by rain). With 29 overs to chase 173 for victory, the West Indies lost Gayle to Anderson in the first over with the score at 1/1, Anderson going on to add the wicket of Kieron Pollard as he finished with match figures of 2/34 from 6 overs as England won the match by 26 runs, with Anderson's Lancashire teammate [[Andrew Flintoff]] taking a [[List of One Day International cricket hat-tricks|hat-trick]].\n\nAnderson finished the tour with 9 wickets at an average of 38.00 from the Test series, with an economy rate of 2.65 runs per over from both innings and best match figures coming in the fifth Test at Trinidad,<ref>[http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/player/8608.html?class=1;template=results;type=bowling;view=series|Bowling Test series averages]</ref> as well as accumulating 24 runs at an average of 12.00, with a highest-score of 20.<ref>[http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/player/8608.html?class=1;template=results;type=batting;view=series|Batting Test series averages]</ref> In the ODIs, Anderson took 9 wickets at 21.11 and an economy rate of 5.00 runs per over<ref>[http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/player/8608.html?class=2;template=results;type=bowling;view=series|Bowling ODI series averages]</ref> and 8 runs at an equivalent average.<ref>[http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/player/8608.html?class=2;template=results;type=batting;view=series|Batting ODI series averages]</ref>\nHe then rejected offers to play in the [[Indian Premier League|IPL]] since he wanted to commit to a bright future for England over the following summer.\n\nThe Wisden Trophy was up for grabs again a few months later when the West Indies replaced [[Zimbabwe national cricket team|Zimbabwe]], who were still excluded from participating in Test match cricket by the ICC (although originally the tour had been scheduled to be played by Sri Lanka, who pulled out to allow their players to play in the IPL), in a two-Test and three-ODI tour. Anderson was selected after a bright start to the season with Lancashire, which included figures of 11\u2013109 in a match against [[Sussex County Cricket Club|Sussex]] at Hove.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cricinfo.com/countycricket2009/engine/match/382914.html |title=Sussex v Lancashire at Hove, Apr 21\u201324, 2009 &#124; ESPN Cricinfo |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=18 July 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe first Test was held at Lord's, beginning on 6 May 2020. Anderson was not involved directly until the second day, with England batting first, but made only a single in a 19-ball innings. With the wicket showing a green tinge and some cloud cover, Anderson was expected to excel. However he struggled to find his length bowling in the first innings and finished wicketless from seven overs having conceded 32.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cricinfo.com/ci/engine/match/380712.html |title=1st Test: England v West Indies at Lord's, May 6\u20138, 2009 &#124; ESPN Cricinfo |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=18 July 2011}}</ref> An improvement in the second innings saw him take the first two wickets after the follow-on, including that of the West Indies captain Chris Gayle, and finishing with figures of 2\u201338 from 15 overs and match figures of 2\u201370 as England won by ten wickets.\n\nFrom Lord's, the teams moved to [[Riverside Ground|Chester-le-Street]] for the second and final Test of the series. England again won the toss and chose to bat, and proceeded to dominate the West Indies bowling attack, amassing 569\u20136 declared. Anderson was sent in at the end of the first day in his role as night-watchman to protect Pietersen. Batting with Alastair Cook, they made a partnership of 44, Anderson hitting 14 of them to extend his run of innings without a duck in Test cricket. Later on day three, he was given the ball as England set out to take 20 West Indian wickets and secure match victory. Anderson found some significant swing in the cloudy conditions there, and proceeded to skittle through the West Indies top order, taking the first three wickets (including Gayle again) leaving the West Indies on 68/3.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cricinfo.com/ci/engine/match/380713.html |title=2nd Test: England v West Indies at Chester-le-Street, May 14\u201318, 2009 &#124; ESPN Cricinfo |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=18 July 2011}}</ref> Two late strikes secured Anderson a five-wicket haul, his first in 19 innings since his 7-wicket haul against New Zealand at Trent Bridge the previous summer.<ref>[http://stats.cricinfo.com/ci/engine/player/8608.html?class=1;template=results;type=bowling;view=innings|Statsguru \u2013 JM Anderson \u2013 Test bowling \u2013 Bowling innings list]. ESPNcricinfo. Retrieved 30 May 2010.  {{webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20120715000329/http://stats.cricinfo.com/ci/engine/player/8608.html?class=1;template=results;type=bowling;view=innings |date= 15 July 2012 |title=Statsguru }}</ref> Anderson went on to take 4 further wickets after the West Indies were asked to follow-on (for the second time in the series) and England went on to win by an innings and 83 runs. With nine wickets in the match for 125 runs, Anderson was named the Man of the Match,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cricinfo.com/engvwi2009/content/story/405039.html |title=Anderson has Ashes in his sights |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=14 July 2013}}</ref> only the second time in his career he had achieved this in a Test match.\n\n[[File:Anderson bowls in the Ashes, 2009.jpg|thumb|300px|Anderson bowling at Edgbaston during the 2009 Ashes]]\n\nThe first match of the following ODI series at Headingley was abandoned due to heavy rain, leaving two One-Day matches to be played. Anderson was named in the England squad for the series, and was selected for both matches. In the first match at [[Bristol]], he bowled six overs for nineteen, with one maiden, but finished wicketless as the West Indies were bowled out for 160.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cricinfo.com/ci/engine/match/380715.html |title=2nd ODI: England v West Indies at Bristol, May 24, 2009 &#124; ESPN Cricinfo |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=18 July 2011}}</ref> England went on to win the match by six wickets, meaning Anderson was not needed to bat. Neither was he required to bat in the last match of the tour as England scored 328/7 from their 50 overs. Although Anderson went at a run a ball in reply, conceding 58 from 9.4 overs, he took three wickets including the last of the match (that of [[Sulieman Benn]]) as the West Indies fell 58 runs short, sealing a 2\u20130 victory for England in both the Test and ODI series.\n\n===2009\u201310: South Africa===\nAnderson went on the tour of South Africa as one of the leaders of the English attack, having established himself in all formats of the game. In the opening T20 International, Anderson failed to pick up a wicket, although he was fairly economical, going at 8 runs an over. Anderson improved in the following match, bowling 4 for 28 runs, picking up a wicket. He was the pick of the English bowlers as South Africa won the match, posting over 200. Anderson bowled well in the ODI series, picking up regular wickets. He claimed 3\u201360 in the second ODI, and 5\u201323 in the fourth match. The four-match Test series was drawn 1\u20131, with Anderson bowling well. He picked up 5 wickets for 63 runs during the 3rd Test, as well as 4\u201373 in the opening match.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/rsaveng09/content/story/437662.html |title=Anderson almost missed one-dayers |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=19 May 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/england/content/story/453492.html |title=Anderson still in the dark over knee problem |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=19 May 2013}}</ref>\n\n===2010: Bangladesh and Pakistan===\nAnderson was selected in the England squad for the 2010 T20 World Cup, despite not being regarded as a specialist in this format of cricket. He did not play in the opening group match against the West Indies. With England playing well in the tournament, and with the three-man seam attack of Stuart Broad, Ryan Sidebottom and Tim Bresnan performing, Anderson could not break into the side. England went on to win the tournament, beating Australia in the final.\n\nEngland faced Bangladesh in a two-match Test series. England were expected to win easily and cruised to victory in the first Test, with Anderson taking figures of 4\u201378 and 1\u201384. Anderson also played in the second Test, finishing with figures of 1\u201345 and 3\u201316. England won the series 2\u20130. Anderson played in the first ODI, but was expensive, taking figures of 3\u201374. He was wicketless in the second game as England suffered a shock defeat. Anderson did not play in the decider, which England won to take the series.\n\nEngland then played Pakistan at home. It was during this series that Anderson established himself as one of the world's best Test bowlers. In the first match he took 5\u201354 and 6\u201317 which England won. This left Anderson with match figures of 11\u201371. He helped England win the second Test, achieving figures of 4\u201320 in the first innings. Anderson continued to impress in the final two Tests continuing to be economical and providing a wicket-taking threat. Anderson was rested for the first ODI, but returned in the second, taking 1\u201336 in ten overs. He then took 3\u201326 in the third match, before playing the remaining matches of the series. Although Anderson struggled to take wickets, his economical bowling frustrated the opposition and kept the run rate down. By the end of the tour, Anderson had established himself as the leader of the England attack, with his swing bowling making him one of the most feared bowlers in the world.\n\n===2010\u201311: Australia===\nAs expected, Anderson was selected in the England squad to play Australia, where he developed his own wobble-seam delivery to combat the Kookaburra ball that doesn't swing as much for as long.<ref>{{Citation|last=ajit ray|title=James Anderson Masterclass \u2013 Part 1|date=16 November 2016|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=TELre9qg0LI|accessdate=7 August 2017}}</ref> Anderson played well in the opening tour games and took two wickets in the opening Test match, which finished as a draw. In the second Test England thrashed Australia, winning by an innings and 71 runs. Anderson took 4\u201351 in the first innings and Australia were never able to recover. England lost the third Test, but Anderson still impressed taking 4 wickets. Anderson took 4\u201344 in the fourth Test, which England won to retain the Ashes. He then took 4\u201366 and 3\u201361 as England won the fifth Test and series 3\u20131. During the series Anderson became the second youngest England bowler to claim 200 Test wickets.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/cricket/international/england/8211822/The-Ashes-2010-James-Andersons-200-Test-wicket-milestone-fails-to-paper-over-England-fielding-faults.html |title=The Ashes 2010: James Anderson's 200 Test wicket milestone fails to paper over England fielding faults |author=Scyld Berry |newspaper=The Telegraph |accessdate=25 May 2013 |location=London |date=18 December 2010}}</ref> Anderson was rested at the start of the ODI series, but with England struggling he was recalled, taking 2\u201357 in the third match. In the sixth match Anderson took 1\u201391 of his ten overs as the England team struggled. Anderson took 3\u201348 in the final match of the series, but it wasn't enough to prevent another defeat as England lost the one-day series 6\u20131.\n\n===2011: World Cup, Sri Lanka and India===\nAnderson was selected in the squad for the 2011 World Cup and played in the opening game against the Netherlands. He was involved in the dramatic tie against India, where both teams posted 338, and also played as England suffered an embarrassing defeat against Ireland. His best match of the tournament came when he helped England defend 171 against South Africa, where he bowled six overs, collecting figures of 2\u201316. He was left out of the team against the West Indies, which England won. Anderson did not appear in England's final match against Sri Lanka, in which they lost by ten wickets and so bowed out at the quarter-final stage of the competition. Overall, Anderson had a disappointing tournament, although the pitches did not suit his style of bowling being unable to get the ball to swing.\n\nAnderson was part of the England team when Sri Lanka toured in 2011. Anderson took 3\u201366 in the first innings, but was unable to bowl in the second due to an injury. England won the first Test after Sri Lanka collapsed for 82 all out in the second innings. Anderson was ruled out of the second Test through injury but returned for the third, taking figures of 2\u201356 and 2\u201381 as England drew the match, but won the series 1\u20130. Anderson took 4\u201318 in the first ODI but was wicketless in the second match. In the fourth match he returned to his best, taking 3\u201324. In the final match he took 2\u201355, helping England to a series win.\n\nEngland's next opponents were India. England needed to win the four match series by two games to overtake India in the world rankings and become the new top-ranked Test team. Anderson shone in the first Test, taking 5\u201365 as England took a 1\u20130 lead. Anderson took 5 more wickets in the second Test and a further 6 in the third as England took a 3\u20130 series lead. Anderson took 3 more wickets in the final Test as England won the series 4\u20130 and became the new world Number Ones. Following Anderson's performance, he was widely considered the premier fast bowler in the world. Anderson took 3\u201348 in the third ODI but was left out of the final game of the series as had already won, taking a 2\u20130 lead into the final match, which they also won by 6 wickets.\n\n===2011\u201312: Pakistan and Sri Lanka===\nEngland toured Pakistan at the back end of 2012. The series was held in [[UAE|the UAE]]. England struggled in the conditions and slumped to a heavy defeat in the first Test, with Anderson largely ineffectual. England again lost the second Test, with poor performances from the batsmen giving the bowlers little to work with. Anderson took his best figures of the tour, 3\u201335 in the final match of the series, but it wasn't enough to prevent a whitewash for Pakistan. After the series, England moved on to Sri Lanka for a two-match Test series. Anderson took 5\u201372 in the first innings but it wasn't enough to prevent a fourth straight defeat for England. Anderson was praised for his performance in conditions which did not favour seam bowlers. England won the final Test to level the series, with Anderson taking figures of 4\u201398 in the match. As a result of his performances, Anderson was named England Cricketer of the Year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/england/content/story/564834.html |title=Anderson voted Player of the Year |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=19 May 2013}}</ref>\n\n===2012: West Indies and South Africa===\nIn the second Test against West Indies, Anderson took 4\u201343 at Trent Bridge, a ground where he always performed due to the swing-friendly conditions. With England taking a 2\u20130 series lead, Anderson was rested for the final match of the series to help him avoid burnout.  Anderson played in the ODI series against the West Indies, taking 2\u201338 in the second match. England then played Australia in 5 ODIs. Anderson took 2\u201355 in the first match, and 2\u201334 in the fourth match. There were suggestions that Anderson would play no part in the series, both to rest him and to deprive Australia of facing him ahead of the Ashes series the following year. However, despite this, Anderson played a key part in the series.\n\nEngland faced South Africa at the end of the summer, with their Number One ranking on the line. The series was also anticipated as a chance to see Anderson go head to head with Dale Steyn, regarded as the world's two best seam bowlers. The series was a disappointment for England. They lost the first Test by an innings, with Anderson managing figures of 1\u2013116. The second Test was a tighter affair, with the match ending in a draw, but Anderson could only manage three wickets in the match. England lost the third Test, meaning a 2\u20130 series defeat, and South Africa earned their place at the top of the Test rankings. Anderson took 4\u201344 in the third ODI, and 2\u201341 in the fifth as the series ended as 2\u20132 draw. This was seen as a positive result for England, with several young players being blooded against an experienced South African team.\n\n===2012\u201313: India, New Zealand and Champions Trophy===\nFollowing the defeat to South Africa, Andrew Strauss retired and was replaced as captain by Alistair Cook. The first series under the leadership of Cook was against India. England lost the first Test by 9 wickets, with Anderson taking just one wicket in the match. England won the second Test convincingly, but Anderson again struggled in conditions more suited to spinners. Anderson performed much better in the third Test, taking six wickets overall. Anderson took the wicket of [[Sachin Tendulkar]] in the 1st innings of the third Test to equal [[Muttiah Muralitharan]] as the most successful bowler against Tendulkar with a total of eight dismissals. With England needing just a draw to win the series in the final Test, Anderson took 4\u201381 to help England draw the match and win the series 2\u20131.\n\nIn the tour of New Zealand, Anderson returned to the ODI side. In February 2013 during England's loss of the [[English cricket team in New Zealand in 2012\u201313#1st ODI|1st One day international in New Zealand]], with the wicket of [[BJ Watling]], his 529th in international cricket, Anderson overtook [[Ian Botham]] to become England's all-time highest wicket-taker.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2013/feb/19/james-anderson-ian-botham-england-record |title=James Anderson 'honoured' to overhaul Sir Ian Botham's England record |accessdate=18 May 2013|work=The Guardian|location=London|date=19 February 2013}}</ref> He took 5\u201334 in the second match as England went on to win the series. Anderson took 4\u2013137 in the first Test and went on to take wickets in every innings in the series. The series itself finished 0\u20130, with the batsmen dominating on good batting wickets.\n\n[[File:Anderson bowling, 2013.jpg|thumb|300px|Anderson bowling during the Champions Trophy match in which he became England's leading wicket-taker in ODIs]]\n\nAnderson played a key role in the 2013 Champions Trophy. He took 3\u201330 against Australia as England made a winning start to their campaign. During the match [[2013 ICC Champions Trophy|ICC Champions Trophy match against Australia]] he became England's leading ODI wicket-taker when he took his 235th wicket.<ref name=\"ODIWickets\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/cricket/22829402 |title=James Anderson becomes England's leading ODI wicket-taker |accessdate=8 June 2013|publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref> In the final Group A match he took 3\u201332 as England reached the semi-finals of the competition. England shocked South Africa and won by 7 wickets, with Anderson taking 2\u201314 off 8 overs. England played India, the favourites for the competition in the final, in what proved to be a rain interrupted match. Only being able to bowl four overs, Anderson took 1\u201324, but a poor batting performance meant that England lost the match and India went on to become champions.\n\nIn the opening match of the Test series against New Zealand, Anderson took match figures of 7\u201370. One the second day of the [[New Zealand cricket team in England in 2013#1st Test|1st Test against New Zealand]], he became the fourth English bowler to take 300 Test wickets when he dismissed [[Peter Fulton]].<ref name=\"Anderson300\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/cricket/22573162 |title=James Anderson takes 300th Test wicket for England |accessdate=17 May 2013|publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref> England went on to win the series 2\u20130. Anderson took 3\u201331 in the first ODI, and also played in the second match. England lost the series 2\u20131.\n\n===2013\u201314: Australia===\nDuring the summer of 2013, England played Australia in the first of what would be back-to-back Ashes Series. The first Test of the [[2013 Ashes Series|home series]] was held at Trent Bridge. Despite being favourites, England struggled in the first innings, posting just 215. Anderson led the fightback, taking 5\u201385 as England bowled Australia out for 280. As Australia closed in on winning the match in the second innings, Anderson took 5\u201373, including the winning wicket. Anderson was required to bowl a long spell to win England the match, and Kevin Pietersen later posted a picture of Anderson lying exhausted on the floor. England won the second Test, although this time Anderson was less influential, taking only three wickets. Anderson was again quiet in the third Test, in which England managed to hold on to a draw following a long rain delay. Anderson took 2\u201365 in the fourth Test as England went 3\u20130 up in the series. Following the game, there was speculation Anderson would be rested for the final Test to ensure he would be fresh for the return series in Australia. However, Anderson played and took 4\u201395 in the first innings, as the match ended in a draw and England won the series 3\u20130. Anderson was rested for the ODI series as back up bowlers such as Ben Stokes and Boyd Rankin were given the chance to play.\n\nAnderson again toured Australia as part of the [[2013\u201314 Ashes series]]. It proved to be a miserable tour for Anderson and the rest of his England teammates. Anderson was ineffectual in the first Test as England lost convincingly. He took 3 wickets in the second Test but it was clear the conditions did not suit his game. In the third Test he bowled 19 wicketless overs and conceded 105 runs as England lost the series. He took 4\u201367 in the fourth Test but was unable to prevent defeat as the English batsmen continued to struggle. In the fifth Test Australia completed the whitewash, with Anderson taking three wickets in the match. Anderson was rested for the ODI series, which England again struggled in, losing 4\u20131.\n\n===2014: Sri Lanka and India===\n\nFollowing the Ashes series, England played Sri Lanka at home. In the first match of the series Anderson had figures of 1\u201322. In the second ODI between England and Sri Lanka, Anderson took two wickets for 38 runs. He finished with figures of 2\u201310 in the next match as England won by 10 wickets. He took 2\u201360 in the next match as Sri Lanka levelled the series at 2\u20132. England lost the final match of the series, with Anderson finishing with figures of 1\u201333. After picking up figures of 3\u201393 in the Sri Lankan first innings, he took 4\u201325 in the second as England fell narrowly short of victory as the first Test ended in a draw. In the second Test, he took 2\u201349 in the first innings before taking 3\u201391 in the second. As England battled to save the Test, Anderson faced 55 balls but was dismissed on the penultimate ball of the match as England lost the match. Anderson was named England's man of the series after taking 12 wickets in the series.\n\nOn 12 July 2014, in the First Test of the [[Indian cricket team in England in 2014|series against India]], Anderson and teammate [[Joe Root]] broke numerous records in England's first innings of the first Test against [[Indian national cricket team|India]] at Trent Bridge. Anderson hit his maiden first-class fifty as well as posting the highest score (81 runs) by an England No 11 batsman in Test history. His innings was also the longest innings by a No 11 batsman in Test history. Timed at 230 minutes, it surpassed the previous record set by Mushtaq Ahmed in 1997 (183 minutes) by almost an hour. He and Root also set a new [[world record]] for a 10th-wicket partnership in Test cricket scoring 198 runs, beating the 163 run-partnership by Australians [[Phillip Hughes]] and [[Ashton Agar]] at [[Trent Bridge]] on 11 July 2013. Anderson and fellow bowler Stuart Broad were criticised for their performance in the second Test after failing to capitalise on a good bowling surface. Anderson finished with match figures of 5\u2013137 as England lost the match, increasing the pressure on the team. He returned to his best in the next Test as England levelled the series as he took figures of 5\u201353 in the first innings and 2\u201324 in the second. His first-innings spell was nominated to be one of the best Test bowling performance of the year 2014 by ESPNCricinfo.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/awards2014/content/story/819605.html|title=All hail the left-armers|website=www.espncricinfo.com|access-date=2020-02-24}}</ref>\nIn the fourth match of the series he took match figures of 5\u201364 as England won the match by an innings to go 2\u20131 up in the series. Anderson was again pivotal as England won the final match of the series, taking four wickets in the match. After the conclusion of the 5th Test, Anderson was named Man of the Series for taking 25 wickets. Anderson had a mixed ODI series against India. After the first match was abandoned, Anderson was wicket less in the first three games of the series, taking figures of 0\u201357, 0\u201329 and 0\u201338 as England went 3\u20130 down in the series. However, he bowled well in the final match of the series, taking figures of 2\u201339 as England won the match.\n\n===2015: Tri-Series===\nFollowing injury, Anderson returned to the England team for the second match of the Tri-Series against India, where he had figures of 4\u201318 to help England win. In the next match against Australia he was wicket less as England were defeated. In the game against India, Anderson picked up figures of 1\u201324 to help England qualify for the final. In the final, Anderson picked up two wickets but England lost the match and finished runners-up.\n\n===2015: World Cup===\nAnderson failed to take a wicket in the first match against Australia, finishing with figures of 0\u201367. In the next match against New Zealand he finished with figures of 0\u201337 as England suffered a humiliating eight wicket defeat. He took his first wickets of the tournament against Scotland as he collected figures of 2\u201330 as England won their first game of the tournament. He was again wicket less in England's defeat to Sri Lanka. In their must win game against Bangladesh, Anderson took figures of 2\u201345 but was later the last man out as England lost the game to exit the World Cup. In their final group game against Afghanistan, Anderson bowled economically, finishing with figures of 1\u201318 as England won their final match of the tournament.\n\n===2015: West Indies and New Zealand===\nIn April 2015, during the drawn first Test of the [[English cricket team in the West Indies in 2014\u201315|West Indies tour]] in [[Antigua]] (Anderson's 100th match), he had West Indies captain [[Denesh Ramdin]] caught at [[Slip (cricket)|slip]] for his 384th Test wicket, thus overtaking another [[Ian Botham]] record and becoming England's all-time highest Test match wicket-taker.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/cricket/32361929 |title=James Anderson proud to surpass Sir Ian Botham's Test record |accessdate=18 April 2015|publisher=BBC Sport|location=London|date=18 April 2015}}</ref> Despite Anderson's best efforts, the match ended in a draw. In the second Test Anderson took 2\u201347 West Indies first innings as they were bowled out for 299. His figures of 4\u201343 in the second innings helped England put themselves in a match winning position. They won the game by nine wickets to go 1\u20130 up in the series. In the final Test, Anderson took 6\u201342 in the West Indies first innings as England took a first innings lead. However, England collapsed in their second innings and although Anderson took a wicket in the West Indies second innings, it wasn't enough to prevent a five wicket defeat as the series ended in a 1\u20131 draw. He was awarded with the player of the series award.\n\n[[New Zealand cricket team in England in 2015|New Zealand toured England]] for a 2 test and 5 ODI series. Anderson took 1\u201388 in New Zealand's first innings in the first Test between the two sides. In the second innings he took 1\u201331 as England won the match by 124 runs to go 1\u20130 up in the series. In the second Test he took 2\u201343 as New Zealand were bowled out for 350. He made an unbeaten ten with the bat to help England reach 350 and level the scores. In New Zealand's second innings he took 2\u201396 as New Zealand won the Test to level the series at 1\u20131. During the series Anderson took his 400th Test wicket and scored his 1000th Test run.\n\n===2015: Australia===\nIn the first Test Anderson took figures of 3\u201343 in Australia's first innings to help restrict them to 308, and England went on to win the game by 169 runs. In the second Test he failed to take a wicket in the whole match, finishing with figures of 0\u201399 in the first innings and 0\u201348 in the second innings as Australia won the match by 405 runs. In the third Test, Anderson took 6\u201347 in the Australian first innings to help restrict them to 136. He took 1\u201315 in the second innings but injured himself in the process. Although England won the game to go 2\u20131 up in the series, Anderson was ruled out of the remainder of the series through injury. England went on to win the series 3\u20132.\n\n===2015: Pakistan===\nAnderson recovered from his injury in time for the Test series against Pakistan. In the first innings of the first Test, Anderson took figures of 2\u201342 and bowled economically as Pakistan were dismissed for 523. In the second innings he took figures of 2\u201330 as Pakistan were bowled out for 173, but England did not have enough time to force a win and the match finished in a draw. In the second Test Anderson took 1\u201340 in the first innings, before finishing with figures of 2\u201322 in Pakistan's second innings as they were dismissed for 354. However, England's batting was unable to chase down the target and the suffered a 127 run defeat. England needed to win the final Test of the series to level it, and Pakistan were dismissed cheaply for 234 in the first innings, with Anderson taking 4\u201317. However, they recovered in their second innings, scoring 355, despite Anderson taking 2\u201352. An England second innings collapse saw Pakistan win the series 2\u20130.\n\n===2015\u201316: South Africa===\nAnderson was injured for the first Test against South Africa. He returned to the side for the second Test but failed to make an impact, taking 1\u201377 as the match ended in a draw. In the third Test Anderson took 1\u201360 in South Africa's first innings, before taking 1\u201326 in their second innings as they collapsed to 83 all out to hand England a historic victory on South Africa soil. Anderson took his best figures of the series in the final Test, finishing with 3\u201347 in South Africa's second innings, but a poor batting performance from England saw South Africa win the Test by 280 run, although England won the series 2\u20131.\n\n===2016: Sri Lanka and Pakistan===\nIn the first Test against Sri Lanka, Anderson was in sublime form, taking figures of 5\u201316 in the tourist's first innings to restrict them to 91. In their second innings, he took figures of 5\u201329 as England secured a comprehensive victory by a margin of an innings and 88 runs. In the second Test, Anderson took 3\u201336 in Sri Lanka's first innings, and followed this up with 5\u201358 in their second innings as England secured another win, this time by nine wickets. In the final, rain affected match of the series, Anderson took figures of 2\u201361 in Sri Lanka's first innings, and then took the only wicket to fall in Sri Lanka's second innings as the match ended in a draw. Following his exploits, Anderson ended the series as the World's Number One Test bowler.\n\nAfter missing the first Test through injury, Anderson returned in the second match of the series and took four wickets in the match as England won to level the series at 1\u20131. In the third match, he took figures of 2\u201354 in Pakistan's first innings and then took 2\u201331 in their second innings as England recorded a 141 run victory. England lost the final match of the series, with Anderson taking just one wicket in the match as the series finished 2\u20132.\n\n===2016: India===\nAfter missing the series against Bangladesh through injury, Anderson returned to the side for the second Test against India. He took 3\u201362 in the first innings as India made 455. He then took 1\u201333 in the second innings. India won the match by 246 runs. In the third Test he did not take a wicket in India's first innings, and with India needing a small target to win the game in the second innings, Anderson again failed to take a wicket as India won by eight wickets. In the fourth Test he took 0\u201363 as India posted 631 and won the game by an innings and 36 runs. Anderson missed the final Test through injury, with England losing the series 4\u20130.\n\n===2017\u201318: Australia===\nAnderson was named as England Test vice-captain after Ben Stokes was suspended indefinitely. Stokes was arrested in the early hours of the morning following the third ODI against West Indies at Bristol in September 2017 from an incident near a night club, at which teammate [[Alex Hales]] was also present.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2017/sep/26/ben-stokes-england-arrested-night-bristol|title=England's Ben Stokes arrested in Bristol after win over West Indies|website=The Guardian|accessdate=26 September 2017}}</ref>&nbsp;\n\nMidway through the Ashes tour England Lions batsman [[Ben Duckett]] was suspended after pouring a drink over Anderson in a Perth bar. Although coach [[Trevor Bayliss]] described the incident as trivial, coming as it did after the Stokes affair and a head-butting incident between [[Cameron Bancroft (cricketer)|Cameron Bancroft]] and [[Jonny Bairstow]], it seemed to confirm that England had off-field issues during the 2017\u201318 Ashes.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Shemilt |first1=Stephan |title=Ashes: Ben Duckett suspended from playing on England Lions tour |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/cricket/42298950 |publisher=BBC Sport |accessdate=31 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nAnderson played all five Test matches in the Ashes but couldn't prevent his team losing control of the urn, with England slipping to a 4\u20130 series defeat. Despite the poor performance of the team as a whole, Anderson emerged with some considerable personal credit having returned figures of 17 wickets at an average of 27.82 over the Test series, including a haul of 5/43 in the 2nd innings of the day-night 2nd Test at Adelaide.<ref>{{cite web |title=James Anderson out to prove doubters wrong after maiden five-wicket haul in Australia |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/cricket/2017/12/05/james-anderson-prove-doubters-wrong-maiden-five-wicket-haul/ |website=The Telegraph |accessdate=31 July 2018}}</ref> He ended the tour as the top England wicket-taker in the Ashes. Over the entire series Anderson bowled 223.3 overs, the most in a series in his career.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Shemilt |first1=Stephan |title=Ashes: The winners and losers from the 2017\u201318 series |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/cricket/42602440 |publisher=BBC Sport |accessdate=31 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n===2018: New Zealand===\nDuring the [[English cricket team in New Zealand in 2017\u201318#2nd Test|second Test against New Zealand in 2018]], Anderson \u2013 along with partner [[Stuart Broad]] and the two opening bowlers from the opposition ([[Trent Boult]] and [[Tim Southee]]) \u2013 was part of just the third quartet of opening bowlers to take all 20 wickets in the first innings of each team in a single Test match (and the first since 1912).<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/content/story/1142229.html|title=New-ball nirvana: Anderson, Broad, Boult, Southee take all 20 wickets|publisher=ESPNcricinfo|access-date=3 April 2018}}</ref> In the same Test series, Anderson set another milestone by becoming the most heavily-used fast bowler ever in Test history, surpassing [[Courtney Walsh]]'s record of 30,019 deliveries in a Test career.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.timesnownews.com/sports/article/new-zealand-vs-england-james-anderson-overtakes-courtney-walsh-bowls-most-legal-deliveries-in-tests-as-pacer/213308|title=New Zealand vs England: James Anderson overtakes Courtney Walsh, bowls most legal deliveries in Tests as pacer|access-date=3 April 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/sports/cricket/england-in-new-zealand/james-anderson-becomes-most-over-worked-seam-bowler/articleshow/63590186.cms|title=James Anderson becomes most over-worked seam bowler |work=The Times of India|access-date=3 April 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.geo.tv/latest/189258-englands-james-anderson-sets-new-record|title=England's James Anderson sets new record|website=geo.tv|access-date=3 April 2018}}</ref> He was the second highest wicket-taker in the 2 match Test series, taking 8 wickets with England eventually losing the series 1\u20130.\n\n===2018: Pakistan and India===\nAnderson was selected in the England squad to face [[Pakistani cricket team in England in 2018|Pakistan in May 2018]] in a two Test match series. In the [[Pakistani cricket team in England in 2018#1st Test|first Test]] match, which Pakistan won, Anderson had team leading match figures of 4\u201394. In the [[Pakistani cricket team in England in 2018#2nd Test|second Test]] he took 5 wickets at the expense of 78 runs, to help England win by an innings and 55 runs. Overall Anderson took a team leading 9 wickets during the series, with the series being tied 1\u20131.\n\nAnderson was in the side as England played their 1,000th Test match<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sports.ndtv.com/england-vs-india-2018/india-vs-england-england-set-to-play-1000th-test-match-stuart-broad-picks-his-best-1889392|title=England Set To Play 1000th Test, Stuart Broad Picks His Best|website=ndtv.com|access-date=25 March 2019}}</ref>, during the first Test against India at Edgbaston in the [[Indian cricket team in England in 2018|five-match series]]. During the second Test, Anderson picked up his 100th wicket at Lord's in Tests<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2018/aug/12/jimmy-anderson-england-100th-wicket-at-lords-india|title=Jimmy Anderson century of Lord's Test wickets a first for the fast man|website=The Guardian|access-date=25 March 2019}}</ref>, and his 550th Test match wicket<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/sport/cricket/james-anderson-and-chris-woakes-dominate-india-as-england-seal-second-test-victory-at-lords-a3909566.html|title=James Anderson and Chris Woakes dominate India as England seal second Test victory at Lord's|website=London Evening Standard|access-date=25 March 2019}}</ref> as he took 5\u201320 in the first innings, and finished with match figures of 9\u201343. The third Test at Trent Bridge was won by India as they recovered from a 2\u20130 start to the series, Anderson took his 100th wicket against India in Tests.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/cricket/india-vs-england-james-anderson-enters-club-100-against-india-at-trent-bridge/story-SshsjIB4C8CsbXQSqgRw9H.html|title=India vs England: James Anderson enters Club 100 against India at Trent Bridge|website=Hindustan Times|access-date=25 March 2019}}</ref> In the fifth Test, Anderson equalled Glenn McGrath's record for the most Test wickets by a pace bowler (563), he then surpassed this later in the game when he took his 564th Test wicket.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/cricket/45464628|title=England v India: James Anderson breaks Glenn McGrath's record in host's win|publisher=BBC|access-date=25 March 2019}}</ref> Anderson took 24 wickets at an average of 18.13 during the series, the most wickets by any bowler during the series as England beat India 4\u20131.\n\n===2018\u201319: Sri Lanka and West Indies===\nAnderson played the first two Tests of the [[England cricket team in Sri Lanka in 2018-19#Test Series|three-match series]] in Sri Lanka. In the first Test, he took match figures of 1/53 from 22 overs, helping England to their first ever Test win in Galle.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/cricket/46148457|title=\nsri Lanka v England: Tourists complete 211-run win to end losing away streak|publisher=BBC|access-date=26 March 2019}}</ref> The second Test saw a record breaking 38 wickets taken by [[spin bowling|spin bowlers]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.crictracker.com/sri-lanka-vs-england-2018-2nd-test-statistical-highlights|title=Sri Lanka vs England 2018: 2nd Test \u2013 Statistical Highlights|website=crictracker.com|access-date=27 March 2019}}</ref>, with Anderson going wicketless for the first time in almost two years.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.howstat.com/cricket/statistics/players/PlayerProgressBowl.asp?PlayerID=3065|title=James Anderson bowling \u2013 Progressive Average and Aggregate|website=howstat.com|access-date=26 March 2019}}</ref> Anderson was rested for the third Test, to allow Stuart Broad match practice.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cricket.com.au/news/james-anderson-rested-third-test-england-sri-lanka-test-series-colombo/2018-11-21|title=England's Anderson rested for third Test|website=cricket.com.au|access-date=26 March 2019}}</ref> This meant Anderson finished with just 1 wicket in the series, the lowest in a Test series he had participated in since 2003.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.howstat.com/cricket/statistics/players/PlayerProgressBowl.asp?PlayerID=3065|title=James Anderson \u2013 Progressive Average and Aggregate|website=howstat.com|access-date=26 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nAnderson took a five-wicket haul during the first innings of the [[English cricket team in the West Indies in 2018-19#Test Series|three-match Test series]] against the West Indies at [[Kensington Oval]], Barbados. This was his 27th five-wicket haul, tying Ian Botham's record for England in Test matches.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thecricketer.com/Topics/england/james_anderson_takes_27th_test_five-wicket-haul_to_tie_with_sir_ian_botham_at_the_top.html|title=James Anderson takes 27th Test five-wicket-haul to tie with Sir Ian Botham at the top|website=thecricketer.com|access-date=26 March 2019}}</ref> Whilst en route to his five-wicket haul, he also became the first English bowler to take 200 Test wickets away from home.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/cricket/46979512|title=England in West Indies: James Anderson takes four wickets to boost tourists|publisher=BBC|access-date=26 March 2019}}</ref> Despite this, England lost the match by 381 runs, the West Indies' largest  victory in terms of runs at home. Anderson finished the series, which England lost 2\u20131, with 10 wickets at an average of 24.50.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.howstat.com/cricket/statistics/players/PlayerSeries.asp?PlayerID=3065#bowl|title=James Anderson \u2013 Performance Analysis by Series|website=howstat.com|access-date=26 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Achievements==\n{{main|List of international cricket five-wicket hauls by James Anderson}}\n\n*The most Test wickets taken by a pace bowler. (584 wickets) \n*He is currently the 4th highest Test wicket-taker of all time.\n*Anderson has taken 28 Test and 2 ODI five-wicket hauls including 3 Test ten-wicket hauls. \n*He is the only seam bowler to take 300+ Test wickets on home soil.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/england-v-south-africa-2017/content/story/1111078.html|title=Amla's latest landmark, and Anderson's home comforts|publisher=ESPNcricinfo|access-date=11 April 2017}}</ref>\n*He holds the world record for \"not out\" batting performances in Test cricket, achieving his 62nd Test \"not out\" at Lord's in 2017, passing the previous record of 61 set by [[Courtney Walsh]]. He has subsequently extended this record to 87.\n*He is the first England player to take 500 Test wickets.\n*The most international Test deliveries bowled by a pace bowler.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/story/_/id/23007257/anderson-hard-yards-set-new-record|title=Anderson's hard yards set new record|publisher=ESPNcricinfo|access-date=3 April 2018}}</ref>\n*First pace bowler, and second player overall, to take 100 Test wickets at a single venue (at [[Lord's]]; [[Muttiah Muralitharan]] has taken 100 wickets at three separate grounds in Sri Lanka)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2018/aug/12/jimmy-anderson-england-100th-wicket-at-lords-india|title=Jimmy Anderson century of Lord's Test wickets a first for the fast men {{!}} Andy Bull|last=Bull|first=Andy|date=12 August 2018|website=The Guardian|access-date=13 August 2018}}</ref>\n*He has taken 201 overseas wickets.\n\n==Awards==\nOn 8 December 2011 He was awarded the [[Freedom of the City|Freedom of the Borough]] of [[Borough of Burnley|Burnley]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-lancashire-15991447|title=Anderson gets freedom of Burnley|date=2011-12-01|work=BBC News|access-date=2020-02-24|language=en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.burnley.gov.uk/about-council/council-meetings/ful-council-special-meeting-8th-december-2011|title=Ful Council Special Meeting 8th December 2011 {{!}} Burnley Borough Council|website=www.burnley.gov.uk|access-date=2020-02-24}}</ref>\nIn the [[2015 Birthday Honours|2015 Queen's Birthday Honours]], Anderson was appointed an [[Officer of the Order of the British Empire]] (OBE) \"for services to cricket\".<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=61256 | date=12 June 2015 |page=B10| supp=y}}</ref> On 11 February 2016 he received his OBE at [[Buckingham Palace]].<ref name=\"OBEBP\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/england/content/story/971623.html |title=James Anderson receives OBE at Buckingham Palace |accessdate=11 February 2016|publisher=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|James Anderson (cricketer)}}\n* {{cricinfo|id=8608}}\n* [http://jamesanderson613.com/ James Anderon's Official Website]\n\n{{Navboxes colour\n|title= Awards and Achievements\n|bg= skyblue\n|fg= #15295E\n|bordercolor=#15295E\n|list1=\n{{Bowlers who have taken 300 wickets in Test cricket}}\n{{English Test match double}}\n{{Englishmen with 100 or more Test caps}}\n}}\n{{Navboxes colour\n|title= England squads\n|bg= skyblue\n|fg= #15295E\n|bordercolor=#15295E\n|list1=\n{{England Squad 2003 Cricket World Cup}}\n{{England Squad 2007 Cricket World Cup}}\n{{England Squad 2010 ICC World Twenty20}}\n{{England Squad 2011 Cricket World Cup}}\n{{England Squad 2015 Cricket World Cup}}\n}}\n{{Lancashire County Cricket Club squad}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Anderson, James}}\n[[Category:English cricketers]]\n[[Category:England Test cricketers]]\n[[Category:England One Day International cricketers]]\n[[Category:England Twenty20 International cricketers]]\n[[Category:English cricketers of the 21st century]]\n[[Category:Auckland cricketers]]\n[[Category:Lancashire cricketers]]\n[[Category:One Day International hat-trick takers]]\n[[Category:Cricketers at the 2003 Cricket World Cup]]\n[[Category:Cricketers at the 2007 Cricket World Cup]]\n[[Category:Cricketers at the 2011 Cricket World Cup]]\n[[Category:Cricketers at the 2015 Cricket World Cup]]\n[[Category:1982 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Officers of the Order of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Burnley]]\n[[Category:Wisden Cricketers of the Year]]\n[[Category:Lancashire Cricket Board cricketers]]\n[[Category:Cricketers who have taken five wickets on Test debut]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|English cricketer}}\n{{About|the England Test player|the Oxford University player|James Anderson (cricketer, born 1931)}}\n{{EngvarB|date=November 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox cricketer\n| name = James Anderson\n| honorific-suffix = [[Officer of the Order of the British Empire|OBE]]\n| image = JIMMY ANDERSON.jpg\n| caption = Anderson in 2014\n| country = England\n| fullname = James Michael Anderson\n| nickname = The King of Swing,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/cricket/international/theashes/8244183/The-Ashes-James-Anderson-the-king-of-swing-earns-his-place-among-Englands-fast-bowling-greats.html |title= The Ashes: James Anderson, the king of swing, earns his place among England's fast-bowling greats |author=Scyld Berry |work=The Daily Telegraph |date=6 January 2011 | location=London}} Retrieved on 27 June 2008.</ref> The Burnley Express, The Burnley [[Brian Lara|Lara]],<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/cricket/article-2725289/James-Anderson-England-captain-s-dream-gets-job-hand.html |title= James Anderson is an England captain's dream... he gets on with the job in hand |author=David Lloyd |newspaper=Daily Mail |date=14 August 2014 | location=London}} Retrieved on 27 June 2008.</ref> Daisy (early career)<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/cricket/international/england/2302708/James-Andersons-search-for-perfection.html |title= James Anderson's search for perfection |author=Simon Hughes |work=The Daily Telegraph |date=9 June 2008 | location=London}} Retrieved on 27 June 2008.</ref>\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|df=y|1982|7|30}}\n| birth_place = [[Burnley]], Lancashire, England\n| height = 6 ft 2 in\n| role = [[Bowling (cricket)|Bowler]]\n| batting = Left-handed\n| bowling = Right-arm [[Fast bowling|fast-medium]]\n| international = true\n| internationalspan = 2002\u2013present\n| testdebutdate = 22 May\n| testdebutyear = 2003\n| testdebutagainst = Zimbabwe\n| testcap = 613\n| lasttestdate = 3 January\n| lasttestyear = 2020\n| lasttestagainst = South Africa\n| odidebutdate = 15 December\n| odidebutyear = 2002\n| odidebutagainst = Australia\n| odicap = 172\n| odishirt = 9\n| lastodidate = 13 March\n| lastodiyear = 2015\n| lastodiagainst = Afghanistan\n| T20Icap = 21\n| T20Idebutdate = 9 January\n| T20Idebutyear = 2007\n| T20Idebutagainst = Australia\n| lastT20Idate = 15 November\n| lastT20Iyear = 2009\n| lastT20Iagainst = South Africa\n| club1 = [[Lancashire Cricket Board]]\n| year1 = 2000\n| club2 = [[Lancashire County Cricket Club|Lancashire]]\n| year2 = 2002\u2013present\n| clubnumber2 = 9\n| club3 = [[Auckland cricket team|Auckland]]\n| year3 = 2007/08\n| columns = 4\n| column1 = [[Test cricket|Test]]\n| matches1 = 151\n| runs1 = 1,185\n| bat avg1 = 9.63\n| 100s/50s1 = 0/1\n| top score1 = 81\n| deliveries1 = 32,779\n| wickets1 = 584\n| bowl avg1 = 26.83\n| fivefor1 = 28\n| tenfor1 = 3\n| best bowling1 = 7/42\n| catches/stumpings1 = 93/\u2013\n| column2 = [[One Day International|ODI]]\n| matches2 = 194\n| runs2 = 273\n| bat avg2 = 7.58\n| 100s/50s2 = 0/0\n| top score2 = 28\n| deliveries2 = 9,584\n| wickets2 = 269\n| bowl avg2 = 29.22\n| fivefor2 = 2\n| tenfor2 = 0\n| best bowling2 = 5/23\n| catches/stumpings2 = 54/\u2013\n| column3 = [[First-class cricket|FC]]\n| matches3 = 248\n| runs3 = 1,826\n| bat avg3 = 9.61\n| 100s/50s3 = 0/1\n| top score3 = 81\n| deliveries3 = 49,905\n| wickets3 = 959\n| bowl avg3 = 24.92\n| fivefor3 = 48\n| tenfor3 = 6\n| best bowling3 = 7/42\n| catches/stumpings3 = 146/\u2013\n| column4 = [[List A cricket|LA]]\n| matches4 = 261\n| runs4 = 376\n| bat avg4 = 8.95\n| 100s/50s4 = 0/0\n| top score4 = 28\n| deliveries4 = 12,730\n| wickets4 = 358\n| bowl avg4 = 28.57\n| fivefor4 = 2\n| tenfor4 = 0\n| best bowling4 = 5/23\n| catches/stumpings4 = 68/\u2013\n| date = 7 January 2020\n| source = http://www.espncricinfo.com/england/content/player/8608.html ESPNcricinfo\n}}\n\n'''James Michael Anderson''', {{post-nominals|country=GBR|size=100|OBE}} (born 30 July 1982), usually known as '''Jimmy Anderson''', is an English international [[cricket]]er who plays for [[Lancashire County Cricket Club]] and the [[England cricket team]]. Anderson is the [[Fast bowling#Top five fast bowlers|all-time leading wicket-taker among fast bowlers]] surpassing Glenn McGrath (563 wickets) and holds the record of most wickets for England in both Test and One-Day International (ODI) cricket. He is the only English bowler, and the 6th overall, to pass 500 Test wickets.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/wi/content/records/93276.html|title=Test matches {{!}} Most wickets in career |publisher=ESPNcricinfo|access-date=12 September 2018}}</ref>Anderson is also a co-presenter alongside [[Greg James]] and [[Felix White]] on the Tailenders podcast. \n\nAnderson plays [[first-class cricket]] for [[Lancashire County Cricket Club|Lancashire county cricket club]] and since arriving on the international scene in 2002/03 (before his first full season of County cricket) has represented England in 150 [[Test cricket|Test matches]] and nearly 200 [[One Day International]]s.<ref name=\"cricinfo player profile\"/> He is England's all-time highest international wicket-taker when combined across all three formats. He and [[Joe Root]] posted the highest ever 10th-wicket Test batting partnership in the 1st Test of India's 2014 tour of England.\n\nA right-arm [[Fast bowling|pace bowler]], Anderson made his international debut at the age of just 20, on England's 2002/03 tour of [[Australia national cricket team|Australia]]. When he played his first ODI he had only played five [[List A]] matches. Anderson went on to feature in the [[2003 Cricket World Cup|2003 ICC World Cup]] and made his Test match debut against [[Zimbabwe national cricket team|Zimbabwe]] at [[Lord's]] the next summer. Later in 2003, he experienced a dip in form and confidence against [[South Africa national cricket team|South Africa]]. After this, he was in and out of the team and experienced numerous injuries, including a [[stress fracture]] of the back which kept him out of action for most of the 2006 season. He returned to action and is now the opening bowler in England's Test team. He was a regular strike bowler in England's one-day team but has not played in that format since the 2015 World Cup. He is the first English bowler to reach 400 and 500 wickets in Test matches, and on 11 September 2018, he became 4th highest Test wicket-taker of all time. He reached this position when he took his 564th Test wicket, passing [[Glenn McGrath]] as the leading wicket-taker among fast bowlers. {{As of|2019|January}} he is ranked No.2 in the [[ICC Player Rankings#Top 10 Test Bowlers|ICC Test Bowling Rankings]], having previously reached the top position at various times between 2016 and 2018.\n\nOn 25 July 2016, during the second Test of that year's England-Pakistan series at [[Old Trafford Cricket Ground|Old Trafford]], he became the first fast bowler to take 50 wickets against all other 7 major Test-playing nations, Australia, India, [[New Zealand national cricket team|New Zealand]], [[Pakistan national cricket team|Pakistan]], South Africa, [[Sri Lanka national cricket team|Sri Lanka]] and [[West Indies national cricket team|West Indies]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/england/2282874.stm |author=Scott Heinrich |title=Anderson on fast track |publisher=BBC |date=31 December 2002}} Retrieved on 26 June 2008.</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sportstar.thehindu.com/cricket-videos/ashes-2019-james-anderson-world-class-stuart-broad-cricket/article29391846.ece|title=James Anderson delighted for 'world class' Stuart Broad|last=Sportstar|first=Team|website=Sportstar|access-date=10 October 2019}}</ref> In December 2019, in the first Test [[English cricket team in South Africa in 2019\u201320|against South Africa]], Anderson became the ninth cricketer to [[List of Test cricket records#Individual records (other)|play in 150 Test matches]].<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.espncricinfo.com/series/19430/preview/1185304/south-africa-vs-england-1st-test-icc-world-test-championship-2019-2021 |title=Bruised England look to improve touring record against battered South Africa |work=ESPN Cricinfo |accessdate=26 December 2019}}</ref> In January 2020, in the second Test of the series against South Africa, Anderson took his [[List of international cricket five-wicket hauls by James Anderson|28th five-wicket haul]] in Test cricket.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.skysports.com/cricket/news/12123/11901500/james-anderson-completes-five-for-before-england-grow-lead-in-cape-town |title=James Anderson completes five-for before England grow lead in Cape Town |work=Sky Sports |accessdate=5 January 2020}}</ref> He surpassed Sir [[Ian Botham]]'s record of 27, to become the bowler with the [[List of cricketers by number of international five-wicket hauls|most five-wicket hauls]] for England in Test cricket.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eveningexpress.co.uk/sport/dom-sibley-builds-on-more-good-work-from-james-anderson-as-england-flourish/ |title=Dom Sibley builds on more good work from James Anderson as England flourish |work=Evening Express |accessdate=5 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Early and personal life==\nJames Anderson was a pupil at St Mary's and [[St Theodore's RC High School]], [[Burnley]]. He played cricket at [[Burnley Cricket Club]] from a young age. His childhood dream was to be a cricketer, and at the age of 17, after a growth spurt, Anderson was one of the fastest bowlers in the [[Lancashire League (cricket)|Lancashire League]].<ref name=\"lessons in life\">{{cite web |url=http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/england/content/story/133792.html |author=Emma John |title=Lessons in life |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=19 September 2003}} Retrieved on 29 May 2008.</ref> He stated that \"I've always bowled [[seam bowling|seam]], but when I was about 17 I don't know what it was but I just started bowling fast all of a sudden\".<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.cricbuzz.com/cricket-news/81851/england-cricket-team-bowler-james-anderson-becomes-first-seamer-to-take-50-plus-wickets-against-seven-teams |author=Deepu Narayanan |title=Anderson becomes first seamer to take 50-plus wickets against seven teams |publisher=Cricbuzz |date=5 August 2016}} Retrieved on 8 August 2016.</ref>\n\nJust months after his debut he had become one of the biggest stars in English cricket. Continuous alteration of hair styles, attractive looks, and up-to-the-minute outfits earned him comparisons with some of the most recognisable sports personalities around, including [[David Beckham]].<ref name=\"lessons in life\"/> In 2006, at Holy Angels' RC Church, [[Hale, Greater Manchester|Hale]], he married Daniella Lloyd, a model he met in 2004 while on England duty in London; he stated that marriage has made him \"a much happier person\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/wisdencricketer/content/story/313823.html |author=Emma John |title=How the pin-up grew up |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=October 2007}} Retrieved on 10 December 2007.</ref> On 8 January 2009, Daniella Anderson gave birth to a baby girl, Lola Rose. The couple's second daughter, Ruby Luxe, was born on 9 December 2010.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.lccc.co.uk/index.php?p=news&id=2553 |author=Lancashire County Cricket Club |title=Jimmy's Finest Delivery |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=12 January 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110616100852/http://www.lccc.co.uk/index.php?p=news&id=2553 |archivedate=16 June 2011  }} Retrieved on 12 January 2009.</ref>\n\n===Fashion design===\nAnderson has ventured into fashion design since 2012, designing for Elvis Jesus with proceeds of the sale going to his sponsored charity, [[Nordoff-Robbins]]. In April 2014, he launched his first collection with London-based menswear brand, Chess London. He has stated that he would like to be \"the first cricketer to become a designer\".<ref>{{cite news  |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/lifestyle/esmagazine/rising-from-the-ashes-englands-cricket-stars-on-finding-their-mojo-9582207.html?origin=internalSearch |title= Rising from the Ashes: England's cricket stars on finding their mojo |author=Joshi Herrmann |work=London Evening Standard |date=4 July 2014 | location=London}} Retrieved on 13 August 2014</ref> He launched his own menswear brand in late October 2014,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.613collection.com/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=14 October 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141017191000/http://www.613collection.com/ |archivedate=17 October 2014 }}</ref> and has been working in conjunction with British watchmaker [[Christopher Pinchbeck|Harold Pinchbeck]] to release a watch in 2015.<ref>http://www.activatemanagement.co.uk/who-we-manage/james-anderson/</ref>\n\n===Media===\nAnderson became the first cricketer to model naked for ''[[Attitude (magazine)|Attitude]]'', \"Britain's biggest-selling gay magazine\", in September 2010. He stated \"if there are any gay cricketers they should feel confident enough to come out because I don't think there is any homophobia in cricket.\"<ref>{{cite news | url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-lancashire-11377673| title= Naked Lancashire cricketer James Anderson in Attitude| accessdate =20 September 2010| date=20 September 2010|publisher=BBC News }}</ref>\n\nAlongside former cricketer [[Graeme Swann]] and [[BBC Radio 1]] radio presenter [[Greg James]], Anderson hosts a cricket-themed radio show on [[BBC Radio 5 Live]], \"Not Just Cricket\". The radio show was nominated for Best Sports Programme at the 2013 [[Radio Academy Awards]].\n\nOn 15 November 2017, Anderson along with Felix White and Greg James, began hosting a cricketing podcast 'Tailenders'. This was initially a weekly podcast covering the 2017\u201318 Ashes series, since 23 May 2018 it was renewed to continue on a weekly basis.[9] Features include 'General Cricketing Sadness', 'Mattchin's Quiz' and 'Black Wednesday/Xmas Show/App Launch'.\n\n==Domestic career==\nAnderson made his [[first-class cricket|first-class]] debut for Lancashire in 2002; he played 13 matches and took 50 wickets at an average of 22.28, including three five-wicket hauls.<ref name=\"fc bowling by season\">{{cite web |url=http://www.cricketarchive.co.uk/Lancashire/Players/10/10687/f_Bowling_by_Season.html |title=First-class bowling in each season by James Anderson |publisher=Cricket Archive}} Retrieved on 29 May 2008.</ref> He was awarded the [[NBC Denis Compton Award]] for Lancashire's most promising young County player in the 2002 season.<ref name=\"cricinfo player profile\">{{cite web |url=http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/england/content/player/8608.html |title=James Anderson |publisher=ESPNcricinfo}} Retrieved on 29 May 2008.</ref> In 2003, Anderson became the youngest player to take a [[Hat-trick (cricket)|hat-trick]] for Lancashire, just a week before his Test match debut against Zimbabwe; it was the first hat-trick at [[Old Trafford Cricket Ground|Old Trafford]] in eight years.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/england/content/story/131313.html |title=Hat-trick for Anderson as Essex stumble at Old Trafford |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=14 May 2003}} Retrieved on 26 May 2008.</ref> In a match against [[Worcestershire County Cricket Club|Worcestershire]] in May 2004, Anderson recorded his maiden first-class ten-wicket haul.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/england/content/story/140927.html |title=Anderson and Keedy take Lancashire top |author=Andrew Miller |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=14 May 2004}} Retrieved on 29 May 2008.</ref>\n\n2005 was Anderson's first full season for Lancashire. He was propelled into the England side soon after his Lancashire debut and had returned to rediscover his form after winter tours with England where he had spent the majority of his time on the sidelines, and when given a chance for England he often bowled poorly due to a lack of match practice.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/england/content/story/220383.html |title=Cooley backs Anderson for Pakistan |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=28 September 2005}} Retrieved on 30 May 2008.</ref> He finished the season with 60 first-class wickets at an average of 30.21 and 27 one day wickets at an average of 22.00.<ref name=\"fc bowling by season\"/><ref name=\"od bowling by season\">{{cite web |url=http://www.cricketarchive.co.uk/Lancashire/Players/10/10687/a_Bowling_by_Season.html |title=ListA bowling in each season by James Anderson |publisher=Cricket Archive}} Retrieved on 30 May 2008.</ref>\n\nAnderson was prevented from playing much for Lancashire in the 2006 season by a [[stress fracture]] of the back sustained in early May.<ref name=\"stress frac\">{{cite web |url=http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/england/content/story/245931.html |title=Anderson out for two months |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=2 February 2006}} Retrieved on 29 May 2008.</ref>\nHe played in only two matches for Lancashire, and at one point it was considered sending Anderson to play for [[Glamorgan County Cricket Club|Glamorgan]] to prove his fitness; however, Lancashire decided they would rather have Anderson play for them if only in a limited capacity.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/england/content/story/259822.html |title=Anderson included in Lancashire squad |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=17 September 2006}} Retrieved on 29 May 2008.</ref> In the only first-class match he played for Lancashire that season, he was limited to three four-over spells by the [[England and Wales Cricket Board|ECB]] who were wary of injuring him again.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/england/content/story/260182.html |title=Cork haul overshadows Anderson |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=21 September 2006}} Retrieved on 29 May 2008.</ref>\n\nIn 2008, after the Test and One-Day series against South Africa ended at the beginning of September, Anderson was made unavailable to play for Lancashire for the rest of the season.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/england/content/current/story/367275.html |title=Harmison available for season finale |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=1 September 2008}} Retrieved on 1 September 2008.</ref> He finished the season with 20 first-class wickets at 7.75 for Lancashire.<ref name=\"fc bowling by season\"/><ref>\n{{cite web |url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Players/10/10687/t_Bowling_by_Season.html |title=Test bowling in each season by James Anderson |publisher=Cricket Archive}} Retrieved on 26 April 2009.</ref>\n\nAt the start of the 2009 English cricket season, Anderson took career-best match figures in a first-class match with 11/109 against [[Sussex County Cricket Club|Sussex]] as Lancashire won by 8&nbsp;wickets. It was the only first-class match he played for Lancashire before being called into the England squad for a series against the West Indies.<ref>{{Cite book |url=http://content.cricinfo.com/england/content/story/401296.html |title=Big wins for Nottinghamshire and Lancashire |publisher=Cricinfo |author=Cricinfo staff |date=24 April 2009}} Retrieved on 26 April 2009.</ref> As of 26 April 2009, Anderson had taken 188&nbsp;wickets at 24.37 from 48&nbsp;first-class matches with Lancashire,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Players/10/10687/f_Bowling_by_Team.html |title=First-class bowling for each team by James Anderson |publisher=CricketArchive.com}} Retrieved on 26 April 2009.</ref> and 66&nbsp;wickets at 21.78 in 44 list A matches.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Players/10/10687/a_Bowling_by_Team.html |title=List A bowling for each team by James Anderson |publisher=CricketArchive.com}} Retrieved on 26 April 2009.</ref>\n\n==International career==\n===2002\u201303: World Cup, Zimbabwe and South Africa===\n\nWhen Anderson was selected for the England one-day squad, he had played only five List A matches, taking 9 wickets at an average of 26.75.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cricketarchive.co.uk/Lancashire/Players/10/10687/a_Bowling_by_Season.html |title=ListA bowling in each season by James Anderson |publisher=Cricket Archive}} Retrieved on 29 May 2008.</ref> At the age of 20, he made his [[One Day International|ODI]] debut on 15 December 2002 against [[Australia national cricket team|Australia]] at [[Melbourne]]. He opened the bowling and recorded figures of 1/46 from six overs.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cricketarchive.co.uk/Archive/Scorecards/76/76049.html |title=Australia v England VB Series 2002/03; Melbourne Cricket Ground 15 December 2002 (50-over match) (day/night) |publisher=Cricket Archive}} Retrieved on 29 May 2008.</ref> His debut came before he was even awarded his County cap, which occurred in 2003.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cricketarchive.co.uk/Lancashire/Players/10/10687/10687.html |title=James Anderson |publisher=Cricket Archive}} Retrieved on 29 May 2008.</ref> He showed good promise in this series \u2013 a three-team tournament also including [[Sri Lanka national cricket team|Sri Lanka]] \u2013 which earned him a place in the [[2003 Cricket World Cup|2003 World Cup]] squad. It was here that he really broke into international cricket with a match-winning spell against [[Pakistan national cricket team|Pakistan]], where he took four wickets in day/night game to collect the Man of the Match award. In what proved to be England's last match of the tournament he conceded 12 runs off the penultimate [[over (cricket)|over]] against eventual world champions Australia, and England lost a closely fought contest.\n\nIn the summer of 2003, he made his first [[Test cricket]] appearance against [[Zimbabwe national cricket team|Zimbabwe]] at [[Lord's]], and took [[List of England cricketers who have taken five-wicket hauls on Test debut|five wickets in an innings on debut]],<ref name=\"5wktsDebut\">{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/match/64032.html |title=1st Test: England v Zimbabwe at Lord's, May 22\u201324, 2003 |accessdate=13 December 2011|publisher=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref> becoming the 42nd Englishman to do so. His success continued in the subsequent One-Day tournaments against [[Pakistan national cricket team|Pakistan]] (against whom he took a hat-trick at [[The Oval]]), [[South Africa national cricket team|South Africa]] and Zimbabwe. His hat-trick against Pakistan, the first by an English bowler in an ODI, claimed the wickets of [[Abdul Razzaq (cricketer)|Abdul Razzaq]], [[Shoaib Akhtar]] and [[Mohammad Sami]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/statsguru/content/story/129793.html |title=Anderson and Trescothick batter Pakistan to defeat |author=Andrew Miller |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=20 June 2003}} Retrieved on 4 September 2008.</ref>\n\nThe Test series against South Africa dented Anderson's reputation as England's golden boy;<ref>{{cite web |url=http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/england/content/story/124771.html |title=Don't panic! |author=Freddie Auld |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=6 August 2003}} Retrieved on 28 May 2008.</ref> in a series England drew 2\u20132 after coming from behind, Anderson finished the five-match series with 15 wickets at an average of 39.86.<ref name=\"Anderson series by series Test bowling\">{{cite web |url=http://stats.cricinfo.com/statsguru/engine/player/8608.html?class=1;template=results;type=bowling;view=series |title=Statsguru \u2013 JM Anderson \u2013 ODI Batting \u2013 Career summary |publisher=ESPNcricinfo}} Retrieved on 28 May 2008.</ref> His best figures of 5/102 came at [[Trent Bridge]] in the third Test where he used movement of the seam to claim his second five-wicket haul in his fifth Test.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/england/content/story/124964.html |title=Into the hands of fate |author=Andrew Miller |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=6 August 2003}} Retrieved on 16 May 2008.</ref> Although Anderson was England's lead wicket taker,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://stats.cricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/averages/batting_bowling_by_team.html?id=488;team=1;type=series |title=South Africa in England Test Series, 2003 \u2013 England averages |publisher=ESPNcricinfo}} Retrieved on 28 May 2008.</ref> [[Graeme Smith]] \u2013 the South African captain \u2013 particularly punished Anderson's bowling, taking 157 runs at a strike rate of 90.23 off his bowling in the series and only being dismissed once.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/ci/content/story/133550.html |title=As the dust settles ... |author=Rob Smyth |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=9 September 2003}} Retrieved on 28 May 2008.</ref> In August, despite a mixed series against South Africa, Anderson was named [[Cricket Writers' Club Young Cricketer of the Year|Young Cricketer of the Year]]; he became the first player to be unanimously voted the award.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/england/content/story/124942.html |title=Anderson voted Young Cricket of the Year |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=15 August 2003}} Retrieved on 28 May 2008.</ref> In September, Anderson was awarded a central contract with the ECB.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/england/content/story/133589.html |title=Anderson, Flintoff and Collingwood awarded central contracts |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=11 September 2003}} Retrieved on 28 May 2008.</ref> He suffered from a niggling knee injury and fatigue as the season wore on;<ref name=\"automatic choice\"/> the knee injury \u2013 to a tendon on the outside of his left knee \u2013 meant he was rested for the winter tour of [[Bangladesh national cricket team|Bangladesh]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/england/content/story/133938.html |title=Anderson to miss Bangladesh Tests |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=25 September 2003}} Retrieved on 28 May 2008.</ref> After the South Africa series and some good performances by other bowlers during the Bangladesh tour, Anderson admitted that he was no longer an automatic choice for England.<ref name=\"automatic choice\">{{cite web |url=http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/england/content/story/131870.html |title=Anderson \u2013 \"I'm not an automatic choice\" |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=14 November 2003}} Retrieved on 28 May 2008.</ref> England and Wales Cricket Board declared James Anderson as the England Cricketer of the year 2011\u201312.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/cricket/18066639|title=James Anderson\n|accessdate=17 May 2012}}</ref>\n\nAnderson has an unusual bowling action. At the moment of delivery he has his head down, eyes closed and does not look where he is bowling; he attempted to bowl with his head up but found that he lost pace in doing so, so reverted to his original action.<ref name=\"lessons in life\"/> In 2003, ex-England pace bowler [[Bob Willis]] claimed that Anderson would only be able to play for five years with his action.<ref name=\"lessons in life\"/> Between 2004 and 2005, the England coaching staff attempted to alter Anderson's bowling action.<ref name=\"consistency\">{{cite web |url=http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/england/content/story/346937.html |author=Andrew Miller |title=Anderson seeks consistency in England comeback |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=18 April 2008}} Retrieved on 3 June 2008.</ref> Anderson was selected in the One-Day and Test squads for the winter tour [[Sri Lanka national cricket team|Sri Lanka]], but injuries left him able to play in only one of the three Tests on that tour. He bowled well below his potential to collect figures of 0\u201385 in his sole appearance.\n\n===2004\u201305: West Indies, Zimbabwe and Pakistan===\n[[File:James Anderson bowl.jpg|120px|right|thumb|Anderson bowls in the [[Adelaide Oval]] nets.]]\nAlthough fit and included in both the Test and one-day squads for the tour of the West Indies,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/england/content/story/137409.html |title=England name unchanged squad for Windies tour |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=7 January 2004}} Retrieved on 29 May 2008.</ref> Anderson did not play in the Test series, having been superseded by players such as [[James Kirtley]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/england/content/story/134625.html |title=Anderson waits for his opening |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=22 April 2004}} Retrieved on 29 May 2008.</ref> He did feature in the ODI series which England drew 2\u20132, playing in 4&nbsp;matches and taking 4&nbsp;wickets at an average of 37.00;<ref>{{cite web |url=http://uk.cricinfo.com/db/ARCHIVE/2003-04/ENG_IN_WI/STATS/ENG_IN_WI_MAR-MAY2004_ODI_AVS.html |title=England in West Indies, 2003\u201304 One-Day Series Averages |publisher=ESPNcricinfo}} Retrieved on 21 December 2008.</ref> in the final match of the series, Anderson took his 50th ODI wicket, that of [[Chris Gayle]] for 41.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/79/79510.html |title=a15876, o2127: West Indies v England, England in West Indies 2003/04 (7th ODI) |publisher=CricketArchive.com}} Retrieved on 21 December 2008.</ref> After the ODI series against the West Indies, Anderson had 50&nbsp;wickets from 31&nbsp;ODIs at an average of 23.78.<ref name=\"ODI landmarks\">{{cite web |url=http://stats.cricinfo.com/statsguru/engine/player/8608.html?class=2;template=results;type=bowling;view=cumulative |title=JM Anderson: One-Day Internationals \u2013 Bowling analysis, cummulative |publisher=ESPNcricinfo}} Retrieved on 21 December 2008.</ref>\n\nAnderson retained his place in the Test squad, and his next big break came when an injury to [[Simon Jones (cricketer)|Simon Jones]] forced the Welshman out of the last three Tests of the 2004 summer series against the [[West Indian cricket team in England in 2004|West Indies]]. Despite being in the team, Anderson's bowling was used infrequently. It was clear now that Anderson had now not only lost all his form and rhythm, but consequentially all his confidence as well. A performance by a resurgent Anderson in the final Test of the summer prompted speculation that he had regained his confidence and would return to the top of his game.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/england/content/story/135342.html |title=Anderson shines on a golden day |author=Andrew Miller |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=21 August 2004}} Retrieved on 21 December 2008.</ref> He was selected for the winter tour to Zimbabwe and South Africa. Much of the post-season talk, however, was dominated by the debate over whether to go on tour to Zimbabwe. England eventually did end up in [[Harare]], after a brief stop over in [[Namibian cricket team|Namibia]]. Anderson once again struggled in his three One-Day appearances. The England management, however, continued to show faith in his ability.\n\nTravelling as a barely-used reserve on [[English cricket team in South Africa in 2004-05|the winter South Africa tour]] while seemingly struggling for form, Anderson was given another shot at redemption, after Simon Jones was dropped for the third Test after a poor performance in the second. Anderson, though, did even worse than Jones, collecting figures of 2/117 and 0/32 in his two innings. Anderson spent the following summer with Lancashire; bowling regularly a quota of overs one would associate with a new ball bowler, something he had not done enough in his England stint. He was recalled to the England squad for the last match of [[the 2005 Ashes]] series after taking 60&nbsp;wickets for Lancashire in 2005, once again as a replacement for the injured Jones, but all-rounder [[Paul Collingwood]] was selected for the team.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/england/content/story/269504.html |title=Anderson learning a tough lesson |author=Andrew McGlashan |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=9 December 2005}} Retrieved on 26 June 2008.</ref>\n\nAnderson was selected in the Test squad for the tour of Pakistan, but spinner [[Shaun Udal]] was chosen to fill the bowler's spot left empty by the still injured Simon Jones. When [[Ashley Giles]] had to miss the third Test due to injury, young [[Durham County Cricket Club|Durham]] debutant seamer [[Liam Plunkett]] was chosen ahead of Anderson and Anderson did not play a single Test on the tour.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/england/content/story/227560.html |title=Vaughan could prove the difference |author=Andrew Miller |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=28 November 2005}} Retrieved on 21 December 2008.</ref> Despite this disappointment he played in all five of England's One-Day games in Pakistan, showing improvements in form to be England's joint-leading wicket-taker in the series with Andrew Flintoff, taking 7&nbsp;wickets at 25.57.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://uk.cricinfo.com/db/ARCHIVE/2005-06/ENG_IN_PAK/STATS/ENG_IN_PAK_OCT-DEC2005_ODI_AVS.html |title=England in Pakistan, 2005\u201306 One-Day Series Averages |publisher=ESPNcricinfo}} Retrieved on 21 December 2008.</ref>\n\n===2006: India and Australia===\nAnderson was not selected for the senior side's tour to India in January 2006 as Simon Jones returned from injury and was chosen ahead of him.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/england/content/story/232847.html |title=Anderson loses Test place as Jones returns |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=13 January 2006}} Retrieved on 21 December 2008.</ref> Instead, Anderson was selected for England A's tour of the West Indies.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/england/content/story/234702.html |title=Anderson called up for England A tour |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=27 January 2006}} Retrieved on 21 December 2008.</ref> In February, days before the start of the first A-match between England and the West Indies, James Anderson (along with batsmen [[Alastair Cook]] and [[Owais Shah]]) was called up as an injury reinforcement to the England senior squad in India, after captain [[Michael Vaughan]] and fast bowler Simon Jones flew home with knee injuries and vice-captain Marcus Trescothick departed for undisclosed \"personal\" reasons.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/england/content/story/238623.html |title=Cook and Anderson fly to India |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=25 February 2006}} Retrieved on 21 December 2008.</ref> After an unconvincing display by Liam Plunkett in the second Test in [[Mohali]] Anderson was recalled for the final match of the series. He impressed in England's victory, taking figures of 4/40 in the first innings.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/magazine/content/story/241447.html |title=Anderson's resurgence |author=John Stern |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=20 March 2006}} Retrieved on 21 September 2008.</ref>\n\nAfter his impressive display in the final match in India, Anderson looked likely to feature as one of England's main bowlers in both the ODI series and Test matches against Pakistan and Sri Lanka; however an early season stress fracture of the back ruled Anderson out for all of the summer internationals and all but two matches of his county season.<ref name=\"stress frac\"/> Lancashire teammate [[Sajid Mahmood]] was called up to the England squad the replacement for Anderson.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/england/content/story/246404.html |title=Mahmood and Lewis earn call-up |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=8 May 2006}} Retrieved on 29 May 2008.</ref>\n\nAnderson was named in England's [[ICC Champions Trophy|Champions Trophy]] and Ashes squads in September 2006 although at that point he had not played any first-class cricket in six months.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/england/content/story/259631.html |title=Anderson set for Glamorgan loan |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=15 September 2006}} Retrieved on 29 May 2008.</ref> He was straight back into England colours for the 0\u20135 Ashes whitewash against [[Australia national cricket team|Australia]]. His performance, like much of the England team, was well below standard. Anderson was sent home midway through the One-Day tournament with Australia and [[New Zealand national cricket team|New Zealand]] as a precaution when he felt a twinge in his back;<ref>{{cite web |url=http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/england/content/story/280451.html |title=Anderson builds up to bowling |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=15 February 2007}} Retrieved on 31 May 2008.</ref> during the tournament he had begun to regain some of his form and in the four matches he played he took 8 wickets at an average of 20.62.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/england/content/story/277652.html |title=Anderson cool over back stiffness |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=25 January 2007}} Retrieved on 31 May 2008.</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://uk.cricinfo.com/db/ARCHIVE/2006-07/OD_TOURNEYS/CBS/STATS/CBS_JAN-FEB2007_ODI_AVS_ENG.html |title=Commonwealth Bank Series, 2006\u201307 Averages |publisher=ESPNcricinfo}} Retrieved on 31 May 2008.</ref>\n\n===2007: World Cup===\nAlthough Anderson was returned home early from the England's victorious ODI series in Australia, Anderson was selected in England's squad for the [[2007 Cricket World Cup]]. He recovered from his back injury and was expected to play ahead of the likes of [[Liam Plunkett]], [[Sajid Mahmood]] and [[Jon Lewis (cricketer, born 1975)|Jon Lewis]]. However, on 14 March 2007, only days before England's first game, it was reported by the BBC that Anderson had broken his finger during fielding practice and his involvement in the tournament was in question, although he was able to play despite the pain.<ref name=\"broken finger\">{{cite web |url=http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/england/content/story/285240.html |title=England delay Anderson decision |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=15 March 2007}} Retrieved on 26 June 2008.</ref>\n\n===2007: West Indies, India and Sri Lanka===\nWhen [[Peter Moores (cricketer)|Peter Moores]] replaced [[Duncan Fletcher]] as England coach after the World Cup, it was felt that Anderson would benefit under new management; along with the rest of the England team he was allowed to play more for his county. It was felt that it was not beneficial for players who were not representing England to just sit on the sideline and match practice would allow him to rediscover his form.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/magazine/content/story/295114.html |title=Moore's fresh outlook |author=Andrew McGlashan |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=22 May 2007}} Retrieved on 31 May 2008.</ref> Anderson did not feature in the Test series against the West Indies, but he did play in the ODI series. During the second ODI, he clashed with [[Runako Morton]] when he appeared to get in the way of Morton when the batsman was running between the wickets. Anderson was fined half of his match fee for the incident and match referee [[Mike Procter]] stated \"James Anderson is not a player with a reputation for bad behaviour...and I am sure he will do everything he can to ensure there is no repeat of this unfortunate incident\".<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/england/6274274.stm |title=Anderson fined after Morton clash |publisher=BBC |date=5 July 2007}} Retrieved on 22 August 2008.</ref> Anderson finished the series with five wickets at 30.40 as England lost the series 2\u20131.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://stats.cricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/bowling/most_wickets_career.html?id=2870;type=series |title=NatWest Series [West Indies in England], 2007 |publisher=ESPNcricinfo}} Retrieved on 22 August 2008.</ref>\n\n[[File:Anderson bowling, 2007.jpg|thumb|400px|Anderson bowling during the second Test of India's tour of England in 2007. He opened the bowling with [[Ryan Sidebottom]].]]\n\nAnderson played in all three Tests of the series with [[India national cricket team|India]], coming into the side for the injured [[Matthew Hoggard]] and leading a pace attack comprising himself, [[Ryan Sidebottom]] and [[Chris Tremlett]] with only 20 caps between them.<ref name=\"drinks are on Jimmy\">{{cite web |url=http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/magazine/content/story/303500.html |title=The drinks are on Jimmy |author=Andrew McGlashan |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=24 July 2007}} Retrieved on 31 May 2008.</ref> In the first Test of the series, Anderson claimed his 50th Test wicket when he dismissed [[Mahendra Singh Dhoni]] for 0;<ref>{{cite web |url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/103/103089.html |title=t1840, f49898: England v India, India in British Isles 2007 (1st Test) |publisher=CricketArchive.com}} Retrieved on 21 December 2008.</ref> the feat was achieved in Anderson's 17th Test match and after the match he had 53&nbsp;wickets at an average of 35.67.<ref name=\"landmark wickets\">{{cite web |url=http://stats.cricinfo.com/statsguru/engine/player/8608.html?class=1;template=results;type=bowling;view=cumulative |title=JM Anderson: Test matches \u2013 Bowling analysis, cumulative}} Retrieved on 21 December 2008.</ref> He became the first England bowler to dismiss [[Rahul Dravid]], [[Sachin Tendulkar]], and [[Sourav Ganguly]] in the same innings.<ref name=\"drinks are on Jimmy\"/> Although England lost the series, Anderson demonstrated greater consistency than before and managed 14 wickets, at 35.57 and getting the Man of the Series award.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/england/content/story/306970.html |title=The road to redemption |author=Andrew Miller |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=14 August 2007}} Retrieved on 31 May 2008.</ref> He also managed to get his name on the honours board at Lord's for the second time with his best Test figures of 5/42.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/england/content/story/303038.html |title=Zaheer gives India hope after Anderson's haul |author=Andrew McGlashan |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=21 July 2007}} Retrieved on 31 May 2008.</ref> The ODI series which followed was England's first ODI series win at home in three years. Anderson was the leading wicket-taker of either side with 14 wickets at an average of 22.57.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/england/content/story/310141.html |title=The Bell factor and India's bowling worries |author=Mathew Varghese |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=10 September 2007}} Retrieved on 31 May 2008.</ref> In the first ODI of the series, Anderson claimed his 100th ODI wicket when he dismissed [[Gautam Gambhir]] for 3;<ref>{{cite web |url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/103/103097.html |title=o2611, a18335: England v India, India in British Isles 2007 (1st ODI) |publisher=CricketArchive.com}} Retrieved on 21 December 2008.</ref> after the match, he had taken 103&nbsp;wickets from 70&nbsp;matches at an average of 27.02.<ref name=\"ODI landmarks\"/> Anderson was also included for the England squad for the [[2007 ICC World Twenty20|World Twenty20]], held in September 2007, replacing an injured [[Ravi Bopara]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/engvind/content/story/309928.html |title=Anderson replaces Bopara for Twenty20 |author=Andrew McGlashan |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=7 September 2007}} Retrieved on 31 May 2008.</ref> He played in all four of England's matches, taking three wickets at 34.00, as England failed to progress beyond the second stage of the competition.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://stats.cricinfo.com/twenty20wc/engine/records/bowling/most_wickets_career.html?id=3115;type=tournament |title=Most wickets: ICC World Twenty20, 2007/08 |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071012193551/http://stats.cricinfo.com/twenty20wc/engine/records/bowling/most_wickets_career.html?id=3115%3Btype%3Dtournament |archivedate=12 October 2007 }} Retrieved on 27 December 2008.</ref> Following a successful summer, he was one of twelve players awarded a central contract for 2007/08 by the ECB.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/england/content/story/310246.html |title=Prior misses out on central contract |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=10 September 2007}} Retrieved on 31 May 2008.</ref>\n\nAnderson was part of the squad which toured Sri Lanka in the winter. The One-Day side completed their first ever series victory in Sri Lanka; Anderson's contribution was four wickets in five matches at an average of 48.25 and tying down Sri Lanka's top order along with Sidebottom and [[Stuart Broad]], although they finished with more wickets at a lower average.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/england/content/story/314907.html |title=Collingwood's men confound expectations |author=Andrew Miller |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=10 October 2007}} Retrieved on 2 June 2008.</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://stats.cricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/bowling/most_wickets_career.html?id=3151;type=series |title=England in Sri Lanka ODI Series, 2007/08 |publisher=ESPNcricinfo}} Retrieved on 2 June 2008.</ref> Despite suffering a bruised left ankle,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/england/content/story/322999.html |title=Vaughan keeps his cards close |author=Andrew Miller |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=30 November 2007}} Retrieved on 2 June 2008.</ref> Anderson was selected for the first Test. Although he bowled economically in the first innings,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/slveng/content/current/story/323065.html |title=England's bowlers take the honours |author=Andrew McGlashan |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=1 December 2007}} Retrieved on 2 June 2008.</ref> he was expensive in the second; during the course of the second innings he became only the second bowler in Test cricket to have six boundaries taken off a single over.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/slveng/content/current/story/323473.html |title=Sri Lanka build lead on Murali's record day |author=Andrew McGlashan |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=3 December 2007}} Retrieved on 2 June 2008.</ref> He finished the match with figures of two wickets for 167 runs<ref>{{cite web |url=http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/slveng/engine/current/match/291222.html |title=England in Sri Lanka Test Series \u2013 1st Test Sri Lanka v England |publisher=ESPNcricinfo}} Retrieved on 2 June 2008.</ref> and was dropped for the final two Tests; his replacement was debutant Stuart Broad.\n\n===2008: New Zealand, South Africa and India===\nIn the spring of 2008, Anderson toured [[New Zealand national cricket team|New Zealand]] with England. He played in the Twenty20 series, which England won 2\u20130, and he was then involved in the one-day series which New Zealand won 3\u20132. Although he played in all five matches of the One-Day series, he struggled and only managed four wickets at an average of 67.50.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://stats.cricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/bowling/most_wickets_career.html?id=3309;type=series |title=England in New Zealand ODI Series, 2007/08 |publisher=Cricinfo.com Retrieved on 3 June 2008.}}</ref> In an effort to regain some form, Anderson was allowed to join [[Auckland Aces|Auckland Cricket Club]], who were lacking their strike bowlers due to international call ups, as an overseas player.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/england/content/story/341134.html |title=Anderson links up with Auckland |author=Andrew Miller |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=5 March 2008}} Retrieved on 3 June 2008.</ref> The move was controversial with critics including [[Gavin Larsen]], [[Wellington Firebirds|Wellington Cricket Club]]'s chief executive, who feared that Anderson would be able to bowl himself into form.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/england/content/story/341178.html |title=Larsen slams Anderson deal |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=6 March 2008}} Retrieved on 3 June 2008.</ref> Although he was left out for the first Test, Anderson was recalled for the second when he and Stuart Broad replaced the out of form [[Steve Harmison]] and Matthew Hoggard after England were defeated by 189 runs; the decision to axe both bowlers was heralded as the end of an era in English cricket.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/england/content/story/342058.html |title=Harmison and Hoggard axed by England |author=Andrew Miler |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=12 March 2008}} Retrieved on 3 June 2008.</ref> Anderson's selection was a surprise as it was expected that Broad would replace Harmison, but not that Hoggard would be dropped.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/england/content/story/342386.html |title=Many thanks to Auckland |author=Andrew Miler |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=14 March 2008}} Retrieved on 3 June 2008.</ref> In the first innings of the second Test, Anderson took 5/73 and finished with match figures of 7/130 and helped England to a 126-run victory.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/england/content/story/342353.html |title=Anderson five puts England in control |author=Will Luke |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=14 March 2008}} Retrieved on 3 June 2008.</ref> He sustained an ankle injury while playing football before the third Test but recovered in time to be selected. Anderson's performance in the final Test was less effective,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/england/content/story/343980.html |title=Sidebottom's transformation |author=Andrew Miller |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=26 March 2008}} Retrieved on 3 June 2008.</ref> recording match figures of 1/153 as England won the match by 121 runs and the series 2\u20131.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/england/engine/match/300444.html |title=England in New Zealand Test Series \u2013 3rd Test New Zealand v England |publisher=ESPNcricinfo}} Retrieved on 3 June 2008.</ref> Searching for consistency, Anderson's action reverted to the action he used in 2003, one with which he felt comfortable.<ref name=\"consistency\"/>\n\n[[File:Anderson bowls against New Zealand, cropped.jpg|thumb|left|Anderson bowling against New Zealand in England]]\nHe was retained for the home series, when New Zealand toured England later in 2008. He continued to enjoy success against the touring side, taking 19 wickets at 19.31 and finishing as the leading wicket-taker of the series. This was his highest return of wickets in a series.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://stats.cricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/bowling/most_wickets_career.html?id=3241;type=series |title=New Zealand in England Test Series, 2008 |publisher=ESPNcricinfo}} Retrieved on 8 June 2008.</ref> Anderson bowled well in the first Test, recording match figures of 130/5 as the match was drawn.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/engvnz/content/current/story/351200.html |title=England make spirited response to New Zealand's 277 |author=Will Luke |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=16 May 2008}} Retrieved on 8 June 2008.</ref> In the second Test, Anderson finished with match figures of 5/139 as England won by six wickets; on the first day he struck New Zealand batsman [[Daniel Flynn (cricketer)|Daniel Flynn]] in the face, knocking out a tooth, in a spell of short, aggressive bowling when he also hit [[Jacob Oram]] on the helmet.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/engvnz/content/current/story/352057.html |title=Taylor responds in kind to England's aggression |author=Will Luke |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=23 May 2008}} Retrieved on 8 June 2008.</ref> Anderson was disconcerted by injuring Flynn said that striking him \"wasn't pleasant\".<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/7417778.stm |title= Flynn injury disconcerts Anderson |publisher=BBC |date=23 May 2008}} Retrieved on 8 June 2008.</ref> In the final match of the series Anderson scored a career Test best of 28 in a partnership of 76 with Stuart Broad.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/england/7440617.stm |title=Kiwis reeling after Anderson haul |author=Jamie Lillywhite |publisher=BBC |date=6 June 2008}} Retrieved on 8 June 2008.</ref> This was followed up by career best bowling of 7/43 in the first innings and Test best match figures of 9/98 overall as he won the Man of the Match award and England secured an innings and nine run victory and a 2\u20130 series win.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/england/7442595.stm |title=England v New Zealand 3rd Test report |publisher=BBC |date=8 June 2008}} Retrieved on 8 June 2008.</ref> Anderson's performance in the series prompted England bowling coach [[Ottis Gibson]] to say that Anderson has the potential to become a world-class bowler if he can improve his self-belief.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/england/7442595.stm |title=England v New Zealand 3rd Test reaction |publisher=BBC |date=8 June 2008}} Retrieved on 8 June 2008.</ref> In the One-Day series that followed Anderson managed five wickets from five matches at an average of 41.40 as England lost the series 3\u20131.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://stats.cricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/bowling/most_wickets_career.html?id=3245;type=series |title=NatWest Series [New Zealand in England], 2008 |publisher=ESPNcricinfo}} Retrieved on 22 August 2008.</ref>\n\nAfter the Test series against New Zealand, Anderson's figures revealed that he struggled to bowl to left-handed batsmen and his contrasting fortunes between the start of his career and his resurgence. By the end of June 2008, Anderson had played 25 Test matches; in the 16 Tests before July 2007 he took 46 wickets at an average of 38.39, but since then in 9 Tests he took 43 wickets at 30.58 at a much lower strike rate.<ref name=\"achilles\">{{cite web |url=http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/magazine/content/story/354352.html |title=Splendid Anderson and his Achilles heel |author=S Rajesh |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=13 June 2008}} Retrieved on 22 August 2008.</ref> In the five Tests Anderson played against New Zealand in a four-month period, 22 of the 27 wickets he managed were against right-handed batsmen. Against the right-handers he averaged 20.77 compared to 38.60 against left-handers.<ref name=\"achilles\"/> This was an improvement however on his career statistics, since he averaged 70 wickets at 29.11 against right-handers and 19 at 54.94 against left-handers. This first became clear in the 2003 Test series against South Africa when Graeme Smith and [[Gary Kirsten]] milked him for 276 runs while only being dismissed once between them.<ref name=\"achilles\"/>\n\nAnderson's batting showed a marked improvement in the summer's home Test series against South Africa. In the second innings of the second Test, at [[Headingley Carnegie Cricket Ground|Headingley]], Anderson scored a Test-career best 34 runs, having come to the crease as a nightwatchman late on Day 3. In the course of his innings he was struck on the wrist and then on the grille of his helmet by [[Dale Steyn]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/england/content/story/361991.html |author=Andrew McGlashan |title=Ballsy batting, and a different sort of rearguard |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=21 July 2008}} Retrieved on 3 September 2008.</ref>\n\nIn the final match of the series, Anderson took his 100th Test wicket. The landmark wicket was that of [[Jacques Kallis]] [[Leg Before Wicket]] for 2;<ref>{{cite web |url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/123/123962.html |title=f50678, t1885: England v South Africa, South Africa in England 2008 (4th Test) |publisher=CricketArchive.com}} Retrieved on 21 December 2008.</ref> this feat was achieved in Anderson's 29th Test and after the match he had 104&nbsp;wickets at an average of 34.51.<ref name=\"landmark wickets\"/>\n\nEngland's One-Day series in India was cut short due to terror attacks in Mumbai. Seven matches were due to be played, but due to the terrorism England flew home after five games. They were 5\u20130 down in the series and Anderson had not taken one wicket, despite bowling in every one of the five games.\n\n===2009: West Indies===\nFollowing the sacking of [[Peter Moores (cricketer)|Peter Moores]] in January 2009,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/england/7822596.stm |title=Pietersen insists he is blameless |publisher=BBC News |date=11 January 2009 |accessdate=14 July 2013}}</ref> and the replacement of [[Kevin Pietersen]] by [[Andrew Strauss]] as England captain,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/england/7816389.stm |title=Strauss to lead West Indies tour |publisher=BBC News |date=7 January 2009 |accessdate=14 July 2013}}</ref> England left for a tour to the West Indies.\n\nFollowing two low-key performances in the warm-up matches against a St. Kitts XI<ref>{{cite news|title= Tour match: St Kitts Invitational XI v England |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/shared/fds/hi/statistics/cricket/scorecards/2009/1/15127/html/scorecard.stm |publisher=BBC Sport |accessdate=14 May 2013}}</ref> and West Indies A,<ref>{{cite news|title= Tour match: West Indies A v England |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/shared/fds/hi/statistics/cricket/scorecards/2009/1/15128/html/scorecard.stm |publisher=BBC Sport |accessdate=14 May 2013}}</ref> Anderson was dropped for the first Test in [[Jamaica]]. Surprisingly, the West Indies inflicted a large defeat on England, following a third innings batting collapse. With the form of [[Ryan Sidebottom]] a cause for concern, and some doubts over his fitness, Anderson was recalled for the second Test at the [[Sir Vivian Richards Stadium]] in [[Antigua]]. However, this match was abandoned with fewer than two overs bowled due to an unfit outfield.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/england/7886840.stm |title=Test abaondoned over poor outfield |publisher=BBC News |date=13 February 2009 |accessdate=14 July 2013}}</ref> The Test match was rearranged to take place two days later at the [[Antigua Recreation Ground]]. After making 4 as a night-watchman during England's first innings, Anderson bowled 19 wicketless overs as the West Indies were bowled out for 285, although he did take the catch of [[Chris Gayle]] off [[Steve Harmison]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cricinfo.com/ci/engine/match/390680.html |title=3rd Test: West Indies v England at St John's, Feb 15\u201319, 2009 &#124; ESPN Cricinfo |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=18 July 2011}}</ref> After making 20, again as night-watchman, in the second batting innings, England fell one wicket short of bowling the West Indies out and securing a Test victory as the tail-enders of [[Daren Powell]] and [[Fidel Edwards]] survived 10 overs to bat out the draw.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cricinfo.com/wiveng2009/content/story/391505.html |title=West Indies show hitherto hidden steel |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=14 July 2013}}</ref>\n\nAfter sitting out the tour match against the BCA President's XI in [[Barbados]], England and the West Indies played the fourth Test at the [[Kensington Oval]]. Both sides found bowling difficult on a very flat track, and the first two innings produced 1,349 runs for the loss of just 15 wickets. England batted first and made 600/6 declared, and Anderson again opened the bowling in the West Indies reply. After striking early to dismiss Chris Gayle LBW on a [[Umpire Decision Review System|referral]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cricinfo.com/ci/engine/match/352663.html |title=4th Test: West Indies v England at Bridgetown, Feb 26 \u2013 Mar&nbsp;2, 2009 |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=18 July 2011}}</ref> he also dismissed [[Shivnarine Chanderpaul]] and [[Sulieman Benn]], finishing with 3 for 125 from 37 overs. With England batting out the match, Anderson did not feature again as the Test match was drawn.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cricinfo.com/wiveng2009/content/story/393131.html |title=Cook century ensures the stalemate |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=14 July 2013}}</ref> With England still 1\u20130 down in a series they were expected by many to win comfortably, victory was needed in the fifth and final Test at [[Queen's Park Oval]] in [[Trinidad]]. After England made 546/6 declared, Anderson again struggled as the West Indies were bowled out for 544, a deficit of 2 runs, with Anderson picking up the wicket of [[wicket-keeper]] [[Dinesh Ramdin]] for 70 runs, with an economy of just 2.18, one of his best in Test cricket.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cricinfo.com/ci/engine/match/352664.html |title=5th Test: West Indies v England at Port of Spain, Mar 6\u201310, 2009 &#124; ESPN Cricinfo |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=18 July 2011}}</ref> With England setting the West Indies a target of 240 runs to win, Anderson had arguably his best innings of the tour. After dismissing opener [[Lendl Simmons]], Anderson bowled 16 overs of reverse swing, picking up two more wickets as again England fell just short of victory, this time by two wickets.\n\nWith the Test series lost, England were keen to regain some honour in the [[Twenty20|T20]] and [[One Day International|ODIs]] which remained. After taking 3 for 48 in 8 overs in a warm-up match against the WIPA President's Select XI,<ref>{{cite news|title= Tour match: WIPA President's Select v England |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/shared/fds/hi/statistics/cricket/scorecards/2009/3/15134/html/scorecard.stm |publisher=BBC Sport |accessdate=14 May 2013}}</ref> Anderson led the England attack in the T20 international. Despite finishing with decent figures of 1\u201319 in 3 overs,<ref>{{cite news |title=NatWest International Twenty20 Match: West Indies v England |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/shared/fds/hi/statistics/cricket/scorecards/2009/3/15135/html/scorecard.stm |publisher=BBC Sport |accessdate=14 May 2013}}</ref> England were beaten soundly.<ref>{{cite news|last=Brett |first=Oliver |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/england/7939028.stm |title=Sarwan condemns England to defeat |publisher=BBC News |date=15 March 2009 |accessdate=14 July 2013}}</ref> The first One-Day International, however, saw England inflict their first defeat on the West Indies of the tour. After posting 270 for 7 in their 50 overs,<ref>{{cite news|title=One Day International Series: West Indies v England |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/shared/fds/hi/statistics/cricket/scorecards/2009/3/15136/html/scorecard.stm |publisher=BBC Sport |accessdate=14 May 2013}}</ref> Rain interrupted the West Indies' reply, leading to the result being decided on the [[Duckworth\u2013Lewis method]]. With the light fading, Anderson succeeded in having [[Kieron Pollard]] caught on the boundary by Steve Harmison. Due to the intricacies of the D/L system, this wicket ensured England won the match by a single run.<ref>{{cite news|last=Brett |first=Oliver |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/england/7949237.stm |title=England win after farcical finish |publisher=BBC News |date=1 January 1970 |accessdate=14 July 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn the next two ODIs, England suffered two more defeats, with Anderson taking 3 for 37 from 9 overs in the second ODI, as well as making 8 with the bat,<ref>{{cite news |title=One Day International Series: West Indies v England |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/shared/fds/hi/statistics/cricket/scorecards/2009/3/15137/html/scorecard.stm |publisher=BBC Sport |accessdate=14 May 2013}}</ref> and went on to take 1 for 39 from 5 overs and 0 not out<ref>{{cite news |title=One Day International Series: West Indies v England |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/shared/fds/hi/statistics/cricket/scorecards/2009/3/15138/html/scorecard.stm |publisher=BBC Sport |accessdate=14 May 2013}}</ref> as England fell 2\u20131 behind in the five-match series. England therefore needed to win the fourth ODI in Barbados to keep the series alive. Bowling first, England restricted the West Indies to 239/9 in their 50 overs, with Anderson himself taking the wicket of Fidel Edwards to finish with figures of 1 for 41 with 1 maiden in the 10 he bowled. Duckworth-Lewis again helped England as they chased down 136 in 18 overs to win by nine wickets.<ref>{{cite news|title=One Day International Series: West Indies v England |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/shared/fds/hi/statistics/cricket/scorecards/2009/3/15139/html/scorecard.stm |publisher=BBC Sport |accessdate=14 May 2013}}</ref> Thus, the series was tied at 2\u20132 going into the final match in [[St. Lucia]]. The West Indies won the toss and elected to bowl first, with England able to post 172/5 in 29 overs (the innings shortened by rain). With 29 overs to chase 173 for victory, the West Indies lost Gayle to Anderson in the first over with the score at 1/1, Anderson going on to add the wicket of Kieron Pollard as he finished with match figures of 2/34 from 6 overs as England won the match by 26 runs, with Anderson's Lancashire teammate [[Andrew Flintoff]] taking a [[List of One Day International cricket hat-tricks|hat-trick]].\n\nAnderson finished the tour with 9 wickets at an average of 38.00 from the Test series, with an economy rate of 2.65 runs per over from both innings and best match figures coming in the fifth Test at Trinidad,<ref>[http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/player/8608.html?class=1;template=results;type=bowling;view=series|Bowling Test series averages]</ref> as well as accumulating 24 runs at an average of 12.00, with a highest-score of 20.<ref>[http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/player/8608.html?class=1;template=results;type=batting;view=series|Batting Test series averages]</ref> In the ODIs, Anderson took 9 wickets at 21.11 and an economy rate of 5.00 runs per over<ref>[http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/player/8608.html?class=2;template=results;type=bowling;view=series|Bowling ODI series averages]</ref> and 8 runs at an equivalent average.<ref>[http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/player/8608.html?class=2;template=results;type=batting;view=series|Batting ODI series averages]</ref>\nHe then rejected offers to play in the [[Indian Premier League|IPL]] since he wanted to commit to a bright future for England over the following summer.\n\nThe Wisden Trophy was up for grabs again a few months later when the West Indies replaced [[Zimbabwe national cricket team|Zimbabwe]], who were still excluded from participating in Test match cricket by the ICC (although originally the tour had been scheduled to be played by Sri Lanka, who pulled out to allow their players to play in the IPL), in a two-Test and three-ODI tour. Anderson was selected after a bright start to the season with Lancashire, which included figures of 11\u2013109 in a match against [[Sussex County Cricket Club|Sussex]] at Hove.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cricinfo.com/countycricket2009/engine/match/382914.html |title=Sussex v Lancashire at Hove, Apr 21\u201324, 2009 &#124; ESPN Cricinfo |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=18 July 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe first Test was held at Lord's, beginning on 6 May 2020. Anderson was not involved directly until the second day, with England batting first, but made only a single in a 19-ball innings. With the wicket showing a green tinge and some cloud cover, Anderson was expected to excel. However he struggled to find his length bowling in the first innings and finished wicketless from seven overs having conceded 32.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cricinfo.com/ci/engine/match/380712.html |title=1st Test: England v West Indies at Lord's, May 6\u20138, 2009 &#124; ESPN Cricinfo |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=18 July 2011}}</ref> An improvement in the second innings saw him take the first two wickets after the follow-on, including that of the West Indies captain Chris Gayle, and finishing with figures of 2\u201338 from 15 overs and match figures of 2\u201370 as England won by ten wickets.\n\nFrom Lord's, the teams moved to [[Riverside Ground|Chester-le-Street]] for the second and final Test of the series. England again won the toss and chose to bat, and proceeded to dominate the West Indies bowling attack, amassing 569\u20136 declared. Anderson was sent in at the end of the first day in his role as night-watchman to protect Pietersen. Batting with Alastair Cook, they made a partnership of 44, Anderson hitting 14 of them to extend his run of innings without a duck in Test cricket. Later on day three, he was given the ball as England set out to take 20 West Indian wickets and secure match victory. Anderson found some significant swing in the cloudy conditions there, and proceeded to skittle through the West Indies top order, taking the first three wickets (including Gayle again) leaving the West Indies on 68/3.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cricinfo.com/ci/engine/match/380713.html |title=2nd Test: England v West Indies at Chester-le-Street, May 14\u201318, 2009 &#124; ESPN Cricinfo |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=18 July 2011}}</ref> Two late strikes secured Anderson a five-wicket haul, his first in 19 innings since his 7-wicket haul against New Zealand at Trent Bridge the previous summer.<ref>[http://stats.cricinfo.com/ci/engine/player/8608.html?class=1;template=results;type=bowling;view=innings|Statsguru \u2013 JM Anderson \u2013 Test bowling \u2013 Bowling innings list]. ESPNcricinfo. Retrieved 30 May 2010.  {{webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20120715000329/http://stats.cricinfo.com/ci/engine/player/8608.html?class=1;template=results;type=bowling;view=innings |date= 15 July 2012 |title=Statsguru }}</ref> Anderson went on to take 4 further wickets after the West Indies were asked to follow-on (for the second time in the series) and England went on to win by an innings and 83 runs. With nine wickets in the match for 125 runs, Anderson was named the Man of the Match,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cricinfo.com/engvwi2009/content/story/405039.html |title=Anderson has Ashes in his sights |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=14 July 2013}}</ref> only the second time in his career he had achieved this in a Test match.\n\n[[File:Anderson bowls in the Ashes, 2009.jpg|thumb|300px|Anderson bowling at Edgbaston during the 2009 Ashes]]\n\nThe first match of the following ODI series at Headingley was abandoned due to heavy rain, leaving two One-Day matches to be played. Anderson was named in the England squad for the series, and was selected for both matches. In the first match at [[Bristol]], he bowled six overs for nineteen, with one maiden, but finished wicketless as the West Indies were bowled out for 160.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cricinfo.com/ci/engine/match/380715.html |title=2nd ODI: England v West Indies at Bristol, May 24, 2009 &#124; ESPN Cricinfo |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=18 July 2011}}</ref> England went on to win the match by six wickets, meaning Anderson was not needed to bat. Neither was he required to bat in the last match of the tour as England scored 328/7 from their 50 overs. Although Anderson went at a run a ball in reply, conceding 58 from 9.4 overs, he took three wickets including the last of the match (that of [[Sulieman Benn]]) as the West Indies fell 58 runs short, sealing a 2\u20130 victory for England in both the Test and ODI series.\n\n===2009\u201310: South Africa===\nAnderson went on the tour of South Africa as one of the leaders of the English attack, having established himself in all formats of the game. In the opening T20 International, Anderson failed to pick up a wicket, although he was fairly economical, going at 8 runs an over. Anderson improved in the following match, bowling 4 for 28 runs, picking up a wicket. He was the pick of the English bowlers as South Africa won the match, posting over 200. Anderson bowled well in the ODI series, picking up regular wickets. He claimed 3\u201360 in the second ODI, and 5\u201323 in the fourth match. The four-match Test series was drawn 1\u20131, with Anderson bowling well. He picked up 5 wickets for 63 runs during the 3rd Test, as well as 4\u201373 in the opening match.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/rsaveng09/content/story/437662.html |title=Anderson almost missed one-dayers |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=19 May 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/england/content/story/453492.html |title=Anderson still in the dark over knee problem |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=19 May 2013}}</ref>\n\n===2010: Bangladesh and Pakistan===\nAnderson was selected in the England squad for the 2010 T20 World Cup, despite not being regarded as a specialist in this format of cricket. He did not play in the opening group match against the West Indies. With England playing well in the tournament, and with the three-man seam attack of Stuart Broad, Ryan Sidebottom and Tim Bresnan performing, Anderson could not break into the side. England went on to win the tournament, beating Australia in the final.\n\nEngland faced Bangladesh in a two-match Test series. England were expected to win easily and cruised to victory in the first Test, with Anderson taking figures of 4\u201378 and 1\u201384. Anderson also played in the second Test, finishing with figures of 1\u201345 and 3\u201316. England won the series 2\u20130. Anderson played in the first ODI, but was expensive, taking figures of 3\u201374. He was wicketless in the second game as England suffered a shock defeat. Anderson did not play in the decider, which England won to take the series.\n\nEngland then played Pakistan at home. It was during this series that Anderson established himself as one of the world's best Test bowlers. In the first match he took 5\u201354 and 6\u201317 which England won. This left Anderson with match figures of 11\u201371. He helped England win the second Test, achieving figures of 4\u201320 in the first innings. Anderson continued to impress in the final two Tests continuing to be economical and providing a wicket-taking threat. Anderson was rested for the first ODI, but returned in the second, taking 1\u201336 in ten overs. He then took 3\u201326 in the third match, before playing the remaining matches of the series. Although Anderson struggled to take wickets, his economical bowling frustrated the opposition and kept the run rate down. By the end of the tour, Anderson had established himself as the leader of the England attack, with his swing bowling making him one of the most feared bowlers in the world.\n\n===2010\u201311: Australia===\nAs expected, Anderson was selected in the England squad to play Australia, where he developed his own wobble-seam delivery to combat the Kookaburra ball that doesn't swing as much for as long.<ref>{{Citation|last=ajit ray|title=James Anderson Masterclass \u2013 Part 1|date=16 November 2016|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=TELre9qg0LI|accessdate=7 August 2017}}</ref> Anderson played well in the opening tour games and took two wickets in the opening Test match, which finished as a draw. In the second Test England thrashed Australia, winning by an innings and 71 runs. Anderson took 4\u201351 in the first innings and Australia were never able to recover. England lost the third Test, but Anderson still impressed taking 4 wickets. Anderson took 4\u201344 in the fourth Test, which England won to retain the Ashes. He then took 4\u201366 and 3\u201361 as England won the fifth Test and series 3\u20131. During the series Anderson became the second youngest England bowler to claim 200 Test wickets.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/cricket/international/england/8211822/The-Ashes-2010-James-Andersons-200-Test-wicket-milestone-fails-to-paper-over-England-fielding-faults.html |title=The Ashes 2010: James Anderson's 200 Test wicket milestone fails to paper over England fielding faults |author=Scyld Berry |newspaper=The Telegraph |accessdate=25 May 2013 |location=London |date=18 December 2010}}</ref> Anderson was rested at the start of the ODI series, but with England struggling he was recalled, taking 2\u201357 in the third match. In the sixth match Anderson took 1\u201391 of his ten overs as the England team struggled. Anderson took 3\u201348 in the final match of the series, but it wasn't enough to prevent another defeat as England lost the one-day series 6\u20131.\n\n===2011: World Cup, Sri Lanka and India===\nAnderson was selected in the squad for the 2011 World Cup and played in the opening game against the Netherlands. He was involved in the dramatic tie against India, where both teams posted 338, and also played as England suffered an embarrassing defeat against Ireland. His best match of the tournament came when he helped England defend 171 against South Africa, where he bowled six overs, collecting figures of 2\u201316. He was left out of the team against the West Indies, which England won. Anderson did not appear in England's final match against Sri Lanka, in which they lost by ten wickets and so bowed out at the quarter-final stage of the competition. Overall, Anderson had a disappointing tournament, although the pitches did not suit his style of bowling being unable to get the ball to swing.\n\nAnderson was part of the England team when Sri Lanka toured in 2011. Anderson took 3\u201366 in the first innings, but was unable to bowl in the second due to an injury. England won the first Test after Sri Lanka collapsed for 82 all out in the second innings. Anderson was ruled out of the second Test through injury but returned for the third, taking figures of 2\u201356 and 2\u201381 as England drew the match, but won the series 1\u20130. Anderson took 4\u201318 in the first ODI but was wicketless in the second match. In the fourth match he returned to his best, taking 3\u201324. In the final match he took 2\u201355, helping England to a series win.\n\nEngland's next opponents were India. England needed to win the four match series by two games to overtake India in the world rankings and become the new top-ranked Test team. Anderson shone in the first Test, taking 5\u201365 as England took a 1\u20130 lead. Anderson took 5 more wickets in the second Test and a further 6 in the third as England took a 3\u20130 series lead. Anderson took 3 more wickets in the final Test as England won the series 4\u20130 and became the new world Number Ones. Following Anderson's performance, he was widely considered the premier fast bowler in the world. Anderson took 3\u201348 in the third ODI but was left out of the final game of the series as had already won, taking a 2\u20130 lead into the final match, which they also won by 6 wickets.\n\n===2011\u201312: Pakistan and Sri Lanka===\nEngland toured Pakistan at the back end of 2012. The series was held in [[UAE|the UAE]]. England struggled in the conditions and slumped to a heavy defeat in the first Test, with Anderson largely ineffectual. England again lost the second Test, with poor performances from the batsmen giving the bowlers little to work with. Anderson took his best figures of the tour, 3\u201335 in the final match of the series, but it wasn't enough to prevent a whitewash for Pakistan. After the series, England moved on to Sri Lanka for a two-match Test series. Anderson took 5\u201372 in the first innings but it wasn't enough to prevent a fourth straight defeat for England. Anderson was praised for his performance in conditions which did not favour seam bowlers. England won the final Test to level the series, with Anderson taking figures of 4\u201398 in the match. As a result of his performances, Anderson was named England Cricketer of the Year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/england/content/story/564834.html |title=Anderson voted Player of the Year |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |accessdate=19 May 2013}}</ref>\n\n===2012: West Indies and South Africa===\nIn the second Test against West Indies, Anderson took 4\u201343 at Trent Bridge, a ground where he always performed due to the swing-friendly conditions. With England taking a 2\u20130 series lead, Anderson was rested for the final match of the series to help him avoid burnout.  Anderson played in the ODI series against the West Indies, taking 2\u201338 in the second match. England then played Australia in 5 ODIs. Anderson took 2\u201355 in the first match, and 2\u201334 in the fourth match. There were suggestions that Anderson would play no part in the series, both to rest him and to deprive Australia of facing him ahead of the Ashes series the following year. However, despite this, Anderson played a key part in the series.\n\nEngland faced South Africa at the end of the summer, with their Number One ranking on the line. The series was also anticipated as a chance to see Anderson go head to head with Dale Steyn, regarded as the world's two best seam bowlers. The series was a disappointment for England. They lost the first Test by an innings, with Anderson managing figures of 1\u2013116. The second Test was a tighter affair, with the match ending in a draw, but Anderson could only manage three wickets in the match. England lost the third Test, meaning a 2\u20130 series defeat, and South Africa earned their place at the top of the Test rankings. Anderson took 4\u201344 in the third ODI, and 2\u201341 in the fifth as the series ended as 2\u20132 draw. This was seen as a positive result for England, with several young players being blooded against an experienced South African team.\n\n===2012\u201313: India, New Zealand and Champions Trophy===\nFollowing the defeat to South Africa, Andrew Strauss retired and was replaced as captain by Alistair Cook. The first series under the leadership of Cook was against India. England lost the first Test by 9 wickets, with Anderson taking just one wicket in the match. England won the second Test convincingly, but Anderson again struggled in conditions more suited to spinners. Anderson performed much better in the third Test, taking six wickets overall. Anderson took the wicket of [[Sachin Tendulkar]] in the 1st innings of the third Test to equal [[Muttiah Muralitharan]] as the most successful bowler against Tendulkar with a total of eight dismissals. With England needing just a draw to win the series in the final Test, Anderson took 4\u201381 to help England draw the match and win the series 2\u20131.\n\nIn the tour of New Zealand, Anderson returned to the ODI side. In February 2013 during England's loss of the [[English cricket team in New Zealand in 2012\u201313#1st ODI|1st One day international in New Zealand]], with the wicket of [[BJ Watling]], his 529th in international cricket, Anderson overtook [[Ian Botham]] to become England's all-time highest wicket-taker.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2013/feb/19/james-anderson-ian-botham-england-record |title=James Anderson 'honoured' to overhaul Sir Ian Botham's England record |accessdate=18 May 2013|work=The Guardian|location=London|date=19 February 2013}}</ref> He took 5\u201334 in the second match as England went on to win the series. Anderson took 4\u2013137 in the first Test and went on to take wickets in every innings in the series. The series itself finished 0\u20130, with the batsmen dominating on good batting wickets.\n\n[[File:Anderson bowling, 2013.jpg|thumb|300px|Anderson bowling during the Champions Trophy match in which he became England's leading wicket-taker in ODIs]]\n\nAnderson played a key role in the 2013 Champions Trophy. He took 3\u201330 against Australia as England made a winning start to their campaign. During the match [[2013 ICC Champions Trophy|ICC Champions Trophy match against Australia]] he became England's leading ODI wicket-taker when he took his 235th wicket.<ref name=\"ODIWickets\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/cricket/22829402 |title=James Anderson becomes England's leading ODI wicket-taker |accessdate=8 June 2013|publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref> In the final Group A match he took 3\u201332 as England reached the semi-finals of the competition. England shocked South Africa and won by 7 wickets, with Anderson taking 2\u201314 off 8 overs. England played India, the favourites for the competition in the final, in what proved to be a rain interrupted match. Only being able to bowl four overs, Anderson took 1\u201324, but a poor batting performance meant that England lost the match and India went on to become champions.\n\nIn the opening match of the Test series against New Zealand, Anderson took match figures of 7\u201370. One the second day of the [[New Zealand cricket team in England in 2013#1st Test|1st Test against New Zealand]], he became the fourth English bowler to take 300 Test wickets when he dismissed [[Peter Fulton]].<ref name=\"Anderson300\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/cricket/22573162 |title=James Anderson takes 300th Test wicket for England |accessdate=17 May 2013|publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref> England went on to win the series 2\u20130. Anderson took 3\u201331 in the first ODI, and also played in the second match. England lost the series 2\u20131.\n\n===2013\u201314: Australia===\nDuring the summer of 2013, England played Australia in the first of what would be back-to-back Ashes Series. The first Test of the [[2013 Ashes Series|home series]] was held at Trent Bridge. Despite being favourites, England struggled in the first innings, posting just 215. Anderson led the fightback, taking 5\u201385 as England bowled Australia out for 280. As Australia closed in on winning the match in the second innings, Anderson took 5\u201373, including the winning wicket. Anderson was required to bowl a long spell to win England the match, and Kevin Pietersen later posted a picture of Anderson lying exhausted on the floor. England won the second Test, although this time Anderson was less influential, taking only three wickets. Anderson was again quiet in the third Test, in which England managed to hold on to a draw following a long rain delay. Anderson took 2\u201365 in the fourth Test as England went 3\u20130 up in the series. Following the game, there was speculation Anderson would be rested for the final Test to ensure he would be fresh for the return series in Australia. However, Anderson played and took 4\u201395 in the first innings, as the match ended in a draw and England won the series 3\u20130. Anderson was rested for the ODI series as back up bowlers such as Ben Stokes and Boyd Rankin were given the chance to play.\n\nAnderson again toured Australia as part of the [[2013\u201314 Ashes series]]. It proved to be a miserable tour for Anderson and the rest of his England teammates. Anderson was ineffectual in the first Test as England lost convincingly. He took 3 wickets in the second Test but it was clear the conditions did not suit his game. In the third Test he bowled 19 wicketless overs and conceded 105 runs as England lost the series. He took 4\u201367 in the fourth Test but was unable to prevent defeat as the English batsmen continued to struggle. In the fifth Test Australia completed the whitewash, with Anderson taking three wickets in the match. Anderson was rested for the ODI series, which England again struggled in, losing 4\u20131.\n\n===2014: Sri Lanka and India===\n\nFollowing the Ashes series, England played Sri Lanka at home. In the first match of the series Anderson had figures of 1\u201322. In the second ODI between England and Sri Lanka, Anderson took two wickets for 38 runs. He finished with figures of 2\u201310 in the next match as England won by 10 wickets. He took 2\u201360 in the next match as Sri Lanka levelled the series at 2\u20132. England lost the final match of the series, with Anderson finishing with figures of 1\u201333. After picking up figures of 3\u201393 in the Sri Lankan first innings, he took 4\u201325 in the second as England fell narrowly short of victory as the first Test ended in a draw. In the second Test, he took 2\u201349 in the first innings before taking 3\u201391 in the second. As England battled to save the Test, Anderson faced 55 balls but was dismissed on the penultimate ball of the match as England lost the match. Anderson was named England's man of the series after taking 12 wickets in the series.\n\nOn 12 July 2014, in the First Test of the [[Indian cricket team in England in 2014|series against India]], Anderson and teammate [[Joe Root]] broke numerous records in England's first innings of the first Test against [[Indian national cricket team|India]] at Trent Bridge. Anderson hit his maiden first-class fifty as well as posting the highest score (81 runs) by an England No 11 batsman in Test history. His innings was also the longest innings by a No 11 batsman in Test history. Timed at 230 minutes, it surpassed the previous record set by Mushtaq Ahmed in 1997 (183 minutes) by almost an hour. He and Root also set a new [[world record]] for a 10th-wicket partnership in Test cricket scoring 198 runs, beating the 163 run-partnership by Australians [[Phillip Hughes]] and [[Ashton Agar]] at [[Trent Bridge]] on 11 July 2013. Anderson and fellow bowler Stuart Broad were criticised for their performance in the second Test after failing to capitalise on a good bowling surface. Anderson finished with match figures of 5\u2013137 as England lost the match, increasing the pressure on the team. He returned to his best in the next Test as England levelled the series as he took figures of 5\u201353 in the first innings and 2\u201324 in the second. His first-innings spell was nominated to be one of the best Test bowling performance of the year 2014 by ESPNCricinfo.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/awards2014/content/story/819605.html|title=All hail the left-armers|website=www.espncricinfo.com|access-date=2020-02-24}}</ref>\nIn the fourth match of the series he took match figures of 5\u201364 as England won the match by an innings to go 2\u20131 up in the series. Anderson was again pivotal as England won the final match of the series, taking four wickets in the match. After the conclusion of the 5th Test, Anderson was named Man of the Series for taking 25 wickets. Anderson had a mixed ODI series against India. After the first match was abandoned, Anderson was wicket less in the first three games of the series, taking figures of 0\u201357, 0\u201329 and 0\u201338 as England went 3\u20130 down in the series. However, he bowled well in the final match of the series, taking figures of 2\u201339 as England won the match.\n\n===2015: Tri-Series===\nFollowing injury, Anderson returned to the England team for the second match of the Tri-Series against India, where he had figures of 4\u201318 to help England win. In the next match against Australia he was wicket less as England were defeated. In the game against India, Anderson picked up figures of 1\u201324 to help England qualify for the final. In the final, Anderson picked up two wickets but England lost the match and finished runners-up.\n\n===2015: World Cup===\nAnderson failed to take a wicket in the first match against Australia, finishing with figures of 0\u201367. In the next match against New Zealand he finished with figures of 0\u201337 as England suffered a humiliating eight wicket defeat. He took his first wickets of the tournament against Scotland as he collected figures of 2\u201330 as England won their first game of the tournament. He was again wicket less in England's defeat to Sri Lanka. In their must win game against Bangladesh, Anderson took figures of 2\u201345 but was later the last man out as England lost the game to exit the World Cup. In their final group game against Afghanistan, Anderson bowled economically, finishing with figures of 1\u201318 as England won their final match of the tournament.\n\n===2015: West Indies and New Zealand===\nIn April 2015, during the drawn first Test of the [[English cricket team in the West Indies in 2014\u201315|West Indies tour]] in [[Antigua]] (Anderson's 100th match), he had West Indies captain [[Denesh Ramdin]] caught at [[Slip (cricket)|slip]] for his 384th Test wicket, thus overtaking another [[Ian Botham]] record and becoming England's all-time highest Test match wicket-taker.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/cricket/32361929 |title=James Anderson proud to surpass Sir Ian Botham's Test record |accessdate=18 April 2015|publisher=BBC Sport|location=London|date=18 April 2015}}</ref> Despite Anderson's best efforts, the match ended in a draw. In the second Test Anderson took 2\u201347 West Indies first innings as they were bowled out for 299. His figures of 4\u201343 in the second innings helped England put themselves in a match winning position. They won the game by nine wickets to go 1\u20130 up in the series. In the final Test, Anderson took 6\u201342 in the West Indies first innings as England took a first innings lead. However, England collapsed in their second innings and although Anderson took a wicket in the West Indies second innings, it wasn't enough to prevent a five wicket defeat as the series ended in a 1\u20131 draw. He was awarded with the player of the series award.\n\n[[New Zealand cricket team in England in 2015|New Zealand toured England]] for a 2 test and 5 ODI series. Anderson took 1\u201388 in New Zealand's first innings in the first Test between the two sides. In the second innings he took 1\u201331 as England won the match by 124 runs to go 1\u20130 up in the series. In the second Test he took 2\u201343 as New Zealand were bowled out for 350. He made an unbeaten ten with the bat to help England reach 350 and level the scores. In New Zealand's second innings he took 2\u201396 as New Zealand won the Test to level the series at 1\u20131. During the series Anderson took his 400th Test wicket and scored his 1000th Test run.\n\n===2015: Australia===\nIn the first Test Anderson took figures of 3\u201343 in Australia's first innings to help restrict them to 308, and England went on to win the game by 169 runs. In the second Test he failed to take a wicket in the whole match, finishing with figures of 0\u201399 in the first innings and 0\u201348 in the second innings as Australia won the match by 405 runs. In the third Test, Anderson took 6\u201347 in the Australian first innings to help restrict them to 136. He took 1\u201315 in the second innings but injured himself in the process. Although England won the game to go 2\u20131 up in the series, Anderson was ruled out of the remainder of the series through injury. England went on to win the series 3\u20132.\n\n===2015: Pakistan===\nAnderson recovered from his injury in time for the Test series against Pakistan. In the first innings of the first Test, Anderson took figures of 2\u201342 and bowled economically as Pakistan were dismissed for 523. In the second innings he took figures of 2\u201330 as Pakistan were bowled out for 173, but England did not have enough time to force a win and the match finished in a draw. In the second Test Anderson took 1\u201340 in the first innings, before finishing with figures of 2\u201322 in Pakistan's second innings as they were dismissed for 354. However, England's batting was unable to chase down the target and the suffered a 127 run defeat. England needed to win the final Test of the series to level it, and Pakistan were dismissed cheaply for 234 in the first innings, with Anderson taking 4\u201317. However, they recovered in their second innings, scoring 355, despite Anderson taking 2\u201352. An England second innings collapse saw Pakistan win the series 2\u20130.\n\n===2015\u201316: South Africa===\nAnderson was injured for the first Test against South Africa. He returned to the side for the second Test but failed to make an impact, taking 1\u201377 as the match ended in a draw. In the third Test Anderson took 1\u201360 in South Africa's first innings, before taking 1\u201326 in their second innings as they collapsed to 83 all out to hand England a historic victory on South Africa soil. Anderson took his best figures of the series in the final Test, finishing with 3\u201347 in South Africa's second innings, but a poor batting performance from England saw South Africa win the Test by 280 run, although England won the series 2\u20131.\n\n===2016: Sri Lanka and Pakistan===\nIn the first Test against Sri Lanka, Anderson was in sublime form, taking figures of 5\u201316 in the tourist's first innings to restrict them to 91. In their second innings, he took figures of 5\u201329 as England secured a comprehensive victory by a margin of an innings and 88 runs. In the second Test, Anderson took 3\u201336 in Sri Lanka's first innings, and followed this up with 5\u201358 in their second innings as England secured another win, this time by nine wickets. In the final, rain affected match of the series, Anderson took figures of 2\u201361 in Sri Lanka's first innings, and then took the only wicket to fall in Sri Lanka's second innings as the match ended in a draw. Following his exploits, Anderson ended the series as the World's Number One Test bowler.\n\nAfter missing the first Test through injury, Anderson returned in the second match of the series and took four wickets in the match as England won to level the series at 1\u20131. In the third match, he took figures of 2\u201354 in Pakistan's first innings and then took 2\u201331 in their second innings as England recorded a 141 run victory. England lost the final match of the series, with Anderson taking just one wicket in the match as the series finished 2\u20132.\n\n===2016: India===\nAfter missing the series against Bangladesh through injury, Anderson returned to the side for the second Test against India. He took 3\u201362 in the first innings as India made 455. He then took 1\u201333 in the second innings. India won the match by 246 runs. In the third Test he did not take a wicket in India's first innings, and with India needing a small target to win the game in the second innings, Anderson again failed to take a wicket as India won by eight wickets. In the fourth Test he took 0\u201363 as India posted 631 and won the game by an innings and 36 runs. Anderson missed the final Test through injury, with England losing the series 4\u20130.\n\n===2017\u201318: Australia===\nAnderson was named as England Test vice-captain after Ben Stokes was suspended indefinitely. Stokes was arrested in the early hours of the morning following the third ODI against West Indies at Bristol in September 2017 from an incident near a night club, at which teammate [[Alex Hales]] was also present.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2017/sep/26/ben-stokes-england-arrested-night-bristol|title=England's Ben Stokes arrested in Bristol after win over West Indies|website=The Guardian|accessdate=26 September 2017}}</ref>&nbsp;\n\nMidway through the Ashes tour England Lions batsman [[Ben Duckett]] was suspended after pouring a drink over Anderson in a Perth bar. Although coach [[Trevor Bayliss]] described the incident as trivial, coming as it did after the Stokes affair and a head-butting incident between [[Cameron Bancroft (cricketer)|Cameron Bancroft]] and [[Jonny Bairstow]], it seemed to confirm that England had off-field issues during the 2017\u201318 Ashes.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Shemilt |first1=Stephan |title=Ashes: Ben Duckett suspended from playing on England Lions tour |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/cricket/42298950 |publisher=BBC Sport |accessdate=31 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nAnderson played all five Test matches in the Ashes but couldn't prevent his team losing control of the urn, with England slipping to a 4\u20130 series defeat. Despite the poor performance of the team as a whole, Anderson emerged with some considerable personal credit having returned figures of 17 wickets at an average of 27.82 over the Test series, including a haul of 5/43 in the 2nd innings of the day-night 2nd Test at Adelaide.<ref>{{cite web |title=James Anderson out to prove doubters wrong after maiden five-wicket haul in Australia |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/cricket/2017/12/05/james-anderson-prove-doubters-wrong-maiden-five-wicket-haul/ |website=The Telegraph |accessdate=31 July 2018}}</ref> He ended the tour as the top England wicket-taker in the Ashes. Over the entire series Anderson bowled 223.3 overs, the most in a series in his career.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Shemilt |first1=Stephan |title=Ashes: The winners and losers from the 2017\u201318 series |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/cricket/42602440 |publisher=BBC Sport |accessdate=31 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n===2018: New Zealand===\nDuring the [[English cricket team in New Zealand in 2017\u201318#2nd Test|second Test against New Zealand in 2018]], Anderson \u2013 along with partner [[Stuart Broad]] and the two opening bowlers from the opposition ([[Trent Boult]] and [[Tim Southee]]) \u2013 was part of just the third quartet of opening bowlers to take all 20 wickets in the first innings of each team in a single Test match (and the first since 1912).<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/content/story/1142229.html|title=New-ball nirvana: Anderson, Broad, Boult, Southee take all 20 wickets|publisher=ESPNcricinfo|access-date=3 April 2018}}</ref> In the same Test series, Anderson set another milestone by becoming the most heavily-used fast bowler ever in Test history, surpassing [[Courtney Walsh]]'s record of 30,019 deliveries in a Test career.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.timesnownews.com/sports/article/new-zealand-vs-england-james-anderson-overtakes-courtney-walsh-bowls-most-legal-deliveries-in-tests-as-pacer/213308|title=New Zealand vs England: James Anderson overtakes Courtney Walsh, bowls most legal deliveries in Tests as pacer|access-date=3 April 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/sports/cricket/england-in-new-zealand/james-anderson-becomes-most-over-worked-seam-bowler/articleshow/63590186.cms|title=James Anderson becomes most over-worked seam bowler |work=The Times of India|access-date=3 April 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.geo.tv/latest/189258-englands-james-anderson-sets-new-record|title=England's James Anderson sets new record|website=geo.tv|access-date=3 April 2018}}</ref> He was the second highest wicket-taker in the 2 match Test series, taking 8 wickets with England eventually losing the series 1\u20130.\n\n===2018: Pakistan and India===\nAnderson was selected in the England squad to face [[Pakistani cricket team in England in 2018|Pakistan in May 2018]] in a two Test match series. In the [[Pakistani cricket team in England in 2018#1st Test|first Test]] match, which Pakistan won, Anderson had team leading match figures of 4\u201394. In the [[Pakistani cricket team in England in 2018#2nd Test|second Test]] he took 5 wickets at the expense of 78 runs, to help England win by an innings and 55 runs. Overall Anderson took a team leading 9 wickets during the series, with the series being tied 1\u20131.\n\nAnderson was in the side as England played their 1,000th Test match<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sports.ndtv.com/england-vs-india-2018/india-vs-england-england-set-to-play-1000th-test-match-stuart-broad-picks-his-best-1889392|title=England Set To Play 1000th Test, Stuart Broad Picks His Best|website=ndtv.com|access-date=25 March 2019}}</ref>, during the first Test against India at Edgbaston in the [[Indian cricket team in England in 2018|five-match series]]. During the second Test, Anderson picked up his 100th wicket at Lord's in Tests<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2018/aug/12/jimmy-anderson-england-100th-wicket-at-lords-india|title=Jimmy Anderson century of Lord's Test wickets a first for the fast man|website=The Guardian|access-date=25 March 2019}}</ref>, and his 550th Test match wicket<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/sport/cricket/james-anderson-and-chris-woakes-dominate-india-as-england-seal-second-test-victory-at-lords-a3909566.html|title=James Anderson and Chris Woakes dominate India as England seal second Test victory at Lord's|website=London Evening Standard|access-date=25 March 2019}}</ref> as he took 5\u201320 in the first innings, and finished with match figures of 9\u201343. The third Test at Trent Bridge was won by India as they recovered from a 2\u20130 start to the series, Anderson took his 100th wicket against India in Tests.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/cricket/india-vs-england-james-anderson-enters-club-100-against-india-at-trent-bridge/story-SshsjIB4C8CsbXQSqgRw9H.html|title=India vs England: James Anderson enters Club 100 against India at Trent Bridge|website=Hindustan Times|access-date=25 March 2019}}</ref> In the fifth Test, Anderson equalled Glenn McGrath's record for the most Test wickets by a pace bowler (563), he then surpassed this later in the game when he took his 564th Test wicket.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/cricket/45464628|title=England v India: James Anderson breaks Glenn McGrath's record in host's win|publisher=BBC|access-date=25 March 2019}}</ref> Anderson took 24 wickets at an average of 18.13 during the series, the most wickets by any bowler during the series as England beat India 4\u20131.\n\n===2018\u201319: Sri Lanka and West Indies===\nAnderson played the first two Tests of the [[England cricket team in Sri Lanka in 2018-19#Test Series|three-match series]] in Sri Lanka. In the first Test, he took match figures of 1/53 from 22 overs, helping England to their first ever Test win in Galle.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/cricket/46148457|title=\nsri Lanka v England: Tourists complete 211-run win to end losing away streak|publisher=BBC|access-date=26 March 2019}}</ref> The second Test saw a record breaking 38 wickets taken by [[spin bowling|spin bowlers]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.crictracker.com/sri-lanka-vs-england-2018-2nd-test-statistical-highlights|title=Sri Lanka vs England 2018: 2nd Test \u2013 Statistical Highlights|website=crictracker.com|access-date=27 March 2019}}</ref>, with Anderson going wicketless for the first time in almost two years.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.howstat.com/cricket/statistics/players/PlayerProgressBowl.asp?PlayerID=3065|title=James Anderson bowling \u2013 Progressive Average and Aggregate|website=howstat.com|access-date=26 March 2019}}</ref> Anderson was rested for the third Test, to allow Stuart Broad match practice.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cricket.com.au/news/james-anderson-rested-third-test-england-sri-lanka-test-series-colombo/2018-11-21|title=England's Anderson rested for third Test|website=cricket.com.au|access-date=26 March 2019}}</ref> This meant Anderson finished with just 1 wicket in the series, the lowest in a Test series he had participated in since 2003.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.howstat.com/cricket/statistics/players/PlayerProgressBowl.asp?PlayerID=3065|title=James Anderson \u2013 Progressive Average and Aggregate|website=howstat.com|access-date=26 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nAnderson took a five-wicket haul during the first innings of the [[English cricket team in the West Indies in 2018-19#Test Series|three-match Test series]] against the West Indies at [[Kensington Oval]], Barbados. This was his 27th five-wicket haul, tying Ian Botham's record for England in Test matches.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thecricketer.com/Topics/england/james_anderson_takes_27th_test_five-wicket-haul_to_tie_with_sir_ian_botham_at_the_top.html|title=James Anderson takes 27th Test five-wicket-haul to tie with Sir Ian Botham at the top|website=thecricketer.com|access-date=26 March 2019}}</ref> Whilst en route to his five-wicket haul, he also became the first English bowler to take 200 Test wickets away from home.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/cricket/46979512|title=England in West Indies: James Anderson takes four wickets to boost tourists|publisher=BBC|access-date=26 March 2019}}</ref> Despite this, England lost the match by 381 runs, the West Indies' largest  victory in terms of runs at home. Anderson finished the series, which England lost 2\u20131, with 10 wickets at an average of 24.50.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.howstat.com/cricket/statistics/players/PlayerSeries.asp?PlayerID=3065#bowl|title=James Anderson \u2013 Performance Analysis by Series|website=howstat.com|access-date=26 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Achievements==\n{{main|List of international cricket five-wicket hauls by James Anderson}}\n\n*The most Test wickets taken by a pace bowler. (584 wickets) \n*He is currently the 4th highest Test wicket-taker of all time.\n*Anderson has taken 28 Test and 2 ODI five-wicket hauls including 3 Test ten-wicket hauls. \n*He is the only seam bowler to take 300+ Test wickets on home soil.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/england-v-south-africa-2017/content/story/1111078.html|title=Amla's latest landmark, and Anderson's home comforts|publisher=ESPNcricinfo|access-date=11 April 2017}}</ref>\n*He holds the world record for \"not out\" batting performances in Test cricket, achieving his 62nd Test \"not out\" at Lord's in 2017, passing the previous record of 61 set by [[Courtney Walsh]]. He has subsequently extended this record to 87.\n*He is the first England player to take 500 Test wickets.\n*The most international Test deliveries bowled by a pace bowler.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/story/_/id/23007257/anderson-hard-yards-set-new-record|title=Anderson's hard yards set new record|publisher=ESPNcricinfo|access-date=3 April 2018}}</ref>\n*First pace bowler, and second player overall, to take 100 Test wickets at a single venue (at [[Lord's]]; [[Muttiah Muralitharan]] has taken 100 wickets at three separate grounds in Sri Lanka)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2018/aug/12/jimmy-anderson-england-100th-wicket-at-lords-india|title=Jimmy Anderson century of Lord's Test wickets a first for the fast men {{!}} Andy Bull|last=Bull|first=Andy|date=12 August 2018|website=The Guardian|access-date=13 August 2018}}</ref>\n*He has taken 201 overseas wickets.\n\n==Awards==\nOn 8 December 2011 He was awarded the [[Freedom of the City|Freedom of the Borough]] of [[Borough of Burnley|Burnley]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-lancashire-15991447|title=Anderson gets freedom of Burnley|date=2011-12-01|work=BBC News|access-date=2020-02-24|language=en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.burnley.gov.uk/about-council/council-meetings/ful-council-special-meeting-8th-december-2011|title=Ful Council Special Meeting 8th December 2011 {{!}} Burnley Borough Council|website=www.burnley.gov.uk|access-date=2020-02-24}}</ref>\nIn the [[2015 Birthday Honours|2015 Queen's Birthday Honours]], Anderson was appointed an [[Officer of the Order of the British Empire]] (OBE) \"for services to cricket\".<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=61256 | date=12 June 2015 |page=B10| supp=y}}</ref> On 11 February 2016 he received his OBE at [[Buckingham Palace]].<ref name=\"OBEBP\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/england/content/story/971623.html |title=James Anderson receives OBE at Buckingham Palace |accessdate=11 February 2016|publisher=ESPNcricinfo}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|James Anderson (cricketer)}}\n* {{cricinfo|id=8608}}\n* [http://jamesanderson613.com/ James Anderon's Official Website]\n\n{{Navboxes colour\n|title= Awards and Achievements\n|bg= skyblue\n|fg= #000060\n|bordercolor=#000060\n|list1=\n{{Bowlers who have taken 300 wickets in Test cricket}}\n{{English Test match double}}\n{{Englishmen with 100 or more Test caps}}\n}}\n{{Navboxes colour\n|title= England squads\n|bg= skyblue\n|fg= #000060\n|bordercolor=#000060\n|list1=\n{{England Squad 2003 Cricket World Cup}}\n{{England Squad 2007 Cricket World Cup}}\n{{England Squad 2010 ICC World Twenty20}}\n{{England Squad 2011 Cricket World Cup}}\n{{England Squad 2015 Cricket World Cup}}\n}}\n{{Lancashire County Cricket Club squad}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Anderson, James}}\n[[Category:English cricketers]]\n[[Category:England Test cricketers]]\n[[Category:England One Day International cricketers]]\n[[Category:England Twenty20 International cricketers]]\n[[Category:English cricketers of the 21st century]]\n[[Category:Auckland cricketers]]\n[[Category:Lancashire cricketers]]\n[[Category:One Day International hat-trick takers]]\n[[Category:Cricketers at the 2003 Cricket World Cup]]\n[[Category:Cricketers at the 2007 Cricket World Cup]]\n[[Category:Cricketers at the 2011 Cricket World Cup]]\n[[Category:Cricketers at the 2015 Cricket World Cup]]\n[[Category:1982 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Officers of the Order of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Burnley]]\n[[Category:Wisden Cricketers of the Year]]\n[[Category:Lancashire Cricket Board cricketers]]\n[[Category:Cricketers who have taken five wickets on Test debut]]\n", "name_user": "103.60.175.78", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/James_Anderson_(cricketer)"}
{"title_page": "Jos Buttler", "text_new": "{{short description|English cricketer}}\n{{for|cricketer who plays for Guernsey|Josh Butler (cricketer)}}\n{{Use British English|date=September 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox cricketer\n| name = Jos Buttler\n| image = Jos Buttler 2017.jpg\n| image_size = 225\n| caption = Buttler in 2017\n| country = England\n| fullname = Joseph Charles Buttler\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1990|9|8|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Taunton]], [[Somerset]], England\n| heightft = 5\n| heightinch = 11\n| batting = Right-handed\n| role = [[Batting (cricket)|Batsman]], [[wicket-keeper]]\n| international = true\n| internationalspan = 2011\u2013present\n| testdebutdate = 27 July\n| testdebutyear = 2014\n| testdebutagainst = India\n| testcap = 665\n| lasttestdate = 24 January\n| lasttestyear = 2020\n| lasttestagainst = South Africa\n| odidebutdate = 21 February\n| odidebutyear = 2012\n| odidebutagainst = Pakistan\n| odicap = 226\n| lastodidate = 14 July\n| lastodiyear = 2019\n| lastodiagainst = New Zealand\n| odishirt = 63\n| T20Idebutdate = 31 August\n| T20Idebutyear = 2011\n| T20Idebutagainst = India\n| T20Icap = 54\n| lastT20Idate = 16 February\n| lastT20Iyear = 2020\n| lastT20Iagainst = South Africa\n| T20Ishirt = 63\n| club1 = [[Somerset County Cricket Club|Somerset]]\n| year1 = 2009\u20132013\n| clubnumber1 = 15\n| club2 = [[Melbourne Renegades]]\n| year2 = 2013/14\n| club3 = [[Lancashire County Cricket Club|Lancashire]]\n| year3 = 2014\u2013present\n| clubnumber3 = 6\n| club4 = [[Mumbai Indians]]\n| year4 = 2016\u20132017\n| club5 = [[Comilla Victorians]]\n| year5 = 2017\n| club6 = [[Sydney Thunder]]\n| year6 = 2017\u2013present\n| club7 = [[Rajasthan Royals]]\n| year7 = {{nowrap|2018\u2013present}}\n| hidedeliveries = true\n| columns = 4\n| column1 = [[Test cricket|Test]]\n| matches1 = 40\n| runs1 = 2,099\n| bat avg1 = 32.29\n| 100s/50s1 = 1/15\n| top score1 = 106\n| catches/stumpings1 = 83/0\n| column2 = [[One Day International|ODI]]\n| matches2 = 142\n| runs2 = 3,843\n| bat avg2 = 40.88\n| 100s/50s2 = 9/20\n| top score2 = 150\n| catches/stumpings2 = 171/31\n| column3 = [[First-class cricket|FC]]\n| matches3 = 105\n| runs3 = 5,080\n| bat avg3 = 32.35\n| 100s/50s3 = 6/30\n| top score3 = 144\n| catches/stumpings3 = 204/2\n| column4 = [[List A cricket|LA]]\n| matches4 = 213\n| runs4 = 6,009\n| bat avg4 = 44.84\n| 100s/50s4 = 11/36\n| top score4 = 150\n| catches/stumpings4 = 223/36\n| date = 16 February 2020\n| source = http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/content/player/308967.html ESPNcricinfo\n}}\n'''Joseph Charles Buttler''' {{post-nominals|country=GBR|size=100%|MBE}} (born 8 September 1990) is an English international [[cricket]]er who is currently [[Captain (cricket)|vice-captain]] of the [[England cricket team]] in [[limited overs cricket]].<ref name=\"BBC45017582\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/cricket/45017582|title=England v India: Adil Rashid named as hosts' only spinner for first Test|date=2018-07-31|access-date=2019-04-20|language=en-GB}}</ref> A right-handed [[Batting (cricket)|batsman]], he usually fields as a [[wicket-keeper]] and has represented England in [[Test cricket|Test]], [[One Day International]] (ODI) and [[Twenty20 International]] (T20I) cricket. He served as vice-captain of the England squad that won the [[2019 Cricket World Cup]], becoming world champions for the first time in their history.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/content/squad/1181195.html|title=England Squad|website=Cricinfo|language=en|access-date=2019-07-23}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/cricket/48983890|title=England win Cricket World Cup: Ben Stokes stars in dramatic victory over New Zealand|date=2019-07-14|access-date=2019-07-23|language=en-GB}}</ref> He currently plays for [[Lancashire County Cricket Club|Lancashire]] in English domestic cricket having previously played for [[Somerset County Cricket Club|Somerset]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.somersetlive.co.uk/sport/other-sport/england-new-zealand-jos-butler-3091229|title=How Somerset's Jos Buttler helped England win Cricket World Cup|last=Baker|first=Max|date=2019-07-14|website=somersetlive|access-date=2019-07-23}}</ref> He also plays for [[Rajasthan Royals]] in the [[Indian Premier League]] (IPL).<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/cricket/46225438|title=Indian Premier League: Jos Buttler & Ben Stokes retained by Rajasthan Royals|date=2018-11-15|access-date=2019-07-23|language=en-GB}}</ref> Buttler holds the record for the fastest ODI century by an England player and is regarded as one of the best [[Wicket-keeper-batsman|wicket-keeper batsmen]] in the world.<ref name=\"BBC34879336\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/cricket/34879336|title=Jos Buttler breaks record as England beat Pakistan to win series|date=2015-11-20|access-date=2019-05-31|language=en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://metro.co.uk/2019/05/11/england-freak-jos-buttler-good-virat-kohli-ab-de-villiers-ms-dhoni-says-nasser-hussain-9499477/|title=England 'freak' Buttler as good as Kohli, De Villiers and Dhoni \u2013 Hussain|date=2019-05-11|website=Metro|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-12}}</ref> Buttler's ability to recognise and manipulate field placements of opposing teams and score all around the ground has seen him labelled as a \"360-degree\" cricketer.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thecricketer.com/Topics/banner/buttler_brilliance_is_on_par_with_ab_and_williamson_ridiculous_he_hasnt_played_more_tests.html|title=Jos Buttler is on a par with AB de Villiers... he should have played more Tests for England|website=www.thecricketer.com|access-date=2019-07-23}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cricketcountry.com/news/cricket-world-cup-2019-360-degree-jos-buttler-looms-as-confident-englands-game-changer-847338|title=Cricket World Cup 2019: 360-degree Jos Buttler looms as confident England\u2019s game-changer|last=France-Presse|first=Agence|date=2019-05-24|website=Cricket Country|language=en-US|access-date=2019-07-23}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thecricketpaper.com/featured/4870/pringle-column-jos-buttler-really-is-the-cream-of-the-crop/|title=Pringle column: Jos Buttler really is the cream of the crop|last=admin|date=2018-07-04|website=The Cricket Paper|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-07-23}}</ref>\n\nButtler enjoyed a prolific cricket record while at school, sharing a record-breaking opening [[Partnership (cricket)|partnership]] while at [[King's College, Taunton]] in 2008. The following season, his school lost only one of seventeen matches under his captaincy and he was named 2010 [[Young Wisden Schools Cricketer of the Year|''Young Wisden'' Schools Cricketer of the Year]]. He made his Somerset first-team debut in 2009 after having played age-group cricket for the county. His performances led him to be selected to play for England at [[English U-19 cricket team|Under-19]] level before he made his senior England debut in 2011 and his [[Test cricket|Test]] debut in 2014.\n\n==Early life==\nBorn in [[Taunton]], [[Somerset]] on 8 September 1990,<ref name=\"ESPN308967\" /> Buttler was educated at [[King's College, Taunton|King's College]], where he displayed his early talent in cricket.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/cricket/2018/08/21/cant-underestimate-feeling-jos-buttlers-maiden-test-century/|title='You can't underestimate that feeling' \u2013 Jos Buttler's maiden Test century shows he can be heart of England's side|last=Wigmore|first=Tim|date=21 August 2018|work=The Telegraph|access-date=2 September 2019|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref>\n\n==Domestic career==\n\n===Youth career===\n\nButtler played extensively for Somerset's youth teams, appearing at Under-13, Under-15 and Under-17 level.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Players/136/136065/Other_matches.html |title=Other matches played by Joseph Buttler (55) |publisher=CricketArchive |accessdate=14 May 2010}}</ref> He made his senior club cricket debut for Cheddar before moving to Glastonbury in the 2006 season, aged just 15, taking three [[caught|catches]] and 15 [[Run (cricket)|runs]] as wicket-keeper.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/177/177817.html |title=Westbury v Glastonbury |publisher=CricketArchive |date=14 May 2006 |accessdate=30 April 2010}}</ref> Later in the same season, he made his first appearance for Somerset Second XI, scoring 71 in the second-innings, and taking six catches in the three-day match against [[Nottinghamshire County Cricket Club|Nottinghamshire]] Second XI.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/86/86407.html |title=Nottinghamshire Second XI v Somerset Second XI |publisher=CricketArchive |date=30 April 2010}}</ref> Playing for King's College, he finished the 2006 season with the school's leading [[Batting average (cricket)|batting average]], scoring 447 runs at an average of 49.66.<ref>{{cite book |last=Henderson |first=Douglas |editor1-first=Scyld |editor1-last=Berry |title=Wisden Cricketer's Almanack 2007 |edition=144 |year=2007 |publisher=John Wisden & Co. Ltd. |location=[[Alton, Hampshire]] |isbn=978-1-905625-02-4 |page=1020 |chapter=Schools Cricket, 2006}}</ref> The following season he played regularly for Glastonbury in the [[West of England Premier League]], and for Somerset Under-17s, for whom he scored two centuries; an [[Not out|unbeaten]] 119 during a two-day match against [[Surrey County Cricket Club|Surrey]] Under-17s,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/190/190626.html |title=Surrey Under-17s v Somerset Under-17s |publisher=CricketArchive |date=25 July 2007 |accessdate=30 April 2010}}</ref> and 110 against [[Sussex County Cricket Club|Sussex]] Under-17s.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/190/190659.html |title=Sussex Under-17s v Somerset Under-17s |publisher=CricketArchive |date=8 August 2007 |accessdate=30 April 2010}}</ref> He once again led the batting averages for King's College, with his 358 runs coming at 51.14.<ref>{{cite book |last=Henderson |first=Douglas |editor1-first=Scyld |editor1-last=Berry |title=Wisden Cricketer's Almanack 2008 |edition=145 |year=2008 |publisher=John Wisden & Co. Ltd. |location=[[Alton, Hampshire]] |isbn=978-1-905625-11-6 |page=967 |chapter=Schools Cricket, 2007}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Jos_buttler_keeping.jpg|thumb|left|Buttler keeping wicket for [[Somerset County Cricket Club|Somerset]]|alt=A young man with light brown hair is standing on some grass. He is wearing a burgundy, grey and black cricket uniform, large gloves and black trousers covered by black think pads on his lower legs.]]\nThe highlight of his school career came in April 2008, when he scored 227 [[not out]] during a record-breaking opening [[Partnership (cricket)|stand]] in a 50-over national schools game, adding 340 with [[Alex Barrow]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/7375597.stm |title=King's duo break schools record |publisher=[[BBC Sport]] |date=30 April 2008 |accessdate=1 May 2010}}</ref> He [[Captain (cricket)|captained]] King's during the 2008 season, and improved on his batting totals from the previous two years, scoring 851 runs, over 250 more than any other member of the team.<ref>{{cite book |last=Henderson |first=Douglas |editor1-first=Scyld |editor1-last=Berry |title=Wisden Cricketer's Almanack 2009 |edition=146 |year=2009 |publisher=John Wisden & Co. Ltd. |location=[[Alton, Hampshire]] |isbn=978-1-905625-16-1 |page=903 |chapter=Schools Cricket, 2008}}</ref> His batting average of 94.55 was the sixth highest amongst all school's batsmen reported in ''Wisden'', while his high-score of 227* was the highest score they recorded.<ref>{{cite book |last=Henderson |first=Douglas |editor1-first=Scyld |editor1-last=Berry |title=Wisden Cricketer's Almanack 2009 |edition=146 |year=2009 |publisher=John Wisden & Co. Ltd. |location=[[Alton, Hampshire]] |isbn=978-1-905625-16-1 |page=908 |chapter=Schools Cricket, 2008}}</ref> During that 2008 season, Buttler also played for Somerset Second XI. With captain [[Carl Gazzard]] keeping wicket in the majority of these matches, Buttler played purely as a batsman, although in his final match of the season for the team, he kept wicket and took six catches in the first-innings against [[Worcestershire County Cricket Club|Worcestershire]] Second XI.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/158/158388.html |title=Worcestershire Second XI v Somerset Second XI |publisher=CricketArchive |date=10 September 2008 |accessdate=30 April 2010}}</ref> In the previous match, against [[Hampshire County Cricket Club|Hampshire]] Second XI, Buttler had made 140 batting from [[Batting order (cricket)|number four]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/158/158384.html |title=Somerset Second XI v Hampshire Second XI |publisher=CricketArchive |date=3 September 2008 |accessdate=30 April 2010}}</ref>\n\nHe made his [[First-class cricket|first-class]] debut for Somerset in September 2009, replacing the injured [[Justin Langer]] for the [[County Championship]] match against Lancashire, scoring 30 in his only innings.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.westernmorningnews.co.uk/Horton-ton-cancels-Somerset-s-early-gains/story-11514053-detail/story.html|title=Horton ton cancels out Somerset gains|date=10 September 2009|work=Western Morning News|accessdate=15 February 2016}}</ref> He retained his place in the team for the following [[Pro40]] match against Hampshire, making his [[List A cricket|List A]] debut, although he was not required to bat.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/204/204641.html |title=Hampshire v Somerset |publisher=CricketArchive |date=13 September 2009 |accessdate=1 May 2010}}</ref> Selected as part of the Somerset squad for the [[2009 Champions League Twenty20]], Buttler made his debut in the 20-over format of the game in Somerset's final match of the league stage, remaining six not out at the close of the innings.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/251/251438.html |title=New South Wales v Somerset |publisher=CricketArchive |date=18 October 2009 |accessdate=1 May 2010}}</ref> Buttler again captained King's in 2009, and in the seventeen matches under his leadership they lost only once, and also won the Western School Twenty20 competition.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.somersetcountycc.premiumtv.co.uk/page/News/Newsdetail/0,,11333~2025849,00.html |publisher=[[Somerset County Cricket Club]] |title=JOS BUTTLER LIFTS WISDEN SCHOOL'S CRICKETER OF YEAR |date=15 April 2010 |accessdate=3 May 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110725090952/http://www.somersetcountycc.premiumtv.co.uk/page/News/Newsdetail/0%2C%2C11333~2025849%2C00.html |archivedate=25 July 2011 |df=}}</ref> Coupled with his 554 runs for the school at an average of 61.55, and his performances for Somerset, he was named 2010 ''Young Wisden'' Schools Cricketer of the Year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wisden.com/default.aspx?id=3 |title=The Young Wisden Schools Cricketer of the Year |work=Wisden |publisher=John Wisden & Co. |accessdate=1 May 2010}}</ref>\n\n===First-team opportunity===\n[[File:Jos buttler.JPG|thumb|right|150px|Buttler keeping wicket for [[Somerset County Cricket Club|Somerset]] in the [[ECB 40]]|alt=A young man with light brown hair is standing on some grass. He is wearing a burgundy, grey and black cricket uniform, large gloves and black trousers covered by black think pads on his lower legs.]]\n\nWhen [[Craig Kieswetter]] was called up into the England one-day side in 2010, Buttler was given the chance of a prolonged run in Somerset's first team. [[Brian Rose (cricketer)|Brian Rose]], Somerset's Director of Cricket, chose not to bring in an experienced keeper to deputise, explaining that Kieswetter had been in a similar position three years earlier and that he had good reports of Buttler's ability.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thisisbristol.co.uk/news/Somerset-hopeful-Buttler-set-profit-Kieswetter-s-England-heroics/article-1862840-detail/article.html |title=Ambitious Buttler ready to stand in for Kieswetter |work=[[The Herald (Plymouth)|The Herald]] |publisher=[[Northcliffe Media]] |date=22 April 2010 |accessdate=1 May 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130505084350/http://www.thisisbristol.co.uk/news/Somerset-hopeful-Buttler-set-profit-Kieswetter-s-England-heroics/article-1862840-detail/article.html |archivedate=5 May 2013 }}</ref> In his first match of the 2010 season, Buttler remained 22 not out at the close of Somerset's innings, posting his first runs in List A cricket, and he followed this up with two catches to help Somerset beat [[Glamorgan County Cricket Club|Glamorgan]] in their opening [[Clydesdale Bank 40]] fixture.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/262/262613.html |title=Glamorgan v Somerset |publisher=CricketArchive |date=25 April 2010 |accessdate=10 May 2010}}</ref>\n\nHe made his maiden first-class century in his fourth County Championship match, scoring 144 runs in an innings characterised by \"dogged determination and [a] decent range of shots\".<ref name=\"bbc13may10\">{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/counties/8681073.stm |title=Hampshire draw with Somerset as poor start continues |publisher=[[BBC Sport]] |date=13 May 2010 |accessdate=14 May 2010}}</ref> In his next match, he scored his debut List A half-century against Sussex. Buttler joined [[James Hildreth]] at the crease with Somerset at 109/4, requiring 183 more runs to win off 129 [[Delivery (cricket)|balls]]. The pair put on a partnership of 158 runs \"to turn the game on its head\", with Buttler making 69 in 53 balls.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.skysports.com/cricket/match_report/0,19822,11066_85647,00.html |title=Sussex impaled by Sabres |publisher=[[Sky Sports]] |date=15 May 2010 |accessdate=18 May 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100517040647/http://www.skysports.com/cricket/match_report/0%2C19822%2C11066_85647%2C00.html |archivedate=17 May 2010 |df=}}</ref> In doing so, they set a new record partnership for the fifth-wicket against Sussex.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Records/England/ListA/Somerset/Partnership_Records/Highest_Partnerships_Somerset_v_Sussex.html |title=Highest Partnerships For Somerset Against Sussex |publisher=CricketArchive |accessdate=18 May 2010}}</ref> His continued good batting form, which also saw him make scores of 52 and 31* in a County Championship match against [[Yorkshire County Cricket Club|Yorkshire]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/262/262674.html |title=Somerset v Yorkshire |publisher=CricketArchive |date=17 May 2010 |accessdate=30 June 2010}}</ref> saw him retain his place in the Somerset team upon Kieswetter's return.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/cricket/counties/7742271/Jos-Buttler-follows-Craig-Kieswetters-example-as-Somerset-battle-on.html |title=Jos Buttler follows Craig Kieswetter's example as Somerset battle on |publisher=Telegraph |last=Clutton |first=Graham |date=19 May 2010 |accessdate=30 June 2010}}</ref>\n\nButtler was named [[Player of the Match awards (cricket)|Man of the Match]] in Somerset's [[2010 Friends Provident T20]] semi-final victory over Nottinghamshire at the [[Rose Bowl (cricket ground)|Rose Bowl]], reaching a \"breathtaking\" half-century from 21 balls to score an unbeaten 55 runs in a partnership of 75 with [[Kieron Pollard]].<ref name=\"ci14aug10\">McGlashan, Andrew (14 August 2010) [http://www.espncricinfo.com/fpt20/content/story/472435.html Trescothick and Buttler lead Somerset to the final], [[CricInfo]]. Retrieved 11 November 2017.</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/series/8053/scorecard/435839/Nottinghamshire-vs-Somerset-2nd-Semi-Final-twenty20-cup-eng/ |title=Nottinghamshire v Somerset |publisher=CricInfo |date=14 August 2010 |accessdate=11 November 2017}}</ref> His aggressive batting won him many plaudits and helped Somerset reach the final of the [[2010 Clydesdale Bank 40]] as well as the Twenty20 cup.<ref name=\"ci4sep10\" />\n\nHis good form with the bat continued into 2011<ref>[http://www.espncricinfo.com/county-cricket-2011/content/story/522377.html Buttler stars in Somerset rout], [[CricInfo]], 8 July 2011. Retrieved 11 November 2017.</ref><ref>[http://www.espncricinfo.com/county-cricket-2011/content/story/525871.html Buttler responds after Panesar's five], [[CricInfo]], 3 August 2011. Retrieved 11 November 2017.</ref> as Somerset again reached the final of both the [[2011 Friends Life t20|T20]] and [[2011 Clydesdale Bank 40|40 over]] competitions, with Buttler top-scoring with a \"mature\" 86 runs from 72 balls in the 40 over final.<ref>McGlashan, Andrew (17 September 2011) [http://www.espncricinfo.com/county-cricket-2011/content/story/532737.html Hamilton-Brown sets up Surrey triumph], [[CricInfo]]. Retrieved 11 November 2017.</ref><ref>Brickhill, Liam (27 August 2017) [http://www.espncricinfo.com/county-cricket-2011/content/story/530050.html Bristling Somerset storm into final], [[CricInfo]]. Retrieved 11 November 2017.</ref> In both 2010 and 2011 he was awarded the [[NBC Denis Compton Award]] as Somerset's most promising young player<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/england/content/story/209589.html |title=The NBC Denis Compton Awards |publisher=Cricinfo |accessdate=16 December 2011}}</ref> and made his full England debut at the end of the season.<ref name=\"ci26aug11\" />\n\nThe 2012 season proved similarly productive for Buttler, and featured a \"brilliant\" half-century scored from 36 balls against [[Northamptonshire County Cricket Club|Northamptonshire]] in the [[2012 Clydesdale Bank 40|domestic 40 over competition]],<ref>[http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/content/story/568773.html Cool Buttler sees Somerset home], [[CricInfo]], 17 June 2012. Retrieved 11 November 2017.</ref> although increasing international call-ups limited his appearances for Somerset and Kieswetter remained the first-choice wicket-keeper for Somerset.<ref name=\"ci25feb13\" /> The second County Championship match of the 2013 season saw Buttler score 94 runs playing as a specialist batsman and an injury to Kieswetter at the end of April provided an opportunity for Buttler to claim his place as wicket-keeper in the side.<ref name=\"ci20apr13\">Dobell, George (20 April 2013) [http://www.espncricinfo.com/county-cricket-2013/content/story/631278.html Smith helping Surrey smile again], [[CricInfo]]. Retrieved 12 November 2017.</ref><ref>[http://www.espncricinfo.com/county-cricket-2013/content/story/633105.html Kieswetter ruled out for six weeks], [[CricInfo]], 29 April 2013. Retrieved 12 November 2017.</ref> Somerset started the County Championship season poorly, but Buttler was praised for adopting a mature approach to his batting, averaging over 40 with the bat in the Championship at the midpoint of the season and enjoying his most productive first-class season to date.<ref name=\"ci6jun13\">Dobell, George (6 June 2013) [http://www.espncricinfo.com/icc-champions-trophy-2013/content/story/638889.html England blueprint about to be tested], [[CricInfo]]. Retrieved 18 November 2017.</ref><ref name=\"ci28apr14\">Gardner, Alan (28 April 2014) [http://www.espncricinfo.com/county-cricket-2014/content/story/740271.html Buttler shows his first-class mettle], [[CricInfo]]. Retrieved 19 November 2017.</ref> After missing county matches again due to international call-ups, Buttler saw Kieswetter return as wicket-keeper in some T20 county matches and began to publicly question his future at the club if he was not to keep wicket regularly for the one-day side. He delayed signing a new contract he had been offered, concerned that by not being the main wicket-keeper for Somerset that he would put his international wicket-keeping place in jeopardy, despite a strong emotional attachment to the county.<ref>[http://www.espncricinfo.com/county-cricket-2013/content/story/652425.html Buttler mulls over Somerset future], [[CricInfo]], 17 July 2013. Retrieved 12 November 2017.</ref><ref>Dobell, George (30 July 2013) [http://www.espncricinfo.com/county-cricket-2013/content/story/656701.html Compton exit would prompt Taunton transition], [[CricInfo]]. Retrieved 18 November 2017.</ref> Despite Somerset's desire to keep Buttler at the club, they were unable to reach an agreement which satisfied Buttler's desire to keep wicket, and at the end of the season he announced that he would be leaving Somerset with the aim of securing his international place and breaking into the England Test side.<ref>Dobell, George (27 September 2013) [http://www.espncricinfo.com/county-cricket-2013/content/story/675157.html Buttler confirms Somerset departure], [[CricInfo]]. Retrieved 18 November 2017.</ref><ref name=\"ci2oct13\">Hodgson, Myles (2 October 2013) [http://www.espncricinfo.com/england/content/story/676321.html Buttler targets Test cricket from Lancashire move], [[CricInfo]]. Retrieved 18 November 2017.</ref>\n\n===Move to Lancashire===\n\nAt the end of September 2013, Lancashire announced they had signed Buttler.<ref name=\"ci2oct13\" /><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/england/content/current/story/675777.html |title=Lancashire confirm Buttler signing |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=30 September 2013 |accessdate=30 September 2013}}</ref> He scored 42 in his first Championship appearance for the county before compiling a \"game-changing\" innings of 72 on a difficult pitch at [[County Ground, Northampton|Northampton]]. This showcased Buttler's first-class batting potential and contributed to a record seventh wicket partnership for Lancashire against [[Northamptonshire County Cricket Club|Northants]].<ref name=\"ci28apr14\" /><ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/cricket/27183421 Northants v Lancashire: Jos Buttler boosts Red Rose victory hopes], [[BBC Sport]], 28 April 2014. Retrieved 19 November 2017.</ref><ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/cricket/27198784 Northants v Lancashire set up tight finish at Wantage Road], [[BBC Sport]], 29 April 2017. Retrieved 19 November 2017.</ref> He scored his first century for Lancashire (his fourth in first-class cricket) in June against [[Durham County Cricket Club|Durham]]<ref>Hardcastle, Graham (18 June 2014) [http://www.espncricinfo.com/county-cricket-2014/content/story/753571.html Rushworth helps Durham resist Buttler], CricInfo. Retrieved 22 November 2017.</ref> before equalling the record for the fastest fifty scored in T20 cricket, hitting a half-century in 22 balls against Northants on his way to 58 not out in the [[2014 NatWest t20 Blast]].<ref>Press Association (20 June 2014) [http://www.espncricinfo.com/county-cricket-2014/content/story/754197.html Buttler's record burns off champions], CricInfo. Retrieved 22 November 2017.</ref> Lancashire finished runners-up of the T20 competition, losing to [[Warwickshire County Cricket Club|Warwickshire]] in the final.<ref>Dobell, George (23 August 2014) [http://www.espncricinfo.com/series/8053/report/693273/Warwickshire-vs-Lancashire-Final-twenty20-cup-eng Woakes denies Flintoff as Birmingham win Blast], CricInfo. Retrieved 22 November 2017.</ref> He played 10 first-class matches for Lancashire during the season and was called into the England Test side as wicket-keeper in July, replacing the injured [[Matt Prior]], although doubts remained about the quality of his wicket-keeping.<ref>Hopps, David (25 July 2014) [http://www.espncricinfo.com/england-v-india-2014/content/story/764055.html Hope springs eternal in Buttler], CricInfo. Retrieved 22 November 2017.</ref><ref>[https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Players/136/136065/First-Class_Matches.html First-class matches played by Joe Buttler], CricketArchive. Retrieved 22 November 2017.</ref>\n\nHe extended his stay with Lancashire, announcing a new three-year contract on 27 May 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lccc.co.uk/cricket/news/2016-news/buttler-signs-new-three-year-deal-with-lancashire/|title=Buttler signs new three-year deal with Lancashire|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==England career==\n\n===2008\u201310: England youth career===\n\nButtler's first taste of [[international cricket]] came in July 2008, when he represented England Under-17s in two warm-up matches against [[New Zealand U-19 cricket team|New Zealand Under-19s]]. Batting at number five, he scored a rapid 77 not out in the 50-over contest, hitting 11 fours and two sixes during the 49 deliveries he faced.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/251/251728.html |title=England Under-17s v New Zealand Under-19s |publisher=CricketArchive |date=21 July 2008 |accessdate=3 May 2010}}</ref> He also played in the two-day match between the two teams, scoring 45 in the first-innings as the match was drawn.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/251/251729.html |title=England Under-17s v New Zealand Under-19s |publisher=CricketArchive |date=22 July 2008 |accessdate=3 May 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, Buttler played four matches for England Under-18s, two each against Scotland A and Scotland Development XI. He scored 103 not out in the first of these matches,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/259/259918.html |title=Scotland A v England Under-18s |publisher=CricketArchive |date=26 May 2009 |accessdate=1 May 2010}}</ref> and made starts in each of the following matches, reaching double figures on each occasion, but not scoring higher than 28.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/259/259919.html |title=Scotland A v England Under-18s |publisher=CricketArchive |date=27 May 2009 |accessdate=15 April 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/259/259921.html |title=Scotland Development XI v England Under-18s |publisher=CricketArchive |date=29 May 2009 |accessdate=15 April 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/259/259920.html |title=Scotland Development XI v England Under-18s |publisher=CricketArchive |date=29 May 2009 |accessdate=15 April 2010}}</ref> Two months later, Buttler made his England Under-19 debut, appearing in the first T20 against [[Bangladesh U-19 cricket team|Bangladesh Under-19s]]. Playing as a specialist batsman, he scored 33 runs off 17 balls as England won by five wickets.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/247/247628.html |title=England Under-19s v Bangladesh Under-19s |publisher=CricketArchive |date=28 July 2009 |accessdate=1 May 2010}}</ref>\n\nDuring the 2009\u201310 English winter, Buttler toured with the England Under-19 team. He joined up with the squad in Bangladesh following Somerset's elimination from the Champions League Twenty20 for the seven-match youth [[One Day International]] (ODI) series, playing again as a specialist batsman.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://stats.cricinfo.com/ci/engine/player/308967.html?class=21;filter=advanced;keeper=1;orderby=default;template=results;type=allround |title=Statistics / Statsguru / JC Buttler / Under-19s Youth One-Day Internationals |publisher=Cricinfo |accessdate=15 May 2010}}</ref> He failed to make a significant impact until the final match when he top-scored for England with 42 runs.<ref>[http://www.espncricinfo.com/bangladesh/content/story/432949.html Mahmudul and Saikat help Bangladesh sign off on high], [[CricInfo]], 4 November 1999. Retrieved 11 November 2017.</ref> He remained with the team for the [[2010 U-19 Cricket World Cup|Under-19 World Cup]], where he played all but one of England's six matches, keeping wicket in three of them. He scored 91 runs in three innings, with a top-score of 78 against [[Indian U-19 cricket team|India]] in the fifth-place play-off semi-final. His batting average of 30.33 ranked him fifth on the England team.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Events/NZ/ICC_Under-19_World_Cup_2009-10/England_Under-19s_Batting.html |title= Batting and Fielding for England Under-19s: ICC Under-19 World Cup 2009/10 |publisher=CricketArchive |accessdate=1 May 2010}}</ref>\n\n===2011\u201312: Early senior career===\n\nButtler was called into the senior England squad for the [[Twenty20 International]] (T20I) against the [[Indian cricket team in England in 2011#Only T20I|touring Indian team]] in September 2011.<ref name=\"ci26aug11\">{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/england-v-india-2011/content/current/story/529919.html |title=Pietersen rested for India ODIs |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |author=ESPNcricinfo staff |date=26 August 2011 |accessdate=26 August 2011}}</ref> He made his debut for the side in the match as a specialist batsman before going on to play against the [[West Indian cricket team in England in 2011|touring West Indies side]] later the same season.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/england-v-west-indies-2011/content/story/532333.html |title=Swann 'delighted' to lead England |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |author=ESPNcricinfo staff |date=14 September 2011 |accessdate=21 January 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/england-v-west-indies-2011/content/story/533802.html |title=West Indies stun England to level series |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |author=Andrew Miller |date=25 September 2011 |accessdate=21 January 2012}}</ref> During the winter of 2011 he was part of the England performance programme for batting and wicket-keeping in India,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/15112059.stm |title=England call for James Harris and Tom Maynard |publisher=[[BBC Sport]] |date=29 September 2011 |accessdate=21 January 2012}}</ref> and played in the [[England Lions cricket team|England Lions]] tours of Bangladesh and Sri Lanka,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/16217507.stm |title=James Taylor to lead England Lions in Bangladesh |publisher=[[BBC Sport]] |date=16 December 2011 |accessdate=21 January 2012}}</ref> scoring his maiden limited-overs century against [[Sri Lanka A cricket team|Sri Lanka A]] in January 2012.<ref>[http://www.espncricinfo.com/srilanka/content/story/551248.html Buttler serves up victory for England Lions], [[CricInfo]], 27 January 2012. Retrieved 11 November 2017.</ref> He played a T20I against [[India cricket team|India]] in [[Kolkata]] and then toured with [[English cricket team against Pakistan in the UAE in 2011\u201312|England to play Pakistan]] in the United Arab Emirates in early 2012, making his ODI debut, although he was out second ball [[Duck (cricket)|without scoring]].<ref name=\"ci18dec12\">[http://www.espncricinfo.com/india-v-england-2012/content/story/597626.html Anderson, Trott rested from ODIs], [[CricInfo]], 18 December 2012. Retrieved 11 November 2017.</ref>\n\nButtler continued to play regular T20 cricket for England throughout 2012. Against [[South Africa cricket team|South Africa]] at [[Edgbaston Cricket Ground|Edgbaston]], he joined Somerset teammate Craig Kieswetter with England on 64/3 with only 16 balls remaining. The pair gave \"a brutal display of power hitting\", raising the final score to 118/5, with Buttler hitting 30 runs from one 32-run over from [[Wayne Parnell]], the second most productive over in International T20 at the time.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/cricket/19576600|title=England v South Africa: Jos Buttler stars in crushing Twenty20 win|author=Sam Sheringham|publisher=[[BBC Sport]]|date=12 September 2012|accessdate=12 September 2012}}</ref> The innings established Buttler as a key part of the England one-day side; he had made 10 appearances before the match but reached double figures only once in his six innings, and his performance made him \"one of the most talked-about players\" in the England side.<ref name=\"ci16sep12\">Hopps, David (16 September 2012) [http://www.espncricinfo.com/icc-world-twenty20-2012/content/story/582499.html Buttler propelled into the spotlight], [[CricInfo]]. Retrieved 11 November</ref> Buttler spoke about how the innings made him feel \"calmer, more myself, more relaxed\"<ref name=\"ci16sep12\" /> and he received an [[England and Wales Cricket Board|ECB]] incremental contract later in the same month.<ref>[http://www.espncricinfo.com/england/content/story/583457.html Buttler earns incremental contract], [[CricInfo]], 22 September 2012. Retrieved 11 November 2017.</ref> He was selected for the England squad for the [[2012 ICC World Twenty20]], playing in all five of England's matches in the competition, although he scored only 40 runs in his five innings.<ref>[http://stats.espncricinfo.com/icc-world-twenty20-2012/engine/records/averages/batting_bowling_by_team.html?id=6856;team=1;type=tournament ICC World Twenty20 2012/13 \u2013 England/Records: Batting and bowling averages], [[CricInfo]]. Retrieved 11 November 2017.</ref>\n\n===2013\u201314: Test debut, Champions Trophy and T20 World Cup===\n\nButtler replaced a rested [[Jonathan Trott]] in the [[English cricket team in India in 2012\u201313|England ODI squad in India]] in early 2013<ref name=\"ci18dec12\" /> and replaced Craig Kieswetter as the first-choice wicket-keeper halfway through the ODI series.<ref name=\"ci25jan13\">[http://www.espncricinfo.com/india-v-england-2012/content/story/602127.html Buttler admits mixed emotions after ousting friend], [[CricInfo]], 25 January 2013. Retrieved 12 November 2017.</ref> This allowed Buttler to break into the England ODI side on a consistent basis, playing regularly throughout the year in both ODI and T20 formats and increasingly as a wicket-keeper, despite some reservations about the quality of his work behind the stumps.<ref name=\"ci22jan13\">Dobell, George (22 January 2013) [http://www.espncricinfo.com/india-v-england-2012/content/story/601767.html England ring for Buttler], [[CricInfo]]. Retrieved 12 November 2017.</ref><ref name=\"ci11feb13\">Dobell, George (11 February 2013) [http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/content/story/604503.html Would somebody call the Buttler?], [[CricInfo]]. Retrieved 12 November 2017.</ref> He scored his maiden half-century for England in a T20 warm-up match at the start of [[English cricket team in New Zealand in 2012\u201313|England's tour of New Zealand]] followed by his first T20I half-century in the second match of the series.<ref>[http://www.espncricinfo.com/new-zealand-v-england-2013/content/story/603493.html Buttler ready with bat and gloves], [[CricInfo]], 5 February 2013. Retrieved 12 November 2017.</ref><ref>Hopps, David (12 February 2013) [http://www.espncricinfo.com/new-zealand-v-england-2013/content/story/604543.html Brendon McCullum blitz draws New Zealand level], [[CricInfo]]. Retrieved 12 November 2017.</ref> After being confirmed as England's first-choice limited-overs wicket-keeper,<ref name=\"ci25feb13\">Dobell, George (25 February 2013) [http://www.espncricinfo.com/england/content/story/606412.html Giles vows to be more \"ruthless\" as coach], [[CricInfo]]. Retrieved 12 November 2017.</ref> he played in every match in the [[2013 ICC Champions Trophy]] in England. For his performances in 2013, he was named in the T20I XI by [[ESPNCricinfo|Cricinfo]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/review2013/content/story/705667.html|title=AB, Ajmal and Co|website=www.espncricinfo.com}}</ref>\n\nButtler played again in the [[2014 ICC World Twenty20]] in Bangladesh in March and played regular one-day cricket throughout the year. He scored his maiden ODI century against [[Sri Lanka cricket team|Sri Lanka]] at [[Lord's]] in May, scoring 121 in 61 balls with nine fours and four sixes, the then-fastest century by any England batsman.<ref>{{cite web |title=Records / One-Day Internationals / Batting records / Fastest hundreds |url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/content/records/211608.html |publisher=ESPNcricinfo (ESPN Internet Ventures) |accessdate=31 May 2014}}</ref> During the fifth ODI of the [[Sri Lankan cricket team in England in 2014|series]] at [[Edgbaston Cricket Ground|Edgbaston]], Buttler was controversially '[[Run out|Mankaded]]' by [[Sachithra Senanayake]], leading to tension between the sides. England captain [[Alastair Cook]] expressed his disappointment, stating: \"I've never seen it before in a game. I was pretty disappointed. If he was properly trying to steal the single then I could possibly understand it. But he was half a yard out of his crease.\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2014/jun/03/england-fury-sri-lanka-mankad-run-out-jos-buttler|title=England fury as Sri Lanka run out Jos Buttler Mankad-style in last ODI|last=Edgbaston|first=Andy Wilson at|date=2014-06-03|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-05-31|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\nAfter first choice wicket-keeper [[Matt Prior]] stood down after injury on 22 July 2014, Buttler was called up for the England squad for the [[Indian cricket team in England in 2014#3rd Test|third Test against India]]. He made 85 runs from 83 balls in his first Test innings. He played in the final three Tests of the series before reverting to one-day duty, touring Sri Lanka at the end of the year.\n\n===2015\u201317: World Cup, Ashes series, UAE and tour of Bangladesh===\n\nAfter playing for England in the [[Carlton Mid Triangular Series in Australia in 2014\u201315|Tri-series in Australia]] at the start of the year, Buttler was once again involved with England at an international tournament, playing in the [[2015 Cricket World Cup]] in Australia and New Zealand. He scored an unbeaten 39 in 19 balls against Sri Lanka<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/series/8039/scorecard/656441/england-vs-sri-lanka-22nd-match-pool-a-icc-cricket-world-cup-2014-15|title=Full Scorecard of England vs Sri Lanka, World Cup, 22nd Match, Pool A \u2013 Score Report {{!}} ESPNcricinfo.com|website=ESPNcricinfo|language=en|access-date=2019-05-29}}</ref> and made 65 against [[Bangladesh cricket team|Bangladesh]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/series/8039/scorecard/656463/bangladesh-vs-england-33rd-match-pool-a-icc-cricket-world-cup-2014-15|title=Full Scorecard of Bangladesh vs England, World Cup, 33rd Match, Pool A \u2013 Score Report {{!}} ESPNcricinfo.com|website=ESPNcricinfo|language=en|access-date=2019-05-29}}</ref> but ultimately England lost both matches in a disastrous campaign, failing to progress beyond the group stages.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/cricket/31792930|title=Cricket World Cup 2015: England knocked out by Bangladesh|date=2015-03-09|access-date=2019-05-29|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\nLater in the English winter he was called back into the Test side, as wicket-keeper, during the [[English cricket team in the West Indies in 2014\u201315|tour of the West Indies]]. He continued in the role throughout the English summer, playing both [[New Zealand cricket team in England in 2015|Tests against New Zealand]] and all five [[Australia cricket team in England in 2015|Ashes Tests against Australia]]. Buttler's batting during the Ashes series was criticised by [[Geoffrey Boycott]], who stated:\n\n{{quotation|Jos Buttler is like a rabbit caught in the headlights of Ashes cricket. A seven-year-old schoolboy would have played better. He hasn't made a run all series. He hasn't shown any application whatsoever. It looks to me like his mind and confidence is shot for Test cricket\u2014it's pathetic.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/cricket/34023919|title=Ashes 2015: Geoffrey Boycott angry at England against Australia|date=21 August 2015|publisher=|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref>}}\n\nHe continued to play one-day cricket alongside his Test role, making his then-highest ODI score of 129 from 77 balls against [[New Zealand cricket team|New Zealand]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/cricket/33065934|title=England hit record 408\u20139 to thrash New Zealand in ODI|date=2015-06-09|access-date=2019-05-31|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\nAfter playing in the [[English cricket team against Pakistan in the UAE in 2015\u201316|first two Tests against Pakistan]] in the [[United Arab Emirates]] during October, Buttler was dropped for the third Test, replaced as wicket-keeper by [[Jonny Bairstow]], and was not selected for any of the Test matches during [[English cricket team in South Africa in 2015\u201316|England's tour of South Africa]], although he did play again in the one-day fixtures during the tour. In the fourth ODI against Pakistan in [[Dubai]] in November, he scored a 46-ball century, the fastest ODI hundred by an England player.<ref name=\"BBC34879336\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/pakistan-v-england-2015-16/content/story/942455.html|title=Buttler's record-breaking ton demolishes Pakistan|date=2015-11-20|website=Cricinfo|language=en|access-date=2019-05-31}}</ref>\n\nButtler again played for England in the [[2016 ICC World Twenty20]] and was a regular fixture in the limited-overs squad throughout the year. He scored an unbeaten 90 runs against Pakistan as part of an England record score of 444/3, the fastest half-century by an Englishman.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/content/records/284095.html |title=Fastest 50 in ODIs |publisher=ESPNcricinfo | accessdate=31 August 2016}}</ref> Both records have since been surpassed.\n\nButtler captained the England side in the [[England cricket team in Bangladesh in 2016\u201317|ODI series]] against Bangladesh in October 2016 after numerous players, including regular captain [[Eoin Morgan]], declined to tour over raised security concerns following a [[July 2016 Dhaka attack|terrorist attack in Dhaka]] in July.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/cricket/2016/09/09/jos-buttler-to-captain-englands-one-day-team-in-bangladesh-follo/|title=Jos Buttler to captain England in Bangladesh following Eoin Morgan\u2019s decision to pull out of tour|last=Hoult|first=Nick|date=2016-09-09|work=The Telegraph|access-date=2019-05-29|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref> In the second ODI, there was some controversy as Buttler was involved in a heated exchange with numerous Bangladesh players following his dismissal to [[Taskin Ahmed]]. Buttler, aggravated by the opposition's excessive celebrations, turned to confront them, resulting in him being ushered away by the [[Umpire (cricket)|umpires]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.skysports.com/cricket/news/12123/10612206/bangladesh-v-england-tempers-flare-during-and-after-second-odi|title=Bangladesh v England: Tempers flare during and after second ODI|website=Sky Sports|language=en|access-date=2019-05-29}}</ref> Following the incident, Buttler was reprimanded by the [[International Cricket Council]] (ICC) and received one demerit point to his disciplinary record, while Bangladesh captain [[Mashrafe Mortaza]] and [[Sabbir Rahman]] were each fined 20% of their match fees and given a demerit point.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/cricket/37607649|title=England's Jos Buttler given ICC reprimand as Bangladesh players fined|date=2016-10-10|access-date=2019-05-29|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\nButtler was again reserve wicket-keeper for the Test series against Bangladesh. He returned to the England Test side for the third Test against India in November, playing in the final three Tests of the series. He continued as a regular in the limited-overs side throughout 2016 and 2017, playing again for England in the [[2017 ICC Champions Trophy]], but was unable to break back into the Test side and was not selected for the [[2017\u201318 Ashes series]] in Australia. He was named in the [[ICC Awards|ICC World ODI XI]] in 2016.<ref name=\"ESPN1073990\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/review2016/content/story/1073990.html|title=The trump cards of 2016|date=30 December 2016|website=Cricinfo}}</ref>\n\n===2018\u2013present: Return to Test cricket, World Cup and Ashes series===\n\nIn May 2018, Buttler was recalled into England's Test squad to [[Pakistani cricket team in England in 2018|play Pakistan]] at Lord's later that month.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/cricket/44105904|title=England v Pakistan: Jos Buttler & Dominic Bess named in squad for first Test|date=2018-05-15|work=BBC Sport|access-date=2018-05-15|language=en-GB}}</ref> He had a successful return to Test cricket, scoring two half-centuries and scoring the most runs in the series; he also won the Man of the Match award at [[Headingley Cricket Ground|Headingley]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Dobell |first1=George |title=Success on Test recall 'was a bit of a surprise' \u2013 Jos Buttler |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/story/_/id/23735055/success-test-recall-was-bit-surprise-jos-buttler |accessdate=24 June 2018 |work=ESPNcricinfo |date=8 June 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn the subsequent [[Australian cricket team in England in 2018|ODI series against Australia]] in June 2018, he scored two half-centuries in the first four matches and then, in the fifth and final game of the series, he made 110 not out to take England to a historic series whitewash.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/cricket/44595347|title=England v Australia: Jos Buttler century secures 5\u20130 ODI whitewash|date=2018-06-24|access-date=2019-05-29|language=en-GB}}</ref> In this match, no other English batsman made more than 20 and Buttler was afterwards described as \"the best white-ball wicketkeeper batsman in the world\".<ref>{{cite web |title=Batting records {{!}} One-Day Internationals {{!}} Cricinfo Statsguru {{!}} ESPNcricinfo |url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/player/308967.html?class=2;spanmin2=1+Jun+2018;spanval2=span;template=results;type=batting;view=innings |website=Cricinfo |accessdate=24 June 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Dobell |first1=George |title=Jos Buttler earns 'best in the world' tag after immense century |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/story/_/id/23896950/jos-buttler-earns-best-world-tag-immense-century |accessdate=24 June 2018 |work=ESPNcricinfo |date=24 June 2018}}</ref> Buttler was named Man of the Match for his 110 not out, and also named Man of the Series for his impressive contributions with both bat and gloves.<ref>{{cite web |title=England hero Jos Buttler: 'Winning games you don't deserve to are the most enjoyable' |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/cricket/2018/06/24/england-hero-jos-buttler-winning-games-dont-deserve-enjoyable/ |website=The Telegraph |accessdate=10 July 2018}}</ref> In the T20I match of Australia's tour, Buttler scored the fastest T20I half-century by an English cricketer, in 22 balls.<ref>Dobell, George. (27 June 2018) [http://www.espncricinfo.com/series/18021/report/1119542/england-vs-australia-only-t20i-aus-in-eng-2018 Jos Buttler and Adil Rashid ensure Australia end tour winless]. ESPNcricinfo. Retrieved 3 July 2018</ref>\n\nButtler replaced [[James Anderson (cricketer)|James Anderson]] as the Test vice-captain on 31 July 2018, thus combining the role in all formats.<ref name=\"BBC45017582\" /> He registered his maiden Test century in the third Test of [[Indian cricket team in England in 2018|India's tour of England]] in August 2018, with a score of 106.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/cricket/jos-buttler-century-england-vs-india-test-scorecard-scoreboard-jonathan-liew-a8501911.html|title=Jos Buttler emerges from Test wilderness to savour his century|date=2018-08-21|website=The Independent|language=en|access-date=2019-04-20}}</ref> Buttler then retained his place in the Test and one-day squads, being selected to [[England cricket team in Sri Lanka in 2018\u201319|tour Sri Lanka]] in October and into the following year.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ecb.co.uk/england/men/news/854903/england-confirm-test-squad-for-sri-lanka-series|title=England confirm Test squad for Sri Lanka series|last=|first=|date=21 September 2018|website=England and Wales Cricket Board|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=|access-date=1 June 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2019, during the fourth ODI of [[English cricket team in the West Indies in 2018\u201319|England's tour of the West Indies]], Buttler scored a career-best 150 from 77 deliveries as England reached 418/6.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/series/18913/scorecard/1158069/west-indies-vs-england-4th-odi-england-tour-of-wi-2018-19|title=Full Scorecard of West Indies vs England 4th ODI 2019 \u2013 Score Report {{!}} ESPNcricinfo.com|website=ESPNcricinfo|language=en|access-date=2019-04-20}}</ref> During this innings, he hit 12 sixes, at the time the most by any English batsman in an ODI, and went from 51 to 100 in just 15 balls and from 100 to 150 in just 16 deliveries. This was part of an England world record for the most sixes in an ODI, with 24.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sports.ndtv.com/cricket/england-hit-record-24-sixes-against-the-windies-and-jos-buttler-smashes-half-of-them-watch-2000529|title=England Hit Record 24 Sixes Against The Windies And Jos Buttler Smashes Half Of Them \u2013 Watch {{!}} Cricket News|last=NDTVSports.com|website=NDTVSports.com|language=en|access-date=2019-04-20}}</ref> Following the innings, West Indian batsman [[Chris Gayle]] praised Buttler, stating, \"He is superb, one of the best strikers [of the ball] in world cricket today.{{nbsp}}... We can see he is a game-winner, a game-changer and every team needs a player like that to win games.\", while England captain Eoin Morgan described him as \"built like a champion [[racehorse]]\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.skysports.com/cricket/news/12123/11650422/eoin-morgan-hails-england-match-winner-jos-buttler-as-champion-racehorse-after-stunning-150|title=Eoin Morgan hails England match winner Jos Buttler as 'champion racehorse' after stunning 150|website=Sky Sports|language=en|access-date=2019-04-20}}</ref>\n\nIn the second ODI of the five-match [[Pakistan cricket team in England in 2019|series against Pakistan]] in May, Buttler scored an unbeaten 110 from 55 balls, his century coming in only 50 deliveries. This is the second fastest hundred by an English batsman in ODI cricket after his own record set against Pakistan in 2015.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/cricket/48239995|title=England v Pakistan: Jos Buttler stars as hosts wins second ODI|date=2019-05-11|access-date=2019-05-31|language=en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/cricket/48241463|title=Jos Buttler: Eoin Morgan praises 'freakish' England batsman after ODI win|date=2019-05-11|access-date=2019-05-31|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n====2019 Cricket World Cup====\n\nIn April 2019, he was named as the vice-captain of the [[2019 Cricket World Cup squads#England|England squad]] for the [[2019 Cricket World Cup]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/content/story/1181187.html |title=Jofra Archer misses World Cup cut but included to play Ireland, Pakistan |work=ESPN Cricinfo |accessdate=17 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.icc-cricket.com/news/1183273 |title=England leave out Jofra Archer from World Cup squad |work=International Cricket Council |accessdate=17 April 2019}}</ref> The ICC named Buttler as the key player of England's squad prior to the tournament.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.icc-cricket.com/news/1227388 |title=Team preview: England |work=International Cricket Council |accessdate=28 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nButtler made a quiet start to the tournament, scoring only 18 runs in the opening match of the tournament against South Africa at [[The Oval]], which ended in a comprehensive 104-run win for England.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.skysports.com/live-scores/cricket/england-v-south-africa/21515/scorecard|title=England vs South Africa {{!}} Sky Sports Live Cricket|website=SkySports|language=en|access-date=2019-06-01}}</ref> In the next match against Pakistan, he scored 103 from 76 balls (the then-fastest century by an English batsman in a World Cup) and shared a 130-run partnership with [[Joe Root]] for the fourth wicket, despite a shock 14-run defeat.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/cricket/48504940|title=Cricket World Cup: Pakistan shock England at Trent Bridge|date=2019-06-03|access-date=2019-06-03|language=en-GB}}</ref> He made 64 in the third match against Bangladesh as England posted 386/6, their highest ever World Cup score.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/story/_/id/26926622/england-record-streak-300-plus-scores|title=England's record streak of 300-plus scores|date=2019-06-08|website=ESPNcricinfo|language=en|access-date=2019-06-08}}</ref> However, he did not keep wicket during Bangladesh's innings after sustaining a minor hip injury while batting, making way for [[Jonny Bairstow]] to assume the role for the match,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://metro.co.uk/2019/06/08/jos-buttler-injury-update-englands-cricket-world-cup-victory-bangladesh-9873952/|title=Jos Buttler injury update after England's World Cup victory over Bangladesh|date=2019-06-08|website=Metro|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-08}}</ref> which England won by 106 runs.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/cricket/48569905|title=Cricket World Cup: Jason Roy hits 153 as England beat Bangladesh in Cardiff|date=2019-06-08|access-date=2019-06-08|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\nButtler scored 59 runs in the [[2019 Cricket World Cup Final|final]] against New Zealand and contributed to a crucial 110-run partnership with [[Ben Stokes]] to help tie the match, with both teams making 241 from their respective innings. He was selected to bat in the ensuing [[Super Over]] along with Stokes, from which the pair scored 15 runs; Buttler scoring seven with a boundary from the final ball. He completed the [[run out (cricket)|run out]] of [[Martin Guptill]] on the last ball of New Zealand's over as he attempted a match-winning second run. This tied the Super Over and secured England's maiden World Cup title, winning by a superior boundary count.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/cricket/48983890|title=England win Cricket World Cup: Ben Stokes stars in dramatic victory over New Zealand|date=2019-07-14|access-date=2019-07-15|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2019, following England's World Cup success, the ECB named Buttler in the fourteen-man Test squad for the upcoming [[2019 Ashes series|Ashes series]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ecb.co.uk/england/men/news/1294745/england-name-squad-for-first-ashes-test|title=England name squad for first Ashes Test|last=|first=|date=2019-07-27|website=England and Wales Cricket Board|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=|access-date=2019-07-31}}</ref>\n\n==T20 franchise career==\nButtler has become increasingly involved in playing franchise T20 cricket around the world, and has been described as arguably England's \"first ever global Twenty20 superstar\".<ref name=\"ESPN308967\" />\n\n===2013\u201314 Big Bash League===\n\nButtler's first experience of franchise cricket came in 2013/14 when he played for [[Melbourne Renegades]] in the [[2013\u201314 Big Bash League season]] in Australia. This coincided with the buildup to the England one-day side playing in Australia at the beginning of 2014 and followed him having been with the England development squad in [[Perth, Western Australia|Perth]] for a month prior to the start of the competition.<ref>Hogan, Jesse (16 December 2013) [http://www.smh.com.au/sport/cricket/rising-english-cricket-star-jos-buttler-to-turn-out-for-melbourne-renegades-20131215-2zfbo.html Rising English cricket star Jos Buttler to turn out for Melbourne Renegades], ''[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]''. Retrieved 19 November 2017.</ref> Buttler was initially only expected to play for Melbourne in their first two matches of the competition but this was extended due to the late arrival of Pakistani all-rounder [[Mohammad Hafeez]], who had been called into the [[Pakistan cricket team|Pakistan]] Test squad. After having scored a \"stunning\" 61 runs against [[Brisbane Heat]] in his third match,<ref>[http://www.heraldsun.com.au/melbourne-renegades-hold-onto-bighitting-englishman-jos-buttler-for-one-more-game/news-story/582ef43e920877896cca84701c820e9f Melbourne Renegades hold onto big-hitting Englishman Jos Buttler for one more game], ''[[Herald Sun]]'', 31 December 2013. Retrieved 19 November 2014.</ref> Buttler eventually played in five Big Bash matches for Melbourne before leaving to join the England squad.<ref>Hayes, Mark (4 January 2014) [http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/sport/cricket/glenn-maxwell-cameron-white-guide-melbourne-stars-past-melbourne-renegades/news-story/808a091223d0313cacf430612843f705 Glenn Maxwell, Cameron White guide Melbourne Stars past Melbourne Renegades], ''[[The Daily Telegraph (Sydney)]]''. Retrieved 19 November 2017.</ref><ref>Hogan, Jesse (11 January 2014) [http://www.smh.com.au/sport/cricket/dwayne-bravo-returns-to-melbourne-to-play-for-big-bashs-renegades-20140110-30mnw.html Dwayne Bravo returns to Melbourne to play for Big Bash's Renegades], ''[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]''. Retrieved 19 November 2017.</ref>\n\n===2016 and 2017 Indian Premier League===\n\nButtler played for [[Mumbai Indians]] in the 2016 and 2017 [[Indian Premier League]] (IPL) seasons.\n\n===2017\u201318 Bangladesh Premier League===\n\nExpecting to be left out of the [[2017\u201318 Ashes series]] in Australia, Buttler signed a two-year contract in August 2017 with [[Comilla Victorians]] to appear in the [[Bangladesh Premier League]] (BPL).<ref>Martin, Ali (11 August 2017) [https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2017/aug/11/jos-buttler-bangladesh-premier-league-ashes-cricket-twenty-20 Jos Buttler signs Bangladesh T20 deal before expected Ashes snub], ''[[The Guardian]]''. Retrieved 19 November 2017.</ref><ref>[http://www.thedailystar.net/sports/cricket/buttler-set-join-comilla-1447183 Buttler set to join Comilla], ''[[The Daily Star (Bangladesh)]]'', 11 August 2017. Retrieved 19 November 2017.</ref> He made his BPL debut in November 2017, scoring 48 runs from 42 balls in his second match for Comilla and recorded his first BPL half-century in his third match.<ref>Manhar Uddin (8 November 2017) [http://www.thedailystar.net/sports/bangladesh-cricket/bangladesh-premier-league-bpl-2017-victorians-outclass-stuttering-vikings-1488028 Victorians outclass stuttering Vikings], ''[[The Daily Star (Bangladesh)]]''. Retrieved 19 November 2017.</ref><ref>Mohammad Isam (12 November 2017) [http://www.espncricinfo.com/bangladesh-premier-league-2016-17/content/story/1125886.html Mohammad Nabi and Rashid Khan hand Rajshahi a thrashing], CricInfo. Retrieved 19 November 2017.</ref>\n\n===2017\u201318 Big Bash League===\n\nIn November 2017, Buttler was signed as an overseas player for Sydney Thunder for the upcoming [[2017\u201318 Big Bash League season|Big Bash League season]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cricbuzz.com/cricket-news/98559/sydney-thunder-sign-jos-buttler-for-forthcoming-bbl-07-season|title=Sydney Thunder sign Jos Buttler for forthcoming BBL season|website=Cricbuzz|language=en|access-date=2019-06-01}}</ref> He played in the first six games for Thunder before joining the England squad for the limited-over fixtures of [[England cricket team in Australia in 2017\u201318|England's tour of Australia]]. He scored 67 and 81 in separate games against [[Hobart Hurricanes]], being named Player of the Match in the first fixture.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/series/8044/game/1114866/hobart-hurricanes-vs-sydney-thunder-11th-match-big-bash-league-2017-18|title=Sydney Thunder beat Hobart Hurricanes by 57 runs \u2013 Hobart Hurricanes vs Sydney Thunder, Big Bash League, 11th Match Match Summary, Report {{!}} ESPNcricinfo.com|website=ESPNcricinfo|language=en|access-date=2019-06-01}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/series/8044/report/1114868/sydney-thunder-vs-hobart-hurricanes-13th-match-big-bash-league-2017-18|title=Recent Match Report \u2013 Sydney Thunder vs Hobart Hurricanes, Big Bash League, 13th Match {{!}} ESPNcricinfo.com|website=ESPNcricinfo|language=en|access-date=2019-06-01}}</ref>\n\n===2018 Indian Premier League===\n\nIn January 2018, Buttler was bought by the Rajasthan Royals in the [[List of 2018 Indian Premier League personnel changes|2018 IPL auction]] for {{INRConvert|4.4|c|-3}}.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/story/_/id/22218394/ipl-2018-player-auction-list-sold-unsold-players |title=List of sold and unsold players |accessdate=27 January 2018 |work=ESPN Cricinfo}}</ref> Buttler had a difficult start for the Royals, making a high score of just 29 in his first seven innings. However, on being promoted to open the batting mid-tournament, his performances significantly improved. He subsequently became only the second batsman in IPL history to achieve five scores of fifty or more in consecutive matches.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cricket.com.au/news/match-report/rajasthan-royals-mumbai-indians-ipl-match-report-jos-buttler-sanju-samson-evin-lewis-playoffs/2018-05-14 |title=Buttler equals long-standing IPL record |accessdate=29 April 2019 |work=Cricket.com.au}}</ref> He made an unbeaten 95 from 60 balls against [[Chennai Super Kings]], his highest score in the T20 format to date.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/series/8048/report/1136603/rajasthan-royals-vs-chennai-super-kings-43rd-match-indian-premier-league-2018|title=Recent Match Report \u2013 Rajasthan Royals vs Chennai Super Kings, Indian Premier League, 43rd match {{!}} ESPNcricinfo.com|website=ESPNcricinfo|language=en|access-date=2019-05-31}}</ref>\n\n===2018\u201319 Big Bash League===\n\nButtler again played for Sydney Thunder in the [[2018\u201319 Big Bash League season|2018\u201319 Big Bash League]], this time alongside England teammate [[Joe Root]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/cricket/45288760|title=Big Bash: Joe Root and Jos Buttler agree Sydney Thunder stint|date=2018-08-23|access-date=2019-06-01|language=en-GB}}</ref> The [[England and Wales Cricket Board]] (ECB) allowed Buttler and Root to play the first half of the season, despite a busy international schedule throughout 2019.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/cricket/2018/08/23/ecb-give-joe-root-jos-buttler-green-light-represent-sydney-thunder/|title=ECB give Joe Root and Jos Buttler green light to represent Sydney Thunder in Big Bash despite hectic 2019 schedule|last=Berry|first=Scyld|date=2018-08-23|work=The Telegraph|access-date=2019-06-01|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref>\n\nButtler made his highest BBL score of 89 from 54 deliveries against Hobart Hurricanes, despite a seven-wicket defeat,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.news.com.au/sport/cricket/big-bash/live-hobart-hurricanes-vs-sydney-thunder-at-blundstone-arena/news-story/f7a5d539f0725814ae58d08395c06179|title=Thunder crack in \u2018disastrous\u2019 finish|date=2018-12-28|website=NewsComAu|language=en|access-date=2019-06-01}}</ref> before making 55 in a thrilling one-run win over [[Perth Scorchers]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/cricket/46734798|title=Big Bash League: Jos Buttler shines but Joe Root fails again|date=2019-01-02|access-date=2019-06-01|language=en-GB}}</ref> Buttler departed as the tournament's leading run-scorer, with 273 from seven innings, making three half-centuries at an average of 39.00.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/cricket/46793136|title=Big Bash League: Joe Root and Jos Buttler end BBL stint with defeat|date=2019-01-08|access-date=2019-06-01|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n===2019 Indian Premier League===\n\nRajasthan Royals retained Buttler for the [[2019 Indian Premier League|2019 IPL season]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.skysports.com/cricket/news/15815/11554933/ben-stokes-and-jos-buttler-retained-by-rajasthan-for-2019-ipl-david-warner-and-steve-smith-to-return|title=Ben Stokes and Jos Buttler retained by Rajasthan for 2019 IPL; David Warner and Steve Smith to return|website=Sky Sports|language=en|access-date=2019-05-30}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/cricket/46225438|title=Indian Premier League: Jos Buttler & Ben Stokes retained by Rajasthan Royals|date=2018-11-15|access-date=2019-05-30|language=en-GB}}</ref> In a match between Rajasthan Royals and [[Kings XI Punjab]], Buttler was controversially [[run out]] on 69 by Indian bowler [[Ravichandran Ashwin]] via 'Mankading', an act that Ashwin was heavily criticised for.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/cricket/47697369|title=Jos Buttler 'Mankad' dismissal: England batsman controversially run out in IPL|date=2019-03-25|access-date=2019-05-30|language=en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/cricket/47728182|title=Jos Buttler: 'Mankad' dismissal not 'in the spirit of the game' \u2013 MCC|date=2019-03-27|access-date=2019-05-31|language=en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.crictracker.com/dale-steyn-slams-ravi-ashwin-for-mankading-jos-buttler/|title=Dale Steyn slams Ravi Ashwin for 'Mankading' Jos Buttler|date=2019-03-25|website=CricTracker|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-31}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.icc-cricket.com/news/1113878|title=Buttler's controversial \u2018Mankad\u2019 run out \u2013 best of the reaction|website=www.icc-cricket.com|language=en|access-date=2019-05-31}}</ref> Former Australian bowler and Rajasthan mentor [[Shane Warne]] called the incident a \"disgraceful and low act\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.foxsports.com.au/cricket/indian-premier-league/completely-out-of-order-shane-warne-leads-cricket-worlds-condemnation-of-disgraceful-ravi-ashwin-mankad/news-story/91250e7213da89e4501cce6ffb3ce6fb|title=Ravi Ashwin mankad controversy: Shane Warne slams \u2018disgraceful\u2019 act|date=2019-03-26|website=Fox Sports|language=en-AU|access-date=2019-06-01}}</ref> This is the second instance in which Buttler has been dismissed in this fashion, the other occasion in an ODI match for England against Sri Lanka in 2014.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.skysports.com/cricket/news/12123/11683985/jos-buttler-says-he-wont-be-mankaded-again-following-ravi-ashwins-controversial-ipl-dismissal|title=Jos Buttler says he 'won't be Mankaded again' following Ravi Ashwin's controversial IPL dismissal|website=Sky Sports|language=en|access-date=2019-06-01}}</ref> In his next two matches for Rajasthan, he was dismissed for scores of just five and six but returned to form after hitting 59 from 43 balls in a fixture against [[Royal Challengers Bangalore]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://metro.co.uk/2019/04/03/jos-buttler-finally-breaks-silence-ravi-ashwin-mankad-indian-premier-league-9108542/|title=Buttler finally breaks silence on Ashwin 'Mankad' at Indian Premier League|date=2019-04-03|website=Metro|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-31}}</ref> He also made a score of 89 from 43 deliveries against [[Mumbai Indians]], hitting 28 runs off the 13th over.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/series/8048/game/1178402/mumbai-indians-vs-rajasthan-royals-27th-match-indian-premier-league-2019|title=Rajasthan Royals beat Mumbai Indians by 4 wickets (with 3 balls remaining) \u2013 Mumbai Indians vs Rajasthan Royals, Indian Premier League, 27th Match Match Summary, Report {{!}} ESPNcricinfo.com|website=ESPNcricinfo|language=en|access-date=2019-05-31}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nIn October 2017, Buttler married Louise Webber. England teammates [[Steven Finn (cricketer)|Steven Finn]] and [[Alex Hales]] acted as ushers for the wedding.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mirror.co.uk/sport/cricket/england-cricketer-jos-buttler-gets-11398671|title=England cricket star quietly gets married as club let news slip|last=Whaling|first=James|date=2017-10-24|website=mirror|access-date=2019-05-29}}</ref> Their daughter, Georgia Rose, was born in April 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.crictracker.com/england-batsman-jos-buttler-becomes-father-of-a-baby-girl/|title=England batsman Jos Buttler becomes father of a baby girl|date=2019-04-28|website=CricTracker|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-29}}</ref>\n\nButtler was appointed [[Member of the Order of the British Empire]] (MBE) in the [[2020 New Year Honours]] for services to cricket.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=62866|supp=y|page=N16|date=28 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Playing style==\n{{Quote box|quoted=true |bgcolor=#F5F6CE|salign=left|quote=[Jos Buttler] is an extravagantly talented batsman with the power and range of strokes to damage any bowling attack. There may be moments, against the very best bowling, when his improvisation gets him into trouble but, so capable of unorthodoxy is he, that even the best could be discombobulated.| source=[[George Dobell]], June 2013<ref name=\"ci6jun13\" />|align=right|width=275px}}\n\nA tall and strongly-built cricketer, Buttler has an upright stance in the [[Crease (cricket)|crease]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/sport/cricket/article7124545.ece |title=Jos Buttler's century shows future rosy for Somerset |work=Times Online |date=12 May 2010 |last=Dean |first=Geoffrey |accessdate=14 May 2010}}</ref> During his maiden first-class century against Hampshire in 2010, he \"hit the ball hard and straight\", \"moving his feet decisively, playing with his bat close to his body and selecting the right balls to attack\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/sport/cricket/article7125841.ece |title=Jos Buttler makes most of Craig Kieswetter's absence |work=Times Online |date=13 May 2010 |last=Dean |first=Geoffrey |accessdate=14 May 2010}}</ref> Buttler was praised for \"remaining cool and composed at the crease\" and for his \"dogged determination and decent range of shots\" during the innings.<ref name=\"bbc13may10\" /> Somerset captain [[Marcus Trescothick]] suggested that Buttler could challenge teammate Craig Kieswetter's place in the England team.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thisissomerset.co.uk/sport/Trescothick-Somerset-teenager-Buttler-day-wicket-England/article-2157368-detail/article.html |title=Trescothick: Somerset teenager Buttler could one day keep wicket for England |work=Somerset Guardian |date=15 April 2010 |accessdate=15 April 2010}}</ref>\n\nButtler's temperament in the longer forms of the game has been questioned at times as his career has developed. In 2013, he was out for 94 runs for Somerset while attempting to reach his century by hitting a six and George Dobell, writing for [[ESPNcricinfo]], questioned \"his ability to defend and deny [bowlers]\".<ref name=\"ci20apr13\" /> Dobell praised the first half of Buttler's innings, which ensured a draw for Somerset, saying that \"it showed a young man responding to his team's needs with a restrained, mature performance that exhibited a decent defence and an ability to leave and play straight\" and that he had \"produced some of those trademark straight drives and several powerful pulls\" but felt that \"it is the strokes he does not play that are as relevant as those he does\".<ref name=\"ci20apr13\" />\n\nIn one day cricket, Buttler quickly established a reputation as an aggressive batsman who could take control of a game at the end of an innings.<ref>[http://www.espncricinfo.com/countycricket2010/content/story/471667.html Somerset limp past Unicorns], [[CricInfo]]. Retrieved 11 November 2017.</ref><ref>McGlashan, Andrew (12 September 2012) [http://www.espncricinfo.com/england-v-south-africa-2012/content/story/581984.html Broad praise for 'game-changing' Buttler], [[CricInfo]]. Retrieved 11 November 2017.</ref><ref name=\"ci22jan13\" /> By the end of his first full-season he was producing \"innings of huge promise\"<ref name=\"ci16aug10\">[http://www.espncricinfo.com/countycricket2010/content/story/472874.html In-form Buttler sets up Lancashire rout], [[CricInfo]], 16 August 2010. Retrieved 11 November 2011.</ref> which were being described as \"breathtaking\"<ref name=\"ci14aug10\" /> and \"swashbuckling\"<ref name=\"ci16aug10\" /> and displaying \"an array of explosive and innovative shots\".<ref>[http://www.espncricinfo.com/countycricket2010/content/story/474988.html Somerset seal semi-final spot], [[CricInfo]], 29 August 2010. Retrieved 11 November 2017.</ref> Still a teenager, his displays in both 40 over and 20 over cricket in 2010 won him plaudits, including a description as a \"supremely talented youngster\" who batted with a \"blend of power and sweet timing\".<ref name=\"ci4sep10\">[http://www.espncricinfo.com/countycricket2010/content/story/475783.html Record-breaking Somerset storm into semi-finals], [[CricInfo]], 4 September 2010. Retrieved 11 November 2017.</ref> His range of shots, including effective use of 'scoop' and 'ramp' shots over the wicket-keeper to [[fine leg]] and variations such as reverse and swivel scoop shots,<ref>Hopps D (11 June 2013) [http://www.espncricinfo.com/icc-champions-trophy-2013/content/story/641047.html Buttler ready for unorthodox duel with Malinga], [[CricInfo]]. Retrieved 18 November 2017.</ref> mean that his game has been considered subtle rather than overly aggressive<ref>[http://www.espncricinfo.com/county-cricket-2011/content/story/526399.html Pollard, Buttler take Somerset through], [[CricInfo]], 7 August 2011. Retrieved 11 November 2017.</ref><ref>McGlashan, Andrew (13 September 2017) [http://www.espncricinfo.com/england/content/story/582103.html Buttler's confidence ramped up], [[CricInfo]]. Retrieved 11 November 2017.</ref> and his \"stunning strokes\",<ref>[http://www.espncricinfo.com/county-cricket-2013/content/story/635371.html Hildreth, Buttler lead Somerset romp], [[CricInfo]], 11 May 2013. Retrieved 18 November 2017.</ref> clean striking and \"crispness when hitting\" the ball along with his \"audacity and adventure\" have all been cited as making him an \"exciting\" batsman.<ref>Dutta, Sahil (26 August 2011) [http://www.espncricinfo.com/county-cricket-2011/content/story/529951.html Spinners give Hampshire the edge], [[CricInfo]]. Retrieved 11 November 2017.</ref>\n\nDespite not always being his county's first-choice wicket-keeper and reservations about the quality of his work behind the stumps, Buttler has frequently been used in that role by the England team since the beginning of 2013, especially in one-day cricket. He was installed in the wicket-keeper role ahead of the [[2013 ICC Champions Trophy]] after Craig Kieswetter faltered in terms of his batting \u2013 Buttler's one-day batting, his potential and his ability to combine power with improvisation being seen as more important than any failings as a wicket-keeper<ref name=\"ci22jan13\" /> \u2013 despite, by his own admission, his \"keeping [being] a work in progress\".<ref name=\"ci25jan13\" /> His wicket-keeping was \"seen by some as having more potential\" than his main rival for the job Jonny Bairstow and England wicket-keeper coach [[Bruce French (cricketer)|Bruce French]] spoke of his \"natural hands\" behind the stumps.<ref name=\"ci11feb13\" />\n\nFollowing Kieswetter's and Matt Prior's international retirements in 2015, Buttler became England's first-choice wicket-keeper in all formats. Whether he should play as a wicket-keeper or specialist batsman was questioned in middle of the 2015 season<ref>{{Cite web|title = Must Buttler keep in all formats?|url = http://www.espncricinfo.com/magazine/content/story/891769.html|accessdate = 29 June 2015}}</ref> and Bairstow replaced him for the third ODI during [[Australian cricket team in England and Ireland in 2015|Australia's 2015 tour]] due to Buttler's poor form with the bat throughout the Australian series.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Buttler rested, Bairstow called up|url = http://www.espncricinfo.com/the-ashes-2015/content/story/918307.html|accessdate = 6 September 2015|date = 2015-09-05|website = ESPN Cricinfo}}</ref> Bairstow eventually became the outright wicket-keeper for Tests in December 2015 for the series against South Africa,<ref>{{Cite web|title = Bairstow ready to wear gloves with pride|url = http://www.espncricinfo.com/south-africa-v-england-2015-16/content/story/952317.html|website = Cricinfo|accessdate = 15 December 2015}}</ref> and Buttler was dropped from the Test side during 2016, whilst continuing to be the first-choice ODI and T20 wicket-keeper.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2016/jun/05/jos-buttler-england-test-royal-london-cup-lancashire|title=Jos Buttler targets regaining England Test place after first-class hiatus|last=Martin|first=Ali|date=2016-06-05|website=the Guardian|language=en|access-date=2018-03-22}}</ref>\n\n==Career best performances==\n{{As of|2019|6}}, Buttler has scored five first-class and 11 List A centuries, nine of which have been scored for England in One Day International matches. He is yet to score a century in the T20 format of the game.<ref name=\"ESPN308967\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/england/content/player/308967.html|title=Jos Buttler|website=ESPNCricinfo|access-date=2019-05-30}}</ref>\n\nButtler made his maiden first-class century in May 2010, scoring 144 for Somerset against Hampshire at the [[Rose Bowl (cricket ground)|Rose Bowl]], [[Southampton]].<ref name=\"bbc13may10\" /><ref>[http://www.espncricinfo.com/countycricket2010/content/story/459448.html Twin hundreds leads Somerset comeback], [[CricInfo]], 12 May 2010. Retrieved 11 November 2017.</ref> {{As of|2018|12}} this remains his highest first-class score. His highest Test match score of 106 was made for England against India in August 2018 at [[Trent Bridge]], [[Nottingham]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/cricket/45258626|title=England v India: Jos Buttler hits century but hosts heading for defeat|date=2018-08-21|access-date=2019-05-30|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\nIn limited overs cricket, Buttler's best List A and ODI score of 150 from 77 deliveries was made in February 2019 against the [[West Indies cricket team|West Indies]] at the [[National Cricket Stadium (Grenada)|National Cricket Stadium]], [[Grenada]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/cricket/47392140|title=England in West Indies: Jos Buttler's 150 inspires tourists to thrilling win|date=2019-02-27|access-date=2019-05-30|language=en-GB}}</ref> This is also the highest ODI score for an Englishman against the West Indies.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/batting/most_runs_innings.html?class=2&id=1&id=4&type=headtohead|title=England v West Indies Cricket Team Records & Stats {{!}} ESPNcricinfo.com|website=Cricinfo|access-date=2019-05-30}}</ref> Buttler is yet to score a century in one-day matches in county cricket.\n\nButtler's highest T20 score of 95 not out from 60 balls was made for Rajasthan Royals against Chennai Super Kings in the [[2018 Indian Premier League]] at the [[Sawai Mansingh Stadium]], [[Jaipur]].<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/cricket/44090045 IPL: Jos Buttler hits highest T20 score as Rajasthan Royals beat Chennai], [[BBC Sport]], 11 May 2018. Retrieved 12 May 2018.</ref> His highest T20I score is 73 not out off 49 balls, and was achieved against Sri Lanka in July 2016 at the Rose Bowl, Southampton.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/cricket/36720351|title=England v Sri Lanka: Jos Buttler eases hosts to T20 victory|date=2016-07-05|access-date=2019-05-30|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n==Honours==\n* [[File:Order of the British Empire (Civil) Ribbon.png|60px]] Buttler was appointed [[Member of the Most Excellent Order of the British Empire]] (MBE) in the [[2020 New Year Honours]] for services to cricket.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=62866|supp=y|Notice ID=3455121|date=28 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://josbuttler.co.uk/ Official website]\n* {{cricinfo|ref=ci/content/player/308967.html}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{succession box|\n  | before = [[James Taylor (cricketer, born 1990)|James Taylor]]\n  | title  = [[Young Wisden Schools Cricketer of the Year]]\n  | years  = 2010\n  | after  = [[Will Vanderspar]]\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{commons category}}\n\n{{England ODI cricket captains}}\n{{England T20I cricket captains}}\n{{Navboxes colour\n|title= England squads \n|bg= skyblue\n|fg= #15295E\n|bordercolor=#15295E\n|list1=\n{{England Squad 2015 Cricket World Cup}}\n{{England Squad 2019 Cricket World Cup}}\n}}\n{{Lancashire County Cricket Club squad}}\n{{Rajasthan Royals squad}}\n{{Good article}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Buttler, Jos}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1990 births]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Taunton]]\n[[Category:People educated at King's College, Taunton]]\n[[Category:English cricketers]]\n[[Category:England Test cricketers]]\n[[Category:England One Day International cricketers]]\n[[Category:England Twenty20 International cricketers]]\n[[Category:Somerset cricketers]]\n[[Category:Lancashire cricketers]]\n[[Category:Melbourne Renegades cricketers]]\n[[Category:Comilla Victorians cricketers]]\n[[Category:Sydney Thunder cricketers]]\n[[Category:NBC Denis Compton Award recipients]]\n[[Category:Cricketers at the 2015 Cricket World Cup]]\n[[Category:Cricketers at the 2019 Cricket World Cup]]\n[[Category:Mumbai Indians cricketers]]\n[[Category:Rajasthan Royals cricketers]]\n[[Category:Wisden Cricketers of the Year]]\n[[Category:Members of the Order of the British Empire]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|English cricketer}}\n{{for|cricketer who plays for Guernsey|Josh Butler (cricketer)}}\n{{Use British English|date=September 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox cricketer\n| name = Jos Buttler\n| image = Jos Buttler 2017.jpg\n| image_size = 225\n| caption = Buttler in 2017\n| country = England\n| fullname = Joseph Charles Buttler\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1990|9|8|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Taunton]], [[Somerset]], England\n| heightft = 5\n| heightinch = 11\n| batting = Right-handed\n| role = [[Batting (cricket)|Batsman]], [[wicket-keeper]]\n| international = true\n| internationalspan = 2011\u2013present\n| testdebutdate = 27 July\n| testdebutyear = 2014\n| testdebutagainst = India\n| testcap = 665\n| lasttestdate = 24 January\n| lasttestyear = 2020\n| lasttestagainst = South Africa\n| odidebutdate = 21 February\n| odidebutyear = 2012\n| odidebutagainst = Pakistan\n| odicap = 226\n| lastodidate = 14 July\n| lastodiyear = 2019\n| lastodiagainst = New Zealand\n| odishirt = 63\n| T20Idebutdate = 31 August\n| T20Idebutyear = 2011\n| T20Idebutagainst = India\n| T20Icap = 54\n| lastT20Idate = 16 February\n| lastT20Iyear = 2020\n| lastT20Iagainst = South Africa\n| T20Ishirt = 63\n| club1 = [[Somerset County Cricket Club|Somerset]]\n| year1 = 2009\u20132013\n| clubnumber1 = 15\n| club2 = [[Melbourne Renegades]]\n| year2 = 2013/14\n| club3 = [[Lancashire County Cricket Club|Lancashire]]\n| year3 = 2014\u2013present\n| clubnumber3 = 6\n| club4 = [[Mumbai Indians]]\n| year4 = 2016\u20132017\n| club5 = [[Comilla Victorians]]\n| year5 = 2017\n| club6 = [[Sydney Thunder]]\n| year6 = 2017\u2013present\n| club7 = [[Rajasthan Royals]]\n| year7 = {{nowrap|2018\u2013present}}\n| hidedeliveries = true\n| columns = 4\n| column1 = [[Test cricket|Test]]\n| matches1 = 40\n| runs1 = 2,099\n| bat avg1 = 32.29\n| 100s/50s1 = 1/15\n| top score1 = 106\n| catches/stumpings1 = 83/0\n| column2 = [[One Day International|ODI]]\n| matches2 = 142\n| runs2 = 3,843\n| bat avg2 = 40.88\n| 100s/50s2 = 9/20\n| top score2 = 150\n| catches/stumpings2 = 171/31\n| column3 = [[First-class cricket|FC]]\n| matches3 = 105\n| runs3 = 5,080\n| bat avg3 = 32.35\n| 100s/50s3 = 6/30\n| top score3 = 144\n| catches/stumpings3 = 204/2\n| column4 = [[List A cricket|LA]]\n| matches4 = 213\n| runs4 = 6,009\n| bat avg4 = 44.84\n| 100s/50s4 = 11/36\n| top score4 = 150\n| catches/stumpings4 = 223/36\n| date = 16 February 2020\n| source = http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/content/player/308967.html ESPNcricinfo\n}}\n'''Joseph Charles Buttler''' {{post-nominals|country=GBR|size=100%|MBE}} (born 8 September 1990) is an English international [[cricket]]er who is currently [[Captain (cricket)|vice-captain]] of the [[England cricket team]] in [[limited overs cricket]].<ref name=\"BBC45017582\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/cricket/45017582|title=England v India: Adil Rashid named as hosts' only spinner for first Test|date=2018-07-31|access-date=2019-04-20|language=en-GB}}</ref> A right-handed [[Batting (cricket)|batsman]], he usually fields as a [[wicket-keeper]] and has represented England in [[Test cricket|Test]], [[One Day International]] (ODI) and [[Twenty20 International]] (T20I) cricket. He served as vice-captain of the England squad that won the [[2019 Cricket World Cup]], becoming world champions for the first time in their history.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/content/squad/1181195.html|title=England Squad|website=Cricinfo|language=en|access-date=2019-07-23}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/cricket/48983890|title=England win Cricket World Cup: Ben Stokes stars in dramatic victory over New Zealand|date=2019-07-14|access-date=2019-07-23|language=en-GB}}</ref> He currently plays for [[Lancashire County Cricket Club|Lancashire]] in English domestic cricket having previously played for [[Somerset County Cricket Club|Somerset]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.somersetlive.co.uk/sport/other-sport/england-new-zealand-jos-butler-3091229|title=How Somerset's Jos Buttler helped England win Cricket World Cup|last=Baker|first=Max|date=2019-07-14|website=somersetlive|access-date=2019-07-23}}</ref> He also plays for [[Rajasthan Royals]] in the [[Indian Premier League]] (IPL).<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/cricket/46225438|title=Indian Premier League: Jos Buttler & Ben Stokes retained by Rajasthan Royals|date=2018-11-15|access-date=2019-07-23|language=en-GB}}</ref> Buttler holds the record for the fastest ODI century by an England player and is regarded as one of the best [[Wicket-keeper-batsman|wicket-keeper batsmen]] in the world.<ref name=\"BBC34879336\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/cricket/34879336|title=Jos Buttler breaks record as England beat Pakistan to win series|date=2015-11-20|access-date=2019-05-31|language=en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://metro.co.uk/2019/05/11/england-freak-jos-buttler-good-virat-kohli-ab-de-villiers-ms-dhoni-says-nasser-hussain-9499477/|title=England 'freak' Buttler as good as Kohli, De Villiers and Dhoni \u2013 Hussain|date=2019-05-11|website=Metro|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-12}}</ref> Buttler's ability to recognise and manipulate field placements of opposing teams and score all around the ground has seen him labelled as a \"360-degree\" cricketer.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thecricketer.com/Topics/banner/buttler_brilliance_is_on_par_with_ab_and_williamson_ridiculous_he_hasnt_played_more_tests.html|title=Jos Buttler is on a par with AB de Villiers... he should have played more Tests for England|website=www.thecricketer.com|access-date=2019-07-23}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cricketcountry.com/news/cricket-world-cup-2019-360-degree-jos-buttler-looms-as-confident-englands-game-changer-847338|title=Cricket World Cup 2019: 360-degree Jos Buttler looms as confident England\u2019s game-changer|last=France-Presse|first=Agence|date=2019-05-24|website=Cricket Country|language=en-US|access-date=2019-07-23}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thecricketpaper.com/featured/4870/pringle-column-jos-buttler-really-is-the-cream-of-the-crop/|title=Pringle column: Jos Buttler really is the cream of the crop|last=admin|date=2018-07-04|website=The Cricket Paper|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-07-23}}</ref>\n\nButtler enjoyed a prolific cricket record while at school, sharing a record-breaking opening [[Partnership (cricket)|partnership]] while at [[King's College, Taunton]] in 2008. The following season, his school lost only one of seventeen matches under his captaincy and he was named 2010 [[Young Wisden Schools Cricketer of the Year|''Young Wisden'' Schools Cricketer of the Year]]. He made his Somerset first-team debut in 2009 after having played age-group cricket for the county. His performances led him to be selected to play for England at [[English U-19 cricket team|Under-19]] level before he made his senior England debut in 2011 and his [[Test cricket|Test]] debut in 2014.\n\n==Early life==\nBorn in [[Taunton]], [[Somerset]] on 8 September 1990,<ref name=\"ESPN308967\" /> Buttler was educated at [[King's College, Taunton|King's College]], where he displayed his early talent in cricket.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/cricket/2018/08/21/cant-underestimate-feeling-jos-buttlers-maiden-test-century/|title='You can't underestimate that feeling' \u2013 Jos Buttler's maiden Test century shows he can be heart of England's side|last=Wigmore|first=Tim|date=21 August 2018|work=The Telegraph|access-date=2 September 2019|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref>\n\n==Domestic career==\n\n===Youth career===\n\nButtler played extensively for Somerset's youth teams, appearing at Under-13, Under-15 and Under-17 level.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Players/136/136065/Other_matches.html |title=Other matches played by Joseph Buttler (55) |publisher=CricketArchive |accessdate=14 May 2010}}</ref> He made his senior club cricket debut for Cheddar before moving to Glastonbury in the 2006 season, aged just 15, taking three [[caught|catches]] and 15 [[Run (cricket)|runs]] as wicket-keeper.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/177/177817.html |title=Westbury v Glastonbury |publisher=CricketArchive |date=14 May 2006 |accessdate=30 April 2010}}</ref> Later in the same season, he made his first appearance for Somerset Second XI, scoring 71 in the second-innings, and taking six catches in the three-day match against [[Nottinghamshire County Cricket Club|Nottinghamshire]] Second XI.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/86/86407.html |title=Nottinghamshire Second XI v Somerset Second XI |publisher=CricketArchive |date=30 April 2010}}</ref> Playing for King's College, he finished the 2006 season with the school's leading [[Batting average (cricket)|batting average]], scoring 447 runs at an average of 49.66.<ref>{{cite book |last=Henderson |first=Douglas |editor1-first=Scyld |editor1-last=Berry |title=Wisden Cricketer's Almanack 2007 |edition=144 |year=2007 |publisher=John Wisden & Co. Ltd. |location=[[Alton, Hampshire]] |isbn=978-1-905625-02-4 |page=1020 |chapter=Schools Cricket, 2006}}</ref> The following season he played regularly for Glastonbury in the [[West of England Premier League]], and for Somerset Under-17s, for whom he scored two centuries; an [[Not out|unbeaten]] 119 during a two-day match against [[Surrey County Cricket Club|Surrey]] Under-17s,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/190/190626.html |title=Surrey Under-17s v Somerset Under-17s |publisher=CricketArchive |date=25 July 2007 |accessdate=30 April 2010}}</ref> and 110 against [[Sussex County Cricket Club|Sussex]] Under-17s.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/190/190659.html |title=Sussex Under-17s v Somerset Under-17s |publisher=CricketArchive |date=8 August 2007 |accessdate=30 April 2010}}</ref> He once again led the batting averages for King's College, with his 358 runs coming at 51.14.<ref>{{cite book |last=Henderson |first=Douglas |editor1-first=Scyld |editor1-last=Berry |title=Wisden Cricketer's Almanack 2008 |edition=145 |year=2008 |publisher=John Wisden & Co. Ltd. |location=[[Alton, Hampshire]] |isbn=978-1-905625-11-6 |page=967 |chapter=Schools Cricket, 2007}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Jos_buttler_keeping.jpg|thumb|left|Buttler keeping wicket for [[Somerset County Cricket Club|Somerset]]|alt=A young man with light brown hair is standing on some grass. He is wearing a burgundy, grey and black cricket uniform, large gloves and black trousers covered by black think pads on his lower legs.]]\nThe highlight of his school career came in April 2008, when he scored 227 [[not out]] during a record-breaking opening [[Partnership (cricket)|stand]] in a 50-over national schools game, adding 340 with [[Alex Barrow]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/7375597.stm |title=King's duo break schools record |publisher=[[BBC Sport]] |date=30 April 2008 |accessdate=1 May 2010}}</ref> He [[Captain (cricket)|captained]] King's during the 2008 season, and improved on his batting totals from the previous two years, scoring 851 runs, over 250 more than any other member of the team.<ref>{{cite book |last=Henderson |first=Douglas |editor1-first=Scyld |editor1-last=Berry |title=Wisden Cricketer's Almanack 2009 |edition=146 |year=2009 |publisher=John Wisden & Co. Ltd. |location=[[Alton, Hampshire]] |isbn=978-1-905625-16-1 |page=903 |chapter=Schools Cricket, 2008}}</ref> His batting average of 94.55 was the sixth highest amongst all school's batsmen reported in ''Wisden'', while his high-score of 227* was the highest score they recorded.<ref>{{cite book |last=Henderson |first=Douglas |editor1-first=Scyld |editor1-last=Berry |title=Wisden Cricketer's Almanack 2009 |edition=146 |year=2009 |publisher=John Wisden & Co. Ltd. |location=[[Alton, Hampshire]] |isbn=978-1-905625-16-1 |page=908 |chapter=Schools Cricket, 2008}}</ref> During that 2008 season, Buttler also played for Somerset Second XI. With captain [[Carl Gazzard]] keeping wicket in the majority of these matches, Buttler played purely as a batsman, although in his final match of the season for the team, he kept wicket and took six catches in the first-innings against [[Worcestershire County Cricket Club|Worcestershire]] Second XI.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/158/158388.html |title=Worcestershire Second XI v Somerset Second XI |publisher=CricketArchive |date=10 September 2008 |accessdate=30 April 2010}}</ref> In the previous match, against [[Hampshire County Cricket Club|Hampshire]] Second XI, Buttler had made 140 batting from [[Batting order (cricket)|number four]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/158/158384.html |title=Somerset Second XI v Hampshire Second XI |publisher=CricketArchive |date=3 September 2008 |accessdate=30 April 2010}}</ref>\n\nHe made his [[First-class cricket|first-class]] debut for Somerset in September 2009, replacing the injured [[Justin Langer]] for the [[County Championship]] match against Lancashire, scoring 30 in his only innings.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.westernmorningnews.co.uk/Horton-ton-cancels-Somerset-s-early-gains/story-11514053-detail/story.html|title=Horton ton cancels out Somerset gains|date=10 September 2009|work=Western Morning News|accessdate=15 February 2016}}</ref> He retained his place in the team for the following [[Pro40]] match against Hampshire, making his [[List A cricket|List A]] debut, although he was not required to bat.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/204/204641.html |title=Hampshire v Somerset |publisher=CricketArchive |date=13 September 2009 |accessdate=1 May 2010}}</ref> Selected as part of the Somerset squad for the [[2009 Champions League Twenty20]], Buttler made his debut in the 20-over format of the game in Somerset's final match of the league stage, remaining six not out at the close of the innings.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/251/251438.html |title=New South Wales v Somerset |publisher=CricketArchive |date=18 October 2009 |accessdate=1 May 2010}}</ref> Buttler again captained King's in 2009, and in the seventeen matches under his leadership they lost only once, and also won the Western School Twenty20 competition.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.somersetcountycc.premiumtv.co.uk/page/News/Newsdetail/0,,11333~2025849,00.html |publisher=[[Somerset County Cricket Club]] |title=JOS BUTTLER LIFTS WISDEN SCHOOL'S CRICKETER OF YEAR |date=15 April 2010 |accessdate=3 May 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110725090952/http://www.somersetcountycc.premiumtv.co.uk/page/News/Newsdetail/0%2C%2C11333~2025849%2C00.html |archivedate=25 July 2011 |df=}}</ref> Coupled with his 554 runs for the school at an average of 61.55, and his performances for Somerset, he was named 2010 ''Young Wisden'' Schools Cricketer of the Year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wisden.com/default.aspx?id=3 |title=The Young Wisden Schools Cricketer of the Year |work=Wisden |publisher=John Wisden & Co. |accessdate=1 May 2010}}</ref>\n\n===First-team opportunity===\n[[File:Jos buttler.JPG|thumb|right|150px|Buttler keeping wicket for [[Somerset County Cricket Club|Somerset]] in the [[ECB 40]]|alt=A young man with light brown hair is standing on some grass. He is wearing a burgundy, grey and black cricket uniform, large gloves and black trousers covered by black think pads on his lower legs.]]\n\nWhen [[Craig Kieswetter]] was called up into the England one-day side in 2010, Buttler was given the chance of a prolonged run in Somerset's first team. [[Brian Rose (cricketer)|Brian Rose]], Somerset's Director of Cricket, chose not to bring in an experienced keeper to deputise, explaining that Kieswetter had been in a similar position three years earlier and that he had good reports of Buttler's ability.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thisisbristol.co.uk/news/Somerset-hopeful-Buttler-set-profit-Kieswetter-s-England-heroics/article-1862840-detail/article.html |title=Ambitious Buttler ready to stand in for Kieswetter |work=[[The Herald (Plymouth)|The Herald]] |publisher=[[Northcliffe Media]] |date=22 April 2010 |accessdate=1 May 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130505084350/http://www.thisisbristol.co.uk/news/Somerset-hopeful-Buttler-set-profit-Kieswetter-s-England-heroics/article-1862840-detail/article.html |archivedate=5 May 2013 }}</ref> In his first match of the 2010 season, Buttler remained 22 not out at the close of Somerset's innings, posting his first runs in List A cricket, and he followed this up with two catches to help Somerset beat [[Glamorgan County Cricket Club|Glamorgan]] in their opening [[Clydesdale Bank 40]] fixture.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/262/262613.html |title=Glamorgan v Somerset |publisher=CricketArchive |date=25 April 2010 |accessdate=10 May 2010}}</ref>\n\nHe made his maiden first-class century in his fourth County Championship match, scoring 144 runs in an innings characterised by \"dogged determination and [a] decent range of shots\".<ref name=\"bbc13may10\">{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/counties/8681073.stm |title=Hampshire draw with Somerset as poor start continues |publisher=[[BBC Sport]] |date=13 May 2010 |accessdate=14 May 2010}}</ref> In his next match, he scored his debut List A half-century against Sussex. Buttler joined [[James Hildreth]] at the crease with Somerset at 109/4, requiring 183 more runs to win off 129 [[Delivery (cricket)|balls]]. The pair put on a partnership of 158 runs \"to turn the game on its head\", with Buttler making 69 in 53 balls.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.skysports.com/cricket/match_report/0,19822,11066_85647,00.html |title=Sussex impaled by Sabres |publisher=[[Sky Sports]] |date=15 May 2010 |accessdate=18 May 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100517040647/http://www.skysports.com/cricket/match_report/0%2C19822%2C11066_85647%2C00.html |archivedate=17 May 2010 |df=}}</ref> In doing so, they set a new record partnership for the fifth-wicket against Sussex.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Records/England/ListA/Somerset/Partnership_Records/Highest_Partnerships_Somerset_v_Sussex.html |title=Highest Partnerships For Somerset Against Sussex |publisher=CricketArchive |accessdate=18 May 2010}}</ref> His continued good batting form, which also saw him make scores of 52 and 31* in a County Championship match against [[Yorkshire County Cricket Club|Yorkshire]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/262/262674.html |title=Somerset v Yorkshire |publisher=CricketArchive |date=17 May 2010 |accessdate=30 June 2010}}</ref> saw him retain his place in the Somerset team upon Kieswetter's return.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/cricket/counties/7742271/Jos-Buttler-follows-Craig-Kieswetters-example-as-Somerset-battle-on.html |title=Jos Buttler follows Craig Kieswetter's example as Somerset battle on |publisher=Telegraph |last=Clutton |first=Graham |date=19 May 2010 |accessdate=30 June 2010}}</ref>\n\nButtler was named [[Player of the Match awards (cricket)|Man of the Match]] in Somerset's [[2010 Friends Provident T20]] semi-final victory over Nottinghamshire at the [[Rose Bowl (cricket ground)|Rose Bowl]], reaching a \"breathtaking\" half-century from 21 balls to score an unbeaten 55 runs in a partnership of 75 with [[Kieron Pollard]].<ref name=\"ci14aug10\">McGlashan, Andrew (14 August 2010) [http://www.espncricinfo.com/fpt20/content/story/472435.html Trescothick and Buttler lead Somerset to the final], [[CricInfo]]. Retrieved 11 November 2017.</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/series/8053/scorecard/435839/Nottinghamshire-vs-Somerset-2nd-Semi-Final-twenty20-cup-eng/ |title=Nottinghamshire v Somerset |publisher=CricInfo |date=14 August 2010 |accessdate=11 November 2017}}</ref> His aggressive batting won him many plaudits and helped Somerset reach the final of the [[2010 Clydesdale Bank 40]] as well as the Twenty20 cup.<ref name=\"ci4sep10\" />\n\nHis good form with the bat continued into 2011<ref>[http://www.espncricinfo.com/county-cricket-2011/content/story/522377.html Buttler stars in Somerset rout], [[CricInfo]], 8 July 2011. Retrieved 11 November 2017.</ref><ref>[http://www.espncricinfo.com/county-cricket-2011/content/story/525871.html Buttler responds after Panesar's five], [[CricInfo]], 3 August 2011. Retrieved 11 November 2017.</ref> as Somerset again reached the final of both the [[2011 Friends Life t20|T20]] and [[2011 Clydesdale Bank 40|40 over]] competitions, with Buttler top-scoring with a \"mature\" 86 runs from 72 balls in the 40 over final.<ref>McGlashan, Andrew (17 September 2011) [http://www.espncricinfo.com/county-cricket-2011/content/story/532737.html Hamilton-Brown sets up Surrey triumph], [[CricInfo]]. Retrieved 11 November 2017.</ref><ref>Brickhill, Liam (27 August 2017) [http://www.espncricinfo.com/county-cricket-2011/content/story/530050.html Bristling Somerset storm into final], [[CricInfo]]. Retrieved 11 November 2017.</ref> In both 2010 and 2011 he was awarded the [[NBC Denis Compton Award]] as Somerset's most promising young player<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/england/content/story/209589.html |title=The NBC Denis Compton Awards |publisher=Cricinfo |accessdate=16 December 2011}}</ref> and made his full England debut at the end of the season.<ref name=\"ci26aug11\" />\n\nThe 2012 season proved similarly productive for Buttler, and featured a \"brilliant\" half-century scored from 36 balls against [[Northamptonshire County Cricket Club|Northamptonshire]] in the [[2012 Clydesdale Bank 40|domestic 40 over competition]],<ref>[http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/content/story/568773.html Cool Buttler sees Somerset home], [[CricInfo]], 17 June 2012. Retrieved 11 November 2017.</ref> although increasing international call-ups limited his appearances for Somerset and Kieswetter remained the first-choice wicket-keeper for Somerset.<ref name=\"ci25feb13\" /> The second County Championship match of the 2013 season saw Buttler score 94 runs playing as a specialist batsman and an injury to Kieswetter at the end of April provided an opportunity for Buttler to claim his place as wicket-keeper in the side.<ref name=\"ci20apr13\">Dobell, George (20 April 2013) [http://www.espncricinfo.com/county-cricket-2013/content/story/631278.html Smith helping Surrey smile again], [[CricInfo]]. Retrieved 12 November 2017.</ref><ref>[http://www.espncricinfo.com/county-cricket-2013/content/story/633105.html Kieswetter ruled out for six weeks], [[CricInfo]], 29 April 2013. Retrieved 12 November 2017.</ref> Somerset started the County Championship season poorly, but Buttler was praised for adopting a mature approach to his batting, averaging over 40 with the bat in the Championship at the midpoint of the season and enjoying his most productive first-class season to date.<ref name=\"ci6jun13\">Dobell, George (6 June 2013) [http://www.espncricinfo.com/icc-champions-trophy-2013/content/story/638889.html England blueprint about to be tested], [[CricInfo]]. Retrieved 18 November 2017.</ref><ref name=\"ci28apr14\">Gardner, Alan (28 April 2014) [http://www.espncricinfo.com/county-cricket-2014/content/story/740271.html Buttler shows his first-class mettle], [[CricInfo]]. Retrieved 19 November 2017.</ref> After missing county matches again due to international call-ups, Buttler saw Kieswetter return as wicket-keeper in some T20 county matches and began to publicly question his future at the club if he was not to keep wicket regularly for the one-day side. He delayed signing a new contract he had been offered, concerned that by not being the main wicket-keeper for Somerset that he would put his international wicket-keeping place in jeopardy, despite a strong emotional attachment to the county.<ref>[http://www.espncricinfo.com/county-cricket-2013/content/story/652425.html Buttler mulls over Somerset future], [[CricInfo]], 17 July 2013. Retrieved 12 November 2017.</ref><ref>Dobell, George (30 July 2013) [http://www.espncricinfo.com/county-cricket-2013/content/story/656701.html Compton exit would prompt Taunton transition], [[CricInfo]]. Retrieved 18 November 2017.</ref> Despite Somerset's desire to keep Buttler at the club, they were unable to reach an agreement which satisfied Buttler's desire to keep wicket, and at the end of the season he announced that he would be leaving Somerset with the aim of securing his international place and breaking into the England Test side.<ref>Dobell, George (27 September 2013) [http://www.espncricinfo.com/county-cricket-2013/content/story/675157.html Buttler confirms Somerset departure], [[CricInfo]]. Retrieved 18 November 2017.</ref><ref name=\"ci2oct13\">Hodgson, Myles (2 October 2013) [http://www.espncricinfo.com/england/content/story/676321.html Buttler targets Test cricket from Lancashire move], [[CricInfo]]. Retrieved 18 November 2017.</ref>\n\n===Move to Lancashire===\n\nAt the end of September 2013, Lancashire announced they had signed Buttler.<ref name=\"ci2oct13\" /><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/england/content/current/story/675777.html |title=Lancashire confirm Buttler signing |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |date=30 September 2013 |accessdate=30 September 2013}}</ref> He scored 42 in his first Championship appearance for the county before compiling a \"game-changing\" innings of 72 on a difficult pitch at [[County Ground, Northampton|Northampton]]. This showcased Buttler's first-class batting potential and contributed to a record seventh wicket partnership for Lancashire against [[Northamptonshire County Cricket Club|Northants]].<ref name=\"ci28apr14\" /><ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/cricket/27183421 Northants v Lancashire: Jos Buttler boosts Red Rose victory hopes], [[BBC Sport]], 28 April 2014. Retrieved 19 November 2017.</ref><ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/cricket/27198784 Northants v Lancashire set up tight finish at Wantage Road], [[BBC Sport]], 29 April 2017. Retrieved 19 November 2017.</ref> He scored his first century for Lancashire (his fourth in first-class cricket) in June against [[Durham County Cricket Club|Durham]]<ref>Hardcastle, Graham (18 June 2014) [http://www.espncricinfo.com/county-cricket-2014/content/story/753571.html Rushworth helps Durham resist Buttler], CricInfo. Retrieved 22 November 2017.</ref> before equalling the record for the fastest fifty scored in T20 cricket, hitting a half-century in 22 balls against Northants on his way to 58 not out in the [[2014 NatWest t20 Blast]].<ref>Press Association (20 June 2014) [http://www.espncricinfo.com/county-cricket-2014/content/story/754197.html Buttler's record burns off champions], CricInfo. Retrieved 22 November 2017.</ref> Lancashire finished runners-up of the T20 competition, losing to [[Warwickshire County Cricket Club|Warwickshire]] in the final.<ref>Dobell, George (23 August 2014) [http://www.espncricinfo.com/series/8053/report/693273/Warwickshire-vs-Lancashire-Final-twenty20-cup-eng Woakes denies Flintoff as Birmingham win Blast], CricInfo. Retrieved 22 November 2017.</ref> He played 10 first-class matches for Lancashire during the season and was called into the England Test side as wicket-keeper in July, replacing the injured [[Matt Prior]], although doubts remained about the quality of his wicket-keeping.<ref>Hopps, David (25 July 2014) [http://www.espncricinfo.com/england-v-india-2014/content/story/764055.html Hope springs eternal in Buttler], CricInfo. Retrieved 22 November 2017.</ref><ref>[https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Players/136/136065/First-Class_Matches.html First-class matches played by Joe Buttler], CricketArchive. Retrieved 22 November 2017.</ref>\n\nHe extended his stay with Lancashire, announcing a new three-year contract on 27 May 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lccc.co.uk/cricket/news/2016-news/buttler-signs-new-three-year-deal-with-lancashire/|title=Buttler signs new three-year deal with Lancashire|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==England career==\n\n===2008\u201310: England youth career===\n\nButtler's first taste of [[international cricket]] came in July 2008, when he represented England Under-17s in two warm-up matches against [[New Zealand U-19 cricket team|New Zealand Under-19s]]. Batting at number five, he scored a rapid 77 not out in the 50-over contest, hitting 11 fours and two sixes during the 49 deliveries he faced.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/251/251728.html |title=England Under-17s v New Zealand Under-19s |publisher=CricketArchive |date=21 July 2008 |accessdate=3 May 2010}}</ref> He also played in the two-day match between the two teams, scoring 45 in the first-innings as the match was drawn.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/251/251729.html |title=England Under-17s v New Zealand Under-19s |publisher=CricketArchive |date=22 July 2008 |accessdate=3 May 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, Buttler played four matches for England Under-18s, two each against Scotland A and Scotland Development XI. He scored 103 not out in the first of these matches,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/259/259918.html |title=Scotland A v England Under-18s |publisher=CricketArchive |date=26 May 2009 |accessdate=1 May 2010}}</ref> and made starts in each of the following matches, reaching double figures on each occasion, but not scoring higher than 28.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/259/259919.html |title=Scotland A v England Under-18s |publisher=CricketArchive |date=27 May 2009 |accessdate=15 April 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/259/259921.html |title=Scotland Development XI v England Under-18s |publisher=CricketArchive |date=29 May 2009 |accessdate=15 April 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/259/259920.html |title=Scotland Development XI v England Under-18s |publisher=CricketArchive |date=29 May 2009 |accessdate=15 April 2010}}</ref> Two months later, Buttler made his England Under-19 debut, appearing in the first T20 against [[Bangladesh U-19 cricket team|Bangladesh Under-19s]]. Playing as a specialist batsman, he scored 33 runs off 17 balls as England won by five wickets.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/247/247628.html |title=England Under-19s v Bangladesh Under-19s |publisher=CricketArchive |date=28 July 2009 |accessdate=1 May 2010}}</ref>\n\nDuring the 2009\u201310 English winter, Buttler toured with the England Under-19 team. He joined up with the squad in Bangladesh following Somerset's elimination from the Champions League Twenty20 for the seven-match youth [[One Day International]] (ODI) series, playing again as a specialist batsman.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://stats.cricinfo.com/ci/engine/player/308967.html?class=21;filter=advanced;keeper=1;orderby=default;template=results;type=allround |title=Statistics / Statsguru / JC Buttler / Under-19s Youth One-Day Internationals |publisher=Cricinfo |accessdate=15 May 2010}}</ref> He failed to make a significant impact until the final match when he top-scored for England with 42 runs.<ref>[http://www.espncricinfo.com/bangladesh/content/story/432949.html Mahmudul and Saikat help Bangladesh sign off on high], [[CricInfo]], 4 November 1999. Retrieved 11 November 2017.</ref> He remained with the team for the [[2010 U-19 Cricket World Cup|Under-19 World Cup]], where he played all but one of England's six matches, keeping wicket in three of them. He scored 91 runs in three innings, with a top-score of 78 against [[Indian U-19 cricket team|India]] in the fifth-place play-off semi-final. His batting average of 30.33 ranked him fifth on the England team.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Events/NZ/ICC_Under-19_World_Cup_2009-10/England_Under-19s_Batting.html |title= Batting and Fielding for England Under-19s: ICC Under-19 World Cup 2009/10 |publisher=CricketArchive |accessdate=1 May 2010}}</ref>\n\n===2011\u201312: Early senior career===\n\nButtler was called into the senior England squad for the [[Twenty20 International]] (T20I) against the [[Indian cricket team in England in 2011#Only T20I|touring Indian team]] in September 2011.<ref name=\"ci26aug11\">{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/england-v-india-2011/content/current/story/529919.html |title=Pietersen rested for India ODIs |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |author=ESPNcricinfo staff |date=26 August 2011 |accessdate=26 August 2011}}</ref> He made his debut for the side in the match as a specialist batsman before going on to play against the [[West Indian cricket team in England in 2011|touring West Indies side]] later the same season.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/england-v-west-indies-2011/content/story/532333.html |title=Swann 'delighted' to lead England |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |author=ESPNcricinfo staff |date=14 September 2011 |accessdate=21 January 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/england-v-west-indies-2011/content/story/533802.html |title=West Indies stun England to level series |publisher=ESPNcricinfo |author=Andrew Miller |date=25 September 2011 |accessdate=21 January 2012}}</ref> During the winter of 2011 he was part of the England performance programme for batting and wicket-keeping in India,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/15112059.stm |title=England call for James Harris and Tom Maynard |publisher=[[BBC Sport]] |date=29 September 2011 |accessdate=21 January 2012}}</ref> and played in the [[England Lions cricket team|England Lions]] tours of Bangladesh and Sri Lanka,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/16217507.stm |title=James Taylor to lead England Lions in Bangladesh |publisher=[[BBC Sport]] |date=16 December 2011 |accessdate=21 January 2012}}</ref> scoring his maiden limited-overs century against [[Sri Lanka A cricket team|Sri Lanka A]] in January 2012.<ref>[http://www.espncricinfo.com/srilanka/content/story/551248.html Buttler serves up victory for England Lions], [[CricInfo]], 27 January 2012. Retrieved 11 November 2017.</ref> He played a T20I against [[India cricket team|India]] in [[Kolkata]] and then toured with [[English cricket team against Pakistan in the UAE in 2011\u201312|England to play Pakistan]] in the United Arab Emirates in early 2012, making his ODI debut, although he was out second ball [[Duck (cricket)|without scoring]].<ref name=\"ci18dec12\">[http://www.espncricinfo.com/india-v-england-2012/content/story/597626.html Anderson, Trott rested from ODIs], [[CricInfo]], 18 December 2012. Retrieved 11 November 2017.</ref>\n\nButtler continued to play regular T20 cricket for England throughout 2012. Against [[South Africa cricket team|South Africa]] at [[Edgbaston Cricket Ground|Edgbaston]], he joined Somerset teammate Craig Kieswetter with England on 64/3 with only 16 balls remaining. The pair gave \"a brutal display of power hitting\", raising the final score to 118/5, with Buttler hitting 30 runs from one 32-run over from [[Wayne Parnell]], the second most productive over in International T20 at the time.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/cricket/19576600|title=England v South Africa: Jos Buttler stars in crushing Twenty20 win|author=Sam Sheringham|publisher=[[BBC Sport]]|date=12 September 2012|accessdate=12 September 2012}}</ref> The innings established Buttler as a key part of the England one-day side; he had made 10 appearances before the match but reached double figures only once in his six innings, and his performance made him \"one of the most talked-about players\" in the England side.<ref name=\"ci16sep12\">Hopps, David (16 September 2012) [http://www.espncricinfo.com/icc-world-twenty20-2012/content/story/582499.html Buttler propelled into the spotlight], [[CricInfo]]. Retrieved 11 November</ref> Buttler spoke about how the innings made him feel \"calmer, more myself, more relaxed\"<ref name=\"ci16sep12\" /> and he received an [[England and Wales Cricket Board|ECB]] incremental contract later in the same month.<ref>[http://www.espncricinfo.com/england/content/story/583457.html Buttler earns incremental contract], [[CricInfo]], 22 September 2012. Retrieved 11 November 2017.</ref> He was selected for the England squad for the [[2012 ICC World Twenty20]], playing in all five of England's matches in the competition, although he scored only 40 runs in his five innings.<ref>[http://stats.espncricinfo.com/icc-world-twenty20-2012/engine/records/averages/batting_bowling_by_team.html?id=6856;team=1;type=tournament ICC World Twenty20 2012/13 \u2013 England/Records: Batting and bowling averages], [[CricInfo]]. Retrieved 11 November 2017.</ref>\n\n===2013\u201314: Test debut, Champions Trophy and T20 World Cup===\n\nButtler replaced a rested [[Jonathan Trott]] in the [[English cricket team in India in 2012\u201313|England ODI squad in India]] in early 2013<ref name=\"ci18dec12\" /> and replaced Craig Kieswetter as the first-choice wicket-keeper halfway through the ODI series.<ref name=\"ci25jan13\">[http://www.espncricinfo.com/india-v-england-2012/content/story/602127.html Buttler admits mixed emotions after ousting friend], [[CricInfo]], 25 January 2013. Retrieved 12 November 2017.</ref> This allowed Buttler to break into the England ODI side on a consistent basis, playing regularly throughout the year in both ODI and T20 formats and increasingly as a wicket-keeper, despite some reservations about the quality of his work behind the stumps.<ref name=\"ci22jan13\">Dobell, George (22 January 2013) [http://www.espncricinfo.com/india-v-england-2012/content/story/601767.html England ring for Buttler], [[CricInfo]]. Retrieved 12 November 2017.</ref><ref name=\"ci11feb13\">Dobell, George (11 February 2013) [http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/content/story/604503.html Would somebody call the Buttler?], [[CricInfo]]. Retrieved 12 November 2017.</ref> He scored his maiden half-century for England in a T20 warm-up match at the start of [[English cricket team in New Zealand in 2012\u201313|England's tour of New Zealand]] followed by his first T20I half-century in the second match of the series.<ref>[http://www.espncricinfo.com/new-zealand-v-england-2013/content/story/603493.html Buttler ready with bat and gloves], [[CricInfo]], 5 February 2013. Retrieved 12 November 2017.</ref><ref>Hopps, David (12 February 2013) [http://www.espncricinfo.com/new-zealand-v-england-2013/content/story/604543.html Brendon McCullum blitz draws New Zealand level], [[CricInfo]]. Retrieved 12 November 2017.</ref> After being confirmed as England's first-choice limited-overs wicket-keeper,<ref name=\"ci25feb13\">Dobell, George (25 February 2013) [http://www.espncricinfo.com/england/content/story/606412.html Giles vows to be more \"ruthless\" as coach], [[CricInfo]]. Retrieved 12 November 2017.</ref> he played in every match in the [[2013 ICC Champions Trophy]] in England. For his performances in 2013, he was named in the T20I XI by [[ESPNCricinfo|Cricinfo]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/review2013/content/story/705667.html|title=AB, Ajmal and Co|website=www.espncricinfo.com}}</ref>\n\nButtler played again in the [[2014 ICC World Twenty20]] in Bangladesh in March and played regular one-day cricket throughout the year. He scored his maiden ODI century against [[Sri Lanka cricket team|Sri Lanka]] at [[Lord's]] in May, scoring 121 in 61 balls with nine fours and four sixes, the then-fastest century by any England batsman.<ref>{{cite web |title=Records / One-Day Internationals / Batting records / Fastest hundreds |url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/content/records/211608.html |publisher=ESPNcricinfo (ESPN Internet Ventures) |accessdate=31 May 2014}}</ref> During the fifth ODI of the [[Sri Lankan cricket team in England in 2014|series]] at [[Edgbaston Cricket Ground|Edgbaston]], Buttler was controversially '[[Run out|Mankaded]]' by [[Sachithra Senanayake]], leading to tension between the sides. England captain [[Alastair Cook]] expressed his disappointment, stating: \"I've never seen it before in a game. I was pretty disappointed. If he was properly trying to steal the single then I could possibly understand it. But he was half a yard out of his crease.\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2014/jun/03/england-fury-sri-lanka-mankad-run-out-jos-buttler|title=England fury as Sri Lanka run out Jos Buttler Mankad-style in last ODI|last=Edgbaston|first=Andy Wilson at|date=2014-06-03|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-05-31|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\nAfter first choice wicket-keeper [[Matt Prior]] stood down after injury on 22 July 2014, Buttler was called up for the England squad for the [[Indian cricket team in England in 2014#3rd Test|third Test against India]]. He made 85 runs from 83 balls in his first Test innings. He played in the final three Tests of the series before reverting to one-day duty, touring Sri Lanka at the end of the year.\n\n===2015\u201317: World Cup, Ashes series, UAE and tour of Bangladesh===\n\nAfter playing for England in the [[Carlton Mid Triangular Series in Australia in 2014\u201315|Tri-series in Australia]] at the start of the year, Buttler was once again involved with England at an international tournament, playing in the [[2015 Cricket World Cup]] in Australia and New Zealand. He scored an unbeaten 39 in 19 balls against Sri Lanka<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/series/8039/scorecard/656441/england-vs-sri-lanka-22nd-match-pool-a-icc-cricket-world-cup-2014-15|title=Full Scorecard of England vs Sri Lanka, World Cup, 22nd Match, Pool A \u2013 Score Report {{!}} ESPNcricinfo.com|website=ESPNcricinfo|language=en|access-date=2019-05-29}}</ref> and made 65 against [[Bangladesh cricket team|Bangladesh]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/series/8039/scorecard/656463/bangladesh-vs-england-33rd-match-pool-a-icc-cricket-world-cup-2014-15|title=Full Scorecard of Bangladesh vs England, World Cup, 33rd Match, Pool A \u2013 Score Report {{!}} ESPNcricinfo.com|website=ESPNcricinfo|language=en|access-date=2019-05-29}}</ref> but ultimately England lost both matches in a disastrous campaign, failing to progress beyond the group stages.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/cricket/31792930|title=Cricket World Cup 2015: England knocked out by Bangladesh|date=2015-03-09|access-date=2019-05-29|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\nLater in the English winter he was called back into the Test side, as wicket-keeper, during the [[English cricket team in the West Indies in 2014\u201315|tour of the West Indies]]. He continued in the role throughout the English summer, playing both [[New Zealand cricket team in England in 2015|Tests against New Zealand]] and all five [[Australia cricket team in England in 2015|Ashes Tests against Australia]]. Buttler's batting during the Ashes series was criticised by [[Geoffrey Boycott]], who stated:\n\n{{quotation|Jos Buttler is like a rabbit caught in the headlights of Ashes cricket. A seven-year-old schoolboy would have played better. He hasn't made a run all series. He hasn't shown any application whatsoever. It looks to me like his mind and confidence is shot for Test cricket\u2014it's pathetic.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/cricket/34023919|title=Ashes 2015: Geoffrey Boycott angry at England against Australia|date=21 August 2015|publisher=|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref>}}\n\nHe continued to play one-day cricket alongside his Test role, making his then-highest ODI score of 129 from 77 balls against [[New Zealand cricket team|New Zealand]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/cricket/33065934|title=England hit record 408\u20139 to thrash New Zealand in ODI|date=2015-06-09|access-date=2019-05-31|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\nAfter playing in the [[English cricket team against Pakistan in the UAE in 2015\u201316|first two Tests against Pakistan]] in the [[United Arab Emirates]] during October, Buttler was dropped for the third Test, replaced as wicket-keeper by [[Jonny Bairstow]], and was not selected for any of the Test matches during [[English cricket team in South Africa in 2015\u201316|England's tour of South Africa]], although he did play again in the one-day fixtures during the tour. In the fourth ODI against Pakistan in [[Dubai]] in November, he scored a 46-ball century, the fastest ODI hundred by an England player.<ref name=\"BBC34879336\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/pakistan-v-england-2015-16/content/story/942455.html|title=Buttler's record-breaking ton demolishes Pakistan|date=2015-11-20|website=Cricinfo|language=en|access-date=2019-05-31}}</ref>\n\nButtler again played for England in the [[2016 ICC World Twenty20]] and was a regular fixture in the limited-overs squad throughout the year. He scored an unbeaten 90 runs against Pakistan as part of an England record score of 444/3, the fastest half-century by an Englishman.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/content/records/284095.html |title=Fastest 50 in ODIs |publisher=ESPNcricinfo | accessdate=31 August 2016}}</ref> Both records have since been surpassed.\n\nButtler captained the England side in the [[England cricket team in Bangladesh in 2016\u201317|ODI series]] against Bangladesh in October 2016 after numerous players, including regular captain [[Eoin Morgan]], declined to tour over raised security concerns following a [[July 2016 Dhaka attack|terrorist attack in Dhaka]] in July.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/cricket/2016/09/09/jos-buttler-to-captain-englands-one-day-team-in-bangladesh-follo/|title=Jos Buttler to captain England in Bangladesh following Eoin Morgan\u2019s decision to pull out of tour|last=Hoult|first=Nick|date=2016-09-09|work=The Telegraph|access-date=2019-05-29|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref> In the second ODI, there was some controversy as Buttler was involved in a heated exchange with numerous Bangladesh players following his dismissal to [[Taskin Ahmed]]. Buttler, aggravated by the opposition's excessive celebrations, turned to confront them, resulting in him being ushered away by the [[Umpire (cricket)|umpires]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.skysports.com/cricket/news/12123/10612206/bangladesh-v-england-tempers-flare-during-and-after-second-odi|title=Bangladesh v England: Tempers flare during and after second ODI|website=Sky Sports|language=en|access-date=2019-05-29}}</ref> Following the incident, Buttler was reprimanded by the [[International Cricket Council]] (ICC) and received one demerit point to his disciplinary record, while Bangladesh captain [[Mashrafe Mortaza]] and [[Sabbir Rahman]] were each fined 20% of their match fees and given a demerit point.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/cricket/37607649|title=England's Jos Buttler given ICC reprimand as Bangladesh players fined|date=2016-10-10|access-date=2019-05-29|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\nButtler was again reserve wicket-keeper for the Test series against Bangladesh. He returned to the England Test side for the third Test against India in November, playing in the final three Tests of the series. He continued as a regular in the limited-overs side throughout 2016 and 2017, playing again for England in the [[2017 ICC Champions Trophy]], but was unable to break back into the Test side and was not selected for the [[2017\u201318 Ashes series]] in Australia. He was named in the [[ICC Awards|ICC World ODI XI]] in 2016.<ref name=\"ESPN1073990\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/review2016/content/story/1073990.html|title=The trump cards of 2016|date=30 December 2016|website=Cricinfo}}</ref>\n\n===2018\u2013present: Return to Test cricket, World Cup and Ashes series===\n\nIn May 2018, Buttler was recalled into England's Test squad to [[Pakistani cricket team in England in 2018|play Pakistan]] at Lord's later that month.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/cricket/44105904|title=England v Pakistan: Jos Buttler & Dominic Bess named in squad for first Test|date=2018-05-15|work=BBC Sport|access-date=2018-05-15|language=en-GB}}</ref> He had a successful return to Test cricket, scoring two half-centuries and scoring the most runs in the series; he also won the Man of the Match award at [[Headingley Cricket Ground|Headingley]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Dobell |first1=George |title=Success on Test recall 'was a bit of a surprise' \u2013 Jos Buttler |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/story/_/id/23735055/success-test-recall-was-bit-surprise-jos-buttler |accessdate=24 June 2018 |work=ESPNcricinfo |date=8 June 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn the subsequent [[Australian cricket team in England in 2018|ODI series against Australia]] in June 2018, he scored two half-centuries in the first four matches and then, in the fifth and final game of the series, he made 110 not out to take England to a historic series whitewash.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/cricket/44595347|title=England v Australia: Jos Buttler century secures 5\u20130 ODI whitewash|date=2018-06-24|access-date=2019-05-29|language=en-GB}}</ref> In this match, no other English batsman made more than 20 and Buttler was afterwards described as \"the best white-ball wicketkeeper batsman in the world\".<ref>{{cite web |title=Batting records {{!}} One-Day Internationals {{!}} Cricinfo Statsguru {{!}} ESPNcricinfo |url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/player/308967.html?class=2;spanmin2=1+Jun+2018;spanval2=span;template=results;type=batting;view=innings |website=Cricinfo |accessdate=24 June 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Dobell |first1=George |title=Jos Buttler earns 'best in the world' tag after immense century |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/story/_/id/23896950/jos-buttler-earns-best-world-tag-immense-century |accessdate=24 June 2018 |work=ESPNcricinfo |date=24 June 2018}}</ref> Buttler was named Man of the Match for his 110 not out, and also named Man of the Series for his impressive contributions with both bat and gloves.<ref>{{cite web |title=England hero Jos Buttler: 'Winning games you don't deserve to are the most enjoyable' |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/cricket/2018/06/24/england-hero-jos-buttler-winning-games-dont-deserve-enjoyable/ |website=The Telegraph |accessdate=10 July 2018}}</ref> In the T20I match of Australia's tour, Buttler scored the fastest T20I half-century by an English cricketer, in 22 balls.<ref>Dobell, George. (27 June 2018) [http://www.espncricinfo.com/series/18021/report/1119542/england-vs-australia-only-t20i-aus-in-eng-2018 Jos Buttler and Adil Rashid ensure Australia end tour winless]. ESPNcricinfo. Retrieved 3 July 2018</ref>\n\nButtler replaced [[James Anderson (cricketer)|James Anderson]] as the Test vice-captain on 31 July 2018, thus combining the role in all formats.<ref name=\"BBC45017582\" /> He registered his maiden Test century in the third Test of [[Indian cricket team in England in 2018|India's tour of England]] in August 2018, with a score of 106.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/cricket/jos-buttler-century-england-vs-india-test-scorecard-scoreboard-jonathan-liew-a8501911.html|title=Jos Buttler emerges from Test wilderness to savour his century|date=2018-08-21|website=The Independent|language=en|access-date=2019-04-20}}</ref> Buttler then retained his place in the Test and one-day squads, being selected to [[England cricket team in Sri Lanka in 2018\u201319|tour Sri Lanka]] in October and into the following year.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ecb.co.uk/england/men/news/854903/england-confirm-test-squad-for-sri-lanka-series|title=England confirm Test squad for Sri Lanka series|last=|first=|date=21 September 2018|website=England and Wales Cricket Board|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=|access-date=1 June 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2019, during the fourth ODI of [[English cricket team in the West Indies in 2018\u201319|England's tour of the West Indies]], Buttler scored a career-best 150 from 77 deliveries as England reached 418/6.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/series/18913/scorecard/1158069/west-indies-vs-england-4th-odi-england-tour-of-wi-2018-19|title=Full Scorecard of West Indies vs England 4th ODI 2019 \u2013 Score Report {{!}} ESPNcricinfo.com|website=ESPNcricinfo|language=en|access-date=2019-04-20}}</ref> During this innings, he hit 12 sixes, at the time the most by any English batsman in an ODI, and went from 51 to 100 in just 15 balls and from 100 to 150 in just 16 deliveries. This was part of an England world record for the most sixes in an ODI, with 24.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sports.ndtv.com/cricket/england-hit-record-24-sixes-against-the-windies-and-jos-buttler-smashes-half-of-them-watch-2000529|title=England Hit Record 24 Sixes Against The Windies And Jos Buttler Smashes Half Of Them \u2013 Watch {{!}} Cricket News|last=NDTVSports.com|website=NDTVSports.com|language=en|access-date=2019-04-20}}</ref> Following the innings, West Indian batsman [[Chris Gayle]] praised Buttler, stating, \"He is superb, one of the best strikers [of the ball] in world cricket today.{{nbsp}}... We can see he is a game-winner, a game-changer and every team needs a player like that to win games.\", while England captain Eoin Morgan described him as \"built like a champion [[racehorse]]\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.skysports.com/cricket/news/12123/11650422/eoin-morgan-hails-england-match-winner-jos-buttler-as-champion-racehorse-after-stunning-150|title=Eoin Morgan hails England match winner Jos Buttler as 'champion racehorse' after stunning 150|website=Sky Sports|language=en|access-date=2019-04-20}}</ref>\n\nIn the second ODI of the five-match [[Pakistan cricket team in England in 2019|series against Pakistan]] in May, Buttler scored an unbeaten 110 from 55 balls, his century coming in only 50 deliveries. This is the second fastest hundred by an English batsman in ODI cricket after his own record set against Pakistan in 2015.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/cricket/48239995|title=England v Pakistan: Jos Buttler stars as hosts wins second ODI|date=2019-05-11|access-date=2019-05-31|language=en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/cricket/48241463|title=Jos Buttler: Eoin Morgan praises 'freakish' England batsman after ODI win|date=2019-05-11|access-date=2019-05-31|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n====2019 Cricket World Cup====\n\nIn April 2019, he was named as the vice-captain of the [[2019 Cricket World Cup squads#England|England squad]] for the [[2019 Cricket World Cup]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/content/story/1181187.html |title=Jofra Archer misses World Cup cut but included to play Ireland, Pakistan |work=ESPN Cricinfo |accessdate=17 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.icc-cricket.com/news/1183273 |title=England leave out Jofra Archer from World Cup squad |work=International Cricket Council |accessdate=17 April 2019}}</ref> The ICC named Buttler as the key player of England's squad prior to the tournament.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.icc-cricket.com/news/1227388 |title=Team preview: England |work=International Cricket Council |accessdate=28 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nButtler made a quiet start to the tournament, scoring only 18 runs in the opening match of the tournament against South Africa at [[The Oval]], which ended in a comprehensive 104-run win for England.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.skysports.com/live-scores/cricket/england-v-south-africa/21515/scorecard|title=England vs South Africa {{!}} Sky Sports Live Cricket|website=SkySports|language=en|access-date=2019-06-01}}</ref> In the next match against Pakistan, he scored 103 from 76 balls (the then-fastest century by an English batsman in a World Cup) and shared a 130-run partnership with [[Joe Root]] for the fourth wicket, despite a shock 14-run defeat.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/cricket/48504940|title=Cricket World Cup: Pakistan shock England at Trent Bridge|date=2019-06-03|access-date=2019-06-03|language=en-GB}}</ref> He made 64 in the third match against Bangladesh as England posted 386/6, their highest ever World Cup score.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/story/_/id/26926622/england-record-streak-300-plus-scores|title=England's record streak of 300-plus scores|date=2019-06-08|website=ESPNcricinfo|language=en|access-date=2019-06-08}}</ref> However, he did not keep wicket during Bangladesh's innings after sustaining a minor hip injury while batting, making way for [[Jonny Bairstow]] to assume the role for the match,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://metro.co.uk/2019/06/08/jos-buttler-injury-update-englands-cricket-world-cup-victory-bangladesh-9873952/|title=Jos Buttler injury update after England's World Cup victory over Bangladesh|date=2019-06-08|website=Metro|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-08}}</ref> which England won by 106 runs.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/cricket/48569905|title=Cricket World Cup: Jason Roy hits 153 as England beat Bangladesh in Cardiff|date=2019-06-08|access-date=2019-06-08|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\nButtler scored 59 runs in the [[2019 Cricket World Cup Final|final]] against New Zealand and contributed to a crucial 110-run partnership with [[Ben Stokes]] to help tie the match, with both teams making 241 from their respective innings. He was selected to bat in the ensuing [[Super Over]] along with Stokes, from which the pair scored 15 runs; Buttler scoring seven with a boundary from the final ball. He completed the [[run out (cricket)|run out]] of [[Martin Guptill]] on the last ball of New Zealand's over as he attempted a match-winning second run. This tied the Super Over and secured England's maiden World Cup title, winning by a superior boundary count.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/cricket/48983890|title=England win Cricket World Cup: Ben Stokes stars in dramatic victory over New Zealand|date=2019-07-14|access-date=2019-07-15|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2019, following England's World Cup success, the ECB named Buttler in the fourteen-man Test squad for the upcoming [[2019 Ashes series|Ashes series]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ecb.co.uk/england/men/news/1294745/england-name-squad-for-first-ashes-test|title=England name squad for first Ashes Test|last=|first=|date=2019-07-27|website=England and Wales Cricket Board|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=|access-date=2019-07-31}}</ref>\n\n==T20 franchise career==\nButtler has become increasingly involved in playing franchise T20 cricket around the world, and has been described as arguably England's \"first ever global Twenty20 superstar\".<ref name=\"ESPN308967\" />\n\n===2013\u201314 Big Bash League===\n\nButtler's first experience of franchise cricket came in 2013/14 when he played for [[Melbourne Renegades]] in the [[2013\u201314 Big Bash League season]] in Australia. This coincided with the buildup to the England one-day side playing in Australia at the beginning of 2014 and followed him having been with the England development squad in [[Perth, Western Australia|Perth]] for a month prior to the start of the competition.<ref>Hogan, Jesse (16 December 2013) [http://www.smh.com.au/sport/cricket/rising-english-cricket-star-jos-buttler-to-turn-out-for-melbourne-renegades-20131215-2zfbo.html Rising English cricket star Jos Buttler to turn out for Melbourne Renegades], ''[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]''. Retrieved 19 November 2017.</ref> Buttler was initially only expected to play for Melbourne in their first two matches of the competition but this was extended due to the late arrival of Pakistani all-rounder [[Mohammad Hafeez]], who had been called into the [[Pakistan cricket team|Pakistan]] Test squad. After having scored a \"stunning\" 61 runs against [[Brisbane Heat]] in his third match,<ref>[http://www.heraldsun.com.au/melbourne-renegades-hold-onto-bighitting-englishman-jos-buttler-for-one-more-game/news-story/582ef43e920877896cca84701c820e9f Melbourne Renegades hold onto big-hitting Englishman Jos Buttler for one more game], ''[[Herald Sun]]'', 31 December 2013. Retrieved 19 November 2014.</ref> Buttler eventually played in five Big Bash matches for Melbourne before leaving to join the England squad.<ref>Hayes, Mark (4 January 2014) [http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/sport/cricket/glenn-maxwell-cameron-white-guide-melbourne-stars-past-melbourne-renegades/news-story/808a091223d0313cacf430612843f705 Glenn Maxwell, Cameron White guide Melbourne Stars past Melbourne Renegades], ''[[The Daily Telegraph (Sydney)]]''. Retrieved 19 November 2017.</ref><ref>Hogan, Jesse (11 January 2014) [http://www.smh.com.au/sport/cricket/dwayne-bravo-returns-to-melbourne-to-play-for-big-bashs-renegades-20140110-30mnw.html Dwayne Bravo returns to Melbourne to play for Big Bash's Renegades], ''[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]''. Retrieved 19 November 2017.</ref>\n\n===2016 and 2017 Indian Premier League===\n\nButtler played for [[Mumbai Indians]] in the 2016 and 2017 [[Indian Premier League]] (IPL) seasons.\n\n===2017\u201318 Bangladesh Premier League===\n\nExpecting to be left out of the [[2017\u201318 Ashes series]] in Australia, Buttler signed a two-year contract in August 2017 with [[Comilla Victorians]] to appear in the [[Bangladesh Premier League]] (BPL).<ref>Martin, Ali (11 August 2017) [https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2017/aug/11/jos-buttler-bangladesh-premier-league-ashes-cricket-twenty-20 Jos Buttler signs Bangladesh T20 deal before expected Ashes snub], ''[[The Guardian]]''. Retrieved 19 November 2017.</ref><ref>[http://www.thedailystar.net/sports/cricket/buttler-set-join-comilla-1447183 Buttler set to join Comilla], ''[[The Daily Star (Bangladesh)]]'', 11 August 2017. Retrieved 19 November 2017.</ref> He made his BPL debut in November 2017, scoring 48 runs from 42 balls in his second match for Comilla and recorded his first BPL half-century in his third match.<ref>Manhar Uddin (8 November 2017) [http://www.thedailystar.net/sports/bangladesh-cricket/bangladesh-premier-league-bpl-2017-victorians-outclass-stuttering-vikings-1488028 Victorians outclass stuttering Vikings], ''[[The Daily Star (Bangladesh)]]''. Retrieved 19 November 2017.</ref><ref>Mohammad Isam (12 November 2017) [http://www.espncricinfo.com/bangladesh-premier-league-2016-17/content/story/1125886.html Mohammad Nabi and Rashid Khan hand Rajshahi a thrashing], CricInfo. Retrieved 19 November 2017.</ref>\n\n===2017\u201318 Big Bash League===\n\nIn November 2017, Buttler was signed as an overseas player for Sydney Thunder for the upcoming [[2017\u201318 Big Bash League season|Big Bash League season]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cricbuzz.com/cricket-news/98559/sydney-thunder-sign-jos-buttler-for-forthcoming-bbl-07-season|title=Sydney Thunder sign Jos Buttler for forthcoming BBL season|website=Cricbuzz|language=en|access-date=2019-06-01}}</ref> He played in the first six games for Thunder before joining the England squad for the limited-over fixtures of [[England cricket team in Australia in 2017\u201318|England's tour of Australia]]. He scored 67 and 81 in separate games against [[Hobart Hurricanes]], being named Player of the Match in the first fixture.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/series/8044/game/1114866/hobart-hurricanes-vs-sydney-thunder-11th-match-big-bash-league-2017-18|title=Sydney Thunder beat Hobart Hurricanes by 57 runs \u2013 Hobart Hurricanes vs Sydney Thunder, Big Bash League, 11th Match Match Summary, Report {{!}} ESPNcricinfo.com|website=ESPNcricinfo|language=en|access-date=2019-06-01}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/series/8044/report/1114868/sydney-thunder-vs-hobart-hurricanes-13th-match-big-bash-league-2017-18|title=Recent Match Report \u2013 Sydney Thunder vs Hobart Hurricanes, Big Bash League, 13th Match {{!}} ESPNcricinfo.com|website=ESPNcricinfo|language=en|access-date=2019-06-01}}</ref>\n\n===2018 Indian Premier League===\n\nIn January 2018, Buttler was bought by the Rajasthan Royals in the [[List of 2018 Indian Premier League personnel changes|2018 IPL auction]] for {{INRConvert|4.4|c|-3}}.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/story/_/id/22218394/ipl-2018-player-auction-list-sold-unsold-players |title=List of sold and unsold players |accessdate=27 January 2018 |work=ESPN Cricinfo}}</ref> Buttler had a difficult start for the Royals, making a high score of just 29 in his first seven innings. However, on being promoted to open the batting mid-tournament, his performances significantly improved. He subsequently became only the second batsman in IPL history to achieve five scores of fifty or more in consecutive matches.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cricket.com.au/news/match-report/rajasthan-royals-mumbai-indians-ipl-match-report-jos-buttler-sanju-samson-evin-lewis-playoffs/2018-05-14 |title=Buttler equals long-standing IPL record |accessdate=29 April 2019 |work=Cricket.com.au}}</ref> He made an unbeaten 95 from 60 balls against [[Chennai Super Kings]], his highest score in the T20 format to date.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/series/8048/report/1136603/rajasthan-royals-vs-chennai-super-kings-43rd-match-indian-premier-league-2018|title=Recent Match Report \u2013 Rajasthan Royals vs Chennai Super Kings, Indian Premier League, 43rd match {{!}} ESPNcricinfo.com|website=ESPNcricinfo|language=en|access-date=2019-05-31}}</ref>\n\n===2018\u201319 Big Bash League===\n\nButtler again played for Sydney Thunder in the [[2018\u201319 Big Bash League season|2018\u201319 Big Bash League]], this time alongside England teammate [[Joe Root]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/cricket/45288760|title=Big Bash: Joe Root and Jos Buttler agree Sydney Thunder stint|date=2018-08-23|access-date=2019-06-01|language=en-GB}}</ref> The [[England and Wales Cricket Board]] (ECB) allowed Buttler and Root to play the first half of the season, despite a busy international schedule throughout 2019.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/cricket/2018/08/23/ecb-give-joe-root-jos-buttler-green-light-represent-sydney-thunder/|title=ECB give Joe Root and Jos Buttler green light to represent Sydney Thunder in Big Bash despite hectic 2019 schedule|last=Berry|first=Scyld|date=2018-08-23|work=The Telegraph|access-date=2019-06-01|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref>\n\nButtler made his highest BBL score of 89 from 54 deliveries against Hobart Hurricanes, despite a seven-wicket defeat,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.news.com.au/sport/cricket/big-bash/live-hobart-hurricanes-vs-sydney-thunder-at-blundstone-arena/news-story/f7a5d539f0725814ae58d08395c06179|title=Thunder crack in \u2018disastrous\u2019 finish|date=2018-12-28|website=NewsComAu|language=en|access-date=2019-06-01}}</ref> before making 55 in a thrilling one-run win over [[Perth Scorchers]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/cricket/46734798|title=Big Bash League: Jos Buttler shines but Joe Root fails again|date=2019-01-02|access-date=2019-06-01|language=en-GB}}</ref> Buttler departed as the tournament's leading run-scorer, with 273 from seven innings, making three half-centuries at an average of 39.00.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/cricket/46793136|title=Big Bash League: Joe Root and Jos Buttler end BBL stint with defeat|date=2019-01-08|access-date=2019-06-01|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n===2019 Indian Premier League===\n\nRajasthan Royals retained Buttler for the [[2019 Indian Premier League|2019 IPL season]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.skysports.com/cricket/news/15815/11554933/ben-stokes-and-jos-buttler-retained-by-rajasthan-for-2019-ipl-david-warner-and-steve-smith-to-return|title=Ben Stokes and Jos Buttler retained by Rajasthan for 2019 IPL; David Warner and Steve Smith to return|website=Sky Sports|language=en|access-date=2019-05-30}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/cricket/46225438|title=Indian Premier League: Jos Buttler & Ben Stokes retained by Rajasthan Royals|date=2018-11-15|access-date=2019-05-30|language=en-GB}}</ref> In a match between Rajasthan Royals and [[Kings XI Punjab]], Buttler was controversially [[run out]] on 69 by Indian bowler [[Ravichandran Ashwin]] via 'Mankading', an act that Ashwin was heavily criticised for.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/cricket/47697369|title=Jos Buttler 'Mankad' dismissal: England batsman controversially run out in IPL|date=2019-03-25|access-date=2019-05-30|language=en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/cricket/47728182|title=Jos Buttler: 'Mankad' dismissal not 'in the spirit of the game' \u2013 MCC|date=2019-03-27|access-date=2019-05-31|language=en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.crictracker.com/dale-steyn-slams-ravi-ashwin-for-mankading-jos-buttler/|title=Dale Steyn slams Ravi Ashwin for 'Mankading' Jos Buttler|date=2019-03-25|website=CricTracker|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-31}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.icc-cricket.com/news/1113878|title=Buttler's controversial \u2018Mankad\u2019 run out \u2013 best of the reaction|website=www.icc-cricket.com|language=en|access-date=2019-05-31}}</ref> Former Australian bowler and Rajasthan mentor [[Shane Warne]] called the incident a \"disgraceful and low act\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.foxsports.com.au/cricket/indian-premier-league/completely-out-of-order-shane-warne-leads-cricket-worlds-condemnation-of-disgraceful-ravi-ashwin-mankad/news-story/91250e7213da89e4501cce6ffb3ce6fb|title=Ravi Ashwin mankad controversy: Shane Warne slams \u2018disgraceful\u2019 act|date=2019-03-26|website=Fox Sports|language=en-AU|access-date=2019-06-01}}</ref> This is the second instance in which Buttler has been dismissed in this fashion, the other occasion in an ODI match for England against Sri Lanka in 2014.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.skysports.com/cricket/news/12123/11683985/jos-buttler-says-he-wont-be-mankaded-again-following-ravi-ashwins-controversial-ipl-dismissal|title=Jos Buttler says he 'won't be Mankaded again' following Ravi Ashwin's controversial IPL dismissal|website=Sky Sports|language=en|access-date=2019-06-01}}</ref> In his next two matches for Rajasthan, he was dismissed for scores of just five and six but returned to form after hitting 59 from 43 balls in a fixture against [[Royal Challengers Bangalore]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://metro.co.uk/2019/04/03/jos-buttler-finally-breaks-silence-ravi-ashwin-mankad-indian-premier-league-9108542/|title=Buttler finally breaks silence on Ashwin 'Mankad' at Indian Premier League|date=2019-04-03|website=Metro|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-31}}</ref> He also made a score of 89 from 43 deliveries against [[Mumbai Indians]], hitting 28 runs off the 13th over.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/series/8048/game/1178402/mumbai-indians-vs-rajasthan-royals-27th-match-indian-premier-league-2019|title=Rajasthan Royals beat Mumbai Indians by 4 wickets (with 3 balls remaining) \u2013 Mumbai Indians vs Rajasthan Royals, Indian Premier League, 27th Match Match Summary, Report {{!}} ESPNcricinfo.com|website=ESPNcricinfo|language=en|access-date=2019-05-31}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nIn October 2017, Buttler married Louise Webber. England teammates [[Steven Finn (cricketer)|Steven Finn]] and [[Alex Hales]] acted as ushers for the wedding.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mirror.co.uk/sport/cricket/england-cricketer-jos-buttler-gets-11398671|title=England cricket star quietly gets married as club let news slip|last=Whaling|first=James|date=2017-10-24|website=mirror|access-date=2019-05-29}}</ref> Their daughter, Georgia Rose, was born in April 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.crictracker.com/england-batsman-jos-buttler-becomes-father-of-a-baby-girl/|title=England batsman Jos Buttler becomes father of a baby girl|date=2019-04-28|website=CricTracker|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-29}}</ref>\n\nButtler was appointed [[Member of the Order of the British Empire]] (MBE) in the [[2020 New Year Honours]] for services to cricket.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=62866|supp=y|page=N16|date=28 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Playing style==\n{{Quote box|quoted=true |bgcolor=#F5F6CE|salign=left|quote=[Jos Buttler] is an extravagantly talented batsman with the power and range of strokes to damage any bowling attack. There may be moments, against the very best bowling, when his improvisation gets him into trouble but, so capable of unorthodoxy is he, that even the best could be discombobulated.| source=[[George Dobell]], June 2013<ref name=\"ci6jun13\" />|align=right|width=275px}}\n\nA tall and strongly-built cricketer, Buttler has an upright stance in the [[Crease (cricket)|crease]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/sport/cricket/article7124545.ece |title=Jos Buttler's century shows future rosy for Somerset |work=Times Online |date=12 May 2010 |last=Dean |first=Geoffrey |accessdate=14 May 2010}}</ref> During his maiden first-class century against Hampshire in 2010, he \"hit the ball hard and straight\", \"moving his feet decisively, playing with his bat close to his body and selecting the right balls to attack\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/sport/cricket/article7125841.ece |title=Jos Buttler makes most of Craig Kieswetter's absence |work=Times Online |date=13 May 2010 |last=Dean |first=Geoffrey |accessdate=14 May 2010}}</ref> Buttler was praised for \"remaining cool and composed at the crease\" and for his \"dogged determination and decent range of shots\" during the innings.<ref name=\"bbc13may10\" /> Somerset captain [[Marcus Trescothick]] suggested that Buttler could challenge teammate Craig Kieswetter's place in the England team.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thisissomerset.co.uk/sport/Trescothick-Somerset-teenager-Buttler-day-wicket-England/article-2157368-detail/article.html |title=Trescothick: Somerset teenager Buttler could one day keep wicket for England |work=Somerset Guardian |date=15 April 2010 |accessdate=15 April 2010}}</ref>\n\nButtler's temperament in the longer forms of the game has been questioned at times as his career has developed. In 2013, he was out for 94 runs for Somerset while attempting to reach his century by hitting a six and George Dobell, writing for [[ESPNcricinfo]], questioned \"his ability to defend and deny [bowlers]\".<ref name=\"ci20apr13\" /> Dobell praised the first half of Buttler's innings, which ensured a draw for Somerset, saying that \"it showed a young man responding to his team's needs with a restrained, mature performance that exhibited a decent defence and an ability to leave and play straight\" and that he had \"produced some of those trademark straight drives and several powerful pulls\" but felt that \"it is the strokes he does not play that are as relevant as those he does\".<ref name=\"ci20apr13\" />\n\nIn one day cricket, Buttler quickly established a reputation as an aggressive batsman who could take control of a game at the end of an innings.<ref>[http://www.espncricinfo.com/countycricket2010/content/story/471667.html Somerset limp past Unicorns], [[CricInfo]]. Retrieved 11 November 2017.</ref><ref>McGlashan, Andrew (12 September 2012) [http://www.espncricinfo.com/england-v-south-africa-2012/content/story/581984.html Broad praise for 'game-changing' Buttler], [[CricInfo]]. Retrieved 11 November 2017.</ref><ref name=\"ci22jan13\" /> By the end of his first full-season he was producing \"innings of huge promise\"<ref name=\"ci16aug10\">[http://www.espncricinfo.com/countycricket2010/content/story/472874.html In-form Buttler sets up Lancashire rout], [[CricInfo]], 16 August 2010. Retrieved 11 November 2011.</ref> which were being described as \"breathtaking\"<ref name=\"ci14aug10\" /> and \"swashbuckling\"<ref name=\"ci16aug10\" /> and displaying \"an array of explosive and innovative shots\".<ref>[http://www.espncricinfo.com/countycricket2010/content/story/474988.html Somerset seal semi-final spot], [[CricInfo]], 29 August 2010. Retrieved 11 November 2017.</ref> Still a teenager, his displays in both 40 over and 20 over cricket in 2010 won him plaudits, including a description as a \"supremely talented youngster\" who batted with a \"blend of power and sweet timing\".<ref name=\"ci4sep10\">[http://www.espncricinfo.com/countycricket2010/content/story/475783.html Record-breaking Somerset storm into semi-finals], [[CricInfo]], 4 September 2010. Retrieved 11 November 2017.</ref> His range of shots, including effective use of 'scoop' and 'ramp' shots over the wicket-keeper to [[fine leg]] and variations such as reverse and swivel scoop shots,<ref>Hopps D (11 June 2013) [http://www.espncricinfo.com/icc-champions-trophy-2013/content/story/641047.html Buttler ready for unorthodox duel with Malinga], [[CricInfo]]. Retrieved 18 November 2017.</ref> mean that his game has been considered subtle rather than overly aggressive<ref>[http://www.espncricinfo.com/county-cricket-2011/content/story/526399.html Pollard, Buttler take Somerset through], [[CricInfo]], 7 August 2011. Retrieved 11 November 2017.</ref><ref>McGlashan, Andrew (13 September 2017) [http://www.espncricinfo.com/england/content/story/582103.html Buttler's confidence ramped up], [[CricInfo]]. Retrieved 11 November 2017.</ref> and his \"stunning strokes\",<ref>[http://www.espncricinfo.com/county-cricket-2013/content/story/635371.html Hildreth, Buttler lead Somerset romp], [[CricInfo]], 11 May 2013. Retrieved 18 November 2017.</ref> clean striking and \"crispness when hitting\" the ball along with his \"audacity and adventure\" have all been cited as making him an \"exciting\" batsman.<ref>Dutta, Sahil (26 August 2011) [http://www.espncricinfo.com/county-cricket-2011/content/story/529951.html Spinners give Hampshire the edge], [[CricInfo]]. Retrieved 11 November 2017.</ref>\n\nDespite not always being his county's first-choice wicket-keeper and reservations about the quality of his work behind the stumps, Buttler has frequently been used in that role by the England team since the beginning of 2013, especially in one-day cricket. He was installed in the wicket-keeper role ahead of the [[2013 ICC Champions Trophy]] after Craig Kieswetter faltered in terms of his batting \u2013 Buttler's one-day batting, his potential and his ability to combine power with improvisation being seen as more important than any failings as a wicket-keeper<ref name=\"ci22jan13\" /> \u2013 despite, by his own admission, his \"keeping [being] a work in progress\".<ref name=\"ci25jan13\" /> His wicket-keeping was \"seen by some as having more potential\" than his main rival for the job Jonny Bairstow and England wicket-keeper coach [[Bruce French (cricketer)|Bruce French]] spoke of his \"natural hands\" behind the stumps.<ref name=\"ci11feb13\" />\n\nFollowing Kieswetter's and Matt Prior's international retirements in 2015, Buttler became England's first-choice wicket-keeper in all formats. Whether he should play as a wicket-keeper or specialist batsman was questioned in middle of the 2015 season<ref>{{Cite web|title = Must Buttler keep in all formats?|url = http://www.espncricinfo.com/magazine/content/story/891769.html|accessdate = 29 June 2015}}</ref> and Bairstow replaced him for the third ODI during [[Australian cricket team in England and Ireland in 2015|Australia's 2015 tour]] due to Buttler's poor form with the bat throughout the Australian series.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Buttler rested, Bairstow called up|url = http://www.espncricinfo.com/the-ashes-2015/content/story/918307.html|accessdate = 6 September 2015|date = 2015-09-05|website = ESPN Cricinfo}}</ref> Bairstow eventually became the outright wicket-keeper for Tests in December 2015 for the series against South Africa,<ref>{{Cite web|title = Bairstow ready to wear gloves with pride|url = http://www.espncricinfo.com/south-africa-v-england-2015-16/content/story/952317.html|website = Cricinfo|accessdate = 15 December 2015}}</ref> and Buttler was dropped from the Test side during 2016, whilst continuing to be the first-choice ODI and T20 wicket-keeper.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2016/jun/05/jos-buttler-england-test-royal-london-cup-lancashire|title=Jos Buttler targets regaining England Test place after first-class hiatus|last=Martin|first=Ali|date=2016-06-05|website=the Guardian|language=en|access-date=2018-03-22}}</ref>\n\n==Career best performances==\n{{As of|2019|6}}, Buttler has scored five first-class and 11 List A centuries, nine of which have been scored for England in One Day International matches. He is yet to score a century in the T20 format of the game.<ref name=\"ESPN308967\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/england/content/player/308967.html|title=Jos Buttler|website=ESPNCricinfo|access-date=2019-05-30}}</ref>\n\nButtler made his maiden first-class century in May 2010, scoring 144 for Somerset against Hampshire at the [[Rose Bowl (cricket ground)|Rose Bowl]], [[Southampton]].<ref name=\"bbc13may10\" /><ref>[http://www.espncricinfo.com/countycricket2010/content/story/459448.html Twin hundreds leads Somerset comeback], [[CricInfo]], 12 May 2010. Retrieved 11 November 2017.</ref> {{As of|2018|12}} this remains his highest first-class score. His highest Test match score of 106 was made for England against India in August 2018 at [[Trent Bridge]], [[Nottingham]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/cricket/45258626|title=England v India: Jos Buttler hits century but hosts heading for defeat|date=2018-08-21|access-date=2019-05-30|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\nIn limited overs cricket, Buttler's best List A and ODI score of 150 from 77 deliveries was made in February 2019 against the [[West Indies cricket team|West Indies]] at the [[National Cricket Stadium (Grenada)|National Cricket Stadium]], [[Grenada]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/cricket/47392140|title=England in West Indies: Jos Buttler's 150 inspires tourists to thrilling win|date=2019-02-27|access-date=2019-05-30|language=en-GB}}</ref> This is also the highest ODI score for an Englishman against the West Indies.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/batting/most_runs_innings.html?class=2&id=1&id=4&type=headtohead|title=England v West Indies Cricket Team Records & Stats {{!}} ESPNcricinfo.com|website=Cricinfo|access-date=2019-05-30}}</ref> Buttler is yet to score a century in one-day matches in county cricket.\n\nButtler's highest T20 score of 95 not out from 60 balls was made for Rajasthan Royals against Chennai Super Kings in the [[2018 Indian Premier League]] at the [[Sawai Mansingh Stadium]], [[Jaipur]].<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/cricket/44090045 IPL: Jos Buttler hits highest T20 score as Rajasthan Royals beat Chennai], [[BBC Sport]], 11 May 2018. Retrieved 12 May 2018.</ref> His highest T20I score is 73 not out off 49 balls, and was achieved against Sri Lanka in July 2016 at the Rose Bowl, Southampton.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/cricket/36720351|title=England v Sri Lanka: Jos Buttler eases hosts to T20 victory|date=2016-07-05|access-date=2019-05-30|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n==Honours==\n* [[File:Order of the British Empire (Civil) Ribbon.png|60px]] Buttler was appointed [[Member of the Most Excellent Order of the British Empire]] (MBE) in the [[2020 New Year Honours]] for services to cricket.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=62866|supp=y|Notice ID=3455121|date=28 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://josbuttler.co.uk/ Official website]\n* {{cricinfo|ref=ci/content/player/308967.html}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{succession box|\n  | before = [[James Taylor (cricketer, born 1990)|James Taylor]]\n  | title  = [[Young Wisden Schools Cricketer of the Year]]\n  | years  = 2010\n  | after  = [[Will Vanderspar]]\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{commons category}}\n\n{{England ODI cricket captains}}\n{{England T20I cricket captains}}\n{{Navboxes colour\n|title= England squads \n|bg= skyblue\n|fg= #000060\n|bordercolor=#000060\n|list1=\n{{England Squad 2015 Cricket World Cup}}\n{{England Squad 2019 Cricket World Cup}}\n}}\n{{Lancashire County Cricket Club squad}}\n{{Rajasthan Royals squad}}\n{{Good article}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Buttler, Jos}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1990 births]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Taunton]]\n[[Category:People educated at King's College, Taunton]]\n[[Category:English cricketers]]\n[[Category:England Test cricketers]]\n[[Category:England One Day International cricketers]]\n[[Category:England Twenty20 International cricketers]]\n[[Category:Somerset cricketers]]\n[[Category:Lancashire cricketers]]\n[[Category:Melbourne Renegades cricketers]]\n[[Category:Comilla Victorians cricketers]]\n[[Category:Sydney Thunder cricketers]]\n[[Category:NBC Denis Compton Award recipients]]\n[[Category:Cricketers at the 2015 Cricket World Cup]]\n[[Category:Cricketers at the 2019 Cricket World Cup]]\n[[Category:Mumbai Indians cricketers]]\n[[Category:Rajasthan Royals cricketers]]\n[[Category:Wisden Cricketers of the Year]]\n[[Category:Members of the Order of the British Empire]]\n", "name_user": "103.60.175.78", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jos_Buttler"}
