{"title_page": "Stuart Broad", "text_new": "{{short description|English cricketer}}\n{{Infobox cricketer\n| honorific_suffix = {{post-nominals|country=GBR|size=100%|MBE}}\n| name = Stuart Broad\n| image = Stuart broad.jpg\n| country = England\n| fullname = Stuart Christopher John Broad\n| nickname = Broady, Malfoy<ref name=\"Stuart Broad\"/><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.nottinghampost.com/Don-t-Malfoy-says-Broad-s-just-quidditch/story-25716505-detail/story.html |title=Stuart Broad |newspaper=Nottingham Post |accessdate=7 August 2014 }}{{Dead link|date=June 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=no }}</ref>\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1986|6|24|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Nottingham]], England\n| height = 6 ft 5 in\n| batting = Left-handed\n| bowling = Right-arm [[Fast bowling|fast-medium]]\n| role = [[Bowling (cricket)|Bowler]]\n| family = [[Chris Broad|BC Broad]] (father)\n| international = true\n| internationalspan = 2006\u2013present\n| testcap = 638\n| testdebutdate = 9 December\n| testdebutyear = 2007\n| testdebutagainst = Sri Lanka\n| lasttestdate = 24 January\n| lasttestyear = 2020\n| lasttestagainst = South Africa\n| odicap = 197\n| odidebutdate = 30 August\n| odidebutyear = 2006\n| odidebutagainst = Pakistan\n| lastodidate = 14 February\n| lastodiyear = 2016\n| lastodiagainst = South Africa\n| T20Icap = 18\n| T20Idebutdate = 28 August\n| T20Idebutyear = 2006\n| T20Idebutagainst = Pakistan\n| lastT20Idate = 31 March\n| lastT20Iyear = 2014\n| lastT20Iagainst = Netherlands\n| club1 = [[Leicestershire County Cricket Club|Leicestershire]]\n| year1 = 2005\u201307\n| club2 = [[Nottinghamshire County Cricket Club|Nottinghamshire]]\n| year2 = 2008\u2013present\n| clubnumber2 = 8\n| club4 = [[Hobart Hurricanes]]\n| year4 = 2016/17\n| clubnumber4 = 8 \n| columns = 4\n| column1 = [[Test cricket|Test]]\n| matches1 = 138\n| runs1 = 3,211\n| bat avg1 = 18.66\n| 100s/50s1 = 1/12\n| top score1 = 169\n| deliveries1 = 28,079\n| wickets1 = 485\n| bowl avg1 = 28.50\n| fivefor1 = 17\n| tenfor1 = 2\n| best bowling1 = 8/15\n| catches/stumpings1 = 46/\u2013\n| column2 = [[One Day International|ODI]]\n| matches2 = 121\n| runs2 = 529\n| bat avg2 = 12.30\n| 100s/50s2 = 0/0\n| top score2 = 45[[not out|*]]\n| deliveries2 = 6,109\n| wickets2 = 178\n| bowl avg2 = 30.13\n| fivefor2 = 1\n| tenfor2 = 0\n| best bowling2 = 5/23\n| catches/stumpings2 = 27/\u2013\n| column3 = [[Twenty 20 International|T20I]]\n| matches3 = 56\n| runs3 = 118\n| bat avg3 = 7.37\n| 100s/50s3 = 0/0\n| top score3 = 18[[not out|*]]\n| deliveries3 = 1173\n| wickets3 = 65\n| bowl avg3 = 22.93\n| fivefor3 = 0\n| tenfor3 = 0\n| best bowling3 = 4/24\n| catches/stumpings3 = 21/\u2013\n| column4 = [[First class cricket|FC]]\n| matches4 = 223\n| runs4 = 5,181\n| bat avg4 = 19.62\n| 100s/50s4 = 1/24\n| top score4 = 169\n| deliveries4 = 42,106\n| wickets4 = 779\n| bowl avg4 = 27.49\n| fivefor4 = 29\n| tenfor4 = 3\n| best bowling4 = 8/15\n| catches/stumpings4 = 82/\u2013\n| date = 28 January\n| year = 2020\n| source = http://www.espncricinfo.com/england/content/player/10617.html ESPNcricinfo\n}}\n'''Stuart Christopher John Broad''', {{post-nominals|size=100%|MBE}} (born 24 June 1986) is an English cricketer who plays [[Test cricket]] for the [[England cricket team]] and a former [[One Day International|ODI]] and [[Twenty 20 International|T20]] captain. A right-arm [[seam bowling|seam bowler]] and left-handed batsman, Broad began his professional career at [[Leicestershire County Cricket Club|Leicestershire]], the team attached to his school, [[Oakham School]]; in 2008 he transferred to [[Nottinghamshire County Cricket Club|Nottinghamshire]], the county of his birth and the team for which his father played. In August 2006 he was voted the [[Cricket Writers' Club Young Cricketer of the Year]]. In the fourth Test of the 2015 Ashes series Broad took career best figures of 8\u201315 in the Australian first innings as they were dismissed for just 60. This performance was named as [[Wisden Cricket Monthly|Wisden's]] Men's Test spell of the decade.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wisden.com/stories/decade-in-review/mens-test-spells-of-the-decade-no-1-broad-wins-the-ashes-in-a-morning|title=Men\u2019s Test Spells Of The Decade, No.1: Stuart Broad's 8-15|date=2019-12-15|website=Wisden|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-01-14}}</ref>\n\nBroad was awarded the Man of the Match in the [[2009 Ashes series#Fifth Test|fifth Test]] of the 2009 Ashes series at [[the Oval]], after figures of 5/37 in the afternoon session of the second day. On 30 July 2011, at the Nottingham Test match against India, he achieved a Test match [[hat trick]] in the process gaining his then best Test figures of 6\u201346.<ref name=\":1\">{{cite news|url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/content/records/136977.html|title=Test match hat-trick takers|work=ESPNcricinfo|accessdate=30 July 2011}}</ref>  As a batsman, he holds the second-highest ever Test score made by a number 9\u2014he made 169, his only century in first-class cricket, against [[Pakistan cricket team|Pakistan]] in August 2010. At the start of the summer in 2012 Broad, returning from injury, produced figures of 7 for 72 in a match haul of 11 wickets against the West Indies.  He is England's second highest wicket taker in [[Test cricket]].\n\n==Early life==\nBroad was born 12 weeks prematurely and his life was saved by a doctor called John, after whom he was (middle) named when he survived.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/cricket/12103482/Stuart-Broad-follows-step-mums-advice-to-seize-the-moment-and-demolishes-South-Africa.html|title=Stuart Broad follows step-mum's advice to seize the moment and demolishes South Africa|last=Sawer|first=Patrick|date=2016-01-16|access-date=2020-01-13|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref> Broad originally started his cricketing career as an opening batsman, following in the footsteps of his father, the former England [[Batting order (cricket)#Opening batsmen|opener]] and current ICC match referee [[Chris Broad]]. It was not until he was 17 and had a growth spurt that he started to consider being a fast bowler.<ref name=\"telegraph\"/> Broad had been associated with Leicestershire since he was 8 years old, having represented them at Under-9 level, and played for Melton Mowbray club Egerton Park, which also produced England seamer [[Tim Munton]]. Broad played for Egerton Park from the ages of 9 to 19; in his final two seasons he opened the batting with fellow Leicestershire player [[Matthew Boyce]] and spearheaded the attack. He was awarded the Leicestershire Young Cricketers Batsman Award in 1996.<ref name=\"telegraph\"/>\n\nBefore he was 17, he also played field hockey as a goalkeeper, and had trialled with [[England men's national field hockey team|England national field hockey team]].{{clarify|reason=If this did happen it is likely this was an age-group trial, not the senior team|date=November 2019}}<ref name=\"Stuart Broad\">{{cite news |url=http://www.cricinfo.com/england/content/player/10617.html |title=Stuart Broad |work=Cricinfo |accessdate=26 August 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Education==\nBroad was educated at Brooke Priory School and [[Oakham School]], a co-educational [[independent school]] in the [[market town]] of [[Oakham]] in Rutland, where he was in the same year as England Rugby back-row [[Tom Croft]].<ref name=\"telegraph\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/cricket/international/theashes/6086500/Stuart-Broad-from-school-all-rounder-to-Englands-world-class-Ashes-winner.html |title=Stuart Broad: from school all-rounder to England's world-class Ashes winner |publisher=Telegraph Online |date=25 August 2009 | location=London | first=Gareth A | last=Davies | accessdate=24 May 2010}}</ref> Broad finished his school career with three B grades at [[A-level]], and was given the choice of a place at [[Durham University]] or a contract with [[Leicestershire County Cricket Club]].<ref name=\"telegraph\"/>\n\n==Domestic career==\nBroad played his first game for Leicestershire 2nd XI in 2004 just before his 18th birthday and impressed enough to be given a full contract for the following season. Broad continued to impress Director of Cricket [[James Whitaker (cricketer)|James Whitaker]] and made his first-class debut early in the 2005 season against [[Durham University Centre of Cricketing Excellence]]. He returned credible figures of 1/40 from 15 overs. His maiden first-class wicket was that of Nick Lamb. Broad followed this appearance with his first County Championship appearance against [[Somerset County Cricket Club|Somerset]] at the familiar location of Oakham.\n\nIn the 2006 season Broad took his first 5 wicket haul against championship favourites Surrey and scored his first championship 50 against Derbyshire. His most eye-catching performances were in the [[Twenty20 Cup]], where his economy of 4.50 was the second-best of the season of bowlers with more than 15 overs bowled.<ref>[https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Events/ENG/Twenty20_Cup_2006/Bowling_by_Average.html Bowling in Twenty20 Cup 2006 (Ordered by Average)], from CricketArchive. Retrieved 26 August 2006</ref> In the County Championship Broad played twelve of Leicestershire's 13 matches until called up for England, and his 44 wickets at an average of 31.38 meant he led his county both in terms of wickets and bowling average.<ref>[https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Events/ENG/Liverpool_Victoria_County_Championship_2006/Leicestershire_Bowling.html Bowling for Leicestershire in Liverpool Victoria County Championship 2006], from Cricinfo. Retrieved 26 August 2006</ref> On 23 August 2007 it was announced that Broad would be leaving Leicestershire at the end of the season to join Nottinghamshire, after choosing not to renew his contract and to return to his home county.<ref>[http://content-aus.cricinfo.com/australia/content/current/story/307924.html Broad joins Nottinghamshire]. Content-aus.cricinfo.com. Retrieved 3 August 2011.</ref>\nIn the 2013 season, Broad played in the final of the [[Yorkshire Bank 40]] tournament. He was out for a duck and got three wickets in his last over wrapping up the game against Glamorgan.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://m.nottinghampost.com/articles/news/article/19828729 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2013-10-05 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20131005122737/http://m.nottinghampost.com/articles/news/article/19828729 |archivedate=5 October 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==International career==\n\n===Development===\nBroad played for the England Under-19 squad in 2005, facing the Sri Lankan U-19 squad, and took five for seventeen in the first \u2019Test\u2019 at Shenley. {{Citation needed|date=March 2014}} He was named in the ECB National Academy squad for the winter of 2005\u201306 and was then called up to the England \u2018A\u2019 squad touring the West Indies, as a replacement for [[James Anderson (cricketer)|James Anderson]], who had been drafted into the Test side touring India. In April 2006, Broad was again called up to the England A squad, facing the touring Sri Lankan team.\n\nBroad was also included in the ECB's 25-man development squad for the 2006 season. [[David Graveney]], the chairman of selectors, said, \"The squad essentially enables the England Head Coach ([[Duncan Fletcher]]), working with his support staff and the National Academy staff, to monitor more closely the development of international players and better prepare them for the demands of the international game.\" {{citation needed|date=February 2014}}\n\n===2006: Pakistan===\n[[File:Stuart Broad.jpg|thumbnail|left|Broad playing against Pakistan in the 3rd ODI at the Rose Bowl in 2006]]\n\nOn 23 August 2006, Broad was included in the England one-day squad for the [[one-day international]]s against Pakistan, and a couple of days later was named Young Cricketer of the Year by the Cricket Writers' Club.<ref>\"[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/cricket/5288076.stm Broad claims young player award]\", from BBC. Retrieved 26 August 2006.</ref> On 28 August, Broad made his first England appearance, in the [[Twenty20]] International against Pakistan. Broad bowled four overs for 35 runs, and took two wickets in two balls, [[Shoaib Malik]] and [[Younis Khan]], and narrowly missed out on a hat-trick, after a lofted shot from [[Shahid Afridi]] fell just short of [[Kevin Pietersen]].<ref>\"[http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/engvpak/content/story/258019.html Pakistan ease to five-wicket win]\", Cricinfo report.</ref> On 30 August, he made his ODI debut, taking a wicket in his first [[over (cricket)|over]], as well as being involved in a last-wicket [[partnership (cricket)|partnership]] of 29 with [[Darren Gough]]. In the third ODI on 5 September 2006, Broad once again found himself on a hat-trick with the wickets of [[Abdul Razzaq (Pakistani cricket player)|Abdul Razzaq]] and [[Kamran Akmal]], but again missed out on the third. He bowled ten overs and ended with figures of three for 57 with one maiden.\n\n===2007: West Indies and India===\nBroad was left out of the squad for the [[2006 ICC Champions Trophy]] and the [[2006-07 Commonwealth Bank Series]]. However, he was called up for the finals in the latter following injuries to [[Jon Lewis (cricketer, born 1975)|Jon Lewis]] and [[Chris Tremlett]].<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/england/6337425.stm England call up Broad for finals] from BBC. Retrieved 7 February 2007</ref> He was also called into England's squad as a replacement partway through the [[2007 Cricket World Cup|2007 World Cup]]. He finished the tournament by scoring the winning runs in England's final match against the West Indies.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/england/6527543.stm England's Lewis departs World Cup], ''bbc.co.uk'', 4 April 2007.</ref>\n\nBroad also featured in the ODI squad at the end of the West Indies tour of England in summer 2007, taking three for twenty in the first match to take England to a 1\u20130 lead in the ODI series.<ref>BBC News [http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/england/6256876.stm ''England v West Indies 1st ODI''] retrieved 1 July 2007</ref> In the second ODI he took 2\u201349 but England lost the match by 61 runs. Broad was expensive in the final match of the series, conceding 71 runs for no wickets.\n\nHe took his first wicket against India in the ODI against them in the second match at Bristol. On 30 August, he took career-best bowling figures of four for 51 as England bowled out India for 212 in the fourth match of the summer's ODI series. Broad also hit an unbeaten 45 to take his first ODI Man of the Match award. The definitive unbeaten partnership of 99 runs he shared with [[Ravi Bopara]] is a record eighth-wicket stand for England in ODIs.<ref>[http://stats.cricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/fow/highest_partnerships_by_wicket.html?class=2;id=1;type=team Record 8th wicket partnership] from Cricinfo. Retrieved 30 August 2007</ref> He bowled poorly in the next match, taking 1\u201384 as India won by 38 runs. He took 2\u201346 at the Oval but India narrowly won the match by 2 runs.\n\n===2007: T20 World Cup===\nBroad took 1\u201329 in the opening match of the 2007 world T20 against Zimbabwe. He followed this up by taking 0\u201323 against Australia as England lost by eight wickets. He took 3\u201337 against South Africa but England suffered another defeat, this time by 19 runs. He took 1\u201335 against New Zealand but could not prevent another defeat for England.\n\nOn 19 September 2007, Indian batsman [[Yuvraj Singh]] hit six sixes from one Broad over in a group match at [[Kingsmead Cricket Ground]] in [[Durban]], South Africa, during 2007's ICC World Twenty20.<ref>[http://www.rediff.com/cricket/2007/sep/19yuvraj.htm Yuvraj belts six sixes in an over]. Rediff.com (31 December 2004). Retrieved 3 August 2011.</ref> This was the fourth time the feat had been performed in senior cricket and the only time in Twenty20 cricket. The performance has never been repeated in any form of international cricket against a Test playing nation.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/cricket/7003537.stm India's Yuvraj smashes Broad for 6 sixes]. Commentators Ravi Shastri & David Lloyd, on ESPN Sky Sports TV, called the over the \"Full Monty\" by saying \u201cWell he has a license here to go for the Full Monty, 6 out of 6\". BBC News (19 September 2007). Retrieved 3 August 2011.</ref> The 36-runs from the Broad over helped Yuvraj Singh make the quickest 50 in international cricket, off just 12 balls. Referring to this rare occurrence as \"Yuvraj's magic moment\", Phil Long of BBC's Test Match Special blogged: \"Every so often you have to take off your England sunhat, sit back and enjoy a once-in-lifetime 'I was there' moment.\"<ref name=\":0\">[https://www.bbc.co.uk/blogs/tms/2007/09/hats_off_to_yuvrajs_magic_mome.shtml Hats off to Yuvraj's magic moment]. BBC Test match Special (20 September 2007). Retrieved 13 July 2013.</ref>\n\n===2007: Sri Lanka===\nBroad enjoyed a hugely successful ODI series in [[Sri Lanka]] in October 2007, taking eleven wickets in the series at an average of 19.27. He took figures of 2\u201354 in the first match and followed this up with 2\u201342 in the second match. In the third match of the series Broad made an unbeaten 20 with the bat and took another two wickets. In the final match of the series he took 3\u201336 and although England lost the match by over 100 runs, they won the series three-two to record its first ever ODI series win in Sri Lanka.<ref>[http://stats.cricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/averages/batting_bowling.html?id=3151;team=1;type=series Statistics \u2013 England in Sri Lanka 2007/08] from Cricinfo. Retrieved 14 October 2007.</ref> This resulted in Broad making his Test debut against Sri Lanka; in a high scoring game, he took a single wicket, conceding 95 runs in the process as the match ended in a draw.\n\n===2008: New Zealand===\nBroad went on to have an equally successful ODI series against [[New Zealand national cricket team|New Zealand]]. Although England fell to a three-one defeat, Broad was the leading wicket taker and held the highest batting average, 52, in the England team.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/england/averages/default.stm England vs. New Zealand \u2013 ODI series, 2008] [[BBC News]] retrieved 25 February 2008.</ref> During the tour of New Zealand in 2008, Broad, along with [[Alastair Cook]] and James Anderson, posed naked for the ''Cosmopolitan'' paper with just a cricket bat for cover.<ref>[http://thevillagecricketer.wordpress.com/2008/04/09/stuart-broad-james-anderson-and-alastair-cook-naked-for-charity-mate/ Stuart Broad, James Anderson and Alastair Cook naked \u2013 for charity mate \u00ab The Village Cricketer]. Thevillagecricketer.wordpress.com (9 April 2008). Retrieved 3 August 2011.</ref> England won the first Test against New Zealand by 121 runs, with Broad taking figures of 3\u201354 to help England win the game.\n\nIn the first Test against New Zealand on home soil, Broad took three wickets in the match. England won the second match by six wickets, although Broad picked up no wickets in the match. On 6 June 2008, Broad scored his maiden Test fifty, against New Zealand at Trent Bridge, making 64 before being bowled by [[Chris Martin (cricketer)|Chris Martin]]. In the first ODI against New Zealand Broad took 2\u201314, before taking another two wickets in the final match of the series, conceding fifty runs in the process.\n\n===2008: South Africa and India===\nHe made his second Test fifty in July 2008, in the Test series against [[South Africa national cricket team|South Africa]], scoring a new best of 76. In the Second Test at [[Headingley Cricket Ground|Headingley]], Broad contributed seventeen runs in the first innings, as England was bowled out on the first day for 203. In the second innings, with the match already lost, Broad top-scored with 67 in an innings that included some impressive drives through midwicket and cover, giving further evidence of his batsmanship.{{who said|reason=WP:OR|date=November 2016}} After this, his Test batting average briefly rose above 40. His performances with the bat at the time led pundits to suggest that he may become a genuine all rounder, with [[Geoffrey Boycott]] comparing him to [[Garfield Sobers]]: \"He's a wonderful player. There's a little bit of Sobers in him\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/england/7518708.stm |title=Boycott hails Broad performance |work=BBC Online |date=22 July 2008}} Retrieved on 22 July 2008.</ref> Broad was surprisingly dropped for the following Test at Edgbaston, making way for the returning Paul Collingwood. England captain Michael Vaughan said he was left out because of his bowling, but the decision has been criticised: Collingwood was no better a bowler than Broad, and Broad's batsmanship quite encouraging.{{citation needed|date=December 2010}} Broad duly took seven wickets for Nottinghamshire against Durham while the Test was being played.\n\nOn 26 August 2008, he recorded the first five-wicket haul in his international career with best figures of five for 23 against South Africa at his home ground in the second ODI of the series, with England winning the series 4\u20130 with Broad taking 8 wickets within the series at an average of 18.4 and shooting up to 4th in the ICC ODI world rankings, the highest in his career and the best by any English bowler since [[Andrew Flintoff]] in 2003.\n\nIn the second ODI against India Broad performed well, taking figures of 4\u201355. He took 1\u201336 in the next match as England lost by 18 runs. In the final match of the series he took 1\u201354, but England lost again, this time by six wickets. In the second Test against India, Broad was ineffectual with the ball. He took 1\u201384 in an India's first innings before taking 1\u201350 in India's second innings as the match ended in a draw.\n\n===2009: West Indies and T20 World Cup===\nOn 26 May 2009, Broad was named Man of the Series (one-day) [[West Indian cricket team in England in 2009|against the West Indies]] in England. He took a total of six wickets, and England won the series two-nil after the first ODI was rained out. In the adjacent Test series, in which the home side fairly routed its opponents, Broad's wickets came at an average of just eighteen&nbsp;\u2013 \"further evidence,\" reckoned journalist Nick Hoult, \"of the top class international cricketer that lurks within. His bowling, particularly the variety he has added to his game, makes him a potential Ashes star [...].\"<ref>Hoult, Nick. \"[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/cricket/international/theashes/5601764/Ashes-2009-England-squad-form-guide.html Ashes 2009: England squad form guide.]\" ''[[The Daily Telegraph|telegraph.co.uk]]''. 22 June 2009.. Retrieved 28 June 2009.</ref>\n\nOn 5 June 2009, [[Netherlands national cricket team|Netherlands]] defeated England by four wickets in the first match of the ICC World Twenty20.<ref>{{Cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/england/8085673.stm |work=BBC News  | title=England v Netherlands as it happened | date=5 June 2009 | accessdate=24 May 2010 | first=Mark | last=Mitchener}}</ref> The Netherlands needed seven to win from the final over with Broad bowling. He spurned two run-out opportunities from the first two balls, and dropped a catch off the third. The Dutch needed two runs from the final ball to win, and got them after Broad picked up the ball in his follow through and, attempting to win the match, overthrew, missing his third run-out opportunity of the over and allowing the batsmen to come back for the match-clinching second run.<ref>{{Cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/8082343.stm |work=BBC News  | title=Superb Netherlands shock England | date=5 June 2009 | accessdate=24 May 2010 | first=Oliver | last=Brett}}</ref> in the next match against Pakistan, he took 3\u201317 to help England win by 48 runs. England also beat India by 3 runs. Although Broad failed to take a wicket, he bowled his four overs for just 21 runs to help England secure a narrow victory. England lost their final game of the tournament against the West Indies, with Broad taking 1\u201320.\n\n===2009: Ashes series===\n[[File:Broad celebrating, 2009.jpg|thumbnail|left|Broad celebrates the wicket of [[Michael Hussey]] with [[Graeme Swann]] in the 3rd Test of the 2009 Ashes Series]]\n\nIn July 2009, Broad was named in [[The Ashes]] squad to face Australia for the first Test at the [[SWALEC Stadium]], Cardiff \u2013 his maiden Ashes Test. He scored a 22-ball 19 in England's first-innings total of 435, but in 32 overs he took just one wicket (that of [[Michael Clarke (cricketer)|Michael Clarke]], caught behind for 83) as Australia amassed 674 for 6 declared, with four centurions. Nonetheless, his final-day 14 proved crucial, keeping the Australians at bay alongside [[Paul Collingwood]] for a minute over an hour before [[James Anderson (cricketer)|James Anderson]] and [[Monty Panesar]] blocked out the final 11\u00bd overs to salvage an unlikely draw.<ref>[http://www.cricinfo.com/ci/engine/match/345970.html England v Australia at Cardiff, 2009]. Cricinfo.com. Retrieved 3 August 2011.</ref>\n\nThe second Test at [[Lord's]] saw Broad take three wickets, including the important wicket of Australian skipper [[Ricky Ponting]], bowled off an inside-edged cut for 38 as England pursued victory, and took a diving outfield catch to remove the opener [[Simon Katich]] in the first innings, as England took a 1\u20130 lead in the series.<ref>[http://www.cricinfo.com/ci/engine/match/345971.html England v Australia at Lord's, 2009]. Cricinfo.com. Retrieved 3 August 2011.</ref>\n\nThough he took no wickets in the first innings of the third Test at [[Edgbaston cricket ground|Edgbaston]], Broad hit a 64-ball 55 to extend England's first-innings lead to 114. On the final day, Broad took two of the three wickets to fall: [[Mike Hussey]] for 64 and, late in the day, [[Marcus North]] for 96. Nonetheless, Australia drew the match with ease.<ref>[http://www.cricinfo.com/ci/engine/match/345972.html England v Australia at Birmingham, 2009]. Cricinfo.com. Retrieved 3 August 2011.</ref>\n\nIn the fourth Test at [[Headingley Cricket Ground|Headingley]], Broad took his place in an England first-innings collapse, clipping [[Stuart Clark]] to square leg for 3 as Australia's seam attack bowled England out for 102. As Australia scored 445, Broad took six wickets for 91 in Australia's only innings, at that time his best first-class innings return, and in the second innings contributed a rapid 61 from 48 balls, though he could not avert an innings defeat.<ref>[http://www.cricinfo.com/ci/engine/match/345973.html England v Australia at Leeds, 2009]. Cricinfo.com. Retrieved 3 August 2011.</ref>\n\nEngland therefore started the fifth Test at [[the Oval]] with the series level at 1\u20131, with a victory required to secure the Ashes. He took 5 for 37 in the afternoon session of the second day, taking five of the first seven wickets to fall to take the Australian innings from 73/0 to 111/7 and eventually 160 all out. He also contributed 37 and 29 with the bat, and on the final day took the wicket of [[Shane Watson]] lbw for 40, the second wicket to fall in consecutive overs to start Australia's collapse, winning the Man of the Match award as England won by 197 runs to regain the 'Ashes' 2\u20131.<ref>[http://www.cricinfo.com/ci/engine/match/345974.html England v Australia at the Oval, 2009]. Cricinfo.com. Retrieved 3 August 2011.</ref>\n\nHe finished the tour with an aggregate of 234 runs and 18 wickets, leading England's bowling figures both in wickets taken and in bowling average (30.22). Though three Australian bowlers took more wickets, Broad was the only bowler from either side to claim two five-wicket innings hauls during the series.<ref>[http://stats.cricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/bowling/most_wickets_career.html?id=4249;type=series The Ashes, 2009: Most Wickets]. Stats.cricinfo.com. Retrieved 3 August 2011.</ref>\n\n===2009: ICC Champions Trophy===\nThis was a good tournament for Broad. He was the second highest wicket taker overall throughout the tournament with 10 wickets in 3 matches, only behind [[Wayne Parnell]] who took 11 in the same number of matches. In the first match of the tournament against Sri Lanka he took 3\u201349 in a winning effort. He followed it up with a 3\u201367 vs South Africa, putting England through to the semi finals. He then took 4\u201339 vs New Zealand in a losing effort after England had already been bowled out for 146, with New Zealand making the runs in just 27.1 overs. This was his last game in the tournament with Broad picking up an injury that kept him out of the semi finals, which England lost to Australia.\n\n===2009\u201310: South Africa===\nBroad's injuries continued through to the tour of South Africa, keeping him out of the two [[twenty20]] matches, which both ended up being abandoned. The weather affected the 1st One Day International which was probably an advantage for Broad and the England team with Broad being fit for the 3rd ODI, with England winning the second ODI by 7 wickets after Paul Collingwood and [[Jonathan Trott]] had a partnership of 162 with Collingwood getting 105.\n\nWhen Broad returned he instantly made an impact with numerous wickets but turned out to be very expensive. With his first game getting figures of 4\u201371, England suffered defeat by 112 runs. Broad improved on his economy rate in the 4th ODI with figures of 2\u201330 from 9.5 overs. This backed up James Anderson who took 5\u201323. The final game was rained off before a ball was bowled to leave England with a 2\u20131 victory and only the second team to win a one-day series vs South Africa in South Africa.\n\nBroad struggled in the First test in [[Centurion, Gauteng|Centurion]] with only taking 1\u201374 in the first innings and 2\u201354 in the second. His batting was unsuccessful, getting only 17 and a duck. The duck was during a dramatic collapse where England went from 205\u20134 to 218\u20139 with [[Graham Onions]] batting out the final over to save the test.\n\nIn the second test Broad showed good form with the ball with 2\u201344 in the first innings but then taking 4\u201343 in the second dismissing [[Jacques Kallis]], [[AB de Villiers]] and [[JP Duminy]] all within 3 overs. He took the wicket of [[Mark Boucher]] the next day to leave [[Graeme Swann]] to dismiss the rest of the South African line up. This gave England an innings and 98 run victory. After this test Broad went up to 7th in the ICC Test bowling rankings, the highest in his career. During this tour he declined to play in the [[Indian Premier League|IPL]] with James Anderson on the grounds he wanted to focus on his Test cricket first, and feared injury in the IPL.\n\n===2010: Bangladesh, T20 World Cup, Australia and Pakistan===\n[[File:Stuart Broad3.JPG|thumbnail|Broad with the Man of the Match award after the Test match against [[Pakistan]] at Lord's in 2010]]\n[[File:Stuart Broad secures his half-century.jpg|thumb|On 27 August 2010 Stuart Broad makes a half century]]\n\nAfter South Africa, England toured [[English cricket team in Bangladesh in 2009\u201310|Bangladesh]], playing three ODIs and two Test matches. Injuries to Anderson, Onions and Sidebottom meant that Broad was the leader of a relatively inexperienced pace attack. However, an injury before the Test series meant that he wasn't fully fit and was outbowled by [[Tim Bresnan]] and debutant [[Steven Finn (cricketer)|Steven Finn]].\n\nEngland then travelled to the West Indies for the [[2010 ICC World Twenty20]]. England won the tournament, beating Australia in the final. Broad won the man of the match award against Sri Lanka in the semi-final, and overall took 8 wickets at an average of 17.50.\n\nBack in England, Broad was rested for the [[Bangladeshi cricket team in England in 2010|home series against Bangladesh]] before returning to the side for a [[Australian cricket team in England in 2010|5-match ODI series against Australia]]. England won the first three games to take the series, with Broad named man of the match in the second game after bowling figures of 4\u201344. England lost the last two games, though Broad did achieve another four-wicket haul in the fifth game to finish the series with an average of 19.83. The ODIs against Bangladesh were less note-worthy \u2013 England won 2\u20131 with Broad taking 4 wickets.\n\nIn the [[Pakistani cricket team in England in 2010|home series against Pakistan]], Broad was involved in a disciplinary incident in the second Test. After Pakistani batsman [[Zulqarnain Haider]] defended a ball bowled by Broad down the pitch, Broad picked the ball up and threw it at Haider, striking him on the hand. Broad was fined 50% of his match fee.\n\nIn the final Test of the series, Broad reached his maiden Test century at Lord's. Coming to the crease at 102\u20137, he scored 169 and put on a 332-run partnership with fellow centurion Jonathan Trott; a [[List of Test cricket records#Partnership records|world record for an eight-wicket partnership]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theage.com.au/sport/cricket/trott-broad-in-worldrecord-partnership-20100828-13wxa.html|title=Trott, Broad in world-record partnership|first=|last=London|publisher=}}</ref> It was his first century in all forms of cricket since an under-19's match for [[Leicestershire County Cricket Club|Leicestershire]] and saw his name go on the Lord's batting honours board, a feat that his father never achieved. He also surpassed his father's Test best of 162, and they became the first father and son both to score centuries for England in Test match cricket. His efforts both with the bat and with the ball (he also took three wickets during the match and made a direct-hit run out) earned him the man of the match award.\n\n===2010\u201311: Ashes series===\n[[File:Board bowling against Sri Lanka at Lord's, 2011.jpg|thumb|left|Broad bowling against [[Sri Lanka]] at Lord's in June 2011]]\n\nBroad had an indifferent [[English cricket team in Australia in 2010-11|tour of Australia]], which was cut short due to injury. He started with a half-century in a warm-up game, and overall took 6 wickets over the two games against [[Western Australia cricket team|Western Australia]] and [[South Australia cricket team|South Australia]].<ref>{{Cite news| url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/the-ashes-2010-11/engine/match/446951.html | work=Cricinfo | title=Tour match: Western Australia v England XI at Perth, Nov 5\u20137, 2010 | date=7 November 2010}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news| url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/the-ashes-2010-11/engine/match/446952.html | work=Cricinfo | title=Tour match: South Australia v England XI at Adelaide, Nov 11\u201313, 2010 | date=13 November 2010}}</ref> In the first Test at [[the Gabba]], [[Brisbane]], he fell for a [[Duck (cricket)|golden duck]] in England's innings, the final victim of [[Peter Siddle|Peter Siddle's]] hat-trick. Wicketless in Australia's first innings, he had [[Simon Katich]] caught in the second as the Test was drawn.<ref>{{Cite news| url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/the-ashes-2010-11/engine/match/428749.html | work=Cricinfo | title=1st Test: Australia v England at Brisbane, Nov 25\u201329, 2010 | date=29 November 2010}}</ref> In the second Test at [[Adelaide Cricket Ground|Adelaide]], he finished Australia's first innings off with the wicket of [[Brad Haddin]], but a stomach muscle injury limited his participation in the second where England won by an innings.<ref>{{Cite news| url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/the-ashes-2010-11/engine/match/428750.html | work=Cricinfo | title=2nd Test: Australia v England at Adelaide, Dec 3\u20137, 2010 | date=7 December 2010}}</ref> That injury was revealed to be a muscle tear, and it ruled Broad out of the remaining three Tests and the one-day series that followed.<ref>{{Cite news| url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/the-ashes-2010-11/content/current/story/490728.html | work=Cricinfo | title=Injured Broad out of tour | date=7 December 2010}}</ref> He was not missed for the rest of the Test series but he was for the [[One Day Internationals|ODIs]] because England were plagued by injuries throughout the 6\u20131 series defeat.\n\n===2011: India===\nAfter a difficult series against Sri Lanka<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/cricket/international/england/8616780/England-v-Sri-Lanka-Enforcer-Stuart-Broad-must-focus-fury-again.html | location=London | work=The Daily Telegraph | first=Derek | last=Pringle | title=England v Sri Lanka: 'Enforcer' Stuart Broad must focus fury again | date=5 July 2011}}</ref> there was much pressure on the England selectors to drop him for the [[Indian cricket team in England in 2011|upcoming series against India]].<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/sport/blog/2011/jul/05/stuart-broad-england-vic-marks Dropping Stuart Broad would do him and England a favour | Vic Marks | Sport]. ''The Guardian''. Retrieved 3 August 2011.</ref>  However, Broad was named in the side for the first Test at Lord's and ended with match figures of 7\u201394, as well as scoring an unbeaten 74 in the second innings, as England won by 196 runs.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport/hi/english/static/cricket/statistics/scorecards/2011/07/86081/html/scorecard.stm Cricket Scorecard]. BBC News (21 July 2011). Retrieved 3 August 2011.</ref> His good form with both bat and ball continued in the second test. Top scoring with an aggressive 64 in the first innings, he helped England recover from 124\u20138 to 221 all out before achieving his career best figures of 6\u201346 in India's first innings. This included a [[hat-trick (cricket)|hat-trick]], taking the wickets of [[Mahendra Singh Dhoni]], [[Harbhajan Singh]] and [[Praveen Kumar]]. Broad took five wickets from his final 16 balls of the innings, without conceding a single run.<ref>[http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/cricket/article-2020522/Hat-trick-hero-Broad-revives-England-Test-best-figures-Dravid-ton.html?ito=feeds-newsxml Hat-trick hero Broad revives England with Test best figures after another Dravid ton]. ''The Daily Mail'' (UK). (30 July 2011). Retrieved 3 August 2011.</ref> With a positive second innings contribution with both bat and ball (44 runs with the bat and then two wickets, including the final wicket of the match) Broad was named Man of the Match.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/cricket/14365256.stm BBC Sport \u2013 England thrash India at Trent Bridge to lead series 2\u20130]. BBC News. Retrieved 3 August 2011.</ref> In the Third Test at Edgbaston, Broad took four wickets along with Tim Bresnan to bowl India out cheaply. In England's innings he was not needed as Alistair Cook scored 294 to pass 700. Broad took two wickets in the second innings to beat India and for England to become World number 1 in Test Cricket. Broad made a lesser impact in the fourth Test with him taking two wickets in both India's innings and he did not bat due to an early declaration.\n\n===2011\u201312: Pakistan and Sri Lanka===\nIn the first Test against Pakistan Broad took 3\u201384 in the first innings. However, England suffered a ten wicket defeat as the batsmen struggled to acclimatise to sub continent conditions. Broad took 4\u201347 in the next match as well as an unbeaten fifty in England's 1st innings (he'd only score 1 test fifty in 5 years after scoring this 50) but another batting collapse saw England lose the match again (bowled out for 72 chasing 145) to go 2\u20130 down in the three match series. In the final match Broad took 4\u201336 in the first innings to help bowl out Pakistan for 99. However, Pakistan made over 300 in their second innings to build up a lead. England were unable to chase down their target and went on to lose the series 3\u20130. England lost their fourth straight match, this time against Sri Lanka as the batsmen continued to struggle. Broad took just two wickets in the match, although he made 33 runs with the bat in the match, and was not out in the second innings.\n\n===2012: West Indies and South Africa===\nBroad started off his summer with his best international innings yet, of 7\u201372, against the West Indies, at [[Lord's]], the first test match of the series, was started with a bang as he was able to get a [[five wicket haul]] at the home of cricket, Lord's, becoming only the 8th player to join an elite club of all-rounders to be on [[Lord's Honours Boards|both honours boards]], after his maiden test century of 169 against Pakistan in 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/content/story/565271.html|title=Broad achieves honours board double|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nHe soon followed this up by taking 4 more wickets in the next innings, missing a possible hat trick however, to get Test best figures of 11 for 165, being the first to take a 10 wicket haul at Lord's since [[Ian Botham]] in 1978. He had to wait until after Lunch on the 4th day to take the last 3 wickets he needed for the haul. He was named Man of the Match the next day after England won by 5 wickets, in a chase of 191.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://metro.co.uk/2012/05/20/stuart-broads-historic-test-feat-eclipsed-by-west-indies-fightback-432337/|title=Stuart Broad's historic Test feat eclipsed by West Indies fightback|first=|last=metrowebukmetro|date=20 May 2012|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nBroad followed the performance by taking four wickets in the second test. which England also won. He was rested for the last Test match against the West Indies along with James Anderson. However the game was heavily disrupted by rain and the game ended as a draw. England won the following One Day series 2\u20130 with the third game being abandoned because of rain. On Broad's 26th birthday, he captained the team to a comfortable victory with Notts teammate Alex Hales scoring 99. He was then named in the squad to play Australia in a five match ODI series. Broad's bowling was overshadowed by Steven Finn who took 11 wickets in four games compared to Broad's 5.\n\nBroad was picked in the first Test against South Africa but failed to take a wicket. He added 16 with the bat in England's first innings of 386. Broad and the England bowlers struggled in South Africa's innings of 637\u20132 with [[Hashim Amla]] scoring a triple century (the first South African to do so) with Jacques Kallis and [[Graeme Smith]] also scoring centuries. In the second innings Broad was out for a duck as England lost by an innings and 12 runs. In the second Test, South Africa scored 419 in the first innings with Broad taking 3\u201396. He then scored 1 run in England's innings of 425. Broad then had a burst of wickets on the last day with the wickets of AB de Villiers and JP Duminy in successive deliveries. He finished with figures of 5\u201369 as England couldn't reach the target and the game ended in a draw. In the following Test, Broad was pushed up the order to number 8 after Tim Bresnan was left out. Broad only managed one wicket in South Africa's first innings of 309. He then added 16 in England's first innings of 315. Broad, who had been down on pace all summer struggled as he took 2\u201376 as South Africa set England 346 to win. England lost by 51 runs, Broad adding 37 runs.\n\n===2013: New Zealand ===\n[[File:Broad bowling, 2013.jpg|thumbnail|Broad comes in to bowl during the England v Australia game of the 2013 ICC Champions Trophy at Edgbaston.]]\n\nOn the fifth day of the [[English cricket team in New Zealand in 2012\u201313|3rd Test against New Zealand]], Broad set a new record for the longest time spent at the crease without scoring a run, with 103 minutes out in the middle, facing 62 balls.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.guinnessworldrecords.com/world-records/longest-test-match-innings-without-scoring-a-run-(male) |title=Longest time taken to score a run |accessdate=19 May 2013|work=Guinness World Records}}</ref> The previous record was 101 minutes set by New Zealander [[Geoff Allott]] against South Africa in 1999.<ref name=\"BBCSport5thTest\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/cricket/21934581 |title=New Zealand v England: Matt Prior earns series draw in Auckland |accessdate=26 March 2013|work=BBC Sport}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/match/569245.html |title=England v New Zealand scorecard |accessdate=19 May 2013|work=cricinfo}}</ref>\n\nOn the 19 May, in the First Test against New Zealand at Lord's, Broad took career best figures of 7/44 in the second innings of the match. In England's second innings, he also contributed 26 runs to their total of 213.<ref name=\"BBCSport-EngNZ\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/cricket/22587365 |title=England v New Zealand: Stuart Broad hurries hosts to Lord's win |accessdate=19 May 2013|work=BBC Sport}}</ref>\n\n===2013: Ashes series===\nIn the first test of the [[2013 Ashes]] held at [[Trent Bridge]], Broad controversially stood his ground after being incorrectly given not out when edging an [[Ashton Agar]] delivery which deflected off wicket keeper Brad Haddin's gloves and was caught by [[Australia national cricket team|Australia]] captainMichael Clarke at first slip; the [[Umpire Decision Review System]] was in use during the series, but Australia had used all of its challenges when the incident occurred. Although neither the rules nor common practice required Broad to [[Glossary of cricket terms#W|walk]], he drew heavy criticism from many observers who thought his edge was too thick to have reasonably stood his ground.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.smh.com.au/sport/cricket/crickets-ethics-demanded-that-stuart-broad-walk-20130713-2pwe8.html|title=Cricket's ethics demanded that Stuart Broad walk|date=13 July 2013|accessdate=13 August 2013|work=Sydney Morning Herald}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/cricket/international/theashes/10177287/Stuart-Broads-sadly-predictable-Ashes-decision-not-to-walk-leaves-Adam-Gilchrist-as-a-moral-man-apart.html|title=Stuart Broad's sadly predictable Ashes decision not to walk leaves Adam Gilchrist as a moral man apart|date=12 July 2013|accessdate=13 August 2013|work=The Telegraph}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/sport/cricket/ashes-2013-stuart-broad-refusing-2048967|title=Oliver Holt on Stuart Broad: What he did wasn\u2019t just disappointing. It was deeply, deeply embarrassing|date=12 July 2013|accessdate=13 August 2013|work=The Mirror}}</ref> Broad was on 37 at the time of the incident<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/cricket/23277348|title=Ashes 2013: England v Australia, first Test, day three as it happened|date=12 July 2013|accessdate=13 August 2013|work=BBC|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130715201023/http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/cricket/23277348|archivedate=15 July 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref> and went to make 65, sharing a partnership of 138 with [[Ian Bell]].<ref name=engaussc>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/cricket/scorecard/87719|title=England v Australia Scorecard|date=14 August 2013|work=BBC|access-date=11 February 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140509032853/http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/cricket/scorecard/87719|archive-date=9 May 2014|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> England went on to win the match by 14 runs with Broad taking the wickets of [[Shane Watson]] and Clarke in Australia's second innings.<ref name=engaussc/> Australia coach [[Darren Lehmann]] was later fined 20% of his match fee for calling Broad a cheat on Australian radio, and in doing so inciting Australian crowds to boo Broad in future English tours of Australia.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/0/cricket/23805302|title=Ashes 2013: Darren Lehmann fined for Stuart Broad criticism|date=23 August 2013|accessdate=29 January 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn 2 August 2013, Broad took his 200th test wicket, bowling Clarke in the first innings of the drawn third Ashes test at [[Old Trafford (cricket ground)|Old Trafford]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/cricket/article-2383671/Ashes-2013-Stuart-Broad-claims-200th-Test-wicket-England-bowling-Australia-captain-Michael-Clarke-Old-Trafford.html|title=The Best of Broad: Bowler becomes 15th Englishman to claim 200 Test wickets with dismissal of Aussie centurion Clarke|date=2 August 2013|accessdate=13 August 2013|work=Daily Mail}}</ref>\n\nIn the fourth test, at the [[Riverside Ground]] in [[Chester-le-Street]], Broad took eleven wickets with [[List of international cricket five-wicket hauls at the Riverside Ground|two five-wicket hauls]] and was named [[man of the match]] as England ensured a series win.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www1.skysports.com/cricket/news/article/8867950/broad-an-amazing-feeling|title=Ashes: England hero Stuart Broad says it feels 'amazing' to win the series |date=12 August 2013|work=BSkyB}}</ref> In the first innings, he took 5\u201371, including a spell of 3\u201312 in the morning session of day 2 where he removed [[David Warner (cricketer)|David Warner]], [[Usman Khawaja]] and Clarke to reduce Australia to 49\u20133.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/cricket/23642354|title=The Ashes: England v Australia, fourth Test, day two as it happened|date=10 August 2013|accessdate=13 August 2013|work=BBC|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130813143227/http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/cricket/23642354|archivedate=13 August 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/cricket/international/theashes/10235391/Ashes-2013-England-bowler-Stuart-Broad-walks-tall-again-with-peak-performance-against-Australia-at-Durham.html|title=\nAshes 2013: England bowler Stuart Broad walks tall again with peak performance against Australia at Durham|date=10 August 2013|accessdate=13 August 2013|work=The Telegraph}}</ref> In their second innings, chasing 299 to win, Australia had made 174\u20133 when Broad took the wicket Clarke for the fifth time in the series with the first delivery after a drinks break. In this spell he took 6\u201320 from 45 balls,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.smh.com.au/sport/cricket/cook-lauds-broad-as-aussies-swept-aside-in-fourth-test-20130813-2rt6f.html|title=Cook lauds Broad as Aussies swept aside in fourth Test|date=13 August 2013|work=Sydney Morning Herald}}</ref> including the final Australian wicket, to bowl Australia out for 224 and win the match by 74 runs.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/cricket/scorecard/87722|title=England v Australia Scorecard|date=12 August 2013|work=BBC|access-date=11 February 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140310194153/http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/cricket/scorecard/87722|archive-date=10 March 2014|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Broad ended the match with his best test bowling match figures of 11\u2013121.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/cricket/international/theashes/10238888/Ashes-2013-Stuart-Broad-Englands-big-game-hunter-causes-real-damage-to-Australian-herd.html|title=Ashes 2013: Stuart Broad, England's big game hunter, causes real damage to Australian herd|date=12 August 2013|work=The Telegraph}}</ref>\n\n===2013\u201314: Ashes series===\nBroad was England's leading wicket taker in the first test of the [[2013\u201314 Ashes series]] at the Gabba in Brisbane, taking 6\u201381 in the first innings and ending with match figures of 8\u2013136, in the match that England lost in four days by 381 runs.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/cricket/scorecard/87887|title=Australia v England Scorecard|accessdate=25 November 2013|work=BBC|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131124143616/http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/cricket/scorecard/87887|archive-date=24 November 2013|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In the second test Broad took 3\u201398 in Australia's first innings, but as England struggled he only bowled six overs in the second innings as Australia romped to victory. Broad took 3\u2013100 in the third test but was then injured by a delivery from Mitchell Johnson, which dismissed him for just 5. The injury which Broad obtained prevented him from bowling in the second innings, as England went on to lose the game and the series. Broad was declared fit for the fourth test and took 3\u201345 in the Australian first innings, but struggled in the second, bowling 10 wicketless overs for 58 runs. In the final test, Broad batted well, making an unbeaten 30 in the first innings and then 42 in the second. England went on to lose the game and the series 5\u20130, leading to the England team being heavily criticised. Despite this, Broad was one of the few members of the team to come out of the series with any credibility.\n\n===2014: West Indies and T20 World Cup===\nBroad continued as captain for the tour of the West Indies. This included three ODI games and three 20/20 games. In the ODI series England won 2\u20131 with Broad bringing England home in the 2nd game with a knock of 28 not out. In the third game he took 2\u201358 as England won by 25 runs. He only played in the first T20 game as England lost by 27 runs, with Broad taking figures of 0\u201326.\n\nBroad was named captain of the England cricket team for the [[2014 ICC World Twenty20]] in [[Bangladesh]]. Broad did not take a wicket in the first two games as England lost to New Zealand and beat Sri Lanka. In the third game against South Africa, Broad took 1\u201333 but England lost the match to end their hopes of qualifying. He took 3\u201324 against the Netherlands, but he was unable to prevent an embarrassing defeat for England.\n\n===2014: Sri Lanka and India===\nIn the first Test Test Broad could only manage one wicket in Sri Lanka's first innings, although he took three in Sri Lanka's second innings as England came close to winning the match. In the second test against Sri Lanka at Headingley Broad became only the fourth player, and first Englishman to take two test hat-tricks, although he needed to be informed of this by the PA system as he was unaware. England went on to lose the game after James Anderson was dismissed in the penultimate ball of the match, meaning England lost the series 1\u20130.\n\nBroad bowled well on a good batting pitch in the first game of the series against India, taking four wickets in the match. However, in the second game he was accused of bowling badly in the first innings as India won the match to go 1\u20130 up in the series. Broad's form improved in the next game, as he took 3\u201366 in the first innings to help England win the game and level the series. He took figures of 6\u201325 in India's first innings of the next game to help dismiss them for 152. Broad was badly injured while batting and was later revealed he had broken his nose. Broad was later named man of the match. Despite being an injury doubt, he took part in the final test, taking 3 wickets in the match and scoring 37 to help England secure a 3\u20131 series win.\n\n===2015: Tri-Series===\nFollowing an injury which had kept him out of the one-day tour of Sri Lanka, Broad returned for the Tri-Series against Australia and India. In the first match of the series he was wicket less as England lost to Australia. In the next match against India, Broad finished with figures of 0\u201333.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://m.cricbuzz.com/cricket-scorecard/13846/aus-vs-eng-1st-match-india-and-england-in-australia-tri-series-2015/1|title=Aus vs Eng \u2013 Scorecard \u2013 Cricbuzz|publisher=}}</ref> His worst performance of the series came in the following match against Australia, where he finished with figures of 0\u201361.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/carlton-mid-triangular-series-2015/content/story/823143.html|title=Smith ton leads Australia to final|publisher=}}</ref> However, he played well in the must win game against India, taking figures of 2\u201356 to help England qualify for the final.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/carlton-mid-triangular-series-2015/content/story/825193.html|title=England through to final, India winless on tour|publisher=}}</ref> In the final match against Australia he took figures of 3\u201355 and made 24 with the bat, but it was not enough to prevent an England defeat as they went on to finish the tournament as runners-up.\n\n===2015: World Cup===\nBroad took figures of 2\u201366 in England's opening game loss to Australia. In the following game against New Zealand, he was unimpressive as England suffered a humiliating eight wicket defeat. He failed to take a wicket against Scotland as England won their first match of the tournament, and also finished wicket less as England suffered a nine wicket defeat against Sri Lanka, meaning he had failed to take a wicket in his past three matches. He finished with 1\u201352 in England's must win game against Bangladesh, but was dismissed for 9 as England lost the game to bow out of the tournament at the group stage. He finished with figures of 1\u201318 against Afghanistan in a rain affected as England won their final match of the tournament by nine wickets.\n\n===2015: West Indies and New Zealand===\nThe first match against the West Indies, Broad took 2\u201367 in their first innings to help restrict them to 295. However, in the second innings he could only manage to take one wicket as the West Indies held on for a draw. In the second Test ok 4\u201361 in West Indies first innings to help out England in a strong position. He took another wicket in the second innings as England forced a result to go 1\u20130 up in the series. In the first Test Broad took 1\u201331 in West Indies first innings to help England into a lead. However, England collapsed in their second innings and Broad himself was out for a duck. He took 1\u201329 in the West Indies second innings but it wasn't enough to prevent a five wicket defeat as the West Indies levelled the series at 1\u20131.\n\nIn the two match series against New Zealand, Broad took 3\u201377 in New Zealand's first innings. With New Zealand chasing a big score to win the match, Broad took 3\u201350 in New Zealand's second innings to help England win by 124 runs and go 1\u20130 up in the series. Broad took 5\u2013109 in New Zealand's first innings of the next Test, although he went at an economy rate of over six an over. He made 46 with the bat to help England level the scores after the first innings. He took 2\u201394 in the second innings but was again expensive, and New Zealand went on to win the match and tie the series 1\u20131.\n\n===2015: Ashes series===\nIn Australia's first innings of the first Test, Broad took figures of 2\u201360 and followed this up by taking 3\u201339 in their second innings as England won the match to take the lead in the series. Broad took 4\u201383 in Australia's first innings of the second Test but they built a large first innings score of 566. Broad did not take a wicket in the Australians second innings as they won by 405 runs. In the third Test Broad took 2\u201344 in Australia's first innings and also took a wicket in their second as England won the game to regain the lead. In the fourth Test Broad took career best figures of 8\u201315 in the Australian first innings as they were dismissed for just 60. England went on to win the match convincingly and regain the Ashes. In the final Test Broad did not take a wicket as Australia won by an innings and 48 runs, although England won the series 3\u20132.\n\n===2015: Pakistan===\n\nBroad played in the first Test against Pakistan, which was played in the UAE. While Broad only took one wicket in the match, he bowled economically, including bowling eight overs for just eight runs in the second innings. England came to close to forcing a result, but the match ended in a draw. In the second Test Broad again only managed to take one wicket as Pakistan enjoyed a convincing win to go 1\u20130 up in the three-match series. In the third Test, Broad continued to bowl economically, taking figures of 2\u201313 from 13 overs in Pakistan's first innings, as they were dismissed for 234. In the second innings, he took 3\u201344 but England struggled in their second innings and Pakistan went on to win the game to win the series 2\u20130.\n\n===2015\u201316: South Africa===\nIn the first test in South Africa, Broad took figures of 4\u201325 and 1\u201329 and hit an unbeaten 32 from just 33 balls as England won by 241 runs. The second game ended in a high scoring draw, with Broad taking 2\u201394 in South Africa's first innings. In the third Test, Broad took 2\u201382 in South Africa's first innings in a game which looked to be finely poised. However, in South Africa's second innings, he ripped through their top order, finishing with figures of 6\u201317. Included in his six wickets were the prized wickets of AB de Villiers and Hashim Amla. England went on to win the game by seven wickets, with the result giving them an unassailable 2\u20130 series lead. England performed poorly in the final game, with Broad taking three wickets in the match as South Africa secured a victory by a margin of 280 runs, meaning the series finished 2\u20131 to England. As a result of his performances, Broad became the number one ranked Test bowler in the world.\n\nAfter not playing for England in limited overs cricket since their poor showing at the 2015 World Cup, Broad was included in the squad for the ODI series against South Africa. He played in the fourth ODI, although he returned expensive figures, finishing up with 1\u201355 in seven overs, as England lost the game. He was selected in the side for the final game, which proved to be the decider, and although he bowled economically, he did not pick up a wicket and England went on to lose the game and the series 3\u20132.\n\n===2016: Sri Lanka and Pakistan===\nBroad took figures of 4\u201321 in Sri Lanka's first innings of the first Test as they were dismissed for just 91. In the second innings he took 1\u201357 as England won by an innings and 88 runs. In the second match, Broad took 4\u201340 in Sri Lanka's first innings, but was less effective in their second, finishing with just one wicket, as England won the match by nine wickets. In the final rain affected match of the series, Broad took 2\u201379 as Sri Lanka were dismissed for 288, but the match ended in a draw due to the bad weather.\n\nBroad took figures of 3\u201371 in Pakistan's first innings of the first Test, and took 3\u201338 in their second innings, although Pakistan did enough to secure a 75 run victory. In the second Test Broad took 1\u201320 in Pakistan's first innings as they were dismissed for 198 and England secured a 330 run victory. In the third Test, Broad took 3\u201383 in Pakistan's first innings as they reached 400, and then took 2\u201324 in their second innings to help England secure an unlikely victory after dismissing them for 201. In the final match of the series, Broad was less effective, taking just one wicket in the match, as England lost by 10 wickets.\n\n===2016: Bangladesh and India===\nIn the first innings of the first Test against Bangladesh, Broad did not take a wicket in the first innings, although he bowled economically. In the second innings he took figures of 2\u201331 to help England win by 21 runs. He was rested for the second Test, which England lost\n\nBroad played in the first Test against India, taking figures of 1\u201378 in the first innings, before taking 0\u20138 in the second innings as the match ended in a draw. In the second Test he took 1\u201349 as India made 455 in their first innings. He took 4\u201333 in the second innings to restrict India to 204 runs, although India won the match by 246 runs. Broad missed the next two Tests through injury, but returned in the fifth Test. He took figures of 2\u201380 as India scored 759/7 and went on to win the match by 75 runs to win the series 4\u20130.\n\n===2018: New Zealand===\nOn 22 March 2018, In the first Test [[English cricket team in New Zealand in 2017\u201318|against New Zealand]], Broad took his [[List of bowlers who have taken 300 or more wickets in Test cricket|400th wicket in Tests]] and became the youngest fast bowler to do so.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.skysports.com/cricket/news/12173/11299662/stuart-broad-takes-his-400th-test-wicket-on-day-one-of-auckland-test |title=Stuart Broad takes his 400th Test wicket on day one of Auckland Test |accessdate=22 March 2018 |publisher=Sky Sports}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/story/_/id/22866057/stats-stuart-broad-youngest-fast-bowler-400-test-wickets|title=Stuart Broad marches on to become the youngest fast bowler to race for 400 test wickets milestone|publisher=ESPN Cricinfo|access-date=24 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n===2019: Ashes series===\nIn the first Test of the [[2019 Ashes series]], Broad took his 100th wicket in The Ashes in the first innings of the match.<ref>{{cite web |title=Stats: Steve Smith\u2019s record ton on Test comeback inspires Australia to a commanding total|url=https://www.crictracker.com/stats-steve-smiths-record-ton-on-test-comeback-inspires-australia-to-a-commanding-total/ |website=Crictracker |accessdate=2 August 2019 |date=2 August 2019}}</ref> In the second innings of the match, he took his 450th wicket in Test cricket, dismissing [[David Warner (cricketer)|David Warner]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.skysports.com/watch/video/sports/cricket/11776606/broad-gets-warner-again |title=Broad makes Warner 450th Test wicket |work=Sky Sports |accessdate=3 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Achievements and honours==\n\n* On 17 September 2015, [[Nottingham Express Transit|NET]] tram 237 was named in honour of Broad.<ref>[http://www.thetram.net/tram-to-be-named-after-nottinghamshire-and-england-cricket-hero.aspx Tram Named After Cricket Hero] Retrieved 14 June 2016</ref>\n\n* [[File:Order of the British Empire (Civil) Ribbon.png|60px]] He was appointed a [[Member of the Order of the British Empire]] (MBE) in the 2016 Birthday Honours for services to cricket.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=61608 |supp=y|page=B16|date=11 June 2016}}</ref>\n\n* At the conclusion of the 5th Test in [[Indian national cricket team|India's]] [[Indian cricket team in England in 2018|tour of the United Kingdom in 2018]], Broad and Anderson had tallied up 850 test wickets playing together across 111 tests, third all-time on the list of bowling pairs in tests, behind only [[Glenn McGrath]] and [[Shane Warne]] (1,001 wickets in 104 tests together) and [[Chaminda Vaas]] and [[Muttiah Muralitharan]] (895 wickets in 95 tests together).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.skysports.com/cricket/news/13294/10997690/crickets-deadly-bowling-duos-where-do-james-anderson-and-stuart-broad-rank|title=Cricket's deadly bowling duos: Where do James Anderson and Stuart Broad rank?|website=Sky Sports|language=en|access-date=2019-11-28}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nStuart Broad's father, [[Chris Broad]], played Test Cricket for England in 1980s. His sister Gemma works for the England team as a team analyst.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/sport/cricket/article2848462.ece|title=Like father, like son for Broads|work=The Times|date=11 November 2007|accessdate=21 August 2009 | location=London | first=Simon | last=Wilde}}</ref> He supports [[Nottingham Forest F.C.]] and [[Leicester Tigers]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aqa.63336.com/celebrityanswers/ca_stuartbroad.htm|title=AQA 63336 LIVE celebrity answers \u2013 Stuart Broad|publisher=aqa.63336.com|accessdate=1 October 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090918170926/http://www.aqa.63336.com/celebrityanswers/ca_stuartbroad.htm|archivedate=18 September 2009|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Stuart's stepmother Michelle \"Miche\" Broad took her own life in July 2010. She was suffering with [[motor neurone disease]].<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-nottinghamshire-11313359 Death of Stuart Broad's Mother].</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Stuart Broad}}\n*{{Cricinfo|id=10617}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070320071228/http://www.cricket-online.org/player.php?player_id=59495 Cricket Online Profile]\n*[http://www.nottsccc.co.uk/cricket/players/2010/stuart-broad.html Nottinghamshire County Cricket Club Profile]\n\n{{England ODI cricket captains}}\n{{England T20I cricket captains}}\n{{Bowlers who have taken 300 or more wickets in Test cricket}}\n{{Englishmen with 100 or more Test caps}}\n{{Navboxes colour\n|title= England squads \n|bg= skyblue\n|fg= #15295E\n|bordercolor=#15295E\n|list1=\n{{England Squad 2007 Cricket World Cup}}\n{{England Squad 2010 ICC World Twenty20}}\n{{England Squad 2011 Cricket World Cup}}\n{{England Squad 2015 Cricket World Cup}}\n}}\n{{Nottinghamshire County Cricket Club squad}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2015}}\n{{Use British English|date=August 2011}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Broad, Stuart}}\n[[Category:Articles with inconsistent citation formats]]\n[[Category:England Test cricketers]]\n[[Category:England One Day International cricketers]]\n[[Category:England Twenty20 International cricketers]]\n[[Category:English cricketers of the 21st century]]\n[[Category:Leicestershire cricketers]]\n[[Category:People educated at Oakham School]]\n[[Category:People from Melton Mowbray]]\n[[Category:1986 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Nottinghamshire cricketers]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Nottingham]]\n[[Category:English cricketers]]\n[[Category:Wisden Cricketers of the Year]]\n[[Category:Cricketers at the 2007 Cricket World Cup]]\n[[Category:Cricketers at the 2011 Cricket World Cup]]\n[[Category:Cricketers at the 2015 Cricket World Cup]]\n[[Category:Test cricket hat-trick takers]]\n[[Category:English cricket captains]]\n[[Category:Kings XI Punjab cricketers]]\n[[Category:Members of the Order of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:Hobart Hurricanes cricketers]]\n[[Category:Marylebone Cricket Club cricketers]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|English cricketer}}\n{{Infobox cricketer\n| honorific_suffix = {{post-nominals|country=GBR|size=100%|MBE}}\n| name = Stuart Broad\n| image = Stuart broad.jpg\n| country = England\n| fullname = Stuart Christopher John Broad\n| nickname = Broady, Malfoy<ref name=\"Stuart Broad\"/><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.nottinghampost.com/Don-t-Malfoy-says-Broad-s-just-quidditch/story-25716505-detail/story.html |title=Stuart Broad |newspaper=Nottingham Post |accessdate=7 August 2014 }}{{Dead link|date=June 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=no }}</ref>\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1986|6|24|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Nottingham]], England\n| height = 6 ft 5 in\n| batting = Left-handed\n| bowling = Right-arm [[Fast bowling|fast-medium]]\n| role = [[Bowling (cricket)|Bowler]]\n| family = [[Chris Broad|BC Broad]] (father)\n| international = true\n| internationalspan = 2006\u2013present\n| testcap = 638\n| testdebutdate = 9 December\n| testdebutyear = 2007\n| testdebutagainst = Sri Lanka\n| lasttestdate = 24 January\n| lasttestyear = 2020\n| lasttestagainst = South Africa\n| odicap = 197\n| odidebutdate = 30 August\n| odidebutyear = 2006\n| odidebutagainst = Pakistan\n| lastodidate = 14 February\n| lastodiyear = 2016\n| lastodiagainst = South Africa\n| T20Icap = 18\n| T20Idebutdate = 28 August\n| T20Idebutyear = 2006\n| T20Idebutagainst = Pakistan\n| lastT20Idate = 31 March\n| lastT20Iyear = 2014\n| lastT20Iagainst = Netherlands\n| club1 = [[Leicestershire County Cricket Club|Leicestershire]]\n| year1 = 2005\u201307\n| club2 = [[Nottinghamshire County Cricket Club|Nottinghamshire]]\n| year2 = 2008\u2013present\n| clubnumber2 = 8\n| club4 = [[Hobart Hurricanes]]\n| year4 = 2016/17\n| clubnumber4 = 8 \n| columns = 4\n| column1 = [[Test cricket|Test]]\n| matches1 = 138\n| runs1 = 3,211\n| bat avg1 = 18.66\n| 100s/50s1 = 1/12\n| top score1 = 169\n| deliveries1 = 28,079\n| wickets1 = 485\n| bowl avg1 = 28.50\n| fivefor1 = 17\n| tenfor1 = 2\n| best bowling1 = 8/15\n| catches/stumpings1 = 46/\u2013\n| column2 = [[One Day International|ODI]]\n| matches2 = 121\n| runs2 = 529\n| bat avg2 = 12.30\n| 100s/50s2 = 0/0\n| top score2 = 45[[not out|*]]\n| deliveries2 = 6,109\n| wickets2 = 178\n| bowl avg2 = 30.13\n| fivefor2 = 1\n| tenfor2 = 0\n| best bowling2 = 5/23\n| catches/stumpings2 = 27/\u2013\n| column3 = [[Twenty 20 International|T20I]]\n| matches3 = 56\n| runs3 = 118\n| bat avg3 = 7.37\n| 100s/50s3 = 0/0\n| top score3 = 18[[not out|*]]\n| deliveries3 = 1173\n| wickets3 = 65\n| bowl avg3 = 22.93\n| fivefor3 = 0\n| tenfor3 = 0\n| best bowling3 = 4/24\n| catches/stumpings3 = 21/\u2013\n| column4 = [[First class cricket|FC]]\n| matches4 = 223\n| runs4 = 5,181\n| bat avg4 = 19.62\n| 100s/50s4 = 1/24\n| top score4 = 169\n| deliveries4 = 42,106\n| wickets4 = 779\n| bowl avg4 = 27.49\n| fivefor4 = 29\n| tenfor4 = 3\n| best bowling4 = 8/15\n| catches/stumpings4 = 82/\u2013\n| date = 28 January\n| year = 2020\n| source = http://www.espncricinfo.com/england/content/player/10617.html ESPNcricinfo\n}}\n'''Stuart Christopher John Broad''', {{post-nominals|size=100%|MBE}} (born 24 June 1986) is an English cricketer who plays [[Test cricket]] for the [[England cricket team]] and a former [[One Day International|ODI]] and [[Twenty 20 International|T20]] captain. A right-arm [[seam bowling|seam bowler]] and left-handed batsman, Broad began his professional career at [[Leicestershire County Cricket Club|Leicestershire]], the team attached to his school, [[Oakham School]]; in 2008 he transferred to [[Nottinghamshire County Cricket Club|Nottinghamshire]], the county of his birth and the team for which his father played. In August 2006 he was voted the [[Cricket Writers' Club Young Cricketer of the Year]]. In the fourth Test of the 2015 Ashes series Broad took career best figures of 8\u201315 in the Australian first innings as they were dismissed for just 60. This performance was named as [[Wisden Cricket Monthly|Wisden's]] Men's Test spell of the decade.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wisden.com/stories/decade-in-review/mens-test-spells-of-the-decade-no-1-broad-wins-the-ashes-in-a-morning|title=Men\u2019s Test Spells Of The Decade, No.1: Stuart Broad's 8-15|date=2019-12-15|website=Wisden|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-01-14}}</ref>\n\nBroad was awarded the Man of the Match in the [[2009 Ashes series#Fifth Test|fifth Test]] of the 2009 Ashes series at [[the Oval]], after figures of 5/37 in the afternoon session of the second day. On 30 July 2011, at the Nottingham Test match against India, he achieved a Test match [[hat trick]] in the process gaining his then best Test figures of 6\u201346.<ref name=\":1\">{{cite news|url=http://stats.espncricinfo.com/ci/content/records/136977.html|title=Test match hat-trick takers|work=ESPNcricinfo|accessdate=30 July 2011}}</ref>  As a batsman, he holds the second-highest ever Test score made by a number 9\u2014he made 169, his only century in first-class cricket, against [[Pakistan cricket team|Pakistan]] in August 2010. At the start of the summer in 2012 Broad, returning from injury, produced figures of 7 for 72 in a match haul of 11 wickets against the West Indies.  He is England's second highest wicket taker in [[Test cricket]].\n\n==Early life==\nBroad was born 12 weeks prematurely and his life was saved by a doctor called John, after whom he was (middle) named when he survived.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/cricket/12103482/Stuart-Broad-follows-step-mums-advice-to-seize-the-moment-and-demolishes-South-Africa.html|title=Stuart Broad follows step-mum's advice to seize the moment and demolishes South Africa|last=Sawer|first=Patrick|date=2016-01-16|access-date=2020-01-13|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref> Broad originally started his cricketing career as an opening batsman, following in the footsteps of his father, the former England [[Batting order (cricket)#Opening batsmen|opener]] and current ICC match referee [[Chris Broad]]. It was not until he was 17 and had a growth spurt that he started to consider being a fast bowler.<ref name=\"telegraph\"/> Broad had been associated with Leicestershire since he was 8 years old, having represented them at Under-9 level, and played for Melton Mowbray club Egerton Park, which also produced England seamer [[Tim Munton]]. Broad played for Egerton Park from the ages of 9 to 19; in his final two seasons he opened the batting with fellow Leicestershire player [[Matthew Boyce]] and spearheaded the attack. He was awarded the Leicestershire Young Cricketers Batsman Award in 1996.<ref name=\"telegraph\"/>\n\nBefore he was 17, he also played field hockey as a goalkeeper, and had trialled with [[England men's national field hockey team|England national field hockey team]].{{clarify|reason=If this did happen it is likely this was an age-group trial, not the senior team|date=November 2019}}<ref name=\"Stuart Broad\">{{cite news |url=http://www.cricinfo.com/england/content/player/10617.html |title=Stuart Broad |work=Cricinfo |accessdate=26 August 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Education==\nBroad was educated at Brooke Priory School and [[Oakham School]], a co-educational [[independent school]] in the [[market town]] of [[Oakham]] in Rutland, where he was in the same year as England Rugby back-row [[Tom Croft]].<ref name=\"telegraph\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/cricket/international/theashes/6086500/Stuart-Broad-from-school-all-rounder-to-Englands-world-class-Ashes-winner.html |title=Stuart Broad: from school all-rounder to England's world-class Ashes winner |publisher=Telegraph Online |date=25 August 2009 | location=London | first=Gareth A | last=Davies | accessdate=24 May 2010}}</ref> Broad finished his school career with three B grades at [[A-level]], and was given the choice of a place at [[Durham University]] or a contract with [[Leicestershire County Cricket Club]].<ref name=\"telegraph\"/>\n\n==Domestic career==\nBroad played his first game for Leicestershire 2nd XI in 2004 just before his 18th birthday and impressed enough to be given a full contract for the following season. Broad continued to impress Director of Cricket [[James Whitaker (cricketer)|James Whitaker]] and made his first-class debut early in the 2005 season against [[Durham University Centre of Cricketing Excellence]]. He returned credible figures of 1/40 from 15 overs. His maiden first-class wicket was that of Nick Lamb. Broad followed this appearance with his first County Championship appearance against [[Somerset County Cricket Club|Somerset]] at the familiar location of Oakham.\n\nIn the 2006 season Broad took his first 5 wicket haul against championship favourites Surrey and scored his first championship 50 against Derbyshire. His most eye-catching performances were in the [[Twenty20 Cup]], where his economy of 4.50 was the second-best of the season of bowlers with more than 15 overs bowled.<ref>[https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Events/ENG/Twenty20_Cup_2006/Bowling_by_Average.html Bowling in Twenty20 Cup 2006 (Ordered by Average)], from CricketArchive. Retrieved 26 August 2006</ref> In the County Championship Broad played twelve of Leicestershire's 13 matches until called up for England, and his 44 wickets at an average of 31.38 meant he led his county both in terms of wickets and bowling average.<ref>[https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Events/ENG/Liverpool_Victoria_County_Championship_2006/Leicestershire_Bowling.html Bowling for Leicestershire in Liverpool Victoria County Championship 2006], from Cricinfo. Retrieved 26 August 2006</ref> On 23 August 2007 it was announced that Broad would be leaving Leicestershire at the end of the season to join Nottinghamshire, after choosing not to renew his contract and to return to his home county.<ref>[http://content-aus.cricinfo.com/australia/content/current/story/307924.html Broad joins Nottinghamshire]. Content-aus.cricinfo.com. Retrieved 3 August 2011.</ref>\nIn the 2013 season, Broad played in the final of the [[Yorkshire Bank 40]] tournament. He was out for a duck and got three wickets in his last over wrapping up the game against Glamorgan.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://m.nottinghampost.com/articles/news/article/19828729 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2013-10-05 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20131005122737/http://m.nottinghampost.com/articles/news/article/19828729 |archivedate=5 October 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==International career==\n\n===Development===\nBroad played for the England Under-19 squad in 2005, facing the Sri Lankan U-19 squad, and took five for seventeen in the first \u2019Test\u2019 at Shenley. {{Citation needed|date=March 2014}} He was named in the ECB National Academy squad for the winter of 2005\u201306 and was then called up to the England \u2018A\u2019 squad touring the West Indies, as a replacement for [[James Anderson (cricketer)|James Anderson]], who had been drafted into the Test side touring India. In April 2006, Broad was again called up to the England A squad, facing the touring Sri Lankan team.\n\nBroad was also included in the ECB's 25-man development squad for the 2006 season. [[David Graveney]], the chairman of selectors, said, \"The squad essentially enables the England Head Coach ([[Duncan Fletcher]]), working with his support staff and the National Academy staff, to monitor more closely the development of international players and better prepare them for the demands of the international game.\" {{citation needed|date=February 2014}}\n\n===2006: Pakistan===\n[[File:Stuart Broad.jpg|thumbnail|left|Broad playing against Pakistan in the 3rd ODI at the Rose Bowl in 2006]]\n\nOn 23 August 2006, Broad was included in the England one-day squad for the [[one-day international]]s against Pakistan, and a couple of days later was named Young Cricketer of the Year by the Cricket Writers' Club.<ref>\"[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/cricket/5288076.stm Broad claims young player award]\", from BBC. Retrieved 26 August 2006.</ref> On 28 August, Broad made his first England appearance, in the [[Twenty20]] International against Pakistan. Broad bowled four overs for 35 runs, and took two wickets in two balls, [[Shoaib Malik]] and [[Younis Khan]], and narrowly missed out on a hat-trick, after a lofted shot from [[Shahid Afridi]] fell just short of [[Kevin Pietersen]].<ref>\"[http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/engvpak/content/story/258019.html Pakistan ease to five-wicket win]\", Cricinfo report.</ref> On 30 August, he made his ODI debut, taking a wicket in his first [[over (cricket)|over]], as well as being involved in a last-wicket [[partnership (cricket)|partnership]] of 29 with [[Darren Gough]]. In the third ODI on 5 September 2006, Broad once again found himself on a hat-trick with the wickets of [[Abdul Razzaq (Pakistani cricket player)|Abdul Razzaq]] and [[Kamran Akmal]], but again missed out on the third. He bowled ten overs and ended with figures of three for 57 with one maiden.\n\n===2007: West Indies and India===\nBroad was left out of the squad for the [[2006 ICC Champions Trophy]] and the [[2006-07 Commonwealth Bank Series]]. However, he was called up for the finals in the latter following injuries to [[Jon Lewis (cricketer, born 1975)|Jon Lewis]] and [[Chris Tremlett]].<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/england/6337425.stm England call up Broad for finals] from BBC. Retrieved 7 February 2007</ref> He was also called into England's squad as a replacement partway through the [[2007 Cricket World Cup|2007 World Cup]]. He finished the tournament by scoring the winning runs in England's final match against the West Indies.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/england/6527543.stm England's Lewis departs World Cup], ''bbc.co.uk'', 4 April 2007.</ref>\n\nBroad also featured in the ODI squad at the end of the West Indies tour of England in summer 2007, taking three for twenty in the first match to take England to a 1\u20130 lead in the ODI series.<ref>BBC News [http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/england/6256876.stm ''England v West Indies 1st ODI''] retrieved 1 July 2007</ref> In the second ODI he took 2\u201349 but England lost the match by 61 runs. Broad was expensive in the final match of the series, conceding 71 runs for no wickets.\n\nHe took his first wicket against India in the ODI against them in the second match at Bristol. On 30 August, he took career-best bowling figures of four for 51 as England bowled out India for 212 in the fourth match of the summer's ODI series. Broad also hit an unbeaten 45 to take his first ODI Man of the Match award. The definitive unbeaten partnership of 99 runs he shared with [[Ravi Bopara]] is a record eighth-wicket stand for England in ODIs.<ref>[http://stats.cricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/fow/highest_partnerships_by_wicket.html?class=2;id=1;type=team Record 8th wicket partnership] from Cricinfo. Retrieved 30 August 2007</ref> He bowled poorly in the next match, taking 1\u201384 as India won by 38 runs. He took 2\u201346 at the Oval but India narrowly won the match by 2 runs.\n\n===2007: T20 World Cup===\nBroad took 1\u201329 in the opening match of the 2007 world T20 against Zimbabwe. He followed this up by taking 0\u201323 against Australia as England lost by eight wickets. He took 3\u201337 against South Africa but England suffered another defeat, this time by 19 runs. He took 1\u201335 against New Zealand but could not prevent another defeat for England.\n\nOn 19 September 2007, Indian batsman [[Yuvraj Singh]] hit six sixes from one Broad over in a group match at [[Kingsmead Cricket Ground]] in [[Durban]], South Africa, during 2007's ICC World Twenty20.<ref>[http://www.rediff.com/cricket/2007/sep/19yuvraj.htm Yuvraj belts six sixes in an over]. Rediff.com (31 December 2004). Retrieved 3 August 2011.</ref> This was the fourth time the feat had been performed in senior cricket and the only time in Twenty20 cricket. The performance has never been repeated in any form of international cricket against a Test playing nation.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/cricket/7003537.stm India's Yuvraj smashes Broad for 6 sixes]. Commentators Ravi Shastri & David Lloyd, on ESPN Sky Sports TV, called the over the \"Full Monty\" by saying \u201cWell he has a license here to go for the Full Monty, 6 out of 6\". BBC News (19 September 2007). Retrieved 3 August 2011.</ref> The 36-runs from the Broad over helped Yuvraj Singh make the quickest 50 in international cricket, off just 12 balls. Referring to this rare occurrence as \"Yuvraj's magic moment\", Phil Long of BBC's Test Match Special blogged: \"Every so often you have to take off your England sunhat, sit back and enjoy a once-in-lifetime 'I was there' moment.\"<ref name=\":0\">[https://www.bbc.co.uk/blogs/tms/2007/09/hats_off_to_yuvrajs_magic_mome.shtml Hats off to Yuvraj's magic moment]. BBC Test match Special (20 September 2007). Retrieved 13 July 2013.</ref>\n\n===2007: Sri Lanka===\nBroad enjoyed a hugely successful ODI series in [[Sri Lanka]] in October 2007, taking eleven wickets in the series at an average of 19.27. He took figures of 2\u201354 in the first match and followed this up with 2\u201342 in the second match. In the third match of the series Broad made an unbeaten 20 with the bat and took another two wickets. In the final match of the series he took 3\u201336 and although England lost the match by over 100 runs, they won the series three-two to record its first ever ODI series win in Sri Lanka.<ref>[http://stats.cricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/averages/batting_bowling.html?id=3151;team=1;type=series Statistics \u2013 England in Sri Lanka 2007/08] from Cricinfo. Retrieved 14 October 2007.</ref> This resulted in Broad making his Test debut against Sri Lanka; in a high scoring game, he took a single wicket, conceding 95 runs in the process as the match ended in a draw.\n\n===2008: New Zealand===\nBroad went on to have an equally successful ODI series against [[New Zealand national cricket team|New Zealand]]. Although England fell to a three-one defeat, Broad was the leading wicket taker and held the highest batting average, 52, in the England team.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/england/averages/default.stm England vs. New Zealand \u2013 ODI series, 2008] [[BBC News]] retrieved 25 February 2008.</ref> During the tour of New Zealand in 2008, Broad, along with [[Alastair Cook]] and James Anderson, posed naked for the ''Cosmopolitan'' paper with just a cricket bat for cover.<ref>[http://thevillagecricketer.wordpress.com/2008/04/09/stuart-broad-james-anderson-and-alastair-cook-naked-for-charity-mate/ Stuart Broad, James Anderson and Alastair Cook naked \u2013 for charity mate \u00ab The Village Cricketer]. Thevillagecricketer.wordpress.com (9 April 2008). Retrieved 3 August 2011.</ref> England won the first Test against New Zealand by 121 runs, with Broad taking figures of 3\u201354 to help England win the game.\n\nIn the first Test against New Zealand on home soil, Broad took three wickets in the match. England won the second match by six wickets, although Broad picked up no wickets in the match. On 6 June 2008, Broad scored his maiden Test fifty, against New Zealand at Trent Bridge, making 64 before being bowled by [[Chris Martin (cricketer)|Chris Martin]]. In the first ODI against New Zealand Broad took 2\u201314, before taking another two wickets in the final match of the series, conceding fifty runs in the process.\n\n===2008: South Africa and India===\nHe made his second Test fifty in July 2008, in the Test series against [[South Africa national cricket team|South Africa]], scoring a new best of 76. In the Second Test at [[Headingley Cricket Ground|Headingley]], Broad contributed seventeen runs in the first innings, as England was bowled out on the first day for 203. In the second innings, with the match already lost, Broad top-scored with 67 in an innings that included some impressive drives through midwicket and cover, giving further evidence of his batsmanship.{{who said|reason=WP:OR|date=November 2016}} After this, his Test batting average briefly rose above 40. His performances with the bat at the time led pundits to suggest that he may become a genuine all rounder, with [[Geoffrey Boycott]] comparing him to [[Garfield Sobers]]: \"He's a wonderful player. There's a little bit of Sobers in him\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/england/7518708.stm |title=Boycott hails Broad performance |work=BBC Online |date=22 July 2008}} Retrieved on 22 July 2008.</ref> Broad was surprisingly dropped for the following Test at Edgbaston, making way for the returning Paul Collingwood. England captain Michael Vaughan said he was left out because of his bowling, but the decision has been criticised: Collingwood was no better a bowler than Broad, and Broad's batsmanship quite encouraging.{{citation needed|date=December 2010}} Broad duly took seven wickets for Nottinghamshire against Durham while the Test was being played.\n\nOn 26 August 2008, he recorded the first five-wicket haul in his international career with best figures of five for 23 against South Africa at his home ground in the second ODI of the series, with England winning the series 4\u20130 with Broad taking 8 wickets within the series at an average of 18.4 and shooting up to 4th in the ICC ODI world rankings, the highest in his career and the best by any English bowler since [[Andrew Flintoff]] in 2003.\n\nIn the second ODI against India Broad performed well, taking figures of 4\u201355. He took 1\u201336 in the next match as England lost by 18 runs. In the final match of the series he took 1\u201354, but England lost again, this time by six wickets. In the second Test against India, Broad was ineffectual with the ball. He took 1\u201384 in an India's first innings before taking 1\u201350 in India's second innings as the match ended in a draw.\n\n===2009: West Indies and T20 World Cup===\nOn 26 May 2009, Broad was named Man of the Series (one-day) [[West Indian cricket team in England in 2009|against the West Indies]] in England. He took a total of six wickets, and England won the series two-nil after the first ODI was rained out. In the adjacent Test series, in which the home side fairly routed its opponents, Broad's wickets came at an average of just eighteen&nbsp;\u2013 \"further evidence,\" reckoned journalist Nick Hoult, \"of the top class international cricketer that lurks within. His bowling, particularly the variety he has added to his game, makes him a potential Ashes star [...].\"<ref>Hoult, Nick. \"[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/cricket/international/theashes/5601764/Ashes-2009-England-squad-form-guide.html Ashes 2009: England squad form guide.]\" ''[[The Daily Telegraph|telegraph.co.uk]]''. 22 June 2009.. Retrieved 28 June 2009.</ref>\n\nOn 5 June 2009, [[Netherlands national cricket team|Netherlands]] defeated England by four wickets in the first match of the ICC World Twenty20.<ref>{{Cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/england/8085673.stm |work=BBC News  | title=England v Netherlands as it happened | date=5 June 2009 | accessdate=24 May 2010 | first=Mark | last=Mitchener}}</ref> The Netherlands needed seven to win from the final over with Broad bowling. He spurned two run-out opportunities from the first two balls, and dropped a catch off the third. The Dutch needed two runs from the final ball to win, and got them after Broad picked up the ball in his follow through and, attempting to win the match, overthrew, missing his third run-out opportunity of the over and allowing the batsmen to come back for the match-clinching second run.<ref>{{Cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/cricket/8082343.stm |work=BBC News  | title=Superb Netherlands shock England | date=5 June 2009 | accessdate=24 May 2010 | first=Oliver | last=Brett}}</ref> in the next match against Pakistan, he took 3\u201317 to help England win by 48 runs. England also beat India by 3 runs. Although Broad failed to take a wicket, he bowled his four overs for just 21 runs to help England secure a narrow victory. England lost their final game of the tournament against the West Indies, with Broad taking 1\u201320.\n\n===2009: Ashes series===\n[[File:Broad celebrating, 2009.jpg|thumbnail|left|Broad celebrates the wicket of [[Michael Hussey]] with [[Graeme Swann]] in the 3rd Test of the 2009 Ashes Series]]\n\nIn July 2009, Broad was named in [[The Ashes]] squad to face Australia for the first Test at the [[SWALEC Stadium]], Cardiff \u2013 his maiden Ashes Test. He scored a 22-ball 19 in England's first-innings total of 435, but in 32 overs he took just one wicket (that of [[Michael Clarke (cricketer)|Michael Clarke]], caught behind for 83) as Australia amassed 674 for 6 declared, with four centurions. Nonetheless, his final-day 14 proved crucial, keeping the Australians at bay alongside [[Paul Collingwood]] for a minute over an hour before [[James Anderson (cricketer)|James Anderson]] and [[Monty Panesar]] blocked out the final 11\u00bd overs to salvage an unlikely draw.<ref>[http://www.cricinfo.com/ci/engine/match/345970.html England v Australia at Cardiff, 2009]. Cricinfo.com. Retrieved 3 August 2011.</ref>\n\nThe second Test at [[Lord's]] saw Broad take three wickets, including the important wicket of Australian skipper [[Ricky Ponting]], bowled off an inside-edged cut for 38 as England pursued victory, and took a diving outfield catch to remove the opener [[Simon Katich]] in the first innings, as England took a 1\u20130 lead in the series.<ref>[http://www.cricinfo.com/ci/engine/match/345971.html England v Australia at Lord's, 2009]. Cricinfo.com. Retrieved 3 August 2011.</ref>\n\nThough he took no wickets in the first innings of the third Test at [[Edgbaston cricket ground|Edgbaston]], Broad hit a 64-ball 55 to extend England's first-innings lead to 114. On the final day, Broad took two of the three wickets to fall: [[Mike Hussey]] for 64 and, late in the day, [[Marcus North]] for 96. Nonetheless, Australia drew the match with ease.<ref>[http://www.cricinfo.com/ci/engine/match/345972.html England v Australia at Birmingham, 2009]. Cricinfo.com. Retrieved 3 August 2011.</ref>\n\nIn the fourth Test at [[Headingley Cricket Ground|Headingley]], Broad took his place in an England first-innings collapse, clipping [[Stuart Clark]] to square leg for 3 as Australia's seam attack bowled England out for 102. As Australia scored 445, Broad took six wickets for 91 in Australia's only innings, at that time his best first-class innings return, and in the second innings contributed a rapid 61 from 48 balls, though he could not avert an innings defeat.<ref>[http://www.cricinfo.com/ci/engine/match/345973.html England v Australia at Leeds, 2009]. Cricinfo.com. Retrieved 3 August 2011.</ref>\n\nEngland therefore started the fifth Test at [[the Oval]] with the series level at 1\u20131, with a victory required to secure the Ashes. He took 5 for 37 in the afternoon session of the second day, taking five of the first seven wickets to fall to take the Australian innings from 73/0 to 111/7 and eventually 160 all out. He also contributed 37 and 29 with the bat, and on the final day took the wicket of [[Shane Watson]] lbw for 40, the second wicket to fall in consecutive overs to start Australia's collapse, winning the Man of the Match award as England won by 197 runs to regain the 'Ashes' 2\u20131.<ref>[http://www.cricinfo.com/ci/engine/match/345974.html England v Australia at the Oval, 2009]. Cricinfo.com. Retrieved 3 August 2011.</ref>\n\nHe finished the tour with an aggregate of 234 runs and 18 wickets, leading England's bowling figures both in wickets taken and in bowling average (30.22). Though three Australian bowlers took more wickets, Broad was the only bowler from either side to claim two five-wicket innings hauls during the series.<ref>[http://stats.cricinfo.com/ci/engine/records/bowling/most_wickets_career.html?id=4249;type=series The Ashes, 2009: Most Wickets]. Stats.cricinfo.com. Retrieved 3 August 2011.</ref>\n\n===2009: ICC Champions Trophy===\nThis was a good tournament for Broad. He was the second highest wicket taker overall throughout the tournament with 10 wickets in 3 matches, only behind [[Wayne Parnell]] who took 11 in the same number of matches. In the first match of the tournament against Sri Lanka he took 3\u201349 in a winning effort. He followed it up with a 3\u201367 vs South Africa, putting England through to the semi finals. He then took 4\u201339 vs New Zealand in a losing effort after England had already been bowled out for 146, with New Zealand making the runs in just 27.1 overs. This was his last game in the tournament with Broad picking up an injury that kept him out of the semi finals, which England lost to Australia.\n\n===2009\u201310: South Africa===\nBroad's injuries continued through to the tour of South Africa, keeping him out of the two [[twenty20]] matches, which both ended up being abandoned. The weather affected the 1st One Day International which was probably an advantage for Broad and the England team with Broad being fit for the 3rd ODI, with England winning the second ODI by 7 wickets after Paul Collingwood and [[Jonathan Trott]] had a partnership of 162 with Collingwood getting 105.\n\nWhen Broad returned he instantly made an impact with numerous wickets but turned out to be very expensive. With his first game getting figures of 4\u201371, England suffered defeat by 112 runs. Broad improved on his economy rate in the 4th ODI with figures of 2\u201330 from 9.5 overs. This backed up James Anderson who took 5\u201323. The final game was rained off before a ball was bowled to leave England with a 2\u20131 victory and only the second team to win a one-day series vs South Africa in South Africa.\n\nBroad struggled in the First test in [[Centurion, Gauteng|Centurion]] with only taking 1\u201374 in the first innings and 2\u201354 in the second. His batting was unsuccessful, getting only 17 and a duck. The duck was during a dramatic collapse where England went from 205\u20134 to 218\u20139 with [[Graham Onions]] batting out the final over to save the test.\n\nIn the second test Broad showed good form with the ball with 2\u201344 in the first innings but then taking 4\u201343 in the second dismissing [[Jacques Kallis]], [[AB de Villiers]] and [[JP Duminy]] all within 3 overs. He took the wicket of [[Mark Boucher]] the next day to leave [[Graeme Swann]] to dismiss the rest of the South African line up. This gave England an innings and 98 run victory. After this test Broad went up to 7th in the ICC Test bowling rankings, the highest in his career. During this tour he declined to play in the [[Indian Premier League|IPL]] with James Anderson on the grounds he wanted to focus on his Test cricket first, and feared injury in the IPL.\n\n===2010: Bangladesh, T20 World Cup, Australia and Pakistan===\n[[File:Stuart Broad3.JPG|thumbnail|Broad with the Man of the Match award after the Test match against [[Pakistan]] at Lord's in 2010]]\n[[File:Stuart Broad secures his half-century.jpg|thumb|On 27 August 2010 Stuart Broad makes a half century]]\n\nAfter South Africa, England toured [[English cricket team in Bangladesh in 2009\u201310|Bangladesh]], playing three ODIs and two Test matches. Injuries to Anderson, Onions and Sidebottom meant that Broad was the leader of a relatively inexperienced pace attack. However, an injury before the Test series meant that he wasn't fully fit and was outbowled by [[Tim Bresnan]] and debutant [[Steven Finn (cricketer)|Steven Finn]].\n\nEngland then travelled to the West Indies for the [[2010 ICC World Twenty20]]. England won the tournament, beating Australia in the final. Broad won the man of the match award against Sri Lanka in the semi-final, and overall took 8 wickets at an average of 17.50.\n\nBack in England, Broad was rested for the [[Bangladeshi cricket team in England in 2010|home series against Bangladesh]] before returning to the side for a [[Australian cricket team in England in 2010|5-match ODI series against Australia]]. England won the first three games to take the series, with Broad named man of the match in the second game after bowling figures of 4\u201344. England lost the last two games, though Broad did achieve another four-wicket haul in the fifth game to finish the series with an average of 19.83. The ODIs against Bangladesh were less note-worthy \u2013 England won 2\u20131 with Broad taking 4 wickets.\n\nIn the [[Pakistani cricket team in England in 2010|home series against Pakistan]], Broad was involved in a disciplinary incident in the second Test. After Pakistani batsman [[Zulqarnain Haider]] defended a ball bowled by Broad down the pitch, Broad picked the ball up and threw it at Haider, striking him on the hand. Broad was fined 50% of his match fee.\n\nIn the final Test of the series, Broad reached his maiden Test century at Lord's. Coming to the crease at 102\u20137, he scored 169 and put on a 332-run partnership with fellow centurion Jonathan Trott; a [[List of Test cricket records#Partnership records|world record for an eight-wicket partnership]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theage.com.au/sport/cricket/trott-broad-in-worldrecord-partnership-20100828-13wxa.html|title=Trott, Broad in world-record partnership|first=|last=London|publisher=}}</ref> It was his first century in all forms of cricket since an under-19's match for [[Leicestershire County Cricket Club|Leicestershire]] and saw his name go on the Lord's batting honours board, a feat that his father never achieved. He also surpassed his father's Test best of 162, and they became the first father and son both to score centuries for England in Test match cricket. His efforts both with the bat and with the ball (he also took three wickets during the match and made a direct-hit run out) earned him the man of the match award.\n\n===2010\u201311: Ashes series===\n[[File:Board bowling against Sri Lanka at Lord's, 2011.jpg|thumb|left|Broad bowling against [[Sri Lanka]] at Lord's in June 2011]]\n\nBroad had an indifferent [[English cricket team in Australia in 2010-11|tour of Australia]], which was cut short due to injury. He started with a half-century in a warm-up game, and overall took 6 wickets over the two games against [[Western Australia cricket team|Western Australia]] and [[South Australia cricket team|South Australia]].<ref>{{Cite news| url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/the-ashes-2010-11/engine/match/446951.html | work=Cricinfo | title=Tour match: Western Australia v England XI at Perth, Nov 5\u20137, 2010 | date=7 November 2010}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news| url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/the-ashes-2010-11/engine/match/446952.html | work=Cricinfo | title=Tour match: South Australia v England XI at Adelaide, Nov 11\u201313, 2010 | date=13 November 2010}}</ref> In the first Test at [[the Gabba]], [[Brisbane]], he fell for a [[Duck (cricket)|golden duck]] in England's innings, the final victim of [[Peter Siddle|Peter Siddle's]] hat-trick. Wicketless in Australia's first innings, he had [[Simon Katich]] caught in the second as the Test was drawn.<ref>{{Cite news| url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/the-ashes-2010-11/engine/match/428749.html | work=Cricinfo | title=1st Test: Australia v England at Brisbane, Nov 25\u201329, 2010 | date=29 November 2010}}</ref> In the second Test at [[Adelaide Cricket Ground|Adelaide]], he finished Australia's first innings off with the wicket of [[Brad Haddin]], but a stomach muscle injury limited his participation in the second where England won by an innings.<ref>{{Cite news| url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/the-ashes-2010-11/engine/match/428750.html | work=Cricinfo | title=2nd Test: Australia v England at Adelaide, Dec 3\u20137, 2010 | date=7 December 2010}}</ref> That injury was revealed to be a muscle tear, and it ruled Broad out of the remaining three Tests and the one-day series that followed.<ref>{{Cite news| url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/the-ashes-2010-11/content/current/story/490728.html | work=Cricinfo | title=Injured Broad out of tour | date=7 December 2010}}</ref> He was not missed for the rest of the Test series but he was for the [[One Day Internationals|ODIs]] because England were plagued by injuries throughout the 6\u20131 series defeat.\n\n===2011: India===\nAfter a difficult series against Sri Lanka<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/cricket/international/england/8616780/England-v-Sri-Lanka-Enforcer-Stuart-Broad-must-focus-fury-again.html | location=London | work=The Daily Telegraph | first=Derek | last=Pringle | title=England v Sri Lanka: 'Enforcer' Stuart Broad must focus fury again | date=5 July 2011}}</ref> there was much pressure on the England selectors to drop him for the [[Indian cricket team in England in 2011|upcoming series against India]].<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/sport/blog/2011/jul/05/stuart-broad-england-vic-marks Dropping Stuart Broad would do him and England a favour | Vic Marks | Sport]. ''The Guardian''. Retrieved 3 August 2011.</ref>  However, Broad was named in the side for the first Test at Lord's and ended with match figures of 7\u201394, as well as scoring an unbeaten 74 in the second innings, as England won by 196 runs.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport/hi/english/static/cricket/statistics/scorecards/2011/07/86081/html/scorecard.stm Cricket Scorecard]. BBC News (21 July 2011). Retrieved 3 August 2011.</ref> His good form with both bat and ball continued in the second test. Top scoring with an aggressive 64 in the first innings, he helped England recover from 124\u20138 to 221 all out before achieving his career best figures of 6\u201346 in India's first innings. This included a [[hat-trick (cricket)|hat-trick]], taking the wickets of [[Mahendra Singh Dhoni]], [[Harbhajan Singh]] and [[Praveen Kumar]]. Broad took five wickets from his final 16 balls of the innings, without conceding a single run.<ref>[http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/cricket/article-2020522/Hat-trick-hero-Broad-revives-England-Test-best-figures-Dravid-ton.html?ito=feeds-newsxml Hat-trick hero Broad revives England with Test best figures after another Dravid ton]. ''The Daily Mail'' (UK). (30 July 2011). Retrieved 3 August 2011.</ref> With a positive second innings contribution with both bat and ball (44 runs with the bat and then two wickets, including the final wicket of the match) Broad was named Man of the Match.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/cricket/14365256.stm BBC Sport \u2013 England thrash India at Trent Bridge to lead series 2\u20130]. BBC News. Retrieved 3 August 2011.</ref> In the Third Test at Edgbaston, Broad took four wickets along with Tim Bresnan to bowl India out cheaply. In England's innings he was not needed as Alistair Cook scored 294 to pass 700. Broad took two wickets in the second innings to beat India and for England to become World number 1 in Test Cricket. Broad made a lesser impact in the fourth Test with him taking two wickets in both India's innings and he did not bat due to an early declaration.\n\n===2011\u201312: Pakistan and Sri Lanka===\nIn the first Test against Pakistan Broad took 3\u201384 in the first innings. However, England suffered a ten wicket defeat as the batsmen struggled to acclimatise to sub continent conditions. Broad took 4\u201347 in the next match as well as an unbeaten fifty in England's 1st innings (he'd only score 1 test fifty in 5 years after scoring this 50) but another batting collapse saw England lose the match again (bowled out for 72 chasing 145) to go 2\u20130 down in the three match series. In the final match Broad took 4\u201336 in the first innings to help bowl out Pakistan for 99. However, Pakistan made over 300 in their second innings to build up a lead. England were unable to chase down their target and went on to lose the series 3\u20130. England lost their fourth straight match, this time against Sri Lanka as the batsmen continued to struggle. Broad took just two wickets in the match, although he made 33 runs with the bat in the match, and was not out in the second innings.\n\n===2012: West Indies and South Africa===\nBroad started off his summer with his best international innings yet, of 7\u201372, against the West Indies, at [[Lord's]], the first test match of the series, was started with a bang as he was able to get a [[five wicket haul]] at the home of cricket, Lord's, becoming only the 8th player to join an elite club of all-rounders to be on [[Lord's Honours Boards|both honours boards]], after his maiden test century of 169 against Pakistan in 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/content/story/565271.html|title=Broad achieves honours board double|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nHe soon followed this up by taking 4 more wickets in the next innings, missing a possible hat trick however, to get Test best figures of 11 for 165, being the first to take a 10 wicket haul at Lord's since [[Ian Botham]] in 1978. He had to wait until after Lunch on the 4th day to take the last 3 wickets he needed for the haul. He was named Man of the Match the next day after England won by 5 wickets, in a chase of 191.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://metro.co.uk/2012/05/20/stuart-broads-historic-test-feat-eclipsed-by-west-indies-fightback-432337/|title=Stuart Broad's historic Test feat eclipsed by West Indies fightback|first=|last=metrowebukmetro|date=20 May 2012|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nBroad followed the performance by taking four wickets in the second test. which England also won. He was rested for the last Test match against the West Indies along with James Anderson. However the game was heavily disrupted by rain and the game ended as a draw. England won the following One Day series 2\u20130 with the third game being abandoned because of rain. On Broad's 26th birthday, he captained the team to a comfortable victory with Notts teammate Alex Hales scoring 99. He was then named in the squad to play Australia in a five match ODI series. Broad's bowling was overshadowed by Steven Finn who took 11 wickets in four games compared to Broad's 5.\n\nBroad was picked in the first Test against South Africa but failed to take a wicket. He added 16 with the bat in England's first innings of 386. Broad and the England bowlers struggled in South Africa's innings of 637\u20132 with [[Hashim Amla]] scoring a triple century (the first South African to do so) with Jacques Kallis and [[Graeme Smith]] also scoring centuries. In the second innings Broad was out for a duck as England lost by an innings and 12 runs. In the second Test, South Africa scored 419 in the first innings with Broad taking 3\u201396. He then scored 1 run in England's innings of 425. Broad then had a burst of wickets on the last day with the wickets of AB de Villiers and JP Duminy in successive deliveries. He finished with figures of 5\u201369 as England couldn't reach the target and the game ended in a draw. In the following Test, Broad was pushed up the order to number 8 after Tim Bresnan was left out. Broad only managed one wicket in South Africa's first innings of 309. He then added 16 in England's first innings of 315. Broad, who had been down on pace all summer struggled as he took 2\u201376 as South Africa set England 346 to win. England lost by 51 runs, Broad adding 37 runs.\n\n===2013: New Zealand ===\n[[File:Broad bowling, 2013.jpg|thumbnail|Broad comes in to bowl during the England v Australia game of the 2013 ICC Champions Trophy at Edgbaston.]]\n\nOn the fifth day of the [[English cricket team in New Zealand in 2012\u201313|3rd Test against New Zealand]], Broad set a new record for the longest time spent at the crease without scoring a run, with 103 minutes out in the middle, facing 62 balls.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.guinnessworldrecords.com/world-records/longest-test-match-innings-without-scoring-a-run-(male) |title=Longest time taken to score a run |accessdate=19 May 2013|work=Guinness World Records}}</ref> The previous record was 101 minutes set by New Zealander [[Geoff Allott]] against South Africa in 1999.<ref name=\"BBCSport5thTest\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/cricket/21934581 |title=New Zealand v England: Matt Prior earns series draw in Auckland |accessdate=26 March 2013|work=BBC Sport}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/match/569245.html |title=England v New Zealand scorecard |accessdate=19 May 2013|work=cricinfo}}</ref>\n\nOn the 19 May, in the First Test against New Zealand at Lord's, Broad took career best figures of 7/44 in the second innings of the match. In England's second innings, he also contributed 26 runs to their total of 213.<ref name=\"BBCSport-EngNZ\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/cricket/22587365 |title=England v New Zealand: Stuart Broad hurries hosts to Lord's win |accessdate=19 May 2013|work=BBC Sport}}</ref>\n\n===2013: Ashes series===\nIn the first test of the [[2013 Ashes]] held at [[Trent Bridge]], Broad controversially stood his ground after being incorrectly given not out when edging an [[Ashton Agar]] delivery which deflected off wicket keeper Brad Haddin's gloves and was caught by [[Australia national cricket team|Australia]] captainMichael Clarke at first slip; the [[Umpire Decision Review System]] was in use during the series, but Australia had used all of its challenges when the incident occurred. Although neither the rules nor common practice required Broad to [[Glossary of cricket terms#W|walk]], he drew heavy criticism from many observers who thought his edge was too thick to have reasonably stood his ground.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.smh.com.au/sport/cricket/crickets-ethics-demanded-that-stuart-broad-walk-20130713-2pwe8.html|title=Cricket's ethics demanded that Stuart Broad walk|date=13 July 2013|accessdate=13 August 2013|work=Sydney Morning Herald}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/cricket/international/theashes/10177287/Stuart-Broads-sadly-predictable-Ashes-decision-not-to-walk-leaves-Adam-Gilchrist-as-a-moral-man-apart.html|title=Stuart Broad's sadly predictable Ashes decision not to walk leaves Adam Gilchrist as a moral man apart|date=12 July 2013|accessdate=13 August 2013|work=The Telegraph}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/sport/cricket/ashes-2013-stuart-broad-refusing-2048967|title=Oliver Holt on Stuart Broad: What he did wasn\u2019t just disappointing. It was deeply, deeply embarrassing|date=12 July 2013|accessdate=13 August 2013|work=The Mirror}}</ref> Broad was on 37 at the time of the incident<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/cricket/23277348|title=Ashes 2013: England v Australia, first Test, day three as it happened|date=12 July 2013|accessdate=13 August 2013|work=BBC|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130715201023/http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/cricket/23277348|archivedate=15 July 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref> and went to make 65, sharing a partnership of 138 with [[Ian Bell]].<ref name=engaussc>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/cricket/scorecard/87719|title=England v Australia Scorecard|date=14 August 2013|work=BBC|access-date=11 February 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140509032853/http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/cricket/scorecard/87719|archive-date=9 May 2014|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> England went on to win the match by 14 runs with Broad taking the wickets of [[Shane Watson]] and Clarke in Australia's second innings.<ref name=engaussc/> Australia coach [[Darren Lehmann]] was later fined 20% of his match fee for calling Broad a cheat on Australian radio, and in doing so inciting Australian crowds to boo Broad in future English tours of Australia.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/0/cricket/23805302|title=Ashes 2013: Darren Lehmann fined for Stuart Broad criticism|date=23 August 2013|accessdate=29 January 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn 2 August 2013, Broad took his 200th test wicket, bowling Clarke in the first innings of the drawn third Ashes test at [[Old Trafford (cricket ground)|Old Trafford]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/cricket/article-2383671/Ashes-2013-Stuart-Broad-claims-200th-Test-wicket-England-bowling-Australia-captain-Michael-Clarke-Old-Trafford.html|title=The Best of Broad: Bowler becomes 15th Englishman to claim 200 Test wickets with dismissal of Aussie centurion Clarke|date=2 August 2013|accessdate=13 August 2013|work=Daily Mail}}</ref>\n\nIn the fourth test, at the [[Riverside Ground]] in [[Chester-le-Street]], Broad took eleven wickets with [[List of international cricket five-wicket hauls at the Riverside Ground|two five-wicket hauls]] and was named [[man of the match]] as England ensured a series win.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www1.skysports.com/cricket/news/article/8867950/broad-an-amazing-feeling|title=Ashes: England hero Stuart Broad says it feels 'amazing' to win the series |date=12 August 2013|work=BSkyB}}</ref> In the first innings, he took 5\u201371, including a spell of 3\u201312 in the morning session of day 2 where he removed [[David Warner (cricketer)|David Warner]], [[Usman Khawaja]] and Clarke to reduce Australia to 49\u20133.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/cricket/23642354|title=The Ashes: England v Australia, fourth Test, day two as it happened|date=10 August 2013|accessdate=13 August 2013|work=BBC|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130813143227/http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/cricket/23642354|archivedate=13 August 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/cricket/international/theashes/10235391/Ashes-2013-England-bowler-Stuart-Broad-walks-tall-again-with-peak-performance-against-Australia-at-Durham.html|title=\nAshes 2013: England bowler Stuart Broad walks tall again with peak performance against Australia at Durham|date=10 August 2013|accessdate=13 August 2013|work=The Telegraph}}</ref> In their second innings, chasing 299 to win, Australia had made 174\u20133 when Broad took the wicket Clarke for the fifth time in the series with the first delivery after a drinks break. In this spell he took 6\u201320 from 45 balls,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.smh.com.au/sport/cricket/cook-lauds-broad-as-aussies-swept-aside-in-fourth-test-20130813-2rt6f.html|title=Cook lauds Broad as Aussies swept aside in fourth Test|date=13 August 2013|work=Sydney Morning Herald}}</ref> including the final Australian wicket, to bowl Australia out for 224 and win the match by 74 runs.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/cricket/scorecard/87722|title=England v Australia Scorecard|date=12 August 2013|work=BBC|access-date=11 February 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140310194153/http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/cricket/scorecard/87722|archive-date=10 March 2014|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Broad ended the match with his best test bowling match figures of 11\u2013121.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/cricket/international/theashes/10238888/Ashes-2013-Stuart-Broad-Englands-big-game-hunter-causes-real-damage-to-Australian-herd.html|title=Ashes 2013: Stuart Broad, England's big game hunter, causes real damage to Australian herd|date=12 August 2013|work=The Telegraph}}</ref>\n\n===2013\u201314: Ashes series===\nBroad was England's leading wicket taker in the first test of the [[2013\u201314 Ashes series]] at the Gabba in Brisbane, taking 6\u201381 in the first innings and ending with match figures of 8\u2013136, in the match that England lost in four days by 381 runs.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/cricket/scorecard/87887|title=Australia v England Scorecard|accessdate=25 November 2013|work=BBC|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131124143616/http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/cricket/scorecard/87887|archive-date=24 November 2013|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In the second test Broad took 3\u201398 in Australia's first innings, but as England struggled he only bowled six overs in the second innings as Australia romped to victory. Broad took 3\u2013100 in the third test but was then injured by a delivery from Mitchell Johnson, which dismissed him for just 5. The injury which Broad obtained prevented him from bowling in the second innings, as England went on to lose the game and the series. Broad was declared fit for the fourth test and took 3\u201345 in the Australian first innings, but struggled in the second, bowling 10 wicketless overs for 58 runs. In the final test, Broad batted well, making an unbeaten 30 in the first innings and then 42 in the second. England went on to lose the game and the series 5\u20130, leading to the England team being heavily criticised. Despite this, Broad was one of the few members of the team to come out of the series with any credibility.\n\n===2014: West Indies and T20 World Cup===\nBroad continued as captain for the tour of the West Indies. This included three ODI games and three 20/20 games. In the ODI series England won 2\u20131 with Broad bringing England home in the 2nd game with a knock of 28 not out. In the third game he took 2\u201358 as England won by 25 runs. He only played in the first T20 game as England lost by 27 runs, with Broad taking figures of 0\u201326.\n\nBroad was named captain of the England cricket team for the [[2014 ICC World Twenty20]] in [[Bangladesh]]. Broad did not take a wicket in the first two games as England lost to New Zealand and beat Sri Lanka. In the third game against South Africa, Broad took 1\u201333 but England lost the match to end their hopes of qualifying. He took 3\u201324 against the Netherlands, but he was unable to prevent an embarrassing defeat for England.\n\n===2014: Sri Lanka and India===\nIn the first Test Test Broad could only manage one wicket in Sri Lanka's first innings, although he took three in Sri Lanka's second innings as England came close to winning the match. In the second test against Sri Lanka at Headingley Broad became only the fourth player, and first Englishman to take two test hat-tricks, although he needed to be informed of this by the PA system as he was unaware. England went on to lose the game after James Anderson was dismissed in the penultimate ball of the match, meaning England lost the series 1\u20130.\n\nBroad bowled well on a good batting pitch in the first game of the series against India, taking four wickets in the match. However, in the second game he was accused of bowling badly in the first innings as India won the match to go 1\u20130 up in the series. Broad's form improved in the next game, as he took 3\u201366 in the first innings to help England win the game and level the series. He took figures of 6\u201325 in India's first innings of the next game to help dismiss them for 152. Broad was badly injured while batting and was later revealed he had broken his nose. Broad was later named man of the match. Despite being an injury doubt, he took part in the final test, taking 3 wickets in the match and scoring 37 to help England secure a 3\u20131 series win.\n\n===2015: Tri-Series===\nFollowing an injury which had kept him out of the one-day tour of Sri Lanka, Broad returned for the Tri-Series against Australia and India. In the first match of the series he was wicket less as England lost to Australia. In the next match against India, Broad finished with figures of 0\u201333.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://m.cricbuzz.com/cricket-scorecard/13846/aus-vs-eng-1st-match-india-and-england-in-australia-tri-series-2015/1|title=Aus vs Eng \u2013 Scorecard \u2013 Cricbuzz|publisher=}}</ref> His worst performance of the series came in the following match against Australia, where he finished with figures of 0\u201361.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/carlton-mid-triangular-series-2015/content/story/823143.html|title=Smith ton leads Australia to final|publisher=}}</ref> However, he played well in the must win game against India, taking figures of 2\u201356 to help England qualify for the final.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/carlton-mid-triangular-series-2015/content/story/825193.html|title=England through to final, India winless on tour|publisher=}}</ref> In the final match against Australia he took figures of 3\u201355 and made 24 with the bat, but it was not enough to prevent an England defeat as they went on to finish the tournament as runners-up.\n\n===2015: World Cup===\nBroad took figures of 2\u201366 in England's opening game loss to Australia. In the following game against New Zealand, he was unimpressive as England suffered a humiliating eight wicket defeat. He failed to take a wicket against Scotland as England won their first match of the tournament, and also finished wicket less as England suffered a nine wicket defeat against Sri Lanka, meaning he had failed to take a wicket in his past three matches. He finished with 1\u201352 in England's must win game against Bangladesh, but was dismissed for 9 as England lost the game to bow out of the tournament at the group stage. He finished with figures of 1\u201318 against Afghanistan in a rain affected as England won their final match of the tournament by nine wickets.\n\n===2015: West Indies and New Zealand===\nThe first match against the West Indies, Broad took 2\u201367 in their first innings to help restrict them to 295. However, in the second innings he could only manage to take one wicket as the West Indies held on for a draw. In the second Test ok 4\u201361 in West Indies first innings to help out England in a strong position. He took another wicket in the second innings as England forced a result to go 1\u20130 up in the series. In the first Test Broad took 1\u201331 in West Indies first innings to help England into a lead. However, England collapsed in their second innings and Broad himself was out for a duck. He took 1\u201329 in the West Indies second innings but it wasn't enough to prevent a five wicket defeat as the West Indies levelled the series at 1\u20131.\n\nIn the two match series against New Zealand, Broad took 3\u201377 in New Zealand's first innings. With New Zealand chasing a big score to win the match, Broad took 3\u201350 in New Zealand's second innings to help England win by 124 runs and go 1\u20130 up in the series. Broad took 5\u2013109 in New Zealand's first innings of the next Test, although he went at an economy rate of over six an over. He made 46 with the bat to help England level the scores after the first innings. He took 2\u201394 in the second innings but was again expensive, and New Zealand went on to win the match and tie the series 1\u20131.\n\n===2015: Ashes series===\nIn Australia's first innings of the first Test, Broad took figures of 2\u201360 and followed this up by taking 3\u201339 in their second innings as England won the match to take the lead in the series. Broad took 4\u201383 in Australia's first innings of the second Test but they built a large first innings score of 566. Broad did not take a wicket in the Australians second innings as they won by 405 runs. In the third Test Broad took 2\u201344 in Australia's first innings and also took a wicket in their second as England won the game to regain the lead. In the fourth Test Broad took career best figures of 8\u201315 in the Australian first innings as they were dismissed for just 60. England went on to win the match convincingly and regain the Ashes. In the final Test Broad did not take a wicket as Australia won by an innings and 48 runs, although England won the series 3\u20132.\n\n===2015: Pakistan===\n\nBroad played in the first Test against Pakistan, which was played in the UAE. While Broad only took one wicket in the match, he bowled economically, including bowling eight overs for just eight runs in the second innings. England came to close to forcing a result, but the match ended in a draw. In the second Test Broad again only managed to take one wicket as Pakistan enjoyed a convincing win to go 1\u20130 up in the three-match series. In the third Test, Broad continued to bowl economically, taking figures of 2\u201313 from 13 overs in Pakistan's first innings, as they were dismissed for 234. In the second innings, he took 3\u201344 but England struggled in their second innings and Pakistan went on to win the game to win the series 2\u20130.\n\n===2015\u201316: South Africa===\nIn the first test in South Africa, Broad took figures of 4\u201325 and 1\u201329 and hit an unbeaten 32 from just 33 balls as England won by 241 runs. The second game ended in a high scoring draw, with Broad taking 2\u201394 in South Africa's first innings. In the third Test, Broad took 2\u201382 in South Africa's first innings in a game which looked to be finely poised. However, in South Africa's second innings, he ripped through their top order, finishing with figures of 6\u201317. Included in his six wickets were the prized wickets of AB de Villiers and Hashim Amla. England went on to win the game by seven wickets, with the result giving them an unassailable 2\u20130 series lead. England performed poorly in the final game, with Broad taking three wickets in the match as South Africa secured a victory by a margin of 280 runs, meaning the series finished 2\u20131 to England. As a result of his performances, Broad became the number one ranked Test bowler in the world.\n\nAfter not playing for England in limited overs cricket since their poor showing at the 2015 World Cup, Broad was included in the squad for the ODI series against South Africa. He played in the fourth ODI, although he returned expensive figures, finishing up with 1\u201355 in seven overs, as England lost the game. He was selected in the side for the final game, which proved to be the decider, and although he bowled economically, he did not pick up a wicket and England went on to lose the game and the series 3\u20132.\n\n===2016: Sri Lanka and Pakistan===\nBroad took figures of 4\u201321 in Sri Lanka's first innings of the first Test as they were dismissed for just 91. In the second innings he took 1\u201357 as England won by an innings and 88 runs. In the second match, Broad took 4\u201340 in Sri Lanka's first innings, but was less effective in their second, finishing with just one wicket, as England won the match by nine wickets. In the final rain affected match of the series, Broad took 2\u201379 as Sri Lanka were dismissed for 288, but the match ended in a draw due to the bad weather.\n\nBroad took figures of 3\u201371 in Pakistan's first innings of the first Test, and took 3\u201338 in their second innings, although Pakistan did enough to secure a 75 run victory. In the second Test Broad took 1\u201320 in Pakistan's first innings as they were dismissed for 198 and England secured a 330 run victory. In the third Test, Broad took 3\u201383 in Pakistan's first innings as they reached 400, and then took 2\u201324 in their second innings to help England secure an unlikely victory after dismissing them for 201. In the final match of the series, Broad was less effective, taking just one wicket in the match, as England lost by 10 wickets.\n\n===2016: Bangladesh and India===\nIn the first innings of the first Test against Bangladesh, Broad did not take a wicket in the first innings, although he bowled economically. In the second innings he took figures of 2\u201331 to help England win by 21 runs. He was rested for the second Test, which England lost\n\nBroad played in the first Test against India, taking figures of 1\u201378 in the first innings, before taking 0\u20138 in the second innings as the match ended in a draw. In the second Test he took 1\u201349 as India made 455 in their first innings. He took 4\u201333 in the second innings to restrict India to 204 runs, although India won the match by 246 runs. Broad missed the next two Tests through injury, but returned in the fifth Test. He took figures of 2\u201380 as India scored 759/7 and went on to win the match by 75 runs to win the series 4\u20130.\n\n===2018: New Zealand===\nOn 22 March 2018, In the first Test [[English cricket team in New Zealand in 2017\u201318|against New Zealand]], Broad took his [[List of bowlers who have taken 300 or more wickets in Test cricket|400th wicket in Tests]] and became the youngest fast bowler to do so.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.skysports.com/cricket/news/12173/11299662/stuart-broad-takes-his-400th-test-wicket-on-day-one-of-auckland-test |title=Stuart Broad takes his 400th Test wicket on day one of Auckland Test |accessdate=22 March 2018 |publisher=Sky Sports}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/story/_/id/22866057/stats-stuart-broad-youngest-fast-bowler-400-test-wickets|title=Stuart Broad marches on to become the youngest fast bowler to race for 400 test wickets milestone|publisher=ESPN Cricinfo|access-date=24 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n===2019: Ashes series===\nIn the first Test of the [[2019 Ashes series]], Broad took his 100th wicket in The Ashes in the first innings of the match.<ref>{{cite web |title=Stats: Steve Smith\u2019s record ton on Test comeback inspires Australia to a commanding total|url=https://www.crictracker.com/stats-steve-smiths-record-ton-on-test-comeback-inspires-australia-to-a-commanding-total/ |website=Crictracker |accessdate=2 August 2019 |date=2 August 2019}}</ref> In the second innings of the match, he took his 450th wicket in Test cricket, dismissing [[David Warner (cricketer)|David Warner]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.skysports.com/watch/video/sports/cricket/11776606/broad-gets-warner-again |title=Broad makes Warner 450th Test wicket |work=Sky Sports |accessdate=3 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Achievements and honours==\n\n* On 17 September 2015, [[Nottingham Express Transit|NET]] tram 237 was named in honour of Broad.<ref>[http://www.thetram.net/tram-to-be-named-after-nottinghamshire-and-england-cricket-hero.aspx Tram Named After Cricket Hero] Retrieved 14 June 2016</ref>\n\n* [[File:Order of the British Empire (Civil) Ribbon.png|60px]] He was appointed a [[Member of the Order of the British Empire]] (MBE) in the 2016 Birthday Honours for services to cricket.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=61608 |supp=y|page=B16|date=11 June 2016}}</ref>\n\n* At the conclusion of the 5th Test in [[Indian national cricket team|India's]] [[Indian cricket team in England in 2018|tour of the United Kingdom in 2018]], Broad and Anderson had tallied up 850 test wickets playing together across 111 tests, third all-time on the list of bowling pairs in tests, behind only [[Glenn McGrath]] and [[Shane Warne]] (1,001 wickets in 104 tests together) and [[Chaminda Vaas]] and [[Muttiah Muralitharan]] (895 wickets in 95 tests together).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.skysports.com/cricket/news/13294/10997690/crickets-deadly-bowling-duos-where-do-james-anderson-and-stuart-broad-rank|title=Cricket's deadly bowling duos: Where do James Anderson and Stuart Broad rank?|website=Sky Sports|language=en|access-date=2019-11-28}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nStuart Broad's father, [[Chris Broad]], played Test Cricket for England in 1980s. His sister Gemma works for the England team as a team analyst.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/sport/cricket/article2848462.ece|title=Like father, like son for Broads|work=The Times|date=11 November 2007|accessdate=21 August 2009 | location=London | first=Simon | last=Wilde}}</ref> He supports [[Nottingham Forest F.C.]] and [[Leicester Tigers]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aqa.63336.com/celebrityanswers/ca_stuartbroad.htm|title=AQA 63336 LIVE celebrity answers \u2013 Stuart Broad|publisher=aqa.63336.com|accessdate=1 October 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090918170926/http://www.aqa.63336.com/celebrityanswers/ca_stuartbroad.htm|archivedate=18 September 2009|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Stuart's stepmother Michelle \"Miche\" Broad took her own life in July 2010. She was suffering with [[motor neurone disease]].<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-nottinghamshire-11313359 Death of Stuart Broad's Mother].</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Stuart Broad}}\n*{{Cricinfo|id=10617}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070320071228/http://www.cricket-online.org/player.php?player_id=59495 Cricket Online Profile]\n*[http://www.nottsccc.co.uk/cricket/players/2010/stuart-broad.html Nottinghamshire County Cricket Club Profile]\n\n{{England ODI cricket captains}}\n{{England T20I cricket captains}}\n{{Bowlers who have taken 300 or more wickets in Test cricket}}\n{{Englishmen with 100 or more Test caps}}\n{{Navboxes colour\n|title= England squads \n|bg= skyblue\n|fg= #000060\n|bordercolor=#000060\n|list1=\n{{England Squad 2007 Cricket World Cup}}\n{{England Squad 2010 ICC World Twenty20}}\n{{England Squad 2011 Cricket World Cup}}\n{{England Squad 2015 Cricket World Cup}}\n}}\n{{Nottinghamshire County Cricket Club squad}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2015}}\n{{Use British English|date=August 2011}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Broad, Stuart}}\n[[Category:Articles with inconsistent citation formats]]\n[[Category:England Test cricketers]]\n[[Category:England One Day International cricketers]]\n[[Category:England Twenty20 International cricketers]]\n[[Category:English cricketers of the 21st century]]\n[[Category:Leicestershire cricketers]]\n[[Category:People educated at Oakham School]]\n[[Category:People from Melton Mowbray]]\n[[Category:1986 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Nottinghamshire cricketers]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Nottingham]]\n[[Category:English cricketers]]\n[[Category:Wisden Cricketers of the Year]]\n[[Category:Cricketers at the 2007 Cricket World Cup]]\n[[Category:Cricketers at the 2011 Cricket World Cup]]\n[[Category:Cricketers at the 2015 Cricket World Cup]]\n[[Category:Test cricket hat-trick takers]]\n[[Category:English cricket captains]]\n[[Category:Kings XI Punjab cricketers]]\n[[Category:Members of the Order of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:Hobart Hurricanes cricketers]]\n[[Category:Marylebone Cricket Club cricketers]]\n", "name_user": "103.60.175.78", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eExternal links)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stuart_Broad"}
{"title_page": "Jean Beausejour", "text_new": "{{short description|Chilean footballer}}\n{{Spanish name 2|Beausejour|Coliqueo}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name        = Jean Beausejour\n| image       = Universidad de Chile - Colo-Colo, 2018-04-15 - Jean Beausejour.jpg\n| caption     = Beausejour with [[Club Universidad de Chile|Universidad de Chile]] in 2018\n| image_size  = \n| fullname    = Jean Andr\u00e9 Emanuel Beausejour Coliqueo<ref name=ApoyaLaCausa/>\n| birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1984|6|1|df=y}}<ref name=FIFASquads/>\n| birth_place = [[Santiago]], Chile\n| height      = 1.78 m<ref name=FIFASquads>{{cite web |url=https://www.fifa.com/mm/document/tournament/competition/01/22/85/78/fwc_2010_squadlists.pdf |format=PDF |title=FIFA World Cup South Africa 2010: List of players |publisher=FIFA |date=4 June 2010 |page=6 |accessdate=4 April 2018}}</ref>\n| position    = [[Defender (association football)#Wing-back|Left wing-back]]\n| currentclub = [[Club Universidad de Chile|Universidad de Chile]]\n| clubnumber  = 15\n| youthyears1 = | youthclubs1 = [[Club Universidad de Chile|Universidad de Chile]]\n| youthyears2 = | youthclubs2 = [[Club Deportivo Universidad Cat\u00f3lica|Universidad Cat\u00f3lica]]\n| years1  = 2002\u20132004 | clubs1  = [[Club Deportivo Universidad Cat\u00f3lica|Universidad Cat\u00f3lica]] | caps1  = 16 | goals1  =  3\n| years2  = 2003      | clubs2  = \u2192 [[C.D. Universidad de Concepci\u00f3n|U. de Concepci\u00f3n]] (loan) | caps2  = 30 | goals2  =  3\n| years3  = 2004      | clubs3  = [[Servette FC|Servette]]                                     | caps3  = 11 | goals3  =  1\n| years4  = 2005\u20132006 | clubs4  = [[Gr\u00eamio Foot-Ball Porto Alegrense|Gr\u00eamio]]                  | caps4  = 55 | goals4  =  7\n| years5  = 2006      | clubs5  = [[K.A.A. Gent|Gent]]                                         | caps5  =  0 | goals5  =  0\n| years6  = 2007      | clubs6  = [[Cobreloa]]                                                 | caps6  = 22 | goals6  =  0\n| years7  = 2008      | clubs7  = [[O'Higgins F.C.|O'Higgins]]                                 | caps7  = 34 | goals7  = 13\n| years8  = 2009\u20132010 | clubs8  = [[Club Am\u00e9rica|Am\u00e9rica]]                                     | caps8  = 45 | goals8  =  3\n| years9  = 2010\u20132012 | clubs9  = [[Birmingham City F.C.|Birmingham City]]                     | caps9  = 39 | goals9  =  3\n| years10 = 2012\u20132014 | clubs10 = [[Wigan Athletic F.C.|Wigan Athletic]]                       | caps10 = 85 | goals10 =  3\n| years11 = 2014\u20132016 | clubs11 = [[Colo-Colo]]                                                | caps11 = 54 | goals11 =  7\n| years12 = 2016\u2013     | clubs12 = [[Club Universidad de Chile|Universidad de Chile]]           | caps12 = 69 | goals12 =  1\n<!-- LEAGUE GAMES ONLY - When you update these stats, please also update the club-update parameter by typing ~~~~~ instead of what's already there, the software will convert that to current date/time -->\n| club-update    = 17 January 2020\n| nationalyears1 = 2004\n| nationalteam1  = [[Chile Olympic football team|Chile U23]]\n| nationalcaps1  = 7\n| nationalgoals1 = 2\n| nationalyears2 = 2004\u20132019\n| nationalteam2  = [[Chile national football team|Chile]]\n| nationalcaps2  = 107\n| nationalgoals2 = 6\n<!-- When you update these stats, please also update the nationalteam-update parameter! -->\n| nationalteam-update = 6 July 2019\n| medaltemplates = {{MedalCountry|{{CHI}}}}\n{{Medal|W|[[Copa Am\u00e9rica]]|[[2015 Copa Am\u00e9rica|2015]]}}\n{{Medal|W|[[Copa Am\u00e9rica Centenario]]|[[Copa Am\u00e9rica Centenario|2016]]}}\n{{Medal|RU|[[FIFA Confederations Cup]]|[[2017 FIFA Confederations Cup|2017]]}}\n}}\n'''Jean Andr\u00e9 Emanuel Beausejour Coliqueo''' ({{IPA-es|\u02c8\u025f\u029dam bose\u02c8\u029du\u027e}}; born 1 June 1984) is a Chilean professional [[association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[Defender (association football)#Wing-back|left-sided wing-back]] for [[Chilean Primera Divisi\u00f3n|Primera Divisi\u00f3n]] club [[Club Universidad de Chile|Universidad de Chile]].\n\nHe has played in Chile, Switzerland, Brazil, Belgium, Mexico and England, where he won the [[Football League Cup|League Cup]] with [[Birmingham City F.C.|Birmingham City]] and the [[FA Cup]] with [[Wigan Athletic]].\n\nBeausejour made his debut for the [[Chile national football team|Chilean national team]] in 2004 and his 100th appearance for his country in 2018. He was a member of the [[Copa Am\u00e9rica]]-winning squads in [[2015 Copa Am\u00e9rica|2015]] and [[Copa Am\u00e9rica Centenario|2016]], and is the only Chilean to score in two consecutive [[FIFA World Cup|World Cups]] ([[2010 FIFA World Cup|2010]] and [[2014 FIFA World Cup|2014]]).\n\n==Personal life==\nBeausejour was born in [[Santiago]].<ref name=TheClinic>{{cite news |url=http://www.theclinic.cl/2016/06/10/jean-beausejour-y-el-proceso-constituyente-pocos-quieren-darle-la-posibilidad-de-participar-realmente-a-la-gente/ |title=Jean Beausejour: \"Pocos quieren darle la posibilidad de participar realmente a la gente\" |language=Spanish |trans-title=Jean Beausejour: \"Not many want to give the people the possibility of real participation\" |first=Patricio |last=Fern\u00e1ndez |magazine=The Clinic |location=Santiago |date=10 June 2016 |accessdate=4 April 2018}}</ref> His father, Jean Coty Beausejour,<ref name=Coliqueo>{{cite news |url=http://diario.elmercurio.com/detalle/index.asp?id={d19e897f-4b81-4fda-858d-9963b0e19ccd} |title=El lado Coliqueo de Beausejour |language=Spanish |trans-title=The Coliqueo side of Beausejour |newspaper=El Mercurio |location=Santiago |date=23 August 2014 |accessdate=4 April 2018}}</ref> was a Haitian graduate student of African descent who went on to work for the [[United Nations]],<ref name=ApoyaLaCausa>{{cite news |url=http://www.elciudadano.cl/2009/11/12/14127/jean-beausejour-coliqueo-apoya-la-causa-mapuche/ |title=Jean Beausejour Coliqueo apoya la causa mapuche |language=Spanish |trans-title=Jean Beausejour Coliqueo supports the Mapuche cause |newspaper=El Ciudadano |location=Santiago |date=12 November 2010 |accessdate=4 April 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120115172322/http://www.elciudadano.cl/2009/11/12/14127/jean-beausejour-coliqueo-apoya-la-causa-mapuche/ |archive-date=15 January 2012 |url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=TheClinic/> and his mother, Viviana Coliqueo Collipay,<ref name=SuGente>{{cite web |url=http://www.colocolo.cl/el-futbol-la-tierra-su-gente-y-beausejour/ |title=El f\u00fatbol, la tierra, su gente y Beausejour |language=es |trans-title=Football, the earth, its people and Beausejour |first=Leonardo |last=Salazar M. |publisher=Colo-Colo |date=9 December 2014 |accessdate=4 April 2018}}</ref> is a Chilean of [[Mapuche]] ethnicity whose father, Andres, had migrated to the city to find work.<ref name=Coliqueo/> Beausejour's parents separated when he was very young,<ref name=TheClinic/> and he was raised by his mother and her parents; he regards his grandfather as his father-figure.<ref name=ElCubo>{{cite news |url=http://www.lacuarta.com/noticia/jean-beausejour-sincero-el-cubo/ |title=Jean Beausejour se sincer\u00f3 en ''El Cubo'': Ser mapuche y negro es un orgullo |language=Spanish |trans-title=Jean Beausejour opens up on ''El Cubo'': being Mapuche and black is a matter for pride |first=Felipe |last=Pavez |newspaper=La Cuarta |location=Santiago |date=25 August 2017 |accessdate=4 April 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180405214807/http://www.lacuarta.com/noticia/jean-beausejour-sincero-el-cubo/ |archive-date=5 April 2018 |url-status=dead}}</ref> The family lived in Villa Carmelitas, in the [[Estaci\u00f3n Central]] commune of Santiago, where Beausejour was educated at Escuela Profesor Ram\u00f3n del R\u00edo, Colegio Holanda and Liceo Guillermo Feli\u00fa Cruz.<ref name=Polidep>{{cite news |url=http://municipalidadestacioncentral.cl/polideportivo-de-estacion-central-fue-bautizado-como-jean-beausejour-coliqueo/ |title=Polideportivo de Estaci\u00f3n Central fue bautizado como Jean Beausejour Coliqueo |language=es |trans-title=Estaci\u00f3n Central Sports Centre named after Jean Beausejour Coliqueo |publisher=Municipalidad Estaci\u00f3n Central |date=7 July 2016 |accessdate=4 April 2018}}</ref> In 2010, the local council declared him an ''Hijo Ilustre'', 'honoured son', of the community,<ref name=HijoIllustre>{{cite news |url=http://www.cooperativa.cl/noticias/deportes/mundiales-de-futbol/sudafrica-2010/jean-beausejour-fue-declarado-hijo-ilustre-de-estacion-central/2010-07-07/161750.html |title=Jean Beausejour fue declarado hijo ilustre de Estaci\u00f3n Central |language=es |trans-title=Jean Beausejour declared honoured son of Estaci\u00f3n Central |publisher=Radio Cooperativa |date=7 July 2010 |accessdate=5 July 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150706154509/http://www.cooperativa.cl/noticias/deportes/mundiales-de-futbol/sudafrica-2010/jean-beausejour-fue-declarado-hijo-ilustre-de-estacion-central/2010-07-07/161750.html |archivedate=6 July 2015}}</ref> and six years later a new sports centre was named after him.<ref name=Polidep/>\n\nBecause of his dark skin, he was nicknamed ''Palmatoria'' after a black football-playing character in a [[comics|children's comic]]; despite reports that he hated the name,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.ft.com/content/ddcd2f16-fa25-11e3-a328-00144feab7de |title=World Cup watchers warm to Chile |first=Simon |last=Kuper |newspaper=Financial Times |date=22 June 2014 |accessdate=4 April 2018}}<br>{{cite news |url=http://ecodiario.eleconomista.es/internacional/noticias/2237955/06/10/Jean-Beausejour-el-hijo-de-un-haitiano-nuevo-heroe-de-la-Roja-de-Bielsa.html |title=Jean Beausejour, el hijo de un haitiano, nuevo h\u00e9roe de la 'Roja' de Bielsa |language=Spanish |trans-title=Jean Beausejour, son of a Haitian father, new hero of Bielsa's ''\"Roja\"'' |newspaper=El Economista |location=Madrid |agency=AFP |date=17 June 2010 |accessdate=4 April 2018}}</ref> he says it did not bother him,<ref name=ElCubo/><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.lasegunda.com/Noticias/Deportes/2014/11/975351/el-racismo-que-ronda-al-futbol-nacional |title=El racismo que ronda al f\u00fatbol nacional |language=Spanish |trans-title=The racism that surrounds national football |newspaper=La Segunda |location=Santiago |date=14 November 2014 |accessdate=4 April 2018}}</ref> and that being black caused him fewer problems<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.eldesconcierto.cl/2018/03/02/jean-beausejour-se-mete-en-el-debate-de-la-inmigracion-yo-tuve-mas-problemas-con-el-apellido-mapuche-que-por-ser-negro/ |title=Jean Beausejour se mete en el debate de la inmigraci\u00f3n: 'Yo tuve m\u00e1s problemas con el apellido mapuche que por ser negro' |language=Spanish |trans-title=Jean Beausejour gets into the immigration debate: 'I had more problems with the Mapuche name than with being black' |newspaper=El Desconcierto |location=Santiago |date=2 March 2018 |accessdate=4 April 2018}}</ref> than did the indigenous Mapuche heritage with which he closely identifies.<ref name=ApoyaLaCausa/><ref name=ElCubo/>\n\nBeausejour is married to Karina Ugarte. {{As of|January 2016}}, the couple had two children, Joaqu\u00edn and Luciano.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.observador.cl/6428-jean_beausejour_eligi_la_tranquilidad_de_quillota_para_bautizar_a_su_hijo_menor |title=Jean Beausejour eligi\u00f3 la tranquilidad de Quillota para bautizar a su hijo menor |language=Spanish |trans-title=Jean Beausejour chose the tranquility of Quillota to baptise his younger son |newspaper=El Observador |location=Quillota |date=27 January 2016 |accessdate=12 April 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171014020132/http://www.observador.cl/6428-jean_beausejour_eligi_la_tranquilidad_de_quillota_para_bautizar_a_su_hijo_menor |archive-date=14 October 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Joaqu\u00edn has played football in the junior ranks of Universidad Cat\u00f3lica, the club where his father completed his youth development.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.economiaynegocios.cl/noticias/noticias.asp?id=381624 |title=En San Carlos de Apoquindo se adiestran los hijos de la fama |language=Spanish |trans-title=The sons of the famous do their training at San Carlos de Apoquindo |first=Ra\u00fal |last=Neira B. |newspaper=Econom\u00eda y Negocios |location=Santiago |date=23 July 2017 |accessdate=12 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Club career==\n\n===Early career===\nAs a 10-year-old, Beausejour attended a public trial with the local senior club, [[Club Universidad de Chile|Universidad de Chile]], and was one of four boys chosen to go through further selection procedures to join the club's youth system.<ref name=TheClinic/> At 14, he was released.<ref name=TheClinic/> After a trial with city rivals [[Club Deportivo Universidad Cat\u00f3lica|Universidad Cat\u00f3lica]], he was accepted into their youth system where he continued his football development.<ref name=TheClinic/>\n\nHe began his professional career at Universidad Cat\u00f3lica. In 2002, he debuted after being loaned to [[CD Universidad de Concepci\u00f3n|Universidad de Concepci\u00f3n]] where he had an impressive season alongside [[Jorge Valdivia]].\n\nIn June 2004, he joined Swiss club [[Servette FC|Servette]],<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.emol.com/noticias/deportes/2004/06/16/150531/sin-avisar-jean-beausejour-se-fue-de-la-catolica-al-futbol-suizo.html |title=Sin avisar: Jean Beausejour se fue de la Cat\u00f3lica al f\u00fatbol suizo |language=Spanish |trans-title=Without notice: Jean Beausejour has left Cat\u00f3lica for Swiss football |website=Emol.com |date=16 June 2004 |accessdate=5 April 2018}}</ref> reuniting with Valdivia to play in the [[UEFA Cup]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.emol.com/noticias/deportes/2004/06/24/151283/jorge-valdivia-firmo-en-el-servette-de-beausejour.html |title=Jorge Valdivia firm\u00f3 en el Servette de Beausejour |language=Spanish |trans-title=Jorge Valdivia signed for Beausejour's Servette |website=Emol.com |date=24 June 2004 |accessdate=5 April 2018}}</ref> He scored once from 11 appearances in the [[Swiss Super League]] before the club went bankrupt in February 2005 and it lost its licence to compete at that level.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sfl.ch/fr/news/news/article/les-anecdotes-suisses-de-la-coupe-du-monde-2e-partie/ |title=Les \"anecdotes suisses de la Coupe du Monde\": 2e partie |language=French |trans-title=Swiss World Cup stories: part 2 |publisher=Swiss Football League |date=3 July 2014 |accessdate=6 April 2018}}<br>{{cite web |url=http://www.uefa.com/memberassociations/association=sui/news/newsid=280480.html |title=Final curtain for Servette |publisher=UEFA |date=16 February 2005 |accessdate=6 April 2015}}</ref> His goal, Servette's third in a 4\u20131 win away to [[FC Schaffhausen|Schaffhausen]], proved costly to the player who supplied the cross, [[Paulo Diogo]], who leapt onto the perimeter fence in celebration, caught his wedding ring in the metalwork, and when he jumped down, much of his finger was torn away along with the ring. The finger had to be amputated.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.servettefc.ch/index.php?sp=actu&ida=477 |title=Schaffhouse\u2013Servette 1\u20134 (0\u20132) |language=French |first=Marc |last=Ramer |publisher=Servette FC |date=5 December 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20041209111337/http://www.servettefc.ch/index.php?sp=actu&ida=477 |archivedate=9 December 2004}}<br>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2004/dec/07/newsstory.sport12 |title=No pity for Diogo's fickle finger of fate |first=Mike |last=Baker |newspaper=The Guardian |location=London |date=7 December 2004 |accessdate=6 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2005, Beausejour signed a short-term deal with Brazilian club [[Gr\u00eamio Foot-Ball Porto Alegrense|Gr\u00eamio]],<ref>{{cite news |url=https://theworldgame.sbs.com.au/article/2005/07/02/gremio-signs-chilean-beausejour |title=Gremio signs Chilean Beausejour |website=The World Game |agency=Associated Press |date=2 July 2005 |accessdate=6 April 2015}}</ref> where he helped the team to win the [[S\u00e9rie B]] title.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://espn.uol.com.br/video/348182_caras-da-copa-ex-gremio-o-chileno-beausejour-ja-conquistou-titulos-em-cima-de-arsenal-e-manchester-city |title=Caras da Copa: Ex-Gremio, o Chileno Beausejour j\u00e1 conquistou titulos em cima de Arsenal e Manchester City |language=Portuguese |trans-title=Guys of the Cup: Once of Gremio, the Chilean Beausejour has already beaten Arsenal and Manchester City to win titles |publisher=ESPN Brazil |date=11 August 2013 |accessdate=5 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nHe joined [[KAA Gent]] of Belgium in January 2006 on an 18-month contract,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.uefa.com/memberassociations/news/newsid=390520.html |title=Sinama seals Rovers loan move |publisher=UEFA |date=31 January 2006 |accessdate=6 April 2015}}</ref> but made no appearances and returned to Chile after a year where he signed for [[Cobreloa]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.cooperativa.cl/noticias/site/artic/20070102/pags/20070102095612.html |title=Cobreloa reforz\u00f3 su ataque con Jean Beausejour |language=Spanish |trans-title=Cobreloa strengthened their attack with Jean Beausejour |publisher=Radio Cooperativa |date=2 January 2007 |accessdate=6 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2008, Beausejour joined [[Club Deportivo O'Higgins|O'Higgins]] where he was used as [[Left winger (football)|left winger]] by [[Jorge Sampaoli]] and re-gained status after impressing once again. His performances led him to the [[Chilean national football team|national team]] coached by [[Marcelo Bielsa]] who usually used him in the same position.\n\nOn 1 December 2008, it was reported that Beausejour completed a three-and-half year deal with Mexican club [[Club Am\u00e9rica|Am\u00e9rica]]. He made his debut on 4 January 2009 during a 1\u20131 draw with rivals [[CD Guadalajara|Guadalajara]], scoring the opening goal.\n\nFollowing a one-and-half year spell with the [[M\u00e9xico DF]]\u2013based side and his [[2010 FIFA World Cup|FIFA World Cup]] participation, he signed a three-year contract with [[Premier League]] side [[Birmingham City F.C.|Birmingham City]] for an undisclosed fee in August 2010.\n\n===Birmingham City===\n[[File:Sebasti\u00e1n Pi\u00f1era - Jean Beausejour.jpg|thumb|right|Beausejour with [[President of Chile]] [[Sebasti\u00e1n Pi\u00f1era]], holding a Birmingham City shirt, at London's Olympic Park]]\nAfter 18 months with the [[Mexico City]]-based club followed by a \"tremendous\" [[2010 FIFA World Cup|World Cup]], Beausejour signed a three-year contract with [[Premier League]] club [[Birmingham City F.C.|Birmingham City]] for an undisclosed fee in August 2010. Manager [[Alex McLeish]] stated that Beausejour was a player that had been on their \"list of targets for a long time because he is strong and quick with the ability to beat his man and get crosses in.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.espn.com/blog/los-angeles/soccer/post/_/id/2933/mexico-jean-beausejour-leaves-america-for-england |title=Mexico: Jean Beausejour leaves America for England |first=Scott |last=French |publisher=ESPN |date=31 August 2010 |accessdate=6 April 2018 }}<br>{{cite web |url=http://world.bcfc.com/page/News/NewsDetail/0,,10412~2140094,00.html |title=Beausejour the Blue |publisher=Birmingham City F.C. |date=31 August 2010 |accessdate=5 April 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180407053422/http://world.bcfc.com/page/News/NewsDetail/0,,10412~2140094,00.html |archive-date=7 April 2018 |url-status=dead}}</ref> His debut was delayed while he awaited a working visa,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.skysports.com/football/news/11694/6376580/beausejour-available-for-blues |title=Beausejour available for Blues |publisher=Sky Sports |date=14 September 2010 |accessdate=5 April 2018}}</ref> but he made his first appearance on 18 September as a late substitute, replacing [[Alexander Hleb]] in the 83rd minute as Birmingham lost 3\u20131 at [[West Bromwich Albion]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/9006917.stm |title=West Brom 3\u20131 Birmingham |first=Mark |last=Ashenden |publisher=BBC Sport |date=18 September 2010 |accessdate=18 September 2010}}</ref> He made more impact on his first start, setting up goals for Hleb and [[Nikola \u017digi\u0107]] in the 3\u20131 [[EFL Cup|League Cup]] victory over [[MK Dons]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/9009796.stm |title=Birmingham 3\u20131 MK Dons |publisher=BBC Sport |date=22 September 2010 |accessdate=23 September 2010}}</ref> Described by the ''[[Sunday Mirror]]'' as \"at the heart of everything good about Birmingham\" in the [[FA Cup]] third round against [[Millwall F.C.|Millwall]],<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/sport/football/news/millwall-1-4-birmingham-sunday-mirror-3335472 |title=Millwall 1\u20134 Birmingham: Sunday Mirror match report |newspaper=Sunday Mirror |location=London |date=9 January 2011 |accessdate=5 April 2018}}</ref> Beausejour provided the assist for the opening goal and \"crashed a 20-yard strike off the bar\".<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/fa_cup/9341908.stm |title=Millwall 1\u20134 Birmingham |publisher=BBC Sport |date=8 January 2011 |accessdate=10 January 2011}}</ref> He scored his first goal for the club six minutes into the FA Cup fifth-round defeat of [[Sheffield Wednesday]], with a side-footed shot from a [[Lee Bowyer]] cut-back.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/9401043.stm |title=Birmingham 3\u20130 Sheff Wed |publisher=BBC Sport |date=19 January 2011 |accessdate=21 January 2011}}</ref> He was a second-half substitute as Birmingham won the [[2011 Football League Cup Final|2011 League Cup]], beating favourites [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] 2\u20131 at [[Wembley Stadium]],<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/9405702.stm |title=Arsenal 1\u20132 Birmingham |first=Philip |last=McNulty |publisher=BBC Sport |date=27 February 2011 |accessdate=28 February 2011}}</ref> thus earning qualification for the [[2011\u201312 UEFA Europa League|Europa League]]. On 5 March 2011, Beausejour scored his first Premier League goal in a 3\u20131 defeat at home to West Bromwich Albion,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.birminghammail.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/birmingham-city-1west-bromwich-albion-149778 |title=Birmingham City 1,West Bromwich Albion 3 |first=Colin |last=Tattum |newspaper=Birmingham Mail |date=7 March 2011 |accessdate=5 April 2018}}</ref> and his second came four days later in a 1\u20131 draw at [[Everton F.C.|Everton]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/9415280.stm |title=Everton 1\u20131 Birmingham |first=Saj |last=Chowdhury |publisher=BBC Sport |date=9 March 2011 |accessdate=5 November 2011}}</ref> But his club struggled with injuries for most of the [[2010\u201311 Birmingham City F.C. season|2010\u201311 season]],{{citation needed|date=April 2018}} and were relegated from the Premier League.\n\nBeausejour was the ''[[Birmingham Mail]]''{{'s}} [[man of the match]] in Birmingham's first appearance in major European competition for nearly 50 years, the [[2011\u201312 UEFA Europa League#Play-off round|Europa League play-off round]] first leg against Portuguese club [[C.D. Nacional|Nacional]], which finished goalless.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.birminghammail.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/nacional-0-birmingham-city-0-159852 |title=Nacional 0, Birmingham City 0 |newspaper=Birmingham Mail |first=Colin |last=Tattum |date=19 August 2011 |accessdate=5 April 2018}}</ref> Just days after manager [[Chris Hughton]] suggested he wanted more from Beausejour in an attacking role,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.birminghammail.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/jean-beausejour-urged-to-increase-his-goal-163397 |title=Jean Beausejour urged to increase his goal output at Birmingham City |newspaper=Birmingham Mail |first=Colin |last=Tattum |date=15 October 2011 |accessdate=5 April 2018}}</ref> the player had an eventful man-of-the-match performance as Birmingham beat [[Leicester City F.C.|Leicester City]] 2\u20130. In the first few minutes of the second half, he \"hit the angle of post and bar with a fierce shot\", was considered fortunate by visiting manager [[Sven-G\u00f6ran Eriksson]] to escape a second yellow card, and was tripped by [[Andy King (footballer born 1988)|Andy King]] to earn a penalty kick from which [[Marlon King]] opened the scoring.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/football-league/eriksson-refuses-to-see-red-as-leicester-pay-for-indiscipline-2371649.html |title=Eriksson refuses to see red as Leicester pay for indiscipline |newspaper=The Independent |first=Jon |last=Culley |date=17 October 2011 |accessdate=17 October 2011}}</ref> In the [[2011\u201312 UEFA Europa League group stage|Europa League group stage]], an error by Beausejour led to [[Club Brugge]]'s second goal, but he scored from the rebound after \u017digi\u0107's shot was blocked and was fouled for the penalty from which King equalised.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.uefa.com/uefaeuropaleague/index.html#/iv/match/2007363/stories/1669323 |title=Birmingham fight back against Club Brugge |publisher=UEFA |date=3 November 2011 |accessdate=5 April 2018}}</ref> His first league goal of the season came against [[Burnley F.C.|Burnley]] in November, again from a rebound, in the second minute of a match that Birmingham won 2\u20131 in stoppage time.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/15732474 |title=Birmingham 2\u20131 Burnley |first=Karen |last=Fazackerley |publisher=BBC Sport |date=22 November 2011 |accessdate=6 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Wigan Athletic===\nOn 25 January 2012, Beausejour joined Premier League club [[Wigan Athletic F.C.|Wigan Athletic]] for an undisclosed fee, signing a two-and-a-half-year contract.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/16692150 |title=Wigan sign Birmingham City winger Jean Beausejour |publisher=BBC Sport |date=25 January 2012 |accessdate=5 April 2018}}</ref> He made his debut in the 3\u20131 defeat against [[Tottenham Hotspur]] at [[White Hart Lane]] on 31 January.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.skysports.com/football/match_commentary/0,19764,11065_3408808,00.html |title=FT: Tottenham 3 Wigan 1 |first=Razwan |last=Mirza |publisher=Sky Sports |date=31 January 2012 |accessdate=1 February 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120203020459/http://www.skysports.com/football/match_commentary/0%2C19764%2C11065_3408808%2C00.html |archivedate=3 February 2012}}</ref> On his home debut, against [[Everton F.C.|Everton]], his man-of-the-match performance featured a \"low cross [that] struck [[Phil Neville]] on the foot, before heading in the direction of [[Tim Howard]], but the ball spun sharply, slipping through the American's grasp\" for an [[own goal]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/premier-league/baines-sees-own-goal-as-sods-law-6577512.html |title=Baines sees own goal as Sod's law |first=Will |last=Unwin |newspaper=The Independent |date=6 February 2012 |accessdate=6 February 2012}}</ref> Beausejour slotted well into the [[Formation (association football)#3\u20134\u20133|3\u20134\u20133 formation]] playing at left [[defender (association football)#Wing-back|wing back]].{{Citation needed|date=April 2012}} He helped his team reach the [[2013 FA Cup Final]], but a hamstring injury meant he missed the match itself,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://en.espn.co.uk/football/sport/story/205742.html |title=Wigan set to lose Beausejour for FA Cup final |publisher=ESPN |date=5 May 2013 |accessdate=5 April 2018}}</ref> in which Wigan beat [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] 1\u20130 at [[Wembley Stadium|Wembley]] to win the first major trophy in their history.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/22409634 |title=FA Cup final: Manchester City 0\u20131 Wigan Athletic |first=Phil |last=McNulty |publisher=BBC Sport |date=11 May 2013 |accessdate=5 April 2018}}</ref> Beausejour's second consecutive Premier League relegation was confirmed just days later after a 4\u20131 defeat at the hands of [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://en.espn.co.uk/football/sport/story/207273.html |title=Martinez: Defence to blame |publisher=ESPN |date=15 May 2013 |accessdate=6 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nHe left Wigan Athletic in June 2014 when his contract expired.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.wiganathletic.com/news/2014/july/club-confirm-contracts-expire/ |title=Club confirm contracts expire |publisher=Wigan Athletic F.C. |date=7 July 2014 |accessdate=5 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Colo-Colo===\n\n====2014\u201315 season====\n[[File:INDEPENDIENTE vs COLO COLO (2) cropped.jpg|thumb|150px|right|Beausejour with [[Colo-Colo]]]]\nAfter his participation in the [[2014 FIFA World Cup|World Cup]], Beausejour returned to Chile to play for recent league champions [[Colo-Colo]]. He signed a two-year contract<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.emol.com/noticias/deportes/2014/07/10/669345/un-refuerzo-de-categoria-para-hector-tapia-jean-beausejour-llega-a-acuerdo-con-colo-colo.html |title=Refuerzo de categor\u00eda para H\u00e9ctor Tapia: Jean Beausejour firma por Colo Colo |website=Emol.com |date=10 July 2014 |accessdate=29 December 2014}}</ref> at reported wages of 34&nbsp;million [[Chilean peso|pesos]] ($68,000 approx.) a month.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.latercera.com/noticia/deportes/2014/07/656-586908-9-los-sueldos-mas-altos-que-marcaran-el-torneo-de-apertura-2014.shtml |title=Los sueldos m\u00e1s altos que marcar\u00e1n el Torneo de Apertura 2014 |language=Spanish |trans-title=The highest wages in the 2014 Apertura |first=Mat\u00edas |last=Parker Castro |newspaper=La Tercera |date=18 July 2014 |accessdate=5 April 2018}}</ref> International clearance permitting, coach [[H\u00e9ctor Tapia]] planned to put Beausejour straight into the starting eleven at left back at the expense of [[Luis Pavez Mu\u00f1oz|Luis Pavez]],<ref>{{cite news |url=http://deportes.terra.cl/futbol/primera-division/beausejour-seria-titular-en-colo-colo-como-lateral-izquierdo,c24641d8f0647410VgnVCM3000009af154d0RCRD.html |title=Beausejour ser\u00eda titular en Colo Colo como lateral izquierdo |language=Spanish |trans-title=Beausejour will start for Colo Colo at left back |website=Terra Deportes |date=12 July 2014 |accessdate=29 December 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140720001006/http://deportes.terra.cl/futbol/primera-division/beausejour-seria-titular-en-colo-colo-como-lateral-izquierdo,c24641d8f0647410VgnVCM3000009af154d0RCRD.html |archivedate=20 July 2014}}</ref> but he made his competitive debut in the second match of the [[2014 Torneo Apertura (Chile)|Torneo Apertura]], on 27 June against [[Deportes Iquique]]. Colo-Colo won 2\u20130, both goals scored by [[Esteban Paredes]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://deportes.terra.cl/futbol/primera-division/de-la-mano-de-paredes-colo-colo-vence-en-debut-de-beausejour,cdd357ba93a77410VgnVCM3000009af154d0RCRD.html |title=De la mano de Paredes Colo Colo vence en debut de Beausejour |language=Spanish |trans-title=By the hand of Paredes Colo Colo win on Beausejour's debut |website=Terra Deportes |date=27 July 2014 |accessdate=29 December 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141230095708/http://deportes.terra.cl/futbol/primera-division/de-la-mano-de-paredes-colo-colo-vence-en-debut-de-beausejour,cdd357ba93a77410VgnVCM3000009af154d0RCRD.html |archivedate=30 December 2014}}</ref> On 31 August, Beausejour scored his first competitive goal in a 4\u20130 home win over [[Deportes Antofagasta]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.elmostrador.cl/dia/2014/08/31/colo-colo-derrota-4-0-a-antofagasta-y-sigue-a-la-caza-de-la-u/ |title=Colo-Colo derrota 4\u20130 a Antofagasta y sigue a la caza de la U |language=Spanish |trans-title=Colo-Colo beat Antofagasta 4\u20130 and keep on the track of \"''la U''\" (Universidad de Chile) |newspaper=El Mostrador |agency=UPI Chile |date=12 July 2014 |accessdate=5 April 2018}}</ref> After scoring his second goal, on 14 September against [[CD Palestino|Palestino]] in a 3\u20131 away win, he was sent off for striking [[Leonardo Valencia]] and received a two-match suspension.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://cnnchile.com/noticia/2014/09/14/colo-colo-derroto-3-a-1-a-palestino |title=Colo Colo derrot\u00f3 3 a 1 a Palestino |language=Spanish |trans-title=Colo Colo beat Palestino 3\u20131 |publisher=CNN Chile |date=14 September 2014 |accessdate=5 April 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.emol.com/noticias/deportes/2014/09/16/680641/jean-beausejour-recibio-dos-fechas-de-sancion-y-podra-jugar-el-superclasico-con-la-u.html |title=Dos fechas de sanci\u00f3n para Beausejour y podr\u00e1 jugar el supercl\u00e1sico |language=Spanish |trans-title=Two-match ban for Beausejour and could play in the ''supercl\u00e1sico'' |website=Emol.com |date=12 July 2014 |accessdate=5 April 2018}}</ref> His first match back after the ban was the ''[[Chilean football derby|supercl\u00e1sico]]'' against [[Club Universidad de Chile|Universidad de Chile]] on 19 October, in which he scored his side's second goal in a 2\u20130 victory at the [[Estadio Monumental David Arellano|Estadio Monumental]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.emol.com/noticias/deportes/2014/10/19/685815/colo-colo-se-queda-con-el-superclasico-y-queda-a-2-puntos-de-la-u-en-un-encendido-torneo.html |title=Colo Colo gana el Supercl\u00e1sico y queda a 2 puntos de la U. de Chile en un encendido Torneo |language=Spanish |trans-title=Colo Colo win the Supercl\u00e1sico and are only 2 points off U. de Chile in a fired-up Torneo |website=Emol.com |date=19 October 2014 |accessdate=30 December 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.espn.co.uk/football/blog/name/68/post/2098235/headline |title=Colo Colo's Santiago derby win forces Chilean league down to the wire |first=Tim |last=Vickery |publisher=ESPN |date=20 October 2014 |accessdate=6 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 30 December 2014, Beausejour appeared in the club's 3\u20132 [[:es:Noche Alba|Noche Alba]] win over [[Uni\u00f3n Espa\u00f1ola]] at which the club presented new signings [[Humberto Suazo]] and [[Luis Pedro Figueroa]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www2.latercera.com/noticia/humberto-suazo-redebuta-en-colo-colo-con-triunfo-ante-union-espanola/ |title=Humberto Suazo redebuta en Colo Colo con triunfo ante Uni\u00f3n Espa\u00f1ola |language=Spanish |trans-title=Humberto Suazo makes his second debut for Colo Colo with a win against Uni\u00f3n Espa\u00f1ola |first=R. |last=Retamal |newspaper=La Tercera |date=30 December 2014 |accessdate=5 April 2018}}</ref> They made a poor start to the [[2014\u201315 Primera Divisi\u00f3n of Chile#Torneo Clausura|Clausura]] with a 1\u20130 defeat at home to [[San Marcos de Arica]] on 4 January 2015,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.24horas.cl/deportes/torneodeclausura2015/colo-colo-cae-ante-san-marcos-en-su-debut-en-el-clausura-1545852 |title=Colo Colo cae ante San Marcos en su debut en el Clausura |language=Spanish |trans-title=Colo Colo go down to San Marcos on the opening day of the Clausura |website=24 Horas |publisher=Televisi\u00f3n Nacional de Chile |date=4 January 2014 |accessdate=5 April 2018}}</ref> but ended a four-match winless streak with a 2\u20130 win away to [[O'Higgins F.C.|O'Higgins]] in which Beausejour scored his first goal of the season.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.emol.com/noticias/deportes/2015/02/01/701868/deja-atras-su-mal-inicio-colo-colo-derrota-a-ohiggins-y-logra-su-primer-triunfo-en-el-clausura.html |title=F\u00fatbol Colo Colo deja atr\u00e1s su mal inicio: Derrota a O'Higgins y logra su primer triunfo en el Clausura |language=Spanish |trans-title=Colo Colo leave their bad start behind: Beat O'Higgins for their first win of the Clausura |website=Emol.com |date=1 February 2014 |accessdate=5 April 2018}}</ref> He started the most part of the tournament as full back, completing fourteen games and one goal in a tournament which Colo-Colo finished runner-up.\n\n====2015\u201316 season====\nFor the [[2015\u201316 Chilean Primera Divisi\u00f3n season|2015\u201316 season]] under new coach [[Jos\u00e9 Luis Sierra]], Beausejour returned to his original position of left winger. On 15 September, he scored his fifth competitive goal for the club, his first of the [[2015 Torneo Apertura (Chile)|2015 Apertura]], in a 3\u20131 home win over [[Uni\u00f3n La Calera]] that extended the team's perfect start to six league matches.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.24horas.cl/deportes/futbol-nacional/colo-colo-gana-y-se-afirma-en-la-cima-del-apertura-1786310 |title=Colo Colo gana y se afirma en la cima del Apertura |language=Spanish |trans-title=Colo Colo win and stay top of the Apertura |website=24 Horas |publisher=Televisi\u00f3n Nacional de Chile |date=31 October 2015 |accessdate=22 November 2015}}</ref> Beausejour produced his second consecutive goal in Chilean derbies when he opened the scoring with a header in Colo-Colo's 2\u20130 victory over Universidad de Chile on 31 October.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.goal.com/es-cl/news/4778/main/2015/10/31/16862232/colo-colo-extendi%C3%B3-su-paternidad-ante-la-u-en-el-monumental |title=Colo Colo extendi\u00f3 su paternidad ante la U en el Monumental |language=Spanish |trans-title=Colo Colo extended their superiority over ''la U'' at the Monumental |website=Goal.com |date=31 October 2015 |accessdate=6 April 2018}}</ref> On 6 December, he finally won a domestic league title as Colo-Colo clinched their 31st in embarrassing circumstances: rivals Universidad Cat\u00f3lica lost to [[Audax Italiano]], while Colo-Colo's match, away to [[Santiago Wanderers]], was abandoned before it started because of violent incidents by their own supporters.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.emol.com/noticias/Deportes/2015/12/06/762660/En-medio-de-un-bochornoso-final-Colo-Colo-se-corona-campeon-y-baja-su-estrella-31.html |title=En medio de un bochornoso final, Colo Colo se corona campe\u00f3n y baja su estrella 31 |language=Spanish |trans-title=In the midst of an embarrassing finale, Colo Colo are crowned champions and get their 31st star |website=Emol.com |date=6 December 2015 |accessdate=6 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\n[[File:Jean Beausejour (10888029965).jpg|250px|thumb|right|Beausejour in a friendly match against [[England national football team|England]] at [[Wembley Stadium]] in November 2013.]]\nBeausejour has played for Chile at [[Chile Olympic football team|under-23]] and [[Chile national football team|senior levels]]. He was capped for Chile at the [[2004 CONMEBOL Men Pre-Olympic Tournament|2004 South American Pre-Olympic Tournament]] alongside players such as [[Jorge Valdivia]], [[Mark Gonz\u00e1lez]], [[Claudio Bravo]] and [[Rodrigo Millar]]. However, the team failed to qualify for the [[Football at the 2004 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's tournament|Athens Olympics]], finishing bottom of the final stage after topping their first-stage group, which included [[Brazil national under-23 football team|Brazil]] and eventual qualifiers [[Paraguay national under-23 football team|Paraguay]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tabless/sam-olyqual04.html |title=South-American Olympic Qualifying Tournament 2004 |first=Luis Antonio |last=Reyes |publisher=Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation (RSSSF) |date=28 January 2004 |accessdate=6 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nHe made his senior debut in a [[exhibition match#Friendly international|friendly]] against [[Mexico national football team|Mexico]] in the United States on 18 February 2004, and made the assist for [[Reinaldo Navia]]'s goal in a 1\u20131 draw.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.socceramerica.com/publications/article/5922/international-mexico-chile-in-home-depot-center.html |title=International: Mexico, Chile in Home Depot Center stalemate |publisher=Soccer America |date=19 February 2004 |accessdate=8 April 2018}}</ref> He played twice more that year, but did not appear again until 2008.<ref name=SoloFutbol>{{cite web |url=http://www.solofutbol.cl/seleccion%20chilena/jugadores%20seleccion%20chilena%20B/beausejour,%20jean.html |title=Jean Beausejour |website=solofutbol.cl |accessdate=6 April 2018}}</ref> His first international goal came on 10 June 2009 in a 4\u20130 defeat of [[Bolivia national football team|Bolivia]] at the [[Estadio Nacional Julio Mart\u00ednez Pr\u00e1danos|Estadio Nacional]] in a [[2010 FIFA World Cup qualification (CONMEBOL)|World Cup qualifier]].<ref name=BoliviaGoal/>\n\n[[Marcelo Bielsa]] named Beausejour in [[2010 FIFA World Cup squads#Chile|Chile's 23-man squad]] for the [[2010 FIFA World Cup|2010 World Cup]] finals. He scored the only goal of their first [[2010 FIFA World Cup Group H#Honduras vs Chile|group match]] against [[Honduras national football team|Honduras]] on 16 June, which was the first match that Chile had won at a World Cup since [[1962 FIFA World Cup|1962]].<ref name=HondurasGoal/> He played in all Chile's matches at the tournament until their elimination by [[Brazil national football team|Brazil]] in the round of 16.<ref name=FIFA2010>{{cite web |url=https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/archive/southafrica2010/players/player=209502/profile.html |title=2010 FIFA World Cup \u2013 Jean Beausejour |publisher=FIFA |accessdate=4 June 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130123130459/http://www.fifa.com/worldcup/archive/southafrica2010/players/player=209502/profile.html |archivedate=23 January 2013}}</ref>\n\nDuring the [[2014 FIFA World Cup qualification]] process, he and four teammates were dropped from the national team by coach [[Claudio Borghi (football manager)|Claudio Borghi]] before a match against [[Uruguay national football team|Uruguay]] in 2011 because they returned to Chile's training camp late and intoxicated after attending the baptism of Valdivia's child.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/news/story/_/id/982037/chile-stars-sent-home-for-breaking-curfew?cc=5739 |title=Chile stars sent home in disgrace |publisher=ESPN Soccernet |date=9 November 2011 |accessdate=27 December 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140103005217/http://espnfc.com/news/story/_/id/982037/chile-stars-sent-home-for-breaking-curfew?cc=5739 |archivedate=3 January 2014}}</ref> The [[Asociaci\u00f3n Nacional de F\u00fatbol Profesional]] (ANFP) increased the suspension to ten matches, and Borghi said that while he remained coach, neither Beausejour nor Valdivia would be selected even after the ban.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://uk.reuters.com/article/uk-soccer-latam-chile/five-chile-players-banned-10-games-for-indiscipline-idUKTRE7BK0AW20111221 |title=Five Chile players banned 10 games for indiscipline |first=Rex |last=Gowar |publisher=Reuters |date=21 December 2011 |accessdate=8 April 2018}}<br>{{cite news |url=http://diario.elmercurio.com/detalle/index.asp?id={89142511-19c2-4f90-995d-0533202e3588} |title=Valdivia y Beausejour no vuelven ni aunque los indulten |language=Spanish |trans-title=Valdivia and Beausejour are not coming back even if they are reprieved |newspaper=El Mercurio |location=Santiago |date=20 December 2011 |accessdate=8 April 2018}}</ref> Nevertheless, Borghi recalled Beausejour and [[Gonzalo Jara]] to the squad as soon as they had served their time, for a friendly against [[Colombia national football team|Colombia]],<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.lanacion.cl/hay-nomina-jean-beausejour-y-gonzalo-jara-vuelven-a-la-roja/noticias/2012-08-22/213901.html |title=Hay n\u00f3mina: Jean Beausejour y Gonzalo Jara vuelven a la Roja |language=Spanish |trans-title=Here's the list: Jean Beausejour and Gonzalo Jara return to the national team |newspaper=La Naci\u00f3n |location=Santiago |date=22 August 2012 |accessdate=6 July 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150709003910/http://www.lanacion.cl/hay-nomina-jean-beausejour-y-gonzalo-jara-vuelven-a-la-roja/noticias/2012-08-22/213901.html |archivedate=9 July 2015}}</ref> and Beausejour made his first international appearance for a year in a World Cup qualifier against [[Ecuador national football team|Ecuador]].<ref name=SoloFutbol/> After Borghi was replaced by [[Jorge Sampaoli]], Beausejour's former coach at O'Higgins, he played most of the remaining World Cup qualification process,<ref name=RSSSF>{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/miscellaneous/beausejour-intl.html |title=Jean Andr\u00e9 Emanuel Beausejour \u2013 International Appearances |first=Roberto |last=Mamrud |publisher=RSSSF |date=11 January 2018 |accessdate=6 April 2018}}</ref> alongside Valdivia, who was recalled to the squad in March 2013.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.emol.com/noticias/deportes/2013/03/07/587358/oficial-jorge-valdivia-vuelve-a-la-seleccion-chilena-despues-de-17-meses.html |title=Jorge Valdivia vuelve a la selecci\u00f3n chilena despu\u00e9s de 16 meses |language=Spanish |trans-title=Jorge Valdivia returns to the Chile team after 16 months |website=Emol.com |date=22 August 2012 |accessdate=6 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nDespite scepticism as to Sampaoli putting loyalty ahead of form where Beausejour was concerned, he was included in the [[2014 FIFA World Cup squads#Chile|23-man squad]] for the [[2014 FIFA World Cup]] in Brazil.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.espn.co.uk/football/blog/name/68/post/2098235/headline |title=No surprises in Chile's 23 |first=Angus |last=McNeice |publisher=ESPN |date=2 June 2014 |accessdate=6 April 2018}}</ref> During the first [[2014 FIFA World Cup Group B#Chile vs Australia|group match]], he scored with a shot from outside the box that beat [[Australia national association football team|Australia]] goalkeeper [[Mathew Ryan]] to complete his side's 3\u20131 victory and become the first ever Chilean to score in two different World Cup tournaments.<ref name=AustraliaGoal/>\n\nBeausejour was a member of Chile's [[2015 Copa Am\u00e9rica]] squad that won the tournament for the first time. He played the whole 120 minutes of [[2015 Copa Am\u00e9rica Final|the final]], in which Chile beat [[Argentina national football team|Argentina]] 4\u20131 [[Penalty shoot-out (association football)|on penalties]] at the Estadio Nacional.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/live/2015/jul/04/copa-america-2015-final-chile-argentina-live |title=Chile win Copa Am\u00e9rica after beating Argentina on penalties \u2013 as it happened |first=Tim |last=Hill |website=The Guardian |location=London |date=5 June 2015 |accessdate=6 April 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.alairelibre.cl/noticias/deportes/copa-america/chile-2015/chile-ya-tiene-nomina-definitiva-para-la-copa-america-2015/2015-05-30/154013.html |title=Chile ya tiene n\u00f3mina definitiva para la Copa Am\u00e9rica 2015 |language=Spanish |trans-title=Chile now have a definitive list for the Copa Am\u00e9rica |website=Al Aire Libre |date=30 May 2015 |accessdate=6 April 2018}}</ref> He and his country repeated their success in the following year's [[Copa Am\u00e9rica Centenario|centenary edition]]. Again he played the full 120 minutes of [[Copa Am\u00e9rica Centenario Final|the final]] against Argentina, which again finished goalless [[after extra time]]. This time he took and converted the fourth penalty as Chile went on to win the shootout 4\u20132.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.espn.com/soccer/report?gameId=444696 |title=Lionel Messi misses penalty as Chile beat Argentina in Copa final |publisher=ESPN |date=27 June 2016 |accessdate=6 April 2018}}</ref> Along with seven of his teammates, Beausejour was included in the [[Copa Am\u00e9rica Centenario#Team of the tournament|Tournament Best XI]].<ref name=BestXI>{{cite web |url=http://www.concacaf.com/article/tsg-announces-copa-america-centenario-awards |title=TSG announces Copa Am\u00e9rica Centenario awards |publisher=CONCACAF |date=27 June 2016 |accessdate=2 July 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160701144252/http://www.concacaf.com/article/tsg-announces-copa-america-centenario-awards |archivedate=1 July 2016}}</ref> The 2015 victory qualified Chile for the [[2017 FIFA Confederations Cup|2017 Confederations Cup]]. Beausejour started the first two group matches and was unused in the third. He came back into the team for the semifinal, in which Chile beat [[Portugal national football team|Portugal]] 3\u20130 on penalties, and started in [[2017 FIFA Confederations Cup Final|the final]], which Chile lost 1\u20130 to [[Germany national football team|Germany]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesi/intconcup2017.html |title=Intercontinental Cup for Nations 2017 |first=Neil |last=Morrison |publisher=RSSSF |date=5 July 2017 |accessdate=9 April 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://en.as.com/en/2017/06/28/football/1498635097_929907.html |title=Hero Bravo sends Chile to final after Portugal's penalty pain |first1=C. |last1=Roche |first2=W. |last2=Allen |website=Diario AS |location=Madrid |date=29 June 2017 |accessdate=9 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn a friendly against [[Denmark national football team|Denmark]] on 27 March 2018, Beausejour and [[Arturo Vidal]] became the sixth and seventh players to make their 100th appearances for Chile.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.prensafutbol.cl/227589-al-club-centenario-vidal-y-beausejour-sumaron-100-partidos-con-chile/ |title=Club de los 100: Vidal y Beausejour cumplieron su centenario |language=Spanish |trans-title=100 Club: Vidal and Beausejour complete their centuries |website=Prensa F\u00fatbol |date=27 March 2018 |accessdate=5 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n===International===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|colspan=\"3\"|[[Chile national football team|Chile national team]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.solofutbol.cl/seleccion%20chilena/jugadores%20seleccion%20chilena%20B/beausejour,%20jean.html |title=Jean Beausejour |website=solofutbol.cl |accessdate=5 April 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n!Year!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n|2004||3||0\n|-\n|2008||9||0\n|-\n|2009||11||1\n|-\n|2010||8||1\n|-\n|2011||12||1\n|-\n|2012||3||0\n|-\n|2013||11||2\n|-\n|2014||8||1\n|-\n|2015||8||0\n|-\n|2016||12||0\n|-\n|2017||13||0\n|-\n|2018||3||0\n|-\n|2019||6||0\n|-\n!Total||107||6\n|}\n\n===International goals===\n''The scores and results list Chile's tally first, scores list each Beausejour goal''\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\n! No. !! Date !! Venue !! Opponent !! Score !! Result !! Competition !! Ref\n|-\n| 1. || 10 June 2009|| [[Estadio Nacional de Chile]], [[Santiago]], Chile || {{fb|BOL}} ||align=\"center\"| 1\u20130 ||align=\"center\"| 4\u20130 || [[2010 FIFA World Cup qualification (CONMEBOL)|2010 FIFA World Cup qualification]]\n|align=\"center\"|<ref name=BoliviaGoal>{{cite news |url=https://www.usatoday.com/sports/soccer/2009-06-10-2210789855_x.htm |title=Chile beats Bolivia 4\u20130 in qualifying |agency=Associated Press |publisher=USA Today |date=10 June 2009 |accessdate=4 April 2011}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2. || 16 June 2010 || [[Mbombela Stadium]], [[Nelspruit]], South Africa || {{fb|HON}} ||align=\"center\"| 1\u20130 ||align=\"center\"| 1\u20130 || [[2010 FIFA World Cup]]\n|align=\"center\"|<ref name=HondurasGoal>{{cite web |url=https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/matches/round=249722/match=300061495/match-report.html |title=Beausejour ends Chile wait |publisher=FIFA |date=16 June 2010 |accessdate=6 April 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n| 3. || 29 March 2011 || [[Kyocera Stadion]], [[The Hague]], Netherlands || {{fb|COL}} ||align=\"center\"| 2\u20130 ||align=\"center\"| 2\u20130 || [[Exhibition game#Friendly international|Friendly]]\n|align=\"