\n'''Chile'''\n*[[Copa Am\u00e9rica]]: [[2015 Copa Am\u00e9rica|2015]], [[Copa Am\u00e9rica Centenario|2016]]\n\n===Individual===\n* Copa Am\u00e9rica Team of the Tournament: [[Copa Am\u00e9rica Centenario#Team of the tournament|2016]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.concacaf.com/article/tsg-announces-copa-america-centenario-awards |title=TSG announces Copa Am\u00e9rica Centenario awards |publisher=CONCACAF |date=27 June 2016 |accessdate=2 July 2016}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Soccerbase}}\n* {{Soccerway|jean-andre-emanuel-beausejour/22036}}\n* [http://www.football-lineups.com/footballer/11990/ Jean Beausejour at Football Lineups]\n\n{{Navboxes colour\n|title= Chile squads\n|bg = #E30013\n|fg = white\n|bordercolor = #0035AD\n|list1=\n{{Chile squad 2010 FIFA World Cup}}\n{{Chile squad 2011 Copa Am\u00e9rica}}\n{{Chile squad 2014 FIFA World Cup}}\n{{Chile squad 2015 Copa Am\u00e9rica}}\n{{Chile squad Copa Am\u00e9rica Centenario}}\n{{Chile squad 2017 FIFA Confederations Cup}}\n{{Chile squad 2019 Copa Am\u00e9rica}}\n}}\n{{Universidad de Chile squad}}\n{{Copa Am\u00e9rica Centenario Team of the Tournament}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Beausejour, Jean}}\n[[Category:1984 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Santiago]]\n[[Category:Chilean footballers]]\n[[Category:Chile international footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football wingers]]\n[[Category:Club Deportivo Universidad Cat\u00f3lica footballers]]\n[[Category:Universidad de Concepci\u00f3n footballers]]\n[[Category:Servette FC players]]\n[[Category:Gr\u00eamio Foot-Ball Porto Alegrense players]]\n[[Category:K.A.A. Gent players]]\n[[Category:Cobreloa footballers]]\n[[Category:O'Higgins F.C. footballers]]\n[[Category:Club Am\u00e9rica footballers]]\n[[Category:Birmingham City F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Wigan Athletic F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Colo-Colo footballers]]\n[[Category:Universidad de Chile footballers]]\n[[Category:Liga MX players]]\n[[Category:Chilean Primera Divisi\u00f3n players]]\n[[Category:Premier League players]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n[[Category:2010 FIFA World Cup players]]\n[[Category:2011 Copa Am\u00e9rica players]]\n[[Category:2014 FIFA World Cup players]]\n[[Category:2015 Copa Am\u00e9rica players]]\n[[Category:Copa Am\u00e9rica Centenario players]]\n[[Category:2017 FIFA Confederations Cup players]]\n[[Category:2019 Copa Am\u00e9rica players]]\n[[Category:Chilean people of Haitian descent]]\n[[Category:Chilean people of Mapuche descent]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Switzerland]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Brazil]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Belgium]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Mexico]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in England]]\n[[Category:Chilean expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Indigenous sportspeople of the Americas]]\n[[Category:Chilean expatriate sportspeople in England]]\n[[Category:Copa Am\u00e9rica-winning players]]\n[[Category:FIFA Century Club]]\n[[Category:Mapuche sportspeople]]\n[[Category:20th-century Mapuche people]]\n[[Category:21st-century Mapuche people]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Chilean footballer}}\n{{Spanish name 2|Beausejour|Coliqueo}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name        = Jean Beausejour\n| image       = Universidad de Chile - Colo-Colo, 2018-04-15 - Jean Beausejour.jpg\n| caption     = Beausejour with [[Club Universidad de Chile|Universidad de Chile]] in 2018\n| image_size  = \n| fullname    = Jean Andr\u00e9 Emanuel Beausejour Coliqueo<ref name=ApoyaLaCausa/>\n| birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1984|6|1|df=y}}<ref name=FIFASquads/>\n| birth_place = [[Santiago]], Chile\n| height      = 1.78 m<ref name=FIFASquads>{{cite web |url=https://www.fifa.com/mm/document/tournament/competition/01/22/85/78/fwc_2010_squadlists.pdf |format=PDF |title=FIFA World Cup South Africa 2010: List of players |publisher=FIFA |date=4 June 2010 |page=6 |accessdate=4 April 2018}}</ref>\n| position    = [[Defender (association football)#Wing-back|Left wing-back]]\n| currentclub = [[Club Universidad de Chile|Universidad de Chile]]\n| clubnumber  = 15\n| youthyears1 = | youthclubs1 = [[Club Universidad de Chile|Universidad de Chile]]\n| youthyears2 = | youthclubs2 = [[Club Deportivo Universidad Cat\u00f3lica|Universidad Cat\u00f3lica]]\n| years1  = 2002\u20132004 | clubs1  = [[Club Deportivo Universidad Cat\u00f3lica|Universidad Cat\u00f3lica]] | caps1  = 16 | goals1  =  3\n| years2  = 2003      | clubs2  = \u2192 [[C.D. Universidad de Concepci\u00f3n|U. de Concepci\u00f3n]] (loan) | caps2  = 30 | goals2  =  3\n| years3  = 2004      | clubs3  = [[Servette FC|Servette]]                                     | caps3  = 11 | goals3  =  1\n| years4  = 2005\u20132006 | clubs4  = [[Gr\u00eamio Foot-Ball Porto Alegrense|Gr\u00eamio]]                  | caps4  = 55 | goals4  =  7\n| years5  = 2006      | clubs5  = [[K.A.A. Gent|Gent]]                                         | caps5  =  0 | goals5  =  0\n| years6  = 2007      | clubs6  = [[Cobreloa]]                                                 | caps6  = 22 | goals6  =  0\n| years7  = 2008      | clubs7  = [[O'Higgins F.C.|O'Higgins]]                                 | caps7  = 34 | goals7  = 13\n| years8  = 2009\u20132010 | clubs8  = [[Club Am\u00e9rica|Am\u00e9rica]]                                     | caps8  = 45 | goals8  =  3\n| years9  = 2010\u20132012 | clubs9  = [[Birmingham City F.C.|Birmingham City]]                     | caps9  = 39 | goals9  =  3\n| years10 = 2012\u20132014 | clubs10 = [[Wigan Athletic F.C.|Wigan Athletic]]                       | caps10 = 85 | goals10 =  3\n| years11 = 2014\u20132016 | clubs11 = [[Colo-Colo]]                                                | caps11 = 54 | goals11 =  7\n| years12 = 2016\u2013     | clubs12 = [[Club Universidad de Chile|Universidad de Chile]]           | caps12 = 69 | goals12 =  1\n<!-- LEAGUE GAMES ONLY - When you update these stats, please also update the club-update parameter by typing ~~~~~ instead of what's already there, the software will convert that to current date/time -->\n| club-update    = 17 January 2020\n| nationalyears1 = 2004\n| nationalteam1  = [[Chile Olympic football team|Chile U23]]\n| nationalcaps1  = 7\n| nationalgoals1 = 2\n| nationalyears2 = 2004\u20132019\n| nationalteam2  = [[Chile national football team|Chile]]\n| nationalcaps2  = 107\n| nationalgoals2 = 6\n<!-- When you update these stats, please also update the nationalteam-update parameter! -->\n| nationalteam-update = 6 July 2019\n| medaltemplates = {{MedalCountry|{{CHI}}}}\n{{Medal|W|[[Copa Am\u00e9rica]]|[[2015 Copa Am\u00e9rica|2015]]}}\n{{Medal|W|[[Copa Am\u00e9rica Centenario]]|[[Copa Am\u00e9rica Centenario|2016]]}}\n{{Medal|RU|[[FIFA Confederations Cup]]|[[2017 FIFA Confederations Cup|2017]]}}\n}}\n'''Jean Andr\u00e9 Emanuel Beausejour Coliqueo''' ({{IPA-es|\u02c8\u025f\u029dam bose\u02c8\u029du\u027e}}; born 1 June 1984) is a Chilean professional [[association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[Defender (association football)#Wing-back|left-sided wing-back]] for [[Chilean Primera Divisi\u00f3n|Primera Divisi\u00f3n]] club [[Club Universidad de Chile|Universidad de Chile]].\n\nHe has played in Chile, Switzerland, Brazil, Belgium, Mexico and England, where he won the [[Football League Cup|League Cup]] with [[Birmingham City F.C.|Birmingham City]] and the [[FA Cup]] with [[Wigan Athletic]].\n\nBeausejour made his debut for the [[Chile national football team|Chilean national team]] in 2004 and his 100th appearance for his country in 2018. He was a member of the [[Copa Am\u00e9rica]]-winning squads in [[2015 Copa Am\u00e9rica|2015]] and [[Copa Am\u00e9rica Centenario|2016]], and is the only Chilean to score in two consecutive [[FIFA World Cup|World Cups]] ([[2010 FIFA World Cup|2010]] and [[2014 FIFA World Cup|2014]]).\n\n==Personal life==\nBeausejour was born in [[Santiago]].<ref name=TheClinic>{{cite news |url=http://www.theclinic.cl/2016/06/10/jean-beausejour-y-el-proceso-constituyente-pocos-quieren-darle-la-posibilidad-de-participar-realmente-a-la-gente/ |title=Jean Beausejour: \"Pocos quieren darle la posibilidad de participar realmente a la gente\" |language=Spanish |trans-title=Jean Beausejour: \"Not many want to give the people the possibility of real participation\" |first=Patricio |last=Fern\u00e1ndez |magazine=The Clinic |location=Santiago |date=10 June 2016 |accessdate=4 April 2018}}</ref> His father, Jean Coty Beausejour,<ref name=Coliqueo>{{cite news |url=http://diario.elmercurio.com/detalle/index.asp?id={d19e897f-4b81-4fda-858d-9963b0e19ccd} |title=El lado Coliqueo de Beausejour |language=Spanish |trans-title=The Coliqueo side of Beausejour |newspaper=El Mercurio |location=Santiago |date=23 August 2014 |accessdate=4 April 2018}}</ref> was a Haitian graduate student of African descent who went on to work for the [[United Nations]],<ref name=ApoyaLaCausa>{{cite news |url=http://www.elciudadano.cl/2009/11/12/14127/jean-beausejour-coliqueo-apoya-la-causa-mapuche/ |title=Jean Beausejour Coliqueo apoya la causa mapuche |language=Spanish |trans-title=Jean Beausejour Coliqueo supports the Mapuche cause |newspaper=El Ciudadano |location=Santiago |date=12 November 2010 |accessdate=4 April 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120115172322/http://www.elciudadano.cl/2009/11/12/14127/jean-beausejour-coliqueo-apoya-la-causa-mapuche/ |archive-date=15 January 2012 |url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=TheClinic/> and his mother, Viviana Coliqueo Collipay,<ref name=SuGente>{{cite web |url=http://www.colocolo.cl/el-futbol-la-tierra-su-gente-y-beausejour/ |title=El f\u00fatbol, la tierra, su gente y Beausejour |language=es |trans-title=Football, the earth, its people and Beausejour |first=Leonardo |last=Salazar M. |publisher=Colo-Colo |date=9 December 2014 |accessdate=4 April 2018}}</ref> is a Chilean of [[Mapuche]] ethnicity whose father, Andres, had migrated to the city to find work.<ref name=Coliqueo/> Beausejour's parents separated when he was very young,<ref name=TheClinic/> and he was raised by his mother and her parents; he regards his grandfather as his father-figure.<ref name=ElCubo>{{cite news |url=http://www.lacuarta.com/noticia/jean-beausejour-sincero-el-cubo/ |title=Jean Beausejour se sincer\u00f3 en ''El Cubo'': Ser mapuche y negro es un orgullo |language=Spanish |trans-title=Jean Beausejour opens up on ''El Cubo'': being Mapuche and black is a matter for pride |first=Felipe |last=Pavez |newspaper=La Cuarta |location=Santiago |date=25 August 2017 |accessdate=4 April 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180405214807/http://www.lacuarta.com/noticia/jean-beausejour-sincero-el-cubo/ |archive-date=5 April 2018 |url-status=dead}}</ref> The family lived in Villa Carmelitas, in the [[Estaci\u00f3n Central]] commune of Santiago, where Beausejour was educated at Escuela Profesor Ram\u00f3n del R\u00edo, Colegio Holanda and Liceo Guillermo Feli\u00fa Cruz.<ref name=Polidep>{{cite news |url=http://municipalidadestacioncentral.cl/polideportivo-de-estacion-central-fue-bautizado-como-jean-beausejour-coliqueo/ |title=Polideportivo de Estaci\u00f3n Central fue bautizado como Jean Beausejour Coliqueo |language=es |trans-title=Estaci\u00f3n Central Sports Centre named after Jean Beausejour Coliqueo |publisher=Municipalidad Estaci\u00f3n Central |date=7 July 2016 |accessdate=4 April 2018}}</ref> In 2010, the local council declared him an ''Hijo Ilustre'', 'honoured son', of the community,<ref name=HijoIllustre>{{cite news |url=http://www.cooperativa.cl/noticias/deportes/mundiales-de-futbol/sudafrica-2010/jean-beausejour-fue-declarado-hijo-ilustre-de-estacion-central/2010-07-07/161750.html |title=Jean Beausejour fue declarado hijo ilustre de Estaci\u00f3n Central |language=es |trans-title=Jean Beausejour declared honoured son of Estaci\u00f3n Central |publisher=Radio Cooperativa |date=7 July 2010 |accessdate=5 July 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150706154509/http://www.cooperativa.cl/noticias/deportes/mundiales-de-futbol/sudafrica-2010/jean-beausejour-fue-declarado-hijo-ilustre-de-estacion-central/2010-07-07/161750.html |archivedate=6 July 2015}}</ref> and six years later a new sports centre was named after him.<ref name=Polidep/>\n\nBecause of his dark skin, he was nicknamed ''Palmatoria'' after a black football-playing character in a [[comics|children's comic]]; despite reports that he hated the name,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.ft.com/content/ddcd2f16-fa25-11e3-a328-00144feab7de |title=World Cup watchers warm to Chile |first=Simon |last=Kuper |newspaper=Financial Times |date=22 June 2014 |accessdate=4 April 2018}}<br>{{cite news |url=http://ecodiario.eleconomista.es/internacional/noticias/2237955/06/10/Jean-Beausejour-el-hijo-de-un-haitiano-nuevo-heroe-de-la-Roja-de-Bielsa.html |title=Jean Beausejour, el hijo de un haitiano, nuevo h\u00e9roe de la 'Roja' de Bielsa |language=Spanish |trans-title=Jean Beausejour, son of a Haitian father, new hero of Bielsa's ''\"Roja\"'' |newspaper=El Economista |location=Madrid |agency=AFP |date=17 June 2010 |accessdate=4 April 2018}}</ref> he says it did not bother him,<ref name=ElCubo/><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.lasegunda.com/Noticias/Deportes/2014/11/975351/el-racismo-que-ronda-al-futbol-nacional |title=El racismo que ronda al f\u00fatbol nacional |language=Spanish |trans-title=The racism that surrounds national football |newspaper=La Segunda |location=Santiago |date=14 November 2014 |accessdate=4 April 2018}}</ref> and that being black caused him fewer problems<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.eldesconcierto.cl/2018/03/02/jean-beausejour-se-mete-en-el-debate-de-la-inmigracion-yo-tuve-mas-problemas-con-el-apellido-mapuche-que-por-ser-negro/ |title=Jean Beausejour se mete en el debate de la inmigraci\u00f3n: 'Yo tuve m\u00e1s problemas con el apellido mapuche que por ser negro' |language=Spanish |trans-title=Jean Beausejour gets into the immigration debate: 'I had more problems with the Mapuche name than with being black' |newspaper=El Desconcierto |location=Santiago |date=2 March 2018 |accessdate=4 April 2018}}</ref> than did the indigenous Mapuche heritage with which he closely identifies.<ref name=ApoyaLaCausa/><ref name=ElCubo/>\n\nBeausejour is married to Karina Ugarte. {{As of|January 2016}}, the couple had two children, Joaqu\u00edn and Luciano.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.observador.cl/6428-jean_beausejour_eligi_la_tranquilidad_de_quillota_para_bautizar_a_su_hijo_menor |title=Jean Beausejour eligi\u00f3 la tranquilidad de Quillota para bautizar a su hijo menor |language=Spanish |trans-title=Jean Beausejour chose the tranquility of Quillota to baptise his younger son |newspaper=El Observador |location=Quillota |date=27 January 2016 |accessdate=12 April 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171014020132/http://www.observador.cl/6428-jean_beausejour_eligi_la_tranquilidad_de_quillota_para_bautizar_a_su_hijo_menor |archive-date=14 October 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Joaqu\u00edn has played football in the junior ranks of Universidad Cat\u00f3lica, the club where his father completed his youth development.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.economiaynegocios.cl/noticias/noticias.asp?id=381624 |title=En San Carlos de Apoquindo se adiestran los hijos de la fama |language=Spanish |trans-title=The sons of the famous do their training at San Carlos de Apoquindo |first=Ra\u00fal |last=Neira B. |newspaper=Econom\u00eda y Negocios |location=Santiago |date=23 July 2017 |accessdate=12 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Club career==\n\n===Early career===\nAs a 10-year-old, Beausejour attended a public trial with the local senior club, [[Club Universidad de Chile|Universidad de Chile]], and was one of four boys chosen to go through further selection procedures to join the club's youth system.<ref name=TheClinic/> At 14, he was released.<ref name=TheClinic/> After a trial with city rivals [[Club Deportivo Universidad Cat\u00f3lica|Universidad Cat\u00f3lica]], he was accepted into their youth system where he continued his football development.<ref name=TheClinic/>\n\nHe began his professional career at Universidad Cat\u00f3lica. In 2002, he debuted after being loaned to [[CD Universidad de Concepci\u00f3n|Universidad de Concepci\u00f3n]] where he had an impressive season alongside [[Jorge Valdivia]].\n\nIn June 2004, he joined Swiss club [[Servette FC|Servette]],<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.emol.com/noticias/deportes/2004/06/16/150531/sin-avisar-jean-beausejour-se-fue-de-la-catolica-al-futbol-suizo.html |title=Sin avisar: Jean Beausejour se fue de la Cat\u00f3lica al f\u00fatbol suizo |language=Spanish |trans-title=Without notice: Jean Beausejour has left Cat\u00f3lica for Swiss football |website=Emol.com |date=16 June 2004 |accessdate=5 April 2018}}</ref> reuniting with Valdivia to play in the [[UEFA Cup]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.emol.com/noticias/deportes/2004/06/24/151283/jorge-valdivia-firmo-en-el-servette-de-beausejour.html |title=Jorge Valdivia firm\u00f3 en el Servette de Beausejour |language=Spanish |trans-title=Jorge Valdivia signed for Beausejour's Servette |website=Emol.com |date=24 June 2004 |accessdate=5 April 2018}}</ref> He scored once from 11 appearances in the [[Swiss Super League]] before the club went bankrupt in February 2005 and it lost its licence to compete at that level.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sfl.ch/fr/news/news/article/les-anecdotes-suisses-de-la-coupe-du-monde-2e-partie/ |title=Les \"anecdotes suisses de la Coupe du Monde\": 2e partie |language=French |trans-title=Swiss World Cup stories: part 2 |publisher=Swiss Football League |date=3 July 2014 |accessdate=6 April 2018}}<br>{{cite web |url=http://www.uefa.com/memberassociations/association=sui/news/newsid=280480.html |title=Final curtain for Servette |publisher=UEFA |date=16 February 2005 |accessdate=6 April 2015}}</ref> His goal, Servette's third in a 4\u20131 win away to [[FC Schaffhausen|Schaffhausen]], proved costly to the player who supplied the cross, [[Paulo Diogo]], who leapt onto the perimeter fence in celebration, caught his wedding ring in the metalwork, and when he jumped down, much of his finger was torn away along with the ring. The finger had to be amputated.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.servettefc.ch/index.php?sp=actu&ida=477 |title=Schaffhouse\u2013Servette 1\u20134 (0\u20132) |language=French |first=Marc |last=Ramer |publisher=Servette FC |date=5 December 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20041209111337/http://www.servettefc.ch/index.php?sp=actu&ida=477 |archivedate=9 December 2004}}<br>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2004/dec/07/newsstory.sport12 |title=No pity for Diogo's fickle finger of fate |first=Mike |last=Baker |newspaper=The Guardian |location=London |date=7 December 2004 |accessdate=6 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2005, Beausejour signed a short-term deal with Brazilian club [[Gr\u00eamio Foot-Ball Porto Alegrense|Gr\u00eamio]],<ref>{{cite news |url=https://theworldgame.sbs.com.au/article/2005/07/02/gremio-signs-chilean-beausejour |title=Gremio signs Chilean Beausejour |website=The World Game |agency=Associated Press |date=2 July 2005 |accessdate=6 April 2015}}</ref> where he helped the team to win the [[S\u00e9rie B]] title.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://espn.uol.com.br/video/348182_caras-da-copa-ex-gremio-o-chileno-beausejour-ja-conquistou-titulos-em-cima-de-arsenal-e-manchester-city |title=Caras da Copa: Ex-Gremio, o Chileno Beausejour j\u00e1 conquistou titulos em cima de Arsenal e Manchester City |language=Portuguese |trans-title=Guys of the Cup: Once of Gremio, the Chilean Beausejour has already beaten Arsenal and Manchester City to win titles |publisher=ESPN Brazil |date=11 August 2013 |accessdate=5 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nHe joined [[KAA Gent]] of Belgium in January 2006 on an 18-month contract,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.uefa.com/memberassociations/news/newsid=390520.html |title=Sinama seals Rovers loan move |publisher=UEFA |date=31 January 2006 |accessdate=6 April 2015}}</ref> but made no appearances and returned to Chile after a year where he signed for [[Cobreloa]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.cooperativa.cl/noticias/site/artic/20070102/pags/20070102095612.html |title=Cobreloa reforz\u00f3 su ataque con Jean Beausejour |language=Spanish |trans-title=Cobreloa strengthened their attack with Jean Beausejour |publisher=Radio Cooperativa |date=2 January 2007 |accessdate=6 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2008, Beausejour joined [[Club Deportivo O'Higgins|O'Higgins]] where he was used as [[Left winger (football)|left winger]] by [[Jorge Sampaoli]] and re-gained status after impressing once again. His performances led him to the [[Chilean national football team|national team]] coached by [[Marcelo Bielsa]] who usually used him in the same position.\n\nOn 1 December 2008, it was reported that Beausejour completed a three-and-half year deal with Mexican club [[Club Am\u00e9rica|Am\u00e9rica]]. He made his debut on 4 January 2009 during a 1\u20131 draw with rivals [[CD Guadalajara|Guadalajara]], scoring the opening goal.\n\nFollowing a one-and-half year spell with the [[M\u00e9xico DF]]\u2013based side and his [[2010 FIFA World Cup|FIFA World Cup]] participation, he signed a three-year contract with [[Premier League]] side [[Birmingham City F.C.|Birmingham City]] for an undisclosed fee in August 2010.\n\n===Birmingham City===\n[[File:Sebasti\u00e1n Pi\u00f1era - Jean Beausejour.jpg|thumb|right|Beausejour with [[President of Chile]] [[Sebasti\u00e1n Pi\u00f1era]], holding a Birmingham City shirt, at London's Olympic Park]]\nAfter 18 months with the [[Mexico City]]-based club followed by a \"tremendous\" [[2010 FIFA World Cup|World Cup]], Beausejour signed a three-year contract with [[Premier League]] club [[Birmingham City F.C.|Birmingham City]] for an undisclosed fee in August 2010. Manager [[Alex McLeish]] stated that Beausejour was a player that had been on their \"list of targets for a long time because he is strong and quick with the ability to beat his man and get crosses in.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.espn.com/blog/los-angeles/soccer/post/_/id/2933/mexico-jean-beausejour-leaves-america-for-england |title=Mexico: Jean Beausejour leaves America for England |first=Scott |last=French |publisher=ESPN |date=31 August 2010 |accessdate=6 April 2018 }}<br>{{cite web |url=http://world.bcfc.com/page/News/NewsDetail/0,,10412~2140094,00.html |title=Beausejour the Blue |publisher=Birmingham City F.C. |date=31 August 2010 |accessdate=5 April 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180407053422/http://world.bcfc.com/page/News/NewsDetail/0,,10412~2140094,00.html |archive-date=7 April 2018 |url-status=dead}}</ref> His debut was delayed while he awaited a working visa,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.skysports.com/football/news/11694/6376580/beausejour-available-for-blues |title=Beausejour available for Blues |publisher=Sky Sports |date=14 September 2010 |accessdate=5 April 2018}}</ref> but he made his first appearance on 18 September as a late substitute, replacing [[Alexander Hleb]] in the 83rd minute as Birmingham lost 3\u20131 at [[West Bromwich Albion]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/9006917.stm |title=West Brom 3\u20131 Birmingham |first=Mark |last=Ashenden |publisher=BBC Sport |date=18 September 2010 |accessdate=18 September 2010}}</ref> He made more impact on his first start, setting up goals for Hleb and [[Nikola \u017digi\u0107]] in the 3\u20131 [[EFL Cup|League Cup]] victory over [[MK Dons]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/9009796.stm |title=Birmingham 3\u20131 MK Dons |publisher=BBC Sport |date=22 September 2010 |accessdate=23 September 2010}}</ref> Described by the ''[[Sunday Mirror]]'' as \"at the heart of everything good about Birmingham\" in the [[FA Cup]] third round against [[Millwall F.C.|Millwall]],<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/sport/football/news/millwall-1-4-birmingham-sunday-mirror-3335472 |title=Millwall 1\u20134 Birmingham: Sunday Mirror match report |newspaper=Sunday Mirror |location=London |date=9 January 2011 |accessdate=5 April 2018}}</ref> Beausejour provided the assist for the opening goal and \"crashed a 20-yard strike off the bar\".<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/fa_cup/9341908.stm |title=Millwall 1\u20134 Birmingham |publisher=BBC Sport |date=8 January 2011 |accessdate=10 January 2011}}</ref> He scored his first goal for the club six minutes into the FA Cup fifth-round defeat of [[Sheffield Wednesday]], with a side-footed shot from a [[Lee Bowyer]] cut-back.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/9401043.stm |title=Birmingham 3\u20130 Sheff Wed |publisher=BBC Sport |date=19 January 2011 |accessdate=21 January 2011}}</ref> He was a second-half substitute as Birmingham won the [[2011 Football League Cup Final|2011 League Cup]], beating favourites [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] 2\u20131 at [[Wembley Stadium]],<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/9405702.stm |title=Arsenal 1\u20132 Birmingham |first=Philip |last=McNulty |publisher=BBC Sport |date=27 February 2011 |accessdate=28 February 2011}}</ref> thus earning qualification for the [[2011\u201312 UEFA Europa League|Europa League]]. On 5 March 2011, Beausejour scored his first Premier League goal in a 3\u20131 defeat at home to West Bromwich Albion,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.birminghammail.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/birmingham-city-1west-bromwich-albion-149778 |title=Birmingham City 1,West Bromwich Albion 3 |first=Colin |last=Tattum |newspaper=Birmingham Mail |date=7 March 2011 |accessdate=5 April 2018}}</ref> and his second came four days later in a 1\u20131 draw at [[Everton F.C.|Everton]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/9415280.stm |title=Everton 1\u20131 Birmingham |first=Saj |last=Chowdhury |publisher=BBC Sport |date=9 March 2011 |accessdate=5 November 2011}}</ref> But his club struggled with injuries for most of the [[2010\u201311 Birmingham City F.C. season|2010\u201311 season]],{{citation needed|date=April 2018}} and were relegated from the Premier League.\n\nBeausejour was the ''[[Birmingham Mail]]''{{'s}} [[man of the match]] in Birmingham's first appearance in major European competition for nearly 50 years, the [[2011\u201312 UEFA Europa League#Play-off round|Europa League play-off round]] first leg against Portuguese club [[C.D. Nacional|Nacional]], which finished goalless.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.birminghammail.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/nacional-0-birmingham-city-0-159852 |title=Nacional 0, Birmingham City 0 |newspaper=Birmingham Mail |first=Colin |last=Tattum |date=19 August 2011 |accessdate=5 April 2018}}</ref> Just days after manager [[Chris Hughton]] suggested he wanted more from Beausejour in an attacking role,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.birminghammail.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/jean-beausejour-urged-to-increase-his-goal-163397 |title=Jean Beausejour urged to increase his goal output at Birmingham City |newspaper=Birmingham Mail |first=Colin |last=Tattum |date=15 October 2011 |accessdate=5 April 2018}}</ref> the player had an eventful man-of-the-match performance as Birmingham beat [[Leicester City F.C.|Leicester City]] 2\u20130. In the first few minutes of the second half, he \"hit the angle of post and bar with a fierce shot\", was considered fortunate by visiting manager [[Sven-G\u00f6ran Eriksson]] to escape a second yellow card, and was tripped by [[Andy King (footballer born 1988)|Andy King]] to earn a penalty kick from which [[Marlon King]] opened the scoring.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/football-league/eriksson-refuses-to-see-red-as-leicester-pay-for-indiscipline-2371649.html |title=Eriksson refuses to see red as Leicester pay for indiscipline |newspaper=The Independent |first=Jon |last=Culley |date=17 October 2011 |accessdate=17 October 2011}}</ref> In the [[2011\u201312 UEFA Europa League group stage|Europa League group stage]], an error by Beausejour led to [[Club Brugge]]'s second goal, but he scored from the rebound after \u017digi\u0107's shot was blocked and was fouled for the penalty from which King equalised.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.uefa.com/uefaeuropaleague/index.html#/iv/match/2007363/stories/1669323 |title=Birmingham fight back against Club Brugge |publisher=UEFA |date=3 November 2011 |accessdate=5 April 2018}}</ref> His first league goal of the season came against [[Burnley F.C.|Burnley]] in November, again from a rebound, in the second minute of a match that Birmingham won 2\u20131 in stoppage time.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/15732474 |title=Birmingham 2\u20131 Burnley |first=Karen |last=Fazackerley |publisher=BBC Sport |date=22 November 2011 |accessdate=6 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Wigan Athletic===\nOn 25 January 2012, Beausejour joined Premier League club [[Wigan Athletic F.C.|Wigan Athletic]] for an undisclosed fee, signing a two-and-a-half-year contract.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/16692150 |title=Wigan sign Birmingham City winger Jean Beausejour |publisher=BBC Sport |date=25 January 2012 |accessdate=5 April 2018}}</ref> He made his debut in the 3\u20131 defeat against [[Tottenham Hotspur]] at [[White Hart Lane]] on 31 January.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.skysports.com/football/match_commentary/0,19764,11065_3408808,00.html |title=FT: Tottenham 3 Wigan 1 |first=Razwan |last=Mirza |publisher=Sky Sports |date=31 January 2012 |accessdate=1 February 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120203020459/http://www.skysports.com/football/match_commentary/0%2C19764%2C11065_3408808%2C00.html |archivedate=3 February 2012}}</ref> On his home debut, against [[Everton F.C.|Everton]], his man-of-the-match performance featured a \"low cross [that] struck [[Phil Neville]] on the foot, before heading in the direction of [[Tim Howard]], but the ball spun sharply, slipping through the American's grasp\" for an [[own goal]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/premier-league/baines-sees-own-goal-as-sods-law-6577512.html |title=Baines sees own goal as Sod's law |first=Will |last=Unwin |newspaper=The Independent |date=6 February 2012 |accessdate=6 February 2012}}</ref> Beausejour slotted well into the [[Formation (association football)#3\u20134\u20133|3\u20134\u20133 formation]] playing at left [[defender (association football)#Wing-back|wing back]].{{Citation needed|date=April 2012}} He helped his team reach the [[2013 FA Cup Final]], but a hamstring injury meant he missed the match itself,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://en.espn.co.uk/football/sport/story/205742.html |title=Wigan set to lose Beausejour for FA Cup final |publisher=ESPN |date=5 May 2013 |accessdate=5 April 2018}}</ref> in which Wigan beat [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] 1\u20130 at [[Wembley Stadium|Wembley]] to win the first major trophy in their history.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/22409634 |title=FA Cup final: Manchester City 0\u20131 Wigan Athletic |first=Phil |last=McNulty |publisher=BBC Sport |date=11 May 2013 |accessdate=5 April 2018}}</ref> Beausejour's second consecutive Premier League relegation was confirmed just days later after a 4\u20131 defeat at the hands of [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://en.espn.co.uk/football/sport/story/207273.html |title=Martinez: Defence to blame |publisher=ESPN |date=15 May 2013 |accessdate=6 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nHe left Wigan Athletic in June 2014 when his contract expired.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.wiganathletic.com/news/2014/july/club-confirm-contracts-expire/ |title=Club confirm contracts expire |publisher=Wigan Athletic F.C. |date=7 July 2014 |accessdate=5 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Colo-Colo===\n\n====2014\u201315 season====\n[[File:INDEPENDIENTE vs COLO COLO (2) cropped.jpg|thumb|150px|right|Beausejour with [[Colo-Colo]]]]\nAfter his participation in the [[2014 FIFA World Cup|World Cup]], Beausejour returned to Chile to play for recent league champions [[Colo-Colo]]. He signed a two-year contract<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.emol.com/noticias/deportes/2014/07/10/669345/un-refuerzo-de-categoria-para-hector-tapia-jean-beausejour-llega-a-acuerdo-con-colo-colo.html |title=Refuerzo de categor\u00eda para H\u00e9ctor Tapia: Jean Beausejour firma por Colo Colo |website=Emol.com |date=10 July 2014 |accessdate=29 December 2014}}</ref> at reported wages of 34&nbsp;million [[Chilean peso|pesos]] ($68,000 approx.) a month.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.latercera.com/noticia/deportes/2014/07/656-586908-9-los-sueldos-mas-altos-que-marcaran-el-torneo-de-apertura-2014.shtml |title=Los sueldos m\u00e1s altos que marcar\u00e1n el Torneo de Apertura 2014 |language=Spanish |trans-title=The highest wages in the 2014 Apertura |first=Mat\u00edas |last=Parker Castro |newspaper=La Tercera |date=18 July 2014 |accessdate=5 April 2018}}</ref> International clearance permitting, coach [[H\u00e9ctor Tapia]] planned to put Beausejour straight into the starting eleven at left back at the expense of [[Luis Pavez Mu\u00f1oz|Luis Pavez]],<ref>{{cite news |url=http://deportes.terra.cl/futbol/primera-division/beausejour-seria-titular-en-colo-colo-como-lateral-izquierdo,c24641d8f0647410VgnVCM3000009af154d0RCRD.html |title=Beausejour ser\u00eda titular en Colo Colo como lateral izquierdo |language=Spanish |trans-title=Beausejour will start for Colo Colo at left back |website=Terra Deportes |date=12 July 2014 |accessdate=29 December 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140720001006/http://deportes.terra.cl/futbol/primera-division/beausejour-seria-titular-en-colo-colo-como-lateral-izquierdo,c24641d8f0647410VgnVCM3000009af154d0RCRD.html |archivedate=20 July 2014}}</ref> but he made his competitive debut in the second match of the [[2014 Torneo Apertura (Chile)|Torneo Apertura]], on 27 June against [[Deportes Iquique]]. Colo-Colo won 2\u20130, both goals scored by [[Esteban Paredes]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://deportes.terra.cl/futbol/primera-division/de-la-mano-de-paredes-colo-colo-vence-en-debut-de-beausejour,cdd357ba93a77410VgnVCM3000009af154d0RCRD.html |title=De la mano de Paredes Colo Colo vence en debut de Beausejour |language=Spanish |trans-title=By the hand of Paredes Colo Colo win on Beausejour's debut |website=Terra Deportes |date=27 July 2014 |accessdate=29 December 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141230095708/http://deportes.terra.cl/futbol/primera-division/de-la-mano-de-paredes-colo-colo-vence-en-debut-de-beausejour,cdd357ba93a77410VgnVCM3000009af154d0RCRD.html |archivedate=30 December 2014}}</ref> On 31 August, Beausejour scored his first competitive goal in a 4\u20130 home win over [[Deportes Antofagasta]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.elmostrador.cl/dia/2014/08/31/colo-colo-derrota-4-0-a-antofagasta-y-sigue-a-la-caza-de-la-u/ |title=Colo-Colo derrota 4\u20130 a Antofagasta y sigue a la caza de la U |language=Spanish |trans-title=Colo-Colo beat Antofagasta 4\u20130 and keep on the track of \"''la U''\" (Universidad de Chile) |newspaper=El Mostrador |agency=UPI Chile |date=12 July 2014 |accessdate=5 April 2018}}</ref> After scoring his second goal, on 14 September against [[CD Palestino|Palestino]] in a 3\u20131 away win, he was sent off for striking [[Leonardo Valencia]] and received a two-match suspension.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://cnnchile.com/noticia/2014/09/14/colo-colo-derroto-3-a-1-a-palestino |title=Colo Colo derrot\u00f3 3 a 1 a Palestino |language=Spanish |trans-title=Colo Colo beat Palestino 3\u20131 |publisher=CNN Chile |date=14 September 2014 |accessdate=5 April 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.emol.com/noticias/deportes/2014/09/16/680641/jean-beausejour-recibio-dos-fechas-de-sancion-y-podra-jugar-el-superclasico-con-la-u.html |title=Dos fechas de sanci\u00f3n para Beausejour y podr\u00e1 jugar el supercl\u00e1sico |language=Spanish |trans-title=Two-match ban for Beausejour and could play in the ''supercl\u00e1sico'' |website=Emol.com |date=12 July 2014 |accessdate=5 April 2018}}</ref> His first match back after the ban was the ''[[Chilean football derby|supercl\u00e1sico]]'' against [[Club Universidad de Chile|Universidad de Chile]] on 19 October, in which he scored his side's second goal in a 2\u20130 victory at the [[Estadio Monumental David Arellano|Estadio Monumental]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.emol.com/noticias/deportes/2014/10/19/685815/colo-colo-se-queda-con-el-superclasico-y-queda-a-2-puntos-de-la-u-en-un-encendido-torneo.html |title=Colo Colo gana el Supercl\u00e1sico y queda a 2 puntos de la U. de Chile en un encendido Torneo |language=Spanish |trans-title=Colo Colo win the Supercl\u00e1sico and are only 2 points off U. de Chile in a fired-up Torneo |website=Emol.com |date=19 October 2014 |accessdate=30 December 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.espn.co.uk/football/blog/name/68/post/2098235/headline |title=Colo Colo's Santiago derby win forces Chilean league down to the wire |first=Tim |last=Vickery |publisher=ESPN |date=20 October 2014 |accessdate=6 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 30 December 2014, Beausejour appeared in the club's 3\u20132 [[:es:Noche Alba|Noche Alba]] win over [[Uni\u00f3n Espa\u00f1ola]] at which the club presented new signings [[Humberto Suazo]] and [[Luis Pedro Figueroa]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www2.latercera.com/noticia/humberto-suazo-redebuta-en-colo-colo-con-triunfo-ante-union-espanola/ |title=Humberto Suazo redebuta en Colo Colo con triunfo ante Uni\u00f3n Espa\u00f1ola |language=Spanish |trans-title=Humberto Suazo makes his second debut for Colo Colo with a win against Uni\u00f3n Espa\u00f1ola |first=R. |last=Retamal |newspaper=La Tercera |date=30 December 2014 |accessdate=5 April 2018}}</ref> They made a poor start to the [[2014\u201315 Primera Divisi\u00f3n of Chile#Torneo Clausura|Clausura]] with a 1\u20130 defeat at home to [[San Marcos de Arica]] on 4 January 2015,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.24horas.cl/deportes/torneodeclausura2015/colo-colo-cae-ante-san-marcos-en-su-debut-en-el-clausura-1545852 |title=Colo Colo cae ante San Marcos en su debut en el Clausura |language=Spanish |trans-title=Colo Colo go down to San Marcos on the opening day of the Clausura |website=24 Horas |publisher=Televisi\u00f3n Nacional de Chile |date=4 January 2014 |accessdate=5 April 2018}}</ref> but ended a four-match winless streak with a 2\u20130 win away to [[O'Higgins F.C.|O'Higgins]] in which Beausejour scored his first goal of the season.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.emol.com/noticias/deportes/2015/02/01/701868/deja-atras-su-mal-inicio-colo-colo-derrota-a-ohiggins-y-logra-su-primer-triunfo-en-el-clausura.html |title=F\u00fatbol Colo Colo deja atr\u00e1s su mal inicio: Derrota a O'Higgins y logra su primer triunfo en el Clausura |language=Spanish |trans-title=Colo Colo leave their bad start behind: Beat O'Higgins for their first win of the Clausura |website=Emol.com |date=1 February 2014 |accessdate=5 April 2018}}</ref> He started the most part of the tournament as full back, completing fourteen games and one goal in a tournament which Colo-Colo finished runner-up.\n\n====2015\u201316 season====\nFor the [[2015\u201316 Chilean Primera Divisi\u00f3n season|2015\u201316 season]] under new coach [[Jos\u00e9 Luis Sierra]], Beausejour returned to his original position of left winger. On 15 September, he scored his fifth competitive goal for the club, his first of the [[2015 Torneo Apertura (Chile)|2015 Apertura]], in a 3\u20131 home win over [[Uni\u00f3n La Calera]] that extended the team's perfect start to six league matches.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.24horas.cl/deportes/futbol-nacional/colo-colo-gana-y-se-afirma-en-la-cima-del-apertura-1786310 |title=Colo Colo gana y se afirma en la cima del Apertura |language=Spanish |trans-title=Colo Colo win and stay top of the Apertura |website=24 Horas |publisher=Televisi\u00f3n Nacional de Chile |date=31 October 2015 |accessdate=22 November 2015}}</ref> Beausejour produced his second consecutive goal in Chilean derbies when he opened the scoring with a header in Colo-Colo's 2\u20130 victory over Universidad de Chile on 31 October.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.goal.com/es-cl/news/4778/main/2015/10/31/16862232/colo-colo-extendi%C3%B3-su-paternidad-ante-la-u-en-el-monumental |title=Colo Colo extendi\u00f3 su paternidad ante la U en el Monumental |language=Spanish |trans-title=Colo Colo extended their superiority over ''la U'' at the Monumental |website=Goal.com |date=31 October 2015 |accessdate=6 April 2018}}</ref> On 6 December, he finally won a domestic league title as Colo-Colo clinched their 31st in embarrassing circumstances: rivals Universidad Cat\u00f3lica lost to [[Audax Italiano]], while Colo-Colo's match, away to [[Santiago Wanderers]], was abandoned before it started because of violent incidents by their own supporters.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.emol.com/noticias/Deportes/2015/12/06/762660/En-medio-de-un-bochornoso-final-Colo-Colo-se-corona-campeon-y-baja-su-estrella-31.html |title=En medio de un bochornoso final, Colo Colo se corona campe\u00f3n y baja su estrella 31 |language=Spanish |trans-title=In the midst of an embarrassing finale, Colo Colo are crowned champions and get their 31st star |website=Emol.com |date=6 December 2015 |accessdate=6 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\n[[File:Jean Beausejour (10888029965).jpg|250px|thumb|right|Beausejour in a friendly match against [[England national football team|England]] at [[Wembley Stadium]] in November 2013.]]\nBeausejour has played for Chile at [[Chile Olympic football team|under-23]] and [[Chile national football team|senior levels]]. He was capped for Chile at the [[2004 CONMEBOL Men Pre-Olympic Tournament|2004 South American Pre-Olympic Tournament]] alongside players such as [[Jorge Valdivia]], [[Mark Gonz\u00e1lez]], [[Claudio Bravo]] and [[Rodrigo Millar]]. However, the team failed to qualify for the [[Football at the 2004 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's tournament|Athens Olympics]], finishing bottom of the final stage after topping their first-stage group, which included [[Brazil national under-23 football team|Brazil]] and eventual qualifiers [[Paraguay national under-23 football team|Paraguay]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tabless/sam-olyqual04.html |title=South-American Olympic Qualifying Tournament 2004 |first=Luis Antonio |last=Reyes |publisher=Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation (RSSSF) |date=28 January 2004 |accessdate=6 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nHe made his senior debut in a [[exhibition match#Friendly international|friendly]] against [[Mexico national football team|Mexico]] in the United States on 18 February 2004, and made the assist for [[Reinaldo Navia]]'s goal in a 1\u20131 draw.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.socceramerica.com/publications/article/5922/international-mexico-chile-in-home-depot-center.html |title=International: Mexico, Chile in Home Depot Center stalemate |publisher=Soccer America |date=19 February 2004 |accessdate=8 April 2018}}</ref> He played twice more that year, but did not appear again until 2008.<ref name=SoloFutbol>{{cite web |url=http://www.solofutbol.cl/seleccion%20chilena/jugadores%20seleccion%20chilena%20B/beausejour,%20jean.html |title=Jean Beausejour |website=solofutbol.cl |accessdate=6 April 2018}}</ref> His first international goal came on 10 June 2009 in a 4\u20130 defeat of [[Bolivia national football team|Bolivia]] at the [[Estadio Nacional Julio Mart\u00ednez Pr\u00e1danos|Estadio Nacional]] in a [[2010 FIFA World Cup qualification (CONMEBOL)|World Cup qualifier]].<ref name=BoliviaGoal/>\n\n[[Marcelo Bielsa]] named Beausejour in [[2010 FIFA World Cup squads#Chile|Chile's 23-man squad]] for the [[2010 FIFA World Cup|2010 World Cup]] finals. He scored the only goal of their first [[2010 FIFA World Cup Group H#Honduras vs Chile|group match]] against [[Honduras national football team|Honduras]] on 16 June, which was the first match that Chile had won at a World Cup since [[1962 FIFA World Cup|1962]].<ref name=HondurasGoal/> He played in all Chile's matches at the tournament until their elimination by [[Brazil national football team|Brazil]] in the round of 16.<ref name=FIFA2010>{{cite web |url=https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/archive/southafrica2010/players/player=209502/profile.html |title=2010 FIFA World Cup \u2013 Jean Beausejour |publisher=FIFA |accessdate=4 June 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130123130459/http://www.fifa.com/worldcup/archive/southafrica2010/players/player=209502/profile.html |archivedate=23 January 2013}}</ref>\n\nDuring the [[2014 FIFA World Cup qualification]] process, he and four teammates were dropped from the national team by coach [[Claudio Borghi (football manager)|Claudio Borghi]] before a match against [[Uruguay national football team|Uruguay]] in 2011 because they returned to Chile's training camp late and intoxicated after attending the baptism of Valdivia's child.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/news/story/_/id/982037/chile-stars-sent-home-for-breaking-curfew?cc=5739 |title=Chile stars sent home in disgrace |publisher=ESPN Soccernet |date=9 November 2011 |accessdate=27 December 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140103005217/http://espnfc.com/news/story/_/id/982037/chile-stars-sent-home-for-breaking-curfew?cc=5739 |archivedate=3 January 2014}}</ref> The [[Asociaci\u00f3n Nacional de F\u00fatbol Profesional]] (ANFP) increased the suspension to ten matches, and Borghi said that while he remained coach, neither Beausejour nor Valdivia would be selected even after the ban.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://uk.reuters.com/article/uk-soccer-latam-chile/five-chile-players-banned-10-games-for-indiscipline-idUKTRE7BK0AW20111221 |title=Five Chile players banned 10 games for indiscipline |first=Rex |last=Gowar |publisher=Reuters |date=21 December 2011 |accessdate=8 April 2018}}<br>{{cite news |url=http://diario.elmercurio.com/detalle/index.asp?id={89142511-19c2-4f90-995d-0533202e3588} |title=Valdivia y Beausejour no vuelven ni aunque los indulten |language=Spanish |trans-title=Valdivia and Beausejour are not coming back even if they are reprieved |newspaper=El Mercurio |location=Santiago |date=20 December 2011 |accessdate=8 April 2018}}</ref> Nevertheless, Borghi recalled Beausejour and [[Gonzalo Jara]] to the squad as soon as they had served their time, for a friendly against [[Colombia national football team|Colombia]],<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.lanacion.cl/hay-nomina-jean-beausejour-y-gonzalo-jara-vuelven-a-la-roja/noticias/2012-08-22/213901.html |title=Hay n\u00f3mina: Jean Beausejour y Gonzalo Jara vuelven a la Roja |language=Spanish |trans-title=Here's the list: Jean Beausejour and Gonzalo Jara return to the national team |newspaper=La Naci\u00f3n |location=Santiago |date=22 August 2012 |accessdate=6 July 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150709003910/http://www.lanacion.cl/hay-nomina-jean-beausejour-y-gonzalo-jara-vuelven-a-la-roja/noticias/2012-08-22/213901.html |archivedate=9 July 2015}}</ref> and Beausejour made his first international appearance for a year in a World Cup qualifier against [[Ecuador national football team|Ecuador]].<ref name=SoloFutbol/> After Borghi was replaced by [[Jorge Sampaoli]], Beausejour's former coach at O'Higgins, he played most of the remaining World Cup qualification process,<ref name=RSSSF>{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/miscellaneous/beausejour-intl.html |title=Jean Andr\u00e9 Emanuel Beausejour \u2013 International Appearances |first=Roberto |last=Mamrud |publisher=RSSSF |date=11 January 2018 |accessdate=6 April 2018}}</ref> alongside Valdivia, who was recalled to the squad in March 2013.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.emol.com/noticias/deportes/2013/03/07/587358/oficial-jorge-valdivia-vuelve-a-la-seleccion-chilena-despues-de-17-meses.html |title=Jorge Valdivia vuelve a la selecci\u00f3n chilena despu\u00e9s de 16 meses |language=Spanish |trans-title=Jorge Valdivia returns to the Chile team after 16 months |website=Emol.com |date=22 August 2012 |accessdate=6 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nDespite scepticism as to Sampaoli putting loyalty ahead of form where Beausejour was concerned, he was included in the [[2014 FIFA World Cup squads#Chile|23-man squad]] for the [[2014 FIFA World Cup]] in Brazil.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.espn.co.uk/football/blog/name/68/post/2098235/headline |title=No surprises in Chile's 23 |first=Angus |last=McNeice |publisher=ESPN |date=2 June 2014 |accessdate=6 April 2018}}</ref> During the first [[2014 FIFA World Cup Group B#Chile vs Australia|group match]], he scored with a shot from outside the box that beat [[Australia national association football team|Australia]] goalkeeper [[Mathew Ryan]] to complete his side's 3\u20131 victory and become the first ever Chilean to score in two different World Cup tournaments.<ref name=AustraliaGoal/>\n\nBeausejour was a member of Chile's [[2015 Copa Am\u00e9rica]] squad that won the tournament for the first time. He played the whole 120 minutes of [[2015 Copa Am\u00e9rica Final|the final]], in which Chile beat [[Argentina national football team|Argentina]] 4\u20131 [[Penalty shoot-out (association football)|on penalties]] at the Estadio Nacional.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/live/2015/jul/04/copa-america-2015-final-chile-argentina-live |title=Chile win Copa Am\u00e9rica after beating Argentina on penalties \u2013 as it happened |first=Tim |last=Hill |website=The Guardian |location=London |date=5 June 2015 |accessdate=6 April 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.alairelibre.cl/noticias/deportes/copa-america/chile-2015/chile-ya-tiene-nomina-definitiva-para-la-copa-america-2015/2015-05-30/154013.html |title=Chile ya tiene n\u00f3mina definitiva para la Copa Am\u00e9rica 2015 |language=Spanish |trans-title=Chile now have a definitive list for the Copa Am\u00e9rica |website=Al Aire Libre |date=30 May 2015 |accessdate=6 April 2018}}</ref> He and his country repeated their success in the following year's [[Copa Am\u00e9rica Centenario|centenary edition]]. Again he played the full 120 minutes of [[Copa Am\u00e9rica Centenario Final|the final]] against Argentina, which again finished goalless [[after extra time]]. This time he took and converted the fourth penalty as Chile went on to win the shootout 4\u20132.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.espn.com/soccer/report?gameId=444696 |title=Lionel Messi misses penalty as Chile beat Argentina in Copa final |publisher=ESPN |date=27 June 2016 |accessdate=6 April 2018}}</ref> Along with seven of his teammates, Beausejour was included in the [[Copa Am\u00e9rica Centenario#Team of the tournament|Tournament Best XI]].<ref name=BestXI>{{cite web |url=http://www.concacaf.com/article/tsg-announces-copa-america-centenario-awards |title=TSG announces Copa Am\u00e9rica Centenario awards |publisher=CONCACAF |date=27 June 2016 |accessdate=2 July 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160701144252/http://www.concacaf.com/article/tsg-announces-copa-america-centenario-awards |archivedate=1 July 2016}}</ref> The 2015 victory qualified Chile for the [[2017 FIFA Confederations Cup|2017 Confederations Cup]]. Beausejour started the first two group matches and was unused in the third. He came back into the team for the semifinal, in which Chile beat [[Portugal national football team|Portugal]] 3\u20130 on penalties, and started in [[2017 FIFA Confederations Cup Final|the final]], which Chile lost 1\u20130 to [[Germany national football team|Germany]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesi/intconcup2017.html |title=Intercontinental Cup for Nations 2017 |first=Neil |last=Morrison |publisher=RSSSF |date=5 July 2017 |accessdate=9 April 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://en.as.com/en/2017/06/28/football/1498635097_929907.html |title=Hero Bravo sends Chile to final after Portugal's penalty pain |first1=C. |last1=Roche |first2=W. |last2=Allen |website=Diario AS |location=Madrid |date=29 June 2017 |accessdate=9 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn a friendly against [[Denmark national football team|Denmark]] on 27 March 2018, Beausejour and [[Arturo Vidal]] became the sixth and seventh players to make their 100th appearances for Chile.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.prensafutbol.cl/227589-al-club-centenario-vidal-y-beausejour-sumaron-100-partidos-con-chile/ |title=Club de los 100: Vidal y Beausejour cumplieron su centenario |language=Spanish |trans-title=100 Club: Vidal and Beausejour complete their centuries |website=Prensa F\u00fatbol |date=27 March 2018 |accessdate=5 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n===International===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|colspan=\"3\"|[[Chile national football team|Chile national team]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.solofutbol.cl/seleccion%20chilena/jugadores%20seleccion%20chilena%20B/beausejour,%20jean.html |title=Jean Beausejour |website=solofutbol.cl |accessdate=5 April 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n!Year!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n|2004||3||0\n|-\n|2008||9||0\n|-\n|2009||11||1\n|-\n|2010||8||1\n|-\n|2011||12||1\n|-\n|2012||3||0\n|-\n|2013||11||2\n|-\n|2014||8||1\n|-\n|2015||8||0\n|-\n|2016||12||0\n|-\n|2017||13||0\n|-\n|2018||3||0\n|-\n|2019||6||0\n|-\n!Total||107||6\n|}\n\n===International goals===\n''The scores and results list Chile's tally first, scores list each Beausejour goal''\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\n! No. !! Date !! Venue !! Opponent !! Score !! Result !! Competition !! Ref\n|-\n| 1. || 10 June 2009|| [[Estadio Nacional de Chile]], [[Santiago]], Chile || {{fb|BOL}} ||align=\"center\"| 1\u20130 ||align=\"center\"| 4\u20130 || [[2010 FIFA World Cup qualification (CONMEBOL)|2010 FIFA World Cup qualification]]\n|align=\"center\"|<ref name=BoliviaGoal>{{cite news |url=https://www.usatoday.com/sports/soccer/2009-06-10-2210789855_x.htm |title=Chile beats Bolivia 4\u20130 in qualifying |agency=Associated Press |publisher=USA Today |date=10 June 2009 |accessdate=4 April 2011}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2. || 16 June 2010 || [[Mbombela Stadium]], [[Nelspruit]], South Africa || {{fb|HON}} ||align=\"center\"| 1\u20130 ||align=\"center\"| 1\u20130 || [[2010 FIFA World Cup]]\n|align=\"center\"|<ref name=HondurasGoal>{{cite web |url=https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/matches/round=249722/match=300061495/match-report.html |title=Beausejour ends Chile wait |publisher=FIFA |date=16 June 2010 |accessdate=6 April 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n| 3. || 29 March 2011 || [[Kyocera Stadion]], [[The Hague]], Netherlands || {{fb|COL}} ||align=\"center\"| 2\u20130 ||align=\"center\"| 2\u20130 || [[Exhibition game#Friendly international|Friendly]]\n|align=\"center\"|<ref>{{cite news |url=http://msn.foxsports.com/foxsoccer/latinamerica/story/Chile-beats-Colombia-20-in-friendly |title=Chile beats Colombia 2\u20130 in friendly |agency=Associated Press |publisher=Fox Sports |date=29 March 2011 |accessdate=4 April 2011}}</ref>\n|-\n| 4. || rowspan=2| 14 August 2013 || rowspan=2| [[Br\u00f8ndby Stadium]], [[Br\u00f8ndbyvester]], Denmark || rowspan=2| {{fb|IRQ}} || align=center|4\u20130 || rowspan=2 align=center| 6\u20130 || rowspan=2| Friendly\n|rowspan=2 align=\"center\"|<ref>{{cite news |url=https://int.soccerway.com/news/2013/August/14/international-friendly-chile-6-iraq-0/n237114/ |title=International Friendly: Chile 6 Iraq 0 |work=Soccerway |publisher=Global Sports Media |date=14 August 2013 |accessdate=15 August 2013}}</ref>\n|-\n| 5. ||align=center|5\u20130\n|-\n| 6. || 13 June 2014 || [[Arena Pantanal]], [[Cuiab\u00e1]], Brazil || {{Fb|AUS}} || align=center | 3\u20131 || align=center | 3\u20131 || [[2014 FIFA World Cup Group B#Chile vs Australia|2014 FIFA World Cup]]\n|align=\"center\"|<ref name=AustraliaGoal>{{cite web |url=https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/news/y=2014/m=6/news=a-place-in-history-for-returning-beausejour-2370835.html |title=A place in history for returning Beausejour |publisher=FIFA |date=14 June 2014 |accessdate=6 April 2018}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==Honours==\n\n===Club===\n'''Universidad Cat\u00f3lica'''\n* [[Primera Divisi\u00f3n de Chile]]: [[2002 Torneo Apertura (Chile)|2002 Apertura]]\n'''Gr\u00eamio'''\n* [[Campeonato Brasileiro S\u00e9rie B|S\u00e9rie B]]: [[2005 Campeonato Brasileiro S\u00e9rie B|2005]]\n'''Birmingham City'''\n* [[Football League Cup]]: [[2010\u201311 Football League Cup|2010\u201311]]\n'''Wigan Athletic'''\n* [[FA Cup]]: [[2012\u201313 FA Cup|2012\u201313]]\n'''Colo-Colo'''\n* Primera Divisi\u00f3n de Chile: [[2015 Torneo Apertura (Chile)|2015 Apertura]]\n'''Universidad de Chile'''\n* Primera Divisi\u00f3n de Chile: [[2017 Torneo Clausura (Chile)|2017 Clausura]]\n\n===International===\n'''Chile'''\n*[[Copa Am\u00e9rica]]: [[2015 Copa Am\u00e9rica|2015]], [[Copa Am\u00e9rica Centenario|2016]]\n\n===Individual===\n* Copa Am\u00e9rica Team of the Tournament: [[Copa Am\u00e9rica Centenario#Team of the tournament|2016]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.concacaf.com/article/tsg-announces-copa-america-centenario-awards |title=TSG announces Copa Am\u00e9rica Centenario awards |publisher=CONCACAF |date=27 June 2016 |accessdate=2 July 2016}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Soccerbase}}\n* {{Soccerway|jean-andre-emanuel-beausejour/22036}}\n* [http://www.football-lineups.com/footballer/11990/ Jean Beausejour at Football Lineups]\n\n{{Navboxes colour\n|title= Chile squads\n|bg= #E30013\n|fg= white\n|bordercolor= #0000BE\n|list1=\n{{Chile squad 2010 FIFA World Cup}}\n{{Chile squad 2011 Copa Am\u00e9rica}}\n{{Chile squad 2014 FIFA World Cup}}\n{{Chil